:h1 name=CommandLine.The Command Line
:p.
&4OS2. displays a [c&colon.\] prompt when it is waiting for you to enter a
command. (The actual text depends upon the current drive and
directory as well as your PROMPT settings.) This is called the
command line and the prompt is asking you to enter a command, an
alias or batch file name, or the instructions necessary to begin an
application program.
:p.
This section explains the features that will help you while you are
typing in commands, and how keystrokes are interpreted when you
enter them at the command line. The keystrokes discussed here are
the ones normally used by &4OS2..  If you prefer using different
keystrokes to perform these functions, you can assign new ones with
:link reftype=hd refid=INIKeyMap.key mapping directives:elink. in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:p.
The command line features documented in this section are&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=Editing.Command-Line Editing:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=CmdHist.Command History and Recall:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=HistWin.Command History Window:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=CmdNames.Command Names and Parameters:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=FileComp.Filename Completion:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=AutoDir.Automatic Directory Changes:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=DirHist.Directory History Window:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=MultCmds.Multiple Commands:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=ExpandAlias.Expanding and Disabling Aliases:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=CmdLength.Command-Line Length Limits:elink.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:p.
Additional command-line features are documented under
:link reftype=hd refid=FileSel.File Selection:elink. and :link reftype=hd
refid=TOC_Other.Other Features:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=Editing.Command-Line Editing
:p.
The command line works like a single-line word processor, allowing you to
edit any part of the command at any time before you press :hp2.Enter:ehp2.
to execute it, or :hp2.Esc:ehp2. to erase it. The command line you enter
can be up to 1023 characters long.
:p.
You can use the following editing keys when you are typing a command (the
words :hp2.Ctrl:ehp2. and :hp2.Shift:ehp2. mean to press the Ctrl or Shift
key together with the other key named)&colon.
:p.
:hp2.Cursor Movement Keys&colon.:ehp2.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=16 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.:ehp2.:pd.Move the cursor left one character.
:pt.:hp2.:ehp2.:pd.Move the cursor right one character.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl :ehp2.:pd.Move the cursor left one word.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl :ehp2.:pd.Move the cursor right one word.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl /:ehp2.:pd.Temporarily move the cursor up/down. If the PM window is too small to hold all lines this effectively scrolls the window contents.
The cursor automatically jumps back to the previous position as soon as any other key is pressed.
:pt.:hp2.Home:ehp2.:pd.Move the cursor to the beginning of the line.
:pt.:hp2.End:ehp2.:pd.Move the cursor to the end of the line.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:hp2.Insert and Delete&colon.:ehp2.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=16 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.Ins:ehp2.:pd.Toggle between insert and overtype mode.
:pt.:hp2.Del:ehp2.:pd.Delete the character at the cursor.
:pt.:hp2.Backspace:ehp2.:pd.Delete the character to the left of the cursor.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-L:ehp2.:pd.Delete the word or partial word to the left of the cursor.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-R:ehp2.:pd.or :hp2.Ctrl-Bksp:ehp2. Delete the word or partial word to the right of the cursor.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-Home:ehp2.:pd.Delete from the beginning of the line to the cursor.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-End:ehp2.:pd.Delete from the cursor to the end of the line.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-V:ehp2.:pd.Paste from clipboard.
:pt.:hp2.Esc:ehp2.:pd.Delete the entire line.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:hp2.Execution&colon.:ehp2.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=16 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-C:ehp2.:pd.or :hp2.Ctrl-Break:ehp2. Cancel the command line.
:pt.:hp2.Enter:ehp2.:pd.Execute the command line.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
Most of the command-line editing capabilities are also available
when a &4OS2. command prompts you for a line of input. For example,
you can use the command-line editing keys when
:link reftype=hd refid=DESCRIBE.DESCRIBE:elink. prompts for a file
description, when :link reftype=hd refid=INPUT.INPUT:elink. prompts for
input from an alias or batch file, or when :link reftype=hd
refid=LIST.LIST:elink. prompts you for a search string.
:p.
If you want your input at the command line to be in a different
color from &4OS2.'s prompts or output, you can use the
:link reftype=hd refid=DisplayOption.Display page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
or the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_InputColors.InputColors:elink. directive in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:p.
If you want to spread a long command line across multiple lines,
use the :link reftype=hd refid=Escape.escape character:elink.&per.
&4OS2. will prompt for additional command-line text when you include
the escape character as the very
last character of a typed command line. The default escape character
is the caret [:hp2.^:ehp2.]. For example&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] echo The quick brown fox jumped over the lazy^
    More? sleeping dog. > alphabet
:exmp.
:p.
Note that you will often need to prefix the escape character with a space
to get the results you want.
:p.
One limitation of this technique is that you can only edit the text you entered
after the escape character. However, you can cancel the current input
and use command line completion and recall to quickly retrieve the input
that preceeded the escape character.
:p.
Sometimes you may want to enter one of the command line editing keystrokes
on the command line, instead of performing the key's usual action. For
example, suppose you have a program that requires a Ctrl-R
character on its command line. Normally you couldn't type this
keystroke at the prompt, because it would be interpreted as a
"Delete word right" command.
:p.
To get around this problem, use the special keystroke :hp2.Alt-255:ehp2.&per.
You enter Alt-255 by holding down the :hp2.Alt:ehp2. key while you type
:hp2.255:ehp2. on the numeric keypad, then releasing the :hp2.Alt:ehp2. key (you
must use the number keys on the numeric pad; the row of keys at the
top of your keyboard won't work). This forces &4OS2. to interpret
the next keystroke literally and places it on the command line,
ignoring any special meaning it would normally have as a command-line
editing or history keystroke. You can use Alt-255 to suppress
the normal meaning of command-line editing keystrokes even if they
have been reassigned with :link reftype=hd refid=INIKeyMap.key mapping directives:elink. in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink., and Alt-255 itself can be reassigned with the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_CommandEscape.CommandEscape:elink. directive.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=CmdHist.Command History and Recall
:p.
:hp2.Command History Keys&colon.:ehp2.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=16 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.&uarrow.:ehp2.:pd.Recall the previous (or most recent) command, or the
most recent command that matches a partial command line.
:pt.:hp2.&darrow.:ehp2.:pd.Recall the next (or oldest) command, or the oldest
command that matches a partial command line.
:pt.:hp2.F3:ehp2.:pd.Fill in the rest of the command line from the previous command,
beginning at the current cursor position.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-D:ehp2.:pd.Delete the currently displayed history list entry, erase
the command line, and display the previous (matching) history list entry.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-E:ehp2.:pd.Display the last entry in the history list.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-K:ehp2.:pd.Save the current command line in the history list without
executing it, and then clear the command line.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-Enter:ehp2.:pd.Copy the current command line to the end of
the history list even if it has not been altered, then execute it.
:pt.:hp2.@:ehp2.:pd.As the first character in a line&colon. Do not save the current line
in the history list when it is executed, and do not store it in the :link reftype=hd refid=CMDLINE.CMDLINE:elink.
environment variable.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
Use the :hp2.&uarrow.:ehp2. key repeatedly to scan back through the
history list. When the desired command appears, press :hp2.Enter:ehp2. to
execute it again. After you have found a command, you can edit it
before pressing :hp2.Enter:ehp2.&per.
:p.
The history list is normally "circular". If you move to the last command in
the list and then press the down arrow one more time, you'll see
the first command in the list. Similarly, if you move to the first
command in the list and then press the up arrow one more time,
you'll see the last command in the list. You can disable this feature and
make command history recall stop at the beginning or end of the list by
turning off the History Wrap selection on the
:link reftype=hd refid=CommandLine1Option.Command Line 1 page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.
dialogs, or setting :link reftype=hd refid=INI_HistWrap.Histwrap:elink. to No in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:p.
You can search the command history list to find a previous command
quickly using :hp2.command completion:ehp2.&per. Just enter the first few
characters of the command you want to find and press :hp2.&uarrow.:ehp2.&per.
You only need to enter enough characters to identify the command
that you want to find. If you press the :hp2.&uarrow.:ehp2. key a second
time, you will see the previous command that matches. The system
will beep if there are no matching commands. The search process
stops as soon as you type one of the editing keys, whether or not
the line is changed. At that point, the line you're viewing
becomes the new line to match if you press :hp2.&uarrow.:ehp2. again.
:p.
You can specify the size of the command history list on the
:link reftype=hd refid=StartupOption.Startup page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
or with the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_History.History:elink. directive in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. When the list is full, the
oldest commands are discarded to make room for new ones. You can also use the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_HistMin.HistMin:elink. directive in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. to enable or disable history
saves and to specify the shortest command line to be saved.
:p.
You can prevent any command line from being saved in the history by
beginning it with an at sign [:hp2.@:ehp2.].
:p.
When you execute a command from the history, that command remains
in the history list in its original position. The command is not
copied to the end of the list (unless you modify it). If you want
each command to be copied or moved to the end of the list when it is re-
executed, set :link reftype=hd refid=INI_HistCopy.HistCopy:elink. or
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_HistMove.HistMove:elink. to Yes in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
If you select either of these options, the list entry identified as "current"
(the entry from which commands are retrieved when you press
:hp2.&uarrow.:ehp2.) is also adjusted to refer to the end of the history
list after each recalled command is executed.
:p.
:p.
:hp2.Local and Global Command History:ehp2.
:p.
The command history can be stored in either a "local" or "global"
list.
:p.
With a local command history list, any changes made to the history will
only affect the current copy of &4OS2.. They will not be visible in
other shells, or other sessions.
:p.
With a global command history list, all copies of &4OS2. will share the same
command history, and any changes made to the history in one copy
will affect all other copies. Global lists are the default for
&4OS2..
:p.
You can control the type of command history on the
:link reftype=hd refid=StartupOption.Startup Configuration Page:elink.
of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
with the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_LocalHistory.LocalHistory:elink. directive in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink., or with the :hp2./L:ehp2. and :hp2./LH:ehp2. options
of the :link reftype=hd refid=START.START:elink. command.
:p.
There is no fixed rule for deciding whether to use a local or global
command history list. Depending upon your work style, you may find
it most convenient to use one type, or a mixture of types in
different sessions or shells. We recommend that you start with the
default setting, then modify it if you find a situation where the default is
not convenient.
:p.
If you select a global history list for &4OS2. you can share the
history among all copies of &4OS2. running in any session. When you
close all &4OS2. sessions, the memory for the global history list is
released, and a new, empty history list is created the next time
you start &4OS2..
:p.
If you want the history list to be retained in
memory even when no command processor session is running, execute the :link
reftype=hd refid=SHRALIAS.SHRALIAS:elink. command, which loads a program to
perform this service for the global command history, directory history, and
alias lists.
:p.
Whenever you start a secondary shell which uses a local history list, it
inherits a copy of the command history from the previous shell. However,
any changes to the history made in the secondary shell will affect only that
shell. If you want changes made in a secondary shell to affect the previous
shell, use a global history list in both shells.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=HistWin.Command History Window
:p.
:hp2.Command History Window Keys&colon.:ehp2.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=16 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.PgUp:ehp2.:pd.(from the command line) Open the command history window.
:pt. or :hp2.PgDn:ehp2.:pd.
:pt.:hp2.&uarrow.:ehp2.:pd.Scroll the display up one line.
:pt.:hp2.&darrow.:ehp2.:pd.Scroll the display down one line.
:pt.:hp2.:ehp2.:pd.Scroll the display left 4 columns.
:pt.:hp2.:ehp2.:pd.Scroll the display right 4 columns.
:pt.:hp2.PgUp:ehp2.:pd.(inside the window) Scroll the display up one page.
:pt.:hp2.PgDn:ehp2.:pd.(inside the window) Scroll the display down one page.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-PgUp:ehp2.:pd.Go to the beginning of the history list.
:pt. or :hp2.Home:ehp2.:pd.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-PgDn:ehp2.:pd.Go to the end of the history list.
:pt. or :hp2.End:ehp2.:pd.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-D:ehp2.:pd.Delete the selected line from the history list.
:pt.:hp2.Enter:ehp2.:pd.Execute the selected line.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-Enter:ehp2.:pd.Move the selected line to the command line for editing.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
You can view the command history in a scrollable :hp2.command
history window:ehp2., and select the command to modify or re-execute
from those displayed in the window. To activate the command
history window press :hp2.PgUp:ehp2. or :hp2.PgDn:ehp2. at the command
line. A window will appear in the upper right corner of the screen, with
the command you most recently executed marked with a highlight. (If you
just finished re-executing a command from the history, then the next command
in sequence will be highlighted.)
:p.
The display is not circular as it is at the prompt; it has a fixed beginning
and end. The :hp2.Ctrl-D:ehp2. (delete from history) key works within the
history window as it does at the command line.
:p.
Once you have selected a command in the history window, press
:hp2.Enter:ehp2. to execute it immediately, or :hp2.Ctrl-Enter:ehp2. to move
the line to the prompt for editing (you cannot edit the line directly
in the history window).
:p.
You can bring up a "filtered" history window by typing some
characters on the command line, then pressing :hp2.PgUp:ehp2. or
:hp2.PgDn:ehp2.&per. Only those commands matching the typed characters will be
displayed in the window.
:p.
See :link reftype=hd refid=Popup.Popup Windows:elink. for information on
customizing window position, size, and color.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=CmdNames.Command Names and Parameters
:p.
When you enter a command on the
:link reftype=hd refid=CommandLine.command line:elink.
you type its name at the prompt, followed by a
space and any parameters for the command. For example, all of these
could be valid commands&colon.
:xmp.
   [c&colon.\] dir
   [c&colon.\] copy file1 file2 d&colon.\
   [c&colon.\] f&colon.\util\mapmem /v
   [c&colon.\] "c&colon.\my programs\jp software\take command\tcmdos2.exe" /l
:exmp.:p.
The last three commands above include both a command name, and one or
more parameters. There are no spaces within the command name (except in
quoted filenames), but there is a space between the command name and
any parameeters, and there are spaces between the parameters.
:p.
Some commands may work when parameters are entered directly after the
command (without an intervening space, :hp1.e.g.:ehp1. :hp2.dir/p:ehp2.), or when several
parameters are entered without spaces between them (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1. :hp2.dir /2/p:ehp2.).
A very few older programs may even require this approach. However
leaving out spaces in this way is usually technically incorrect, and is
not recommended as a general practice, as it may not work for all
commands.
:p.
If the command name includes a path, the path elements must be separated with
backslashes (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1. f&colon.\util\mapmem).
If you are accustomed to UNIX syntax
where forward slashes (:hp2./:ehp2.) are used as the path element separator or
the executable you are
invoking requires forward slashes, and you want &4OS2. to
recognize this syntax, you can set :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_UnixPaths.UnixPaths:elink. to Yes in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Warning&colon.:ehp2. UNIX compatibility is not yet fully implemented.
Internal commands will interpret forward slashes in unquoted command arguments
as the switch character.
The workaround is to quote the path arguments that contain the forward slashes.
:p.
For more information on command entry see
:link reftype=hd refid=MultCmds.Multiple Commands:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=CmdLength.Command-Line Length Limits:elink.&per.
For details on how &4OS2. handles the various elements it finds on
the command line see :link reftype=hd refid=Parsing.Command Parsing:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=FileComp.Filename Completion
:p.
:hp2.Filename Completion Keys&colon.:ehp2.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=20 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.F8:ehp2.:pd.Get the previous matching filename.
:pt. or :hp2.Shift-Tab:ehp2.:pd.
:pt.:hp2.F9:ehp2.:pd.Get the next matching filename.
:pt. or :hp2.Tab:ehp2.:pd.
:pt.:hp2.F10:ehp2.:pd.Keep the current matching filename and display the next
matching name immediately after the current one.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
Filename completion can help you by filling in a complete filename
on the command line when you only remember or want to type part of the name.
For example, if you know the name of a file begins :hp1.AU:ehp1. but you
can't remember the rest of the name, type&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy au
:exmp.:p.
and then press the :hp2.Tab:ehp2. key or :hp2.F9:ehp2. key. &4OS2. will
search the current directory for filenames that begin :hp1.AU:ehp1. and
insert the first one onto the command line in place of the :hp1.AU:ehp1.
that you typed.
:p.
If this is the file that you want, simply complete the command. If
&4OS2. didn't find the file that you were looking for, press :hp2.Tab:ehp2.
or :hp2.F9:ehp2. again to substitute the next filename that begins with
:hp1.AU:ehp1.&per. When there are no more filenames that match your pattern,
the system will beep each time you press :hp2.Tab:ehp2. or :hp2.F9:ehp2.&per.
:p.
If you go past the filename that you want, press :hp2.Shift-Tab:ehp2. or
:hp2.F8:ehp2. to back up and return to the previous matching filename.
After you back up to the first filename, the system will beep each
time you press :hp2.Shift-Tab:ehp2. or :hp2.F8:ehp2.&per.
:p.
If you want to enter more than one matching filename on the same
command line, press :hp2.F10:ehp2. when each desired name appears. This
will keep that name and place the next matching filename after it
on the command line. You can then use :hp2.Tab:ehp2. (or :hp2.F9:ehp2.),
:hp2.Shift-Tab:ehp2. (or :hp2.F8:ehp2.), and :hp2.F10:ehp2. to move through
the remaining matching files.
:p.
The pattern you use for matching may contain any valid filename
characters, as well as wildcard characters and extended
:link reftype=hd refid=Wildcards.wildcards:elink.&per. For example, you can copy the first
matching :hp1..TXT:ehp1. file by typing
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy *.txt
:exmp.:p.
and then pressing :hp2.Tab:ehp2.&per.
:p.
If you don't specify part of a filename before pressing :hp2.Tab:ehp2.,
the command processor will match all files. For example, if you enter the
above command as "COPY", without the "*.TXT", and then press :hp2.Tab:ehp2.,
the first filename in the current directory is displayed. Each time you
press :hp2.Tab:ehp2. or :hp2.F9:ehp2. after that, another name from the
current directory is displayed, until all filenames have been displayed.
:p.
If you type a filename without an extension, &4OS2. will add :hp1.*.*:ehp1. to
the name (* on volumes supporting long filenames). It will also place a "*" after a partial
extension. If you are typing a group of filenames in an :link reftype=hd
refid=InclList.include list:elink., the part of the include list at the
cursor will be used as the pattern to match.
:p.
When filename completion is used at the start of the command line,
it will only match directories, executable files, and files with
executable extensions, since these are the only filenames that it
makes sense to use at the start of a command. If a directory is
found, a "\" will be appended to it to enable an
:link reftype=hd refid=AutoDir.automatic directory change:elink.&per.
:p.
:p.
:hp2.Appending Backslashes to Directory Names:ehp2.
:p.
If you set the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_AppendToDir.AppendToDir:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. directive, or the
:hp2.Add '\' to Directories:ehp2. option on the
:link reftype=hd refid=CommandLine1Option.Command Line 1 page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
&4OS2. will add a trailing backslash [:hp2.\:ehp2.] to all directory names. This
feature can be especially handy if you use filename completion to specify files
that are not in the current directory -- a succession of :hp2.Tab :ehp2.(or
:hp2.F9:ehp2.) and :hp2.F10 :ehp2.keystrokes can build a complete path to the
file you want to work with.
:p.
The following example shows the use of this technique to edit the file :hp1.
C&colon.\DATA\FINANCE\MAPS.DAT:ehp1.&per. The lines which include :hp1.<F9>:ehp1.
show where :hp2.F9:ehp2. (or :hp2.Tab:ehp2.) is pressed; the other lines
show how the command line appears after the previous :hp2.F9:ehp2. or
:hp2.Tab:ehp2. (the example is displayed on several lines here, but all
appears at a single command prompt when you actually perform the steps)&colon.
:xmp.
    1  [c&colon.\> edit \da :hp1.<F9>:ehp1.
    2  [c&colon.\> edit \data\
    3  [c&colon.\> edit \data\f :hp1.<F9>:ehp1.
    4  [c&colon.\> edit \data\frank.doc :hp1.<F9>:ehp1.
    5  [c&colon.\> edit \data\finance\
    6  [c&colon.\> edit \data\finance\map :hp1.<F9>:ehp1.
    7  [c&colon.\> edit \data\finance\maps.dat
:exmp.:p.
Note that :hp2.F9:ehp2. was pressed twice in succession on lines 3 and 4,
because the filename displayed on line 3 was not what was needed we were
looking for the FINANCE directory, which came up the second time :hp2.F9:ehp2.
was pressed. In this example, filename completion saves about half the
keystrokes that would be required to type the name in full. If you are using
long file or directory names, the savings can be much greater.
:p.
:p.
:hp2.Customizing Filename Completion:ehp2.
:p.
You can customize filename completion for any internal or external
command or alias. This allows the command processor to display filenames
intelligently based on the command you are entering. For example, you might
want to see only :hp1..TXT:ehp1. files when you use filename completion in
the EDIT command.
:p.
To customize filename completion you can use the :hp2.Options:ehp2. dialog box
on the :link reftype=hd refid=CommandLine1Option.Command Line 1 page:elink. of
the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
or set the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_FileCompletion.FileCompletion:elink.
directive manually in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. You
can also use the
:link reftype=hd refid=FILECOMPLETION.FILECOMPLETION:elink. environment
variable. If you use both, the environment variable will override the
settings in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. You may find it
useful to use the environment variable for experimenting, then create permanent
settings using the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.
or the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_FileCompletion.FileCompletion:elink. directive.
:p.
The format for both the environment variable and
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. is&colon.
:xmp.
    cmd1&colon.ext1 ext2 ...; cmd2&colon. ...
:exmp.:p.
where "cmd" is a command name and "ext" is a file extension (which may
include wildcards) or one of the following file types&colon.
:xmp.
    DIRS    Directories
    RDONLY   Read-only files
    HIDDEN   Hidden files
    SYSTEM   System files
    ARCHIVE  Files modified since the last backup
:exmp.:p.
The command name is the internal command, alias command, or executable
filename (without a path). For example, to have file completion return only
directories for the CD command and only :hp1..C:ehp1. and :hp1..ASM:ehp1.
files for B (the Boxer editor), you would use this setting for filename
completion in the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.&colon.
:xmp.
    FileCompletion=cd&colon.dirs; b&colon.c asm
:exmp.:p.
To set the same values using the environment variable, you would use this
line&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] set filecompletion=cd&colon.dirs; b&colon.c asm
:exmp.:p.
With this setting in effect, if you type "CD " and then pressed :hp2.Tab:ehp2.,
the command processor will return only directories, not files. If you type
"B " and press :hp2.Tab:ehp2., you will see only names of :hp1..C:ehp1. and
:hp1..ASM:ehp1. files.
:p.
&4OS2. does :hp2.not:ehp2. check your command line for aliases before matching
the commands for customized file completion. Instead, they ignore any path
or file extension information in the first word of the command, and then
search the :link reftype=hd refid=FILECOMPLETION.FILECOMPLETION:elink.
environment variable and the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_FileCompletion.FileCompletion:elink.
:hp1.INI:ehp1. directive to find a match that will limit the files selected
for :link reftype=hd refid=FileComp.filename completion:elink.&per.
:p.
:p.
:hp2.Filename Completion Window:ehp2.
:p.
You can also view filenames in a :hp2.filename completion window:ehp2. and
select the file you want to work with. To activate the window, press
:hp2.F7:ehp2. or :hp2.Ctrl-Tab:ehp2. at the command line. You will see a
window in the upper-right corner of the screen, with a sorted list of files
that match any partial filename you have entered on the command line. If
you haven't yet entered a filename, the window will contain the name of all
files in the current directory. You can search for a name by typing the
first few characters. (:hp2.Ctrl-Tab:ehp2. will work only if your keyboard
and keyboard driver support it. If it does not work on your system, use
:hp2.F7:ehp2. instead.)
:p.
See :link reftype=hd refid=Popup.Popup Windows:elink. for information on
customizing window position, size, and color.
:p.
:p.
:hp2.Filename Completion Window Keys&colon.:ehp2.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=20 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.F7:ehp2.:pd.(from the command line) Open the filename completion window.
:pt. or :hp2.Ctrl-Tab:ehp2.:pd.
:pt.:hp2.&uarrow.:ehp2.:pd.Scroll the display up one line.
:pt.:hp2.&darrow.:ehp2.:pd.Scroll the display down one line.
:pt.:hp2.:ehp2.:pd.Scroll the display left 4 columns.
:pt.:hp2.:ehp2.:pd.Scroll the display right 4 columns.
:pt.:hp2.PgUp:ehp2.:pd.Scroll the display up one page.
:pt.:hp2.PgDn:ehp2.:pd.Scroll the display down one page.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-PgUp:ehp2.:pd.Go to the beginning of the filename list.
:pt. or :hp2.Home:ehp2.:pd.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-PgDn:ehp2.:pd.Go to the end of the filename list.
:pt. or :hp2.End:ehp2.:pd.
:pt.:hp2.Enter:ehp2.:pd.Insert the selected filename into the command line.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=AutoDir.Automatic Directory Changes
:p.
The automatic directory change feature lets you change directories
quickly from the command prompt, without entering an explicit
:link reftype=hd refid=CD.CD:elink. or :link reftype=hd refid=CDD.CDD:elink.
command. To do so, simply type the name of the target directory at the
prompt, with a backslash [:hp2.\:ehp2.] at the end. For example&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] 4os2\
    [c&colon.\4os2]
:exmp.:p.
This can make directory changes very simple when it is combined with
:link reftype=hd refid=ExtDirSearch.Extended Directory Searches:elink.
or :link reftype=hd refid=CDPATH.CDPATH:elink.&per. If you have enabled either
of those features, the command processor will use them in searching for any
directory to which you change with an automatic directory change.
:p.
For example, suppose Extended Directory Searches are enabled, and the
directory WIN exists on drive E&colon.&per. You can change to this directory
with a single word on the command line&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\4os2] win\
    [e&colon.\win]
:exmp.:p.
(Depending upon the way Extended Directory Searches are configured, and the
number of subdirectories on your disk whose names contain the string
:hp1.WIN:ehp1., when you execute such a command you may see an immediate
change as shown above, or a popup window which contains a list of
subdirectories named :hp1.WIN:ehp1. to choose from.)
:p.
The text before the backslash can include a drive letter, a full path, a
partial path, or a UNC name. Commands like "....\" can be used to
move up the directory tree quickly (see
:link reftype=hd refid=ParDir.Extended Parent Directory
Names:elink.). Automatic directory changes save the current directory, so
it can be recalled with a "CDD -" or "CD -" command. For example, any of
the following are valid automatic directory change entries&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] d&colon.\data\finance\
    [c&colon.\] archives\
    [c&colon.\] ...\util\os2\
    [c&colon.\] \\server\vol1\george\
:exmp.:p.
The first and last examples change to the named directory. The second
changes to the :hp1.ARCHIVES:ehp1. subdirectory of the current directory, and
the third changes to the :hp1.UTIL\OS2:ehp1. subdirectory of the directory
which is two levels "up" from the current directory in the tree.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=DirHist. Directory History Window
:p.
:hp2.Directory History Window Keys&colon.:ehp2.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=16 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-PgUp:ehp2.:pd.(from the command line) Open the directory history window.
:pt. or :hp2.Ctrl-PgDn:ehp2.:pd.
:pt.:hp2.&uarrow.:ehp2.:pd.Scroll the display up one line.
:pt.:hp2.&darrow.:ehp2.:pd.Scroll the display down one line.
:pt.:hp2.:ehp2.:pd.Scroll the display left 4 columns.
:pt.:hp2.:ehp2.:pd.Scroll the display right 4 columns.
:pt.:hp2.PgUp:ehp2.:pd.Scroll the display up one page.
:pt.:hp2.PgDn:ehp2.:pd.Scroll the display down one page.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-PgUp:ehp2.:pd.Go to the beginning of the directory list.
:pt. or :hp2.Home:ehp2.:pd.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-PgDn:ehp2.:pd.Go to the end of the directory list.
:pt. or :hp2.End:ehp2.:pd.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-D:ehp2.:pd.Delete the selected line from the directory list.
:pt.:hp2.Enter:ehp2.:pd.Change to the selected drive and directory.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-Enter:ehp2.:pd.Move the selected line to the command line
for editing.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:p.
The current directory is recorded automatically in the :hp2.directory history
list:ehp2. just before each change to a new directory or drive.
:p.
You can view the directory history from a :hp2.directory history window:ehp2.
and change to any drive and directory on the list. To activate the directory
history window, press :hp2.Ctrl-PgUp:ehp2. or :hp2.Ctrl-PgDn:ehp2. at the
command line. You can then select a new directory with the :hp2.Enter:ehp2.
key.
:p.
If the directory history list becomes full, old entries are deleted to
make room for new ones. You can set the size of the list with the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_DirHistory.DirHistory:elink. directive in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. In order to conserve space, each directory name is
recorded just once in the directory history, even if you move into and out
of that directory several times. The directory history can be stored in
either a "local" or "global" list. (See :link reftype=hd
refid=GlobalDirHistory.Local and Global Directory History:elink.&per.)
:p.
When you switch directories the original directory is saved in the
directory history list, regardless of whether you change directories at the
command line, from within a batch file, or from within an alias. However,
directory changes made by external directory navigation utilities or other
external programs are not recorded by &4OS2..
:p.
See :link reftype=hd refid=Popup.Popup Windows:elink. for information on
customizing window position, size, and color.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=GlobalDirHistory.Local and Global Directory History
:p.
The directory history can be stored in either a "local" or "global"
list.
:p.
With a local directory history list, any changes made to the list will
only affect the current copy of the command processor. They will not
be visible in other shells, or other sessions.
:p.
With a global list, all copies of the command processor will share the
same directory history, and any changes made to the list in one copy
will affect all other copies.
:p.
You can control the type of directory history list on the
:link reftype=hd refid=StartupOption.Startup Configuration Page:elink.
of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
with the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_LocalDirHistory.LocalDirHistory:elink. directive
in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink., with the :hp2./L:ehp2. and :hp2./LD:ehp2.
:link reftype=hd refid=Startup.startup options:elink., and with the
:hp2./L:ehp2. and :hp2./LD:ehp2. options of the
:link reftype=hd refid=START.START:elink. command.
:p.
There is no fixed rule for deciding whether to use a local or global
directory history list. Depending upon your work style, you may find
it most convenient to use one type, or a mixture of types in
different sessions or shells. We recommend that you start with the
default setting, then modify it if you find a situation where the default is
not convenient.
:p.
If you select a global directory list, you can share the list among
all copies of the command processor running in any session. When you
close all &4OS2. sessions, the memory for the global directory history
list is released, and a new, empty list is created the next time you
start &4OS2..
:p.
If you want the list to be retained in memory even when no command processor
session is running, you need to execute the :link reftype=hd
refid=SHRALIAS.SHRALIAS:elink. command, which loads a program to perform this
service for the global command history, directory history, and alias
lists.
:p.
Whenever you start a secondary shell which uses a local directory history
list, it inherits a copy of the directory history from the previous shell.
However, any changes to the list made in the secondary shell will affect only
that shell. If you want changes made in a secondary shell to affect the
previous shell, use a global directory history list in both shells.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=MultCmds.Multiple Commands
:p.
You can type several commands on the same command line, separated by an
ampersand [:hp2.&amp.:ehp2.]. For example, if you know you want to copy
all of your :hp1..TXT:ehp1. files to drive A&colon. and then run CHKDSK to
be sure that drive A's file structure is in good shape, you could enter
the following command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy *.txt a&colon. &amp. chkdsk a&colon.
:exmp.:p.
You may put as many commands on the command line as you wish, as
long as the total length of the command line does not exceed 1023 characters.
:p.
You can use multiple commands in :link reftype=hd refid=alias.alias:elink.
definitions and :link reftype=hd refid=batch.batch files:elink. as well as
from the command line.
:p.
If you don't like using the default command separator, you can pick
another character using the :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /C command or the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_CommandSep.CommandSep:elink. directive in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. If
you plan to share aliases or batch files between &4OS2. and 4DOS,
4NT, or Take Command, see :link reftype=hd
refid=Compat.Special Character Compatibility:elink. for
details about choosing compatible command separators for two or
more products.
:p.
You can also spread long command lines across multiple lines with the
:link reftype=hd refid=Escape.escape character:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=ExpandAlias.Expanding and Disabling Aliases
:p.
A few command line options are specifically related to :link reftype=hd
refid=ALIAS.aliases:elink., and are documented briefly here for completeness.
:p.
You can expand an alias on the command line and view or edit the results by
pressing :hp2.Ctrl-F:ehp2. before the command is executed. Doing so is
especially useful when you are developing and debugging a complex alias or
if you want to make sure that an alias that you may have forgotten won't
change the intent of your command.
:p.
At times, you may want to temporarily disable an alias that you have defined.
To do so, precede the command with an asterisk [:hp2.*:ehp2.]. For example,
if you have an alias for DIR which changes the display format, you can use
the following command to bypass the alias and display the directory in the
standard format&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] *dir
:exmp.:p.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=CmdLineHelp.Command Line Help
:p.
You can start the online help system at the command line by entering
:hp2.HELP:ehp2. or :hp2.HELP:ehp2. plus a topic, or by pressing the
:hp2.F1:ehp2. key at any time.
:p.
If you have already typed part or all of a command on the line, the help
system will provide "context-sensitive" help by using the first word on the
line as a help topic. If it's a valid topic, you will see help for that
topic automatically; if not, you will see a table of contents and you can
then pick the topic you want. For example, if you press :hp2.F1:ehp2. after
entering each of the command lines shown below you will get the display
indicated&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\]         Topic list / table of contents
    [c&colon.\] copy *.* a&colon.   Help on COPY
    [c&colon.\] c&colon.\util\map   Topic list / table of contents
:exmp.:p.
For quick help you can type the name of any internal command at the prompt,
followed by a slash and a question mark [:hp2./?:ehp2.] like this&colon.
:xmp.
    copy /?
:exmp.:p.
This will show you help for the command in a "quick-reference" style (the
output can be :link reftype=hd refid=RedirPipe.redirected:elink.). The
:hp2./?:ehp2. option may not work correctly if you have redefined how the
command operates with an alias. In this case you may need to add an asterisk
to the beginning of the command to
:link reftype=hd refid=ExpandAlias.disable alias processing:elink.&colon.
:xmp.
    alias copy copy /r
    *copy /?
:exmp.:p.
:hp2./?:ehp2. will only access the help system when you use it with an
internal command. If you use it with an external command name, the external
command will be executed and will interpret the :hp2./?:ehp2. parameter
according to its own rules. Some external commands, including some external
utility programs, do display help when run with a :hp2./?:ehp2. parameter,
but this a characteristic of these commands and does not depend on the
command processor. Many other external commands do not have this feature.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=CmdLength.Command-Line Length Limits
:p.
When you first enter a command at the prompt or in an
alias or batch file, it can be up to 1,023 characters long.
:p.
As &4OS2. scans the command line and substitutes the contents of
aliases and environment variables for their names, the line usually
gets longer. This expanded line is stored in an internal buffer
which allows each individual command to grow to 1,023 characters
during the expansion process. In addition, if you have multiple commands on
a single line, during expansion the entire line can grow to as much as 4,096
characters. If your use of aliases or environment variables causes the
command line to exceed either of these limits as it is expanded, you will
see a "Command line too long" error and the remainder of the line will not be
executed.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h1 name=FileSel.File Selection
:p.
Most internal commands (like COPY, DIR, etc.) work on a file or a
group of files. Besides typing the exact name of the file you want
to work with, you can use several shorthand forms for naming or
selecting files and the applications associated with them.
:p.
Most of the features explained in this section apply to &4OS2. commands only,
and can not be used to pass filenames to external programs unless
those programs were specifically written to support these features.
:p.
The file selection features are&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=ParDir.Extended Parent Directory Names:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=Wildcards.Wildcards:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=Ranges.Date, Time, and Size Ranges:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=ExclRanges.File Exclusion Ranges:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=MultFiles.Multiple Filenames:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=InclList.Include Lists:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=ExeExt.Executable Extensions:elink.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=ParDir.Extended Parent Directory Names
:p.
&4OS2. allows you to extend the traditional syntax for
naming the parent directory, by adding additional [:hp2..:ehp2.]
characters. Each additional [:hp2..:ehp2.] represents an additional
directory level above the current directory. For example,
:hp1..\FILE.DAT:ehp1. refers to a file in the current directory,
:hp1...\FILE.DAT:ehp1. refers to a file one level up (in the parent
directory), and :hp1....\FILE.DAT:ehp1. refers to a file two levels up (in
the parent of the parent directory). If you are in the
C&colon.\DATA\FINANCE\JANUARY directory and want to copy the file
LETTERS.DAT from the directory C&colon.\DATA to drive A&colon.
:xmp.
    [C&colon.\DATA\FINANCE\JANUARY] copy ...\LETTERS.DAT A&colon.
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=Wildcards.Wildcards
:p.
Wildcards let you specify a file or group of files by typing a
partial filename. The appropriate directory is scanned to find all
of the files that match the partial name you have specified.
:p.
Wildcards are usually used to specify which files :hp2.should:ehp2. be
processed by a command. If you need to specify which files should
:hp2.not:ehp2. be processed see
:link reftype=hd refid=ExclRanges.File Exclusion Ranges:elink. (for internal
commands), or :link reftype=hd refid=EXCEPT.EXCEPT:elink. (for external
commands).
:p.
Most internal commands accept filenames with wildcards anywhere that a full
filename can be used. There are two wildcard characters, the asterisk
[:hp2.*:ehp2.] and the question mark [:hp2.?:ehp2.], plus a special method
of specifying a range of permissible characters.
:p.
An asterisk [:hp2.*:ehp2.] in a filename means "any zero or more
characters in this position." For example, this command will
display a list of all files in the current directory&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir *.*
:exmp.:p.
If you want to see all of the files with a :hp1..TXT:ehp1. extension, you
could type this&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir *.txt
:exmp.:p.
If you know that the file you are looking for has a base name that
begins with :hp1.ST:ehp1. and an extension that begins with :hp1..D:ehp1., you
can find it this way. Filenames such as :hp1.STATE.DAT:ehp1.,
:hp1.STEVEN.DOC:ehp1., and :hp1.ST.D:ehp1. will all be displayed&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir st*.d*
:exmp.:p.
With &4OS2., you can also use the asterisk to match filenames with
specific letters somewhere inside the name. The following example
will display any file with a :hp1..TXT:ehp1. extension that has the
letters :hp1.AM:ehp1. together anywhere inside its base name. It will,
for example, display :hp1.AMPLE.TXT:ehp1., :hp1.STAMP:ehp1.&per.:hp1.TXT:ehp1.,
:hp1.CLAM:ehp1.&per.:hp1.TXT:ehp1., and :hp1.AM.TXT:ehp1.&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir *am*.txt
:exmp.:p.
A question mark [:hp2.?:ehp2.] matches any single filename character. You
can put the question mark anywhere in a filename and use as many
question marks as you need. The following example will display
files with names like :hp1.LETTER.DOC:ehp1. and :hp1.LATTER.DAT:ehp1., and
:hp1.LITTER.DU:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir l?tter.d??
:exmp.:p.
The use of an asterisk wildcard before other characters, and of the
character ranges discussed below, are enhancements to the standard
wildcard syntax, and may not work properly with software
other than &4OS2. and Take Command.
:p.
"Extra" question marks in your wildcard specification are ignored
if the filename is shorter than the wildcard specification. For
example, if you have files called :hp1.LETTER.DOC:ehp1.,:hp1. LETTER1.DOC:ehp1.,
and :hp1.LETTERA.DOC:ehp1., this command will display all three names&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir letter?.doc
:exmp.:p.
The file :hp1.LETTER.DOC:ehp1. is included in the display because the
"extra" question mark at the end of ":hp1.LETTER?:ehp1. " is ignored when
matching the shorter name :hp1.LETTER:ehp1.&per.
:p.
In some cases, the question mark wildcard may be too general. You
can also specify what characters you want to accept (or exclude) in
a particular position in the filename by using square brackets.
Inside the brackets, you can put the individual acceptable
characters or ranges of characters. For example, if you wanted to
match :hp1.LETTER0.DOC:ehp1. through :hp1.LETTER9.DOC:ehp1., you could use this
command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir letter[0-9].doc
:exmp.:p.
You could find all files that have a vowel as the second letter in
their name this way. This example also demonstrates how to mix the
wildcard characters&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir ?[aeiouy]*.*
:exmp.:p.
You can exclude a group of characters or a range of characters by
using an exclamation mark [:hp2.!:ehp2.] as the first character inside the
brackets. This example displays all filenames that are at least 2
characters long :hp2.except:ehp2. those which have a vowel as the second
letter in their names&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir ?[!aeiouy]*.*
:exmp.:p.
The next example, which selects files such as :hp1.AIP:ehp1.,:hp1. BIP:ehp1., and
:hp1.TIP:ehp1. but not :hp1.NIP:ehp1., demonstrates how you can use multiple
ranges inside the brackets. It will accept a file that begins with
an :hp2.A:ehp2., :hp2.B:ehp2., :hp2.C:ehp2., :hp2.D:ehp2., :hp2.T:ehp2., :hp2.U:ehp2., or :hp2.V:ehp2.&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir [a-dt-v]ip
:exmp.:p.
You may use a question mark character inside the brackets, but its
meaning is slightly different than a normal (unbracketed) question
mark wildcard. A normal question mark wildcard matches any
character, but will be ignored when matching a name shorter than
the wildcard specification, as described above. A question mark
inside brackets will match any character, but will :hp2.not:ehp2. be
discarded when matching shorter filenames. For example&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir letter[?].doc
:exmp.:p.
will display :hp1.LETTER1.DOC:ehp1. and :hp1.LETTERA.DOC:ehp1., but not
:hp1.LETTER.DOC.:ehp1.
:p.
A pair of brackets with no characters between them [], or an
exclamation point and question mark together [:hp2.!?:ehp2.], will match only if
there is no character in that position. For example,
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir letter[].doc
:exmp.:p.
will not display LETTER1.DOC or LETTERA.DOC, but will display
LETTER.DOC. This is most useful for commands like
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir /I"[]" *.btm
:exmp.:p.
which will display a list of all .BTM files which don't have a
description, because the empty brackets match only an empty description
string (DIR /I selects files to display based on their descriptions).
:p.
You can repeat any of the wildcard characters in any combination
you desire within a single filename. For example, the following
command lists all files which have an :hp2.A:ehp2., :hp2.B:ehp2., or :hp2.C:ehp2. as the
third character, followed by zero or more additional characters,
followed by a :hp2.D:ehp2., :hp2.E:ehp2., or :hp2.F:ehp2., followed optionally by some
additional characters, and with an extension beginning with :hp2.P:ehp2.
or :hp2.Q:ehp2.&per. You probably won't need to do anything this complex, but
we've included it to show you the flexibility of extended
wildcards&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir ??[abc]*[def]*.[pq]*
:exmp.:p.
You can also use the square bracket wildcard syntax to work around
a conflict between long filenames containing semicolons [:hp2.;:ehp2.],
and the use of a semicolon to indicate an
:link reftype=hd refid=InclList.include list:elink.&per.
For example, if you have a file on a volume supporting long filenames
named :hp1.C&colon.\DATA\LETTER1;V2:ehp1. and you enter this command&colon.

:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] del \data\letter1;v2
:exmp.:p.

you will not get the results you expect. Instead of deleting the
named file, &4OS2. will attempt to delete :hp1.LETTER1:ehp1. and then
:hp1.V2:ehp1., because the semicolon indicates an
:link reftype=hd refid=InclList.include list:elink.&per. However
if you use square brackets around the semicolon it will be
interpreted as a filename character, and not as an include list
separator. For example, this command would delete
the filenamed above&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] del \data\letter1[;]v2
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 nosearch name=TOC_Ranges.Ranges
:p.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=Ranges.Date, Time, and Size Ranges:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=ExclRanges.File Exclusion Ranges:elink.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=Ranges.Date, Time, and Size Ranges
:p.
Most internal commands which accept wildcards also allow date,
time, and size ranges to further define the files that you wish to
work with. &4OS2. will examine each file's size and timestamp (a
record of when the file was created, last modified, or last accessed)
to determine if the file meets the range criteria you have specified.
:p.
(&4OS2. also supports :link reftype=hd refid=ExclRanges.File Exclusion
Ranges:elink. to exclude files from a command. These are similar to date,
time, and size ranges, but have a slightly different purpose and therefore
are documented separately.)
:p.
A range begins with the switch character (:hp2./:ehp2.),
followed by a left square bracket (":hp2.[:ehp2.") and a character that
specifies the range type&colon. "s" for a size range, "d" for a date
range, or "t" for a time range. The "s", "d", or "t" is followed
by a start value, and an optional comma and end value. The range
ends with a right square bracket (":hp2.]:ehp2."). For example, to select
files between 100 and 200 bytes long you could use the range
:hp2./[s100,200]:ehp2.&per.
:p.
All ranges are inclusive. For example, a size range which selects files from
10,000 to 20,000 bytes long will match files that are exactly 10,000 bytes and
20,000 bytes long, as well as all sizes in between; a date range that selects
files last modified between 10-27-17 and 10-30-17 will include files modified
on each of those dates, and on the two days in between.
:p.
If you reverse range start and end values the command processor will recognize
the reversal, and will use the second (lower) value as the start point of the
range and the first (higher) value as its end point.  For example, the range
above for files between 100 and 200 bytes long could also be entered as
:hp2./[s200,100]:ehp2.&per.
:p.
See the individual range types for details on specifying ranges&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=DateRanges.Date Ranges:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=TimeRanges.Time Ranges:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=SizeRanges.Size Ranges:elink.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:p.
:hp2.Using Ranges:ehp2.
:p.
If you combine two types of ranges, a file must satisfy both ranges
to be included. For example, :hp2./[d2-8-17,2-9-17] /[s1024,2048]:ehp2.
means files last modified between February 8 and February 9, 2017,
which are also between 1,024 and 2,048 bytes long.
:p.
When you use a date, time, or size range in a command, it should
immediately follow the command name. Unlike some command switches
which apply to only part of the command line, the range usually
applies to all filenames specified for the command. Any
exceptions are noted in the descriptions of individual commands.
:p.
For example, to get a directory of all the :hp1.*.C:ehp1. files dated
October 1, 2017, you could use this command&colon.

:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir /[d10-1-17,+0] *.c
:exmp.

To delete all of the 0-byte files on your hard disk, you could use
this command&colon.

:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] del /[s0,0] *.* /s
:exmp.

And to copy all of the non-zero byte files that you changed
yesterday or today to your floppy disk, you can use this command&colon.

:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy /[d-1] /[s1] *.* a&colon.
:exmp.

The HPFS, JFS, and FAT32 filesystems maintain three sets of dates and times for
each file&colon. :hp1.creation:ehp1., :hp1.last access:ehp1., and
:hp1.last write:ehp1.&per. By default, date and time ranges work with the last
write timestamp. You can use the :hp1.last access:ehp1. (a) or
:hp1.created:ehp1. (c) time stamp in a date or time range with the syntax&colon.

:xmp.
    /[da...] or /[dc...] or /[ta...] or /[tc...]
:exmp.

For example, to select files that were last accessed yesterday or today:

:xmp.
    /[da-1]
:exmp.

Date, time, and size ranges can be used with the
:link reftype=hd refid=ATTRIB.ATTRIB:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=COPY.COPY:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=DEL.DEL:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=DESCRIBE.DESCRIBE:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=DIR.DIR:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=EXCEPT.EXCEPT:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=FFIND.FFIND:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=FOR.FOR:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=MOVE.MOVE:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=RD.RD:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=REN.REN:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=TYPE.TYPE:elink. commands. They cannot be used with
:link reftype=hd refid=FileComp.filename completion:elink. or in filename arguments for variable functions.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=DateRanges.Date Ranges
:p.
Date ranges select files that were created or last modified at any
time between the two dates. For example, :hp2./[d12-1-17,12-5-17]:ehp2.
selects files that were last modified between December 1, 2017, and
December 5, 2017.
:p.
The time for the starting date defaults to 00&colon.00&colon.00 and the time
for the ending date defaults to 23&colon.59&colon.59. You can alter these
defaults, if you wish, by including a start and stop time inside
the date range. The time is separated from the date with an at
sign [:hp2.@:ehp2.]. For example, the range
:hp2./[d7-1-17@8&colon.00a,7-3-17@6&colon.00p]:ehp2. selects files that were modified
at any time between 8&colon.00 am on July 1, 2017 and 6&colon.00 pm on July 3,
2017. If you prefer, you can specify the times in 24-hour format
(:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., @18&colon.00 for the end time in the previous example).
:p.
If you omit the second argument in a date range, &4OS2. substitutes
the current date and time. For example, :hp2./[d10-1-17]:ehp2. selects
files dated between October 1, 2017 and today.
:p.
You can use an offset value for either the beginning or ending
date, or both. An offset begins with a plus sign [:hp2.+:ehp2.] or a
minus sign [:hp2.-:ehp2.] followed by an integer. If you use an offset
for the second value, it is calculated relative to the first. If
you use an offset for the first (or only) value, the current date
is used as the basis for calculation. For example&colon.

:xmp.
    Specification    Selects Files

    /[d10-27-17,+3]   modified between 10-27-17 and 10-30-17
    /[d10-27-17,-3]   modified between 10-24-17 and 10-27-17
    /[d-0]       modified today (from today minus zero days, to today)
    /[d-1]       modified yesterday or today (from today minus one day,
              to today)
    /[d-1,+0]      modified yesterday (from today minus one day, to zero
              days after that)
:exmp.

As a shorthand way of specifying files modified today, you can also use
:hp2./[d]:ehp2.; this has the same effect as the :hp2./[d-0]:ehp2.
example shown above.
:p.
To select files last modified :hp2.n:ehp2. days ago or earlier, use
:hp2./[dn,1/1/80]:ehp2.&per. For example, to get a directory of all files last
modified 3 days or more before today (:hp1.i.e.:ehp1., those files
:hp2.not:ehp2. modified within the last 3 days), you could use this
command&colon.

:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir /[d-3,1/1/80]
:exmp.

This reversed date range (with the later date given first) will be handled
correctly by &4OS2.. It takes advantage of the facts that an offset in the
:hp2.start :ehp2.date is relative to today, and that the base or "zero"
point for PC file dates is January 1, 1980.
:p.
You cannot use offsets in the time portion of a date range (the
part after an at sign), but you can combine a time with a date
offset. For example, :hp2./[d12-8-17@12&colon.00,+2@12&colon.00]:ehp2.
selects files that were last modified between noon on December 8 and noon on
December 10, 2017. Similarly, :hp2./[d-2@15&colon.00,+1]:ehp2. selects files
last modified between 3&colon.00 pm the day before yesterday and the end
of the day one day after that, :hp1.i.e.:ehp1., yesterday. The second
time defaults to the end of the day because no time is given.
:p.
The HPFS, JFS, and FAT32 filesystems maintain three sets of dates and times for
each file&colon. :hp1.creation:ehp1., :hp1.last access:ehp1., and
:hp1.last write:ehp1.&per. By default, date and time ranges work with the last
write timestamp. You can use the :hp1.last access:ehp1. (a) or
:hp1.created:ehp1. (c) time stamp in a date or time range with the syntax&colon.

:xmp.
    /[da...] or /[dc...]
:exmp.

For example, to select files that were last accessed yesterday or
today&colon.

:xmp.
    /[da-1]
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=TimeRanges.Time Ranges
:p.
A time range specifies a file modification time without reference
to the date. For example, to select files modified between noon
and 2&colon.00 pm on any date, use
:hp2./[t12&colon.00p,2&colon.00p]:ehp2.&per. The times in a
time range can either be in 12-hour format, with a trailing "a" for
AM or "p" for PM, or in 24-hour format.
:p.
If you omit the second argument in a time range, you will select
files that were modified between the first time and the current
time, on any date. You can also use offsets, beginning with a plus
sign [:hp2.+:ehp2.] or a minus sign [:hp2.-:ehp2.] for either or both of the
arguments in a time range. The offset values are interpreted as
minutes. Some examples&colon.

:xmp.
    Specification    Selects Files

    /[t12&colon.00p,+120]   modified between noon and 2&colon.00 PM on any date
    /[t-120,+120]    modified between two hours ago and the
              current time on any date
    /[t0&colon.00,11&colon.59]   modified in the morning on any date
:exmp.

The HPFS, JFS, and FAT32 filesystems maintain three sets of dates and times for
each file&colon. :hp1.creation:ehp1., :hp1.last access:ehp1., and
:hp1.last write:ehp1.&per. By default, date and time ranges work with the last
write timestamp. You can use the :hp1.last access:ehp1. (a) or
:hp1.created:ehp1. (c) time stamp in a date or time range with the syntax&colon.

:xmp.
    /[ta...] or /[tc...]
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=SizeRanges.Size Ranges
:p.
Size ranges simply select files whose size is between the limits
given. For example, :hp2./[s10000,20000]:ehp2. selects files between
10,000 and 20,000 bytes long.
:p.
Either or both values in a size range can end with "k" to indicate
thousands of bytes, "K" to indicate kilobytes (1,024 bytes), "m" to
indicate millions of bytes, or "M" to indicate megabytes (1,048,576
bytes). For example, the range above could be rewritten as
:hp2./[s10k,20k]:ehp2.&per.
:p.
All ranges are inclusive. Both examples above will match files
that are exactly 10,000 bytes and 20,000 bytes long, as well as all
sizes in between.
:p.
The second argument of a size range is optional. If you use a
single argument, like :hp2./[s10k]:ehp2., you will select files of that
size or larger. You can also precede the second argument with a
plus sign [:hp2.+:ehp2.]; when you do, it is added to the first value to
determine the largest file size to include in the search. For
example, :hp2./[s10k,+1k]:ehp2. select files from 10,000 through 11,000
bytes in size.
:p.
Some further examples of size ranges&colon.
:xmp.
    Specification    Selects Files

    /[s0,0]       of length zero (empty)
    /[s1M]       1 megabyte or more in length
    /[s10k,+200]    between 10,000 and 10,200 bytes
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=ExclRanges.File Exclusion Ranges
:p.
Most internal commands which accept wildcards also accept file exclusion
ranges to further define the files that you wish to work with. &4OS2.
examines each filename and excludes files that match the names you have
specified in a file exclusion range.
:p.
A file exclusion range begins with the switch character (usually a slash),
followed by a left square bracket and an exclamation mark
(":hp2.[!:ehp2.") The range ends with a right square bracket
(":hp2.]:ehp2.").
:p.
Inside the brackets, you can list one or more filenames to be excluded from
the command. The filenames can include wildcards and extended wildcards,
but cannot include path names or drive letters.
:p.
The following example will display all files in the current directory except
backup files (files with the extension .BAK or .BKP)&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir /[!*.bak *.bkp] *.*
:exmp.:p.
You can combine file exclusion ranges with :link reftype=hd
refid=Ranges.date, time, and size ranges:elink. This example displays all
files that are 10K bytes or larger in size and that were created in the last
7 days, except :hp1..C:ehp1. and :hp1..H:ehp1. files&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir /[s10k] /[d-7] /[!*.c *.h] *.*
:exmp.:p.
File exclusion ranges will only work for &4OS2. internal commands. The
:link reftype=hd refid=EXCEPT.EXCEPT:elink. command can be used to exclude
files from processing by many external commands.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=MultFiles.Multiple Filenames
:p.
Most file processing commands can work with multiple files at one
time. To use multiple filenames, you simply list the files one
after another on the command line, separated by spaces. You can
use wildcards in any or all of the filenames. For example, to copy
all :hp1..TXT:ehp1. and :hp1..DOC:ehp1. files from the current directory to
drive A, you could use this command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy *.txt *.doc a&colon.
:exmp.:p.
If the files you want to work with are not in the default
directory, you must include the full path with each filename&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy a&colon.\details\file1.txt a&colon.\details\file1.doc c&colon.
:exmp.:p.
Multiple filenames are handy when you want to work with a group of
files which cannot be defined with a single filename and wildcards. They
let you be very specific about which files you want to work
with in a command.
:p.
When you use multiple filenames with a command that expects both
a source and a destination, like COPY or MOVE, :hp8.be sure that you
always include a specific destination on the command line:ehp8.&per. If you
don't, the command will assume that the last filename is the
destination and may overwrite important files.
:p.
Like :link reftype=hd refid=Wildcards.extended wildcards:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=InclList.include lists:elink., multiple filenames
will work with internal commands but not with
external programs, unless those programs have been written to
handle multiple filenames on the command line.
:p.
If you have a list of files to process that's too long to put on
the command line or too time-consuming to type, see
:link reftype=hd refid=FOR.FOR:elink. or
:link reftype=hd refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink. for another way of
passing multiple filenames to a command.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=InclList.Include Lists
:p.
Any internal command that accepts :link reftype=hd refid=MultFiles.multiple filenames:elink.
will also accept one or more include lists. An include list is
simply a group of filenames, with or without wildcards, separated
by semicolons [:hp2.;:ehp2.]. All files in the include list must be in
the same directory. You may not add a space on either side of the
semicolon.
:p.
For example, you can shorten this command which uses multiple filenames&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy a&colon.\details\file1.txt a&colon.\details\file1.doc c&colon.
:exmp.:p.
to this using an include list&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy a&colon.\details\file1.txt;file1.doc c&colon.
:exmp.:p.
Include lists are similar to multiple filenames, but have three important
differences. First, you don't have to repeat the path to your files if you
use an include list, because all of the included files must be in the same
directory. Second, if you use include lists, you aren't as likely to
accidentally overwrite files if you forget a destination path for commands
like :link reftype=hd refid=COPY.COPY:elink., because the last name in the
list will be part of the include list, and won't be seen as the destination
filename. (Include lists can only be used as the :hp1.source:ehp1.
parameter - the location files are coming from - for COPY and other similar
commands. They cannot be used to specify a destination for files.)
:p.
Third, multiple filenames and include lists are processed
differently by the :link reftype=hd refid=DIR.DIR:elink. and :link reftype=hd refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink. commands.
If you use multiple filenames, all of the files matching the first
filename are processed, then all of the files matching the second
name, and so on. When you use an include list, all files that
match any entry in the include list are processed together, and
will appear together in the directory display or SELECT list. You
can see this difference clearly if you experiment with both
techniques and the DIR command. For example&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir *.txt *.doc
:exmp.:p.
will list all the :hp1..TXT:ehp1. files with a directory header, the file
list, and a summary of the total number of files and bytes used. Then
it will do the same for the :hp1..DOC:ehp1. files. However,
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir *.txt;*.doc
:exmp.:p.
will display all the files in one list.
:p.

Like :link reftype=hd refid=Wildcards.extended wildcards:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=MultFiles.multiple filenames:elink., the
include list feature will work with internal commands, but not with
external programs (unless they have been programmed especially to
support them). The maximum length of an include list is 260 characters.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=ExeExt.Executable Extensions
:p.
The syntax for creating an executable extension is&colon.
:xmp.
    set .ext=command [options]
:exmp.:p.
This tells &4OS2. to run the specified command whenever you name
a file with the extension :hp2..ext:ehp2. at the prompt.
:p.
:hp1..EXT:ehp1. is the executable file extension; :hp1.command:ehp1. is the
name of the internal command, external program, alias, or batch
file to run; and :hp1.[options]:ehp1. are any command-line startup options
you want to specify for the program, batch file, or alias.
:p.
Normally, when you type a filename (as opposed to an alias or
internal command name) as the first word on the command line, &4OS2.
looks for a file with that name to execute. The file's extension
may be :hp1..EXE:ehp1. or :hp1..COM:ehp1. to indicate that it contains a
program, it may have a batch file extension like :hp1..BTM:ehp1., or the
file's contents may indicate that it is executable. (To change the
default list of extensions see the :link reftype=hd
refid=PATHEXT.PATHEXT:elink. environment variable and the :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_PathExt.PathExt:elink. setting in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.)
:p.
You can add to the default list of extensions, and have &4OS2. take
the action you want with files that are not executable programs or
batch files. The action taken is always based on the file's
extension. For example, you could start your text editor whenever
you type the name of a :hp1..DOC:ehp1. file, or start your database
manager whenever you type the name of a :hp1..DAT:ehp1. file.
:p.
You can use environment variables to define the internal command, external
program, batch file, or alias to run for each defined file
extension. To create an executable extension, use the :link reftype=hd refid=SET.SET:elink.
command to create a new environment variable. An environment
variable is recognized as an executable extension if its name
begins with a period.
:p.
For example, if you want to run a word processor called :hp1.EDITOR:ehp1.
whenever you type the name of a file that has an extension of
:hp1..EDT:ehp1., you could use this command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] set .edt=c&colon.\edit\editor.exe
:exmp.:p.
If the command specified in an executable extension is a batch file or
external program, &4OS2. will search the PATH for it if necessary. However,
you can make sure that the correct program or batch file is used, and
speed up the executable extension, by specifying the full name including
drive, path, filename, and extension.
:p.
Once an executable extension is defined, any time you name a file
with that extension the corresponding program, batch file, or alias
is started, with the name of your file passed to it as a parameter.
:p.
The following example defines :hp1.B.EXE:ehp1. (the Boxer text editor)
as the processor for :hp1..MAK:ehp1. files&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] set .mak=c&colon.\boxer\b.exe -s
:exmp.:p.
With this definition, if you have a file named :hp1.INIT.MAK:ehp1. in
the current directory and enter the command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\source] init
:exmp.:p.
&4OS2. will execute the command&colon.
:xmp.
    c&colon.\boxer\b.exe -s c&colon.\source\init.mak
:exmp.:p.
Notice that the full pathname of :hp1.INIT.MAK:ehp1. is automatically
included. If you enter parameters on the command line, they are appended
to the end of the command. For example, if you changed the above entry
to&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\source] init -w
:exmp.:p.
the command processor would execute the command&colon.
:xmp.
    c&colon.\boxer\b.exe -s c&colon.\source\init.mak -w
:exmp.:p.
In order for executable extensions to work, the command, program,
batch file, or alias must be able to interpret the command line
properly. For example, if a program you want to run doesn't accept
a filename on its command line as shown in these examples, then
executable extensions won't work with that program.
:p.
Executable extensions may include
:link reftype=hd refid=Wildcards.wildcards:elink., so you could, for
example, run your text editor for any file with an extension
beginning with :hp2.T:ehp2. by defining an executable extension called
:hp1..T*:ehp1.&per. Extended wildcards (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., :hp2.DO[CT]:ehp2.
for .DOC and .DOT files) may also be used.
:p.
The search for executable files starts in the current directory, then
proceeds to each subdirectory specified by the
:link reftype=hd refid=PATH_Var.PATH:elink. environment variable
(if a "." is used in the PATH the current directory is :hp2.not:ehp2.
searched first; see the :link reftype=hd refid=PATH.PATH:elink.
command for details).
:p.
You may need to take this search order into account when using executable
extensions. Using the :hp1..MAK:ehp1. example above, if you had a file named
:hp1.FORMAT.MAK:ehp1. in the current directory and entered the command
FORMAT A&colon., your command would run the Boxer editor specified by the
executable extension, instead of finding the standard OS/2 FORMAT command as
you perhaps intended. You can get around this by remembering that the OS/2
FORMAT command is in the file :hp1.FORMAT.COM:ehp1.&per. If you entered the
command FORMAT.COM A&colon. then the :hp1..MAK:ehp1. executable extension
would not be checked, and the search would continue until it found the
:hp1.FORMAT.COM:ehp1. file.
:p.
To remove an executable extension, use the :link reftype=hd
refid=UNSET.UNSET:elink. command to remove the corresponding variable.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h1 name=DirNav.Directory Navigation
:p.
The operating system and command processor remember both a :hp2.current:ehp2.
or :hp2.default drive:ehp2. for your system as a whole, and a
:hp2.current:ehp2. or :hp2.default directory:ehp2. for every drive in your
system. The current directory on the current drive is sometimes called the
:hp2.current working directory:ehp2.&per.
:p.
With traditional command processors, you change the current drive by typing
the new drive letter plus a colon at the prompt, and you change the current
working directory with the CD command. &4OS2. supports those standard
features, and offer a number of enhancements to make directory navigation
much simpler and faster.
:p.
The &4OS2. directory navigation features are in three groups&colon. features
which help the command processor find the directory you want, methods for
initiating a directory change with a minimal amount of typing, and methods
for returning easily to directories you've recently used. Each group is
summarized below.
:p.
:p.
:hp2.Finding Directories:ehp2.
:p.
Traditional command processors require you to explicitly type the name of the
directory to which you want to change. &4OS2. support this method, and also offer
two significant enhancements&colon.
:p.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.*:pd.:hp2.:link reftype=hd refid=ExtDirSearch.Extended Directory
Searches:elink.:ehp2. allow the command processor to search a "database" of
all the directories on your system to find the one you want.
:pt.*:pd.The :hp2.:link reftype=hd refid=CDPATH.CDPATH:elink.:ehp2. allows
you to enter a specific list of directories to be searched, rather than
searching a database. Use CDPATH instead of Extended Directory Searches if
you find the extended searches too broad, or your hard drive has too many
directories for an efficient search.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:p.
:hp2.Initiating a Directory Change:ehp2.
:p.
&4OS2. supports the traditional methods of changing directories, and also
offers several more flexible approaches&colon.
:p.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.*:pd.:hp2.:link reftype=hd refid=AutoDir. Automatic directory changes:elink.:ehp2.
allow you to type a directory name at the prompt and switch to it
automatically, without typing an explicit CD or similar command.
:pt.*:pd.The :hp2.:link reftype=hd refid=CD.CD:elink. command:ehp2. can
change directories on a single drive, and can return to the most recently
used directory.
:pt.*:pd.The :hp2.:link reftype=hd refid=CDD.CDD:elink. command:ehp2. changes
drive and directory at the same time, and can return to the most recently
used drive and directory.
:pt.*:pd.The :hp2.:link reftype=hd refid=PUSHD.PUSHD:elink. command:ehp2.
changes changes the drive and directory like CDD, and records the previous
directory in a directory "stack." You can view the stack with
:link reftype=hd refid=DIRS.DIRS:elink. and return to the directory on the
top of the stack with :link reftype=hd refid=POPD.POPD:elink.&per.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:p.
CDD, PUSHD, and automatic directory changes can also change to a network
drive and directory mapped to a drive letter or specified with a UNC name
(see :link reftype=hd refid=Filesys.Filesystems:elink. for more information
about network directories).
:p.
:p.
:hp2. Returning to a Previous Directory:ehp2.
:p.
Traditional command processors do not remember previously-used directories,
and can only "return" to a directory by changing back to it with a standard
drive change or CD command. &4OS2. supports three additional methods for
returning to a previous directory&colon.
:p.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.*:pd.The :hp2.:link reftype=hd refid=CD.CD -:elink.:ehp2. and
:hp2.:link reftype=hd refid=CDD.CDD -:elink.:ehp2. commands can be used
to return to the previous working directory (the one you used immediately
before the current directory). Use these commands if you are working in two
directories and alternating between them.
:pt.*:pd.The :hp2.:link reftype=hd refid=DirHist.directory history window:elink.:ehp2.
allows you to select one of several recently-used directories from a popup
list and return to it immediately. The window displays the contents of the
directory history list.
:pt.*:pd.The :hp2.:link reftype=hd refid=POPD.POPD:elink. command:ehp2. will
return to the last directory saved by :link reftype=hd refid=PUSHD.PUSHD:elink.&per.
The directory stack holds 511 characters, enough for 20 to 40 typical drive
and directory entries.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=ExtDirSearch.Extended Directory Searches
:p.
When you change directories with an
:link reftype=hd refid=AutoDir.automatic directory change:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=CD.CD:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=CDD.CDD:elink., or
:link reftype=hd refid=PUSHD.PUSHD:elink. command, &4OS2. must find the
target directory. To do so, the command processor first uses
the traditional method to find a new directory&colon. it checks to see
whether you have specified either the name of an existing subdirectory below
the current directory, or the name of an existing directory with a full path
or a drive letter. If you have, the command processor changes to that
directory, and does no further searching.
:p.
This traditional search method requires that you navigate manually through
the directory tree, and type the entire name of each directory to which you want
to change. Extended Directory Searches speed up the navigation process
dramatically by allowing the command processor to find the directory you
want, even if you only enter a small part of its name.
:p.
When the traditional search method fails, &4OS2. try to find the directory you
requested via the :link reftype=hd refid=CDPATH.CDPATH:elink., then via an
Extended Directory Search. This section covers only Extended Directory
Searches, which are more flexible and more commonly used than CDPATH.
:p.
Extended Directory Searches use a database of directory names to facilitate
changing to the correct directory. The database is used only if Extended
Directory Searches are enabled, and if the explicit directory search and
CDPATH search fail to find the directory you requested.
:p.
An extended directory search automatically finds the correct path to the
requested directory and changes to it if that directory exists in your
directory database. If more than one directory in the database matches the
name you have typed, a popup window appears and you can choose the directory
you want.
:p.
You can control the color, position and size of the popup directory search
window from the
:link reftype=hd refid=CommandLine2Option.Command Line 2 page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
or with directives in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink., including
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_CDDWinLeft.CDDWinLeft, CDDWinTop, CDDWinWidth,
and CDDWinHeight:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_CDDWinColors.CDDWinColors:elink.&per. You can also
change the keys used in the popup window with :link reftype=hd
refid=INIKeyMap.key mapping directives:elink. in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:p.
To use extended directory searches, you must explicitly enable them and also
create the directory database.
:p.
:p.
:hp2.The Extended Search Database:ehp2.
:p.
To create or update the database of directory names, use the
:link reftype=hd refid=CDD.CDD:elink. /S command. When you create the
database with CDD /S, you can specify which drives should be included. If
you enable Extended Directory Searches and do not create the database, it
will be created automatically the first time it is required, and will include
all local hard drives.
:p.
The database is stored in the file :hp1.JPSTREE.IDX:ehp1., which is placed in
the &4OS2. installation directory by default or in the root of the boot volume.
The same tree file is used by all JP Software command processors. You can
specify a different location for this file on the
:link reftype=hd refid=CommandLine2Option.Command Line 2 page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
or with the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_TreePath.TreePath:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. directive. If you plan on using
multiple &4OS2. and/or 4DOS, 4NT, or Take Command installations on your computer
and want to have different drives stored in the database for each, use the
dialogs or the TreePath directive to place their database directories in
different locations.
:p.
If you use an internal &4OS2. command to create or delete a directory, the
directory database is automatically updated to reflect the change to your
directory structure. The updates occur if the command processor can find the
:hp1.JPSTREE.IDX:ehp1. file in the &4OS2. installation directory, the root of the
boot volume, or in the location specified by the TreePath
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. directive.
:p.
The internal commands which can modify the directory structure and cause
automatic updates of the file are :link reftype=hd refid=MD.MD:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=RD.RD:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=COPY.COPY /S:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=DEL.DEL /X:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=MOVE.MOVE /S:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=REN.REN:elink.&per.
The :hp2.MD /N:ehp2. command can be used to create a directory without
updating the directory database. This is useful when creating a temporary
directory which you do not want to appear in the database.
:p.
:p.
:hp2.Enabling Extended Searches:ehp2.
:p.
To enable extended directory searches and control their operation, you must
set the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_FuzzyCD.FuzzyCD:elink. directive
in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. You can set FuzzyCD with
the Search Level option on the
:link reftype=hd refid=CommandLine2Option.Command Line 2 page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
or by editing :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. manually.
:p.
:lm margin=8.
If :hp2.FuzzyCD = 0:ehp2., extended searches are disabled, the
:hp1.JPSTREE:ehp1. database is ignored, and :hp2.CD:ehp2., :hp2.CDD:ehp2.,
:hp2.PUSHD:ehp2., and automatic directory changes search for directories
using only explicit names and CDPATH. This is the default.
:p.
If :hp2.FuzzyCD = 1:ehp2. and an extended search is required, then the
command processor will search the :hp1.JPSTREE:ehp1. database for directory
names which :hp2.exactly match:ehp2. the name you specified.
:p.
If :hp2.FuzzyCD = 2:ehp2. and an extended search is required, the command
processor will search the database for exact matches first, just as when
FuzzyCD = 1. If the requested directory is not found, it will search the
database a second time looking for directory names that :hp2.begin with:ehp2.
the name you specified.
:p.
If :hp2.FuzzyCD = 3:ehp2. and an extended search is required, the command
processor will search the database for exact matches first, just as when
FuzzyCD = 1. If the requested directory is not found, it will search the
database a second time looking for directory names that :hp2.contain:ehp2.
the name you specified anywhere within them.
:lm margin=1.
:p.
For example, suppose that you have a directory called
:hp1.C&colon.\DATA\MYDIR:ehp1., CDPATH is not set, and
:hp1.C&colon.\DATA:ehp1. is :hp2.not:ehp2. the current directory on drive
C&colon.&per. The following chart shows what CDD command you might use to change
to this directory.
:p.
:lm margin=8.:parml tsize=12 compact break=fit.
:pt.FuzzyCD:pd.
:pt.Setting:pd.CDD Command
.br
:pt. 0:pd.[c&colon.\] cdd c&colon.\data\mydir
:pt. 1:pd.[c&colon.\] cdd mydir
:pt. 2:pd.[c&colon.\] cdd myd
:pt. 3:pd.[c&colon.\] cdd yd
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
An extended directory search is not used if you specify a full directory path
(one beginning with a backslash [:hp2.\:ehp2.], or a drive letter and a
backslash). If you use a name which begins with a drive letter
(:hp1.e.g. C&colon.MYDIR:ehp1. ), the extended search will examine only
directories on that drive.
:p.
:p.
:hp2.Forcing an Extended Search with Wildcards:ehp2.
:p.
Normally you type a specific directory name for the command processor to
locate, and the search proceeds as described in the preceding sections.
However, you can also force the command processor to perform an extended
directory search by using
:link reftype=hd refid=Wildcards.wildcard characters:elink. in the directory
name. If you use a wildcard, an extended search will occur whether or not
extended searches have been enabled.
:p.
When &4OS2. is changing directories and it finds wildcards in the directory
name, it skips the explicit search and
:link reftype=hd refid=CDPATH.CDPATH:elink. steps and goes directly to the
extended search.
:p.
If a single match is found, the change is made immediately. If more than one
match is found, a popup window is displayed with all matching directories.
:p.
Wildcards can only be used in the final directory name in the path (after the
last backslash in the path name). For example you can find
:hp1.COMM\*A*.*:ehp1. (all directories whose parent directory is COMM and
which have an A somewhere in their names), but you cannot find
:hp1.CO?M\*A*.*:ehp1. because it uses a wildcard before the last backslash.
:p.
If you use wildcards in the directory name as described here, and the
extended directory search database does not exist, it will be built
automatically the first time a wildcard is used. You can update the
database at any time with :link reftype=hd refid=CDD.CDD:elink. /S.
:p.
Internally, extended directory searches use wildcards to scan the directory
database. If FuzzyCD is set to 2, an extended search looks for the name you
typed followed by an asterisk (:hp1.i.e.:ehp1. :hp1.DIRNAME*:ehp1.). If
FuzzyCD is set to 3, it looks for the name preceded and followed by an
asterisk (:hp1.i.e. *DIRNAME*:ehp1.).
:p.
These internal wildcards will be used in addition to any wildcards you use in
the name. For example if you search for :hp1.ABC?DEF:ehp1. (ABC followed by
any character followed by DEF) and FuzzyCD is set to 3, the command processor
will actually search the directory database for :hp1.*ABC?DEF*:ehp1.&per.
:p.
:p.
:hp2.Disabling Extended Searches in Batch Files:ehp2.
:p.
When writing batch files you may want to use the :link reftype=hd
refid=CD.CD:elink. or :link reftype=hd refid=CDD.CDD:elink. command to
switch directories without triggering an extended search. For example,
you may need the search to fail (rather than search the extended search
database) if a directory does not exist, or you may want to ensure that
the extended search popup window does not appear in a batch file
designed to run in unattended mode.
:p.
To disable extended searches, use the :hp2./N:ehp2. option of CD or CDD. When
this option is used and a directory does not exist below the current
directory or on the CDPATH, the command will fail with an error message,
and will not search the extended search database. For example this
command might trigger an extended search&colon.
:xmp.
   cdd testdir
:exmp.:p.
but this one will not&colon.
:xmp.
   cdd /n testdir
:exmp.:p.
Note that this option is not available for :link reftype=hd
refid=PUSHD.PUSHD:elink.&per. To perform the same function when using PUSHD,
save the current directory with PUSHD (without parameters) and then use
CDD /N to change directories, for example&colon.
:xmp.
   pushd
   cdd /n testdir
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=CDPATH.CDPATH
:p.
When you change directories with an
:link reftype=hd refid=AutoDir.automatic directory change:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=CD.CD:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=CDD.CDD:elink., or
:link reftype=hd refid=PUSHD.PUSHD:elink. command, &4OS2. must find the
target directory. To do so, the command processor first uses
the traditional method to find a new directory.
:p.
When the traditional search method fails, &4OS2. tries to find
the directory you requested via the CDPATH, then via an
:link reftype=hd refid=ExtDirSearch.Extended Directory
Search:elink.&per. This section covers only the CDPATH.
:p.
Enabling both CDPATH and Extended Directory Searches can yield confusing
results, so we recommend that you do not use both features at the same time.
If you prefer to explicitly list where the command processor should look for
directories, use CDPATH. If you prefer to have the command processor look at
all of the directory names on your disk, use Extended Directory Searches.
:p.
CDPATH is an environment variable, and is similar to the
:link reftype=hd refid=PATH_Var.PATH:elink. variable used to search for
executable files&colon. it contains an explicit list of directories to
search when attempting to find a new directory. The command processor
appends the specified directory name to each directory in CDPATH and
attempts to change to that drive and directory. It stops when it finds a
match or when it reaches the end of the CDPATH list.
:p.
CDPATH is ignored if a complete directory name (one beginning with a
backslash [:hp2. \:ehp2.]) is specified, or if a drive letter is included
in the name. It is only used when a name is given with no drive letter or
leading backslash.
:p.
CDPATH provides a quick way to find commonly used subdirectories in an
explicit list of locations. You can create CDPATH with the
:link reftype=hd refid=SET.SET:elink. command. The format of CDPATH is
similar to that of PATH&colon. a list of directories separated by semicolons
[:hp2.;:ehp2.]. For example, if you want the directory change commands to
search the :hp1.C&colon.\DATA:ehp1. directory, the
:hp1.D&colon.\SOFTWARE:ehp1. directory, and the root directory of drive
E&colon.\ for the subdirectories that you name, you
should create CDPATH with this command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] set cdpath=c&colon.\data;d&colon.\software;e&colon.\
:exmp.:p.
Suppose you are currently in the directory
:hp1.C&colon.\WP\LETTERS\JANUARY:ehp1., and you'd like to change to
:hp1.D&colon.\SOFTWARE\UTIL:ehp1.&per. You could change directories
explicitly with the command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\wp\letters\january] cdd d&colon.\software\util
:exmp.:p.
However, because the :hp1.D&colon.\SOFTWARE:ehp1. directory is listed in your
CDPATH variable as shown in the previous example (we'll assume it is the first
directory in the list with a UTIL subdirectory), you can simply enter the
command
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\wp\letters\january] cdd util
:exmp.:p.
or, using an automatic directory change&colon.
:p.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\wp\letters\january] util\
:exmp.:p.
to change to :hp1.D&colon.\SOFTWARE\UTIL:ehp1.&per.
:p.
As it handles this request, the command processor looks first in the current
directory, and attempts to find the :hp1.C&colon.\WP\LETTERS\JANUARY\UTIL:ehp1.
subdirectory. Then it looks at CDPATH, and appends the name you entered,
:hp1.UTIL:ehp1., to each entry in the CDPATH variable -- in other words, it
tries to change to :hp1.C&colon.\DATA\UTIL:ehp1., then to
:hp1.D&colon.\SOFTWARE\UTIL:ehp1.&per. Because this change succeeds, the search
stops and the directory change is complete.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h1 nosearch name=TOC_Other.Other Features
:p.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=Prompts.Page and File Prompts:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=RedirPipe.Redirection and Piping:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=KeystackUse.Using the Keystack:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=WaitForApps.Waiting for Applications to Finish:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=CritErr.Critical Errors:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=Conditional.Conditional Commands:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=Grouping.Command Grouping:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=Escape.Escape Character:elink.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=Prompts.Page and File Prompts
:p.
Several &4OS2. commands can generate prompts, which wait for you to
press a key to view a new page or to perform a file activity.
:p.
When &4OS2. is displaying information in page mode, for example with
a DIR /P or SET /P command, it displays the message
:xmp.
    Press Esc to Quit or any other key to continue...
:exmp.:p.
At this prompt, you can press :hp2.Esc:ehp2., :hp2.Ctrl-C:ehp2., or :hp2.Ctrl-
Break:ehp2. if you want to quit the command. You can press almost any
other key to continue with the command and see the next page of
information.
:p.
During file processing, if you have activated prompting with a
command like DEL /P, you will see this prompt before processing
every file&colon.
:xmp.
    Y/N/R ?
:exmp.:p.
You can answer this prompt by pressing :hp2.Y:ehp2. for ":hp2.Y:ehp2.es,
process this file;" :hp2.N:ehp2. for ":hp2.N:ehp2.o, do not process this
file;" :hp2.R:ehp2. for "process the :hp2.R:ehp2.emainder of the files
without further prompting." You can also press :hp2.Ctrl-C:ehp2.,
:hp2.Ctrl-Break:ehp2., or :hp2.Esc:ehp2. at this prompt to cancel the
remainder of the command.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=RedirPipe.Redirection and Piping
:p.
This section covers :hp2.redirection:ehp2. and :hp2.piping:ehp2.&per. You
can use these features to change how &4OS2. and some application programs
handle input and output.
:p.
Internal commands and many external programs get their input from the
computer's :hp2.standard input:ehp2. device and send their output to the
:hp2.standard output:ehp2. device. Some programs also send special messages
to the :hp2.standard error:ehp2. device. Normally, the keyboard is used for
standard input and the video screen for both standard output and standard
error.
:p.
Redirection and piping allow you to change these assignments temporarily.
:p.
:link reftype=hd refid=Redirection.Redirection:elink. changes the standard
input, standard output, or standard error device for a program or command
from the default device (the keyboard or screen), to another device or to a
file.
:p.
:link reftype=hd refid=Piping.Piping:elink. changes the standard output and
/ or standard error device so that the output of one command becomes the
standard input for another program or command.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=Redirection.Redirection
:p.
Redirection can be used to reassign the :hp2.standard input:ehp2.,
:hp2.standard output:ehp2., and :hp2.standard error:ehp2. devices from
their default settings (the keyboard and screen) to another device like the
printer or serial port, to a file, or to the clipboard. You must use some
discretion when you use redirection with a device; there is no way to get
input from the printer, for example.
:p.
Redirection always applies to a specific command, and lasts only
for the duration of that command. When the command is finished,
the assignments for standard input, standard output, and standard
error revert to whatever they were before the command.
:p.
In the descriptions below, :hp2.filename:ehp2. means either the name of a
file or of an appropriate device (PRN, LPT1, LPT2, or LPT3 for printers;
COM1 to COM4 for serial ports; CON for the keyboard and screen; CLIP&colon.
for the clipboard; NUL for the "null" device, etc.).
:p.
Here are the standard redirection options supported by &4OS2. (see below
for additional redirection options using numeric file handles)&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=20 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.< filename:ehp2.:pd.To get input from a file or device instead
of from the keyboard
:pt.:hp2.> filename:ehp2.:pd.Redirect standard output to a file or device
:pt.:hp2.>&amp. filename:ehp2.:pd.Redirect standard output and standard
error to a file or device
:pt.:hp2.>&amp.> filename:ehp2.:pd.Redirect standard error only to a
file or device
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
If you want to append output to the end of an existing file, rather than
creating a new file, replace the first ":hp2.>:ehp2." in the last three
commands above with ":hp2.>>:ehp2." (:hp1.i.e.:ehp1., use :hp2.>>:ehp2.,
:hp2.>>&amp.:ehp2., and :hp2.>>&amp.>:ehp2.).
:p.
To use redirection, place the redirection symbol and filename at
the end of the command line, after the command name and any
parameters. For example, to redirect the output of the DIR command
to a file called :hp1.DIRLIST:ehp1., you could use a command line like
this&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir /b *.dat > dirlist
:exmp.:p.
You can use both input and output redirection for the same command,
if both are appropriate&colon. For example, this command sends input to
SORT from the file :hp1.DIRLIST:ehp1., and sends output from SORT to the file
:hp1.DIRLIST.SRT:ehp1.&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] sort < dirlist > dirlist.srt
:exmp.:p.
You can redirect text to or from the OS/2 clipboard by using the
pseudo-device name :hp2.CLIP&colon.:ehp2. (the colon is required).
:p.
If you redirect the output of a single internal command like DIR,
the redirection ends automatically when that command is done. If
you start a batch file with redirection, all of the batch file's
output is redirected, and redirection ends when the batch file is
done. Similarly, if you use redirection at the end of a
:link reftype=hd refid=Grouping.command group:elink., all of the output from
the command group is redirected, and redirection ends when the command group
is done.
:p.
When output is directed to a file with :hp2.>:ehp2., :hp2.>&amp.:ehp2., or
:hp2.>&amp.>:ehp2., if the file already exists, it will be overwritten. You
can protect existing files by using the
:link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /N1 command, the :hp2.Protect
redirected output files:ehp2. setting available on the
:link reftype=hd refid=Options1.Options 1 page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
or the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_NoClobber.NoClobber:elink. directive in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:p.
When output is appended to a file with :hp2.>>:ehp2., :hp2.>>&amp.:ehp2., or
:hp2.>>&amp.>:ehp2., the file will be created if it doesn't already
exist. However, if NoClobber is set as described in the above,
append redirection will not create a new file; instead, if the output file
does not exist a "File not found" or similar error will be displayed.
:p.
You can temporarily override the current setting of NoClobber by
using an exclamation mark [:hp2.!:ehp2.] after the redirection symbol.
For example, to redirect the output of DIR to the file :hp1.DIROUT:ehp1.,
and allow overwriting of any existing file despite the NoClobber
setting&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir >! dirout
:exmp.:p.
Redirection is fully nestable. For example, you can invoke a batch
file and redirect all of its output to a file or device. Output
redirection on a command within the batch file will take effect for
that command only; when the command is completed, output will
revert to the redirected output file or device in use for the batch
file as a whole.
:p.
You can use redirection if you need to create a zero-byte file. To
do so, enter :hp2.>filename:ehp2. as a command, with no actual command
before the :hp2.>:ehp2. character.
:p.
In addition to the standard redirection options above, &4OS2. also supports the
OS/2 :hp1.CMD.EXE:ehp1. syntax&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.n>file:ehp2.:pd.Redirect handle :hp2.n:ehp2. to the named file
:pt.:hp2.n>&amp.m:ehp2.:pd.Redirect handle :hp2.n:ehp2. to the same place as
handle :hp2.m:ehp2.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
[:hp2.n:ehp2.] and [:hp2.m:ehp2.] are one-digit file handles between 0 and
9. You may not put any spaces between the :hp2.n:ehp2. and the :hp2.>:ehp2.,
or between the :hp2.>:ehp2., :hp2.&amp.:ehp2., and :hp2.m:ehp2. in the
second form. OS/2 interprets "0" as standard input, "1" as standard output,
and "2" as standard error. Handles 3 to 9 will probably not be useful
unless you have an application which uses those handles for a specific,
documented purpose, or you have opened a file with the
%:link reftype=hd refid=_@FILEOPEN.@FILEOPEN:elink. variable function and
the file handle is between 3 and 9.
:p.
The :hp2.n>file:ehp2. syntax redirects output from handle :hp2.n:ehp2. to a
file. You can use this form to redirect two handles to different places. For
example&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir > outfile 2> errfil
:exmp.:p.
sends normal output to a file called :hp1.OUTFILE:ehp1. and any error messages
to a file called :hp1.ERRFILE:ehp1.&per.
:p.
The :hp2.n>&amp.m:ehp2. syntax redirects handle :hp2.n:ehp2. to the same
location as the previously assigned handle :hp2.m:ehp2.&per. For example, to
send standard error to the same file as standard output, you could use this
command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] .dir > outfile 2>&amp.1
:exmp.:p.
Notice that you can perform the same operations by using standard &4OS2.
redirection features. The two examples above could be written as
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir > outfile >&amp.> errfile
:exmp.:p.
and
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir >&amp.outfile
:exmp.:p.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=Piping.Piping
:p.
You can create a "pipe" to send the standard output of one command
to the standard input of another command&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=32 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.command1 &splitvbar. command2:ehp2.:pd.Send the standard
output of :hp1.command1:ehp1. to the standard input of :hp1.command2:ehp1.
:pt.:hp2.command1 &splitvbar.&amp. command2:ehp2.:pd.Send the standard output
and standard error of :hp1.command1:ehp1. to the standard input of :hp1.command2:ehp1.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
For example, to take the output of the SET command (which displays
a list of your environment variables and their values) and pipe it
to the SORT utility to generate a sorted list, you would use the
command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] set &splitvbar. sort
:exmp.:p.
To do the same thing and then pipe the sorted list to the internal
:link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink. command for full-screen viewing&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] set &splitvbar. sort &splitvbar. list
:exmp.:p.
The :link reftype=hd refid=TEE.TEE:elink. and :link reftype=hd refid=Y.Y:elink. commands are "pipe fittings" which
add more flexibility to pipes.
:p.
Like redirection, pipes are fully nestable. For example, you can
invoke a batch file and send all of its output to another command
with a pipe. A pipe on a command within the batch file will take
effect for that command only; when the command is completed, output
will revert to the pipe in use for the batch file as a whole. You may also
have 2 or more pipes operating simultaneously if, for example, you have the
pipes running in different windows.
:p.
&4OS2. implements pipes by starting a new process for the receiving
program instead of using temporary files. The sending and
receiving programs run simultaneously; the sending program writes
to the pipe and the receiving program reads from the pipe. When
the receiving program finishes reading and processing the piped
data, it is ends automatically.
:p.
When you use pipes with &4OS2. make sure you think about any possible
consequences that can occur from using a separate process to run
the receiving program.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=KeystackUse.Using the Keystack
:p.
The Keystack overcomes two weaknesses of input redirection&colon. some
programs ignore standard input and read the keyboard directly, and input
redirection doesn't end until the program or command terminates. You can't,
for example, use redirection to send the opening commands to a program and
then type the rest of the commands yourself. But the Keystack lets you do
exactly that.
:p.
The Keystack sends keystrokes to an application program. Once the Keystack
is empty, the program will receive the rest of its input from the keyboard.
The Keystack is useful when you want a program to take certain actions
automatically when it starts. It is most often used in batch files and
aliases. The Keystack is invoked with the :link reftype=hd
refid=KEYSTACK.KEYSTACK:elink. command.
:p.
KEYSTACK depends on a program called :hp1.KEYSTACK.EXE:ehp1.&per. This file
must be in the same directory as :hp1.4OS2.EXE:ehp1., or in a directory
listed in your :link reftype=hd refid=PATH_Var.PATH:elink.&per. You don't have to
take any special action to activate :hp1.KEYSTACK.EXE:ehp1.; &4OS2. will run
it automatically when you use the KEYSTACK command. If &4OS2. cannot
find :hp1.KEYSTACK.EXE:ehp1., the KEYSTACK command will display an error
message.
:p.
To place the letters, digits, and punctuation marks you would normally type
for your program into the keystack, enclose them in double quotes&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] keystack "myfile"
:exmp.:p.
Many other keys can be entered into the Keystack using their names. This
example puts the :hp2.F1:ehp2. key followed by the :hp2.Enter:ehp2. key in the
keystack&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] keystack F1 Enter
:exmp.:p.
See :link reftype=hd refid=KeyNames.Keys and Key Names:elink. for details on
how key names are entered. See the
:link reftype=hd refid=KEYSTACK.KEYSTACK:elink. command for
information on using numeric key values along with or instead of key names,
and other details about using the Keystack.
:p.
The following command creates an :link reftype=hd refid=ALIAS.alias:elink.
that will run a FoxPro report called :hp1.TIMEREP:ehp1. (it should be entered
on one line)&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias timerep `keystack "use times index times" Enter
       "report form timerep to print" Enter "quit" Enter &amp. foxpro`
:exmp.:p.
This command creates an alias called :hp2.timerep:ehp2. which puts the
following characters on the keystack&colon.
:p.
:lm margin=8.
the characters ":hp2.use times index times:ehp2."
the Enter key's code
the characters ":hp2.report form timerep to print:ehp2."
the Enter key's code
the characters ":hp2.quit:ehp2."
and one more Enter key
:lm margin=1.
:p.
The alias then runs the program :hp1.FOXPRO:ehp1. which receives those
characters just as if you had typed them.
:p.
When you use the Keystack, remember that you must put the keystrokes into the
Keystack :hp2.before:ehp2. you run the program that will receive them. The
Keystack will hold the keystrokes until the program asks for them.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=WaitForApps.Waiting for Applications to Finish
:p.
When you start an OS/2 Presentation Manager application from the prompt, the
command processor does not normally wait for the application to finish
before returning to the prompt. This default behavior allows you to continue
your work at the prompt while the application is running. You can force
&4OS2. to wait for applications to finish before continuing by selecting the
:hp2.Wait for Completion:ehp2. option on the
:link reftype=hd refid=Options2.Options 2 page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
with the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_ExecWait.ExecWait:elink.
directive in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink., or with the
:link reftype=hd refid=START.START:elink. command's :hp2./WAIT:ehp2. switch (you
can also use START to control many other aspects of how your applications are
started).
:p.
Regardless of the ExecWait setting, &4OS2. always waits for applications which
are run from batch files before continuing with subsequent commands in the
batch file. To start an application from a batch file and continue with the
batch file immediately, without waiting for the application to finish, use
the :link reftype=hd refid=START.START:elink. command (without the
:hp2./WAIT:ehp2. switch).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=CritErr.Critical Errors
:p.
OS/2 watches for physical errors during
input and output operations. Physical errors are those due to
hardware problems, such as trying to read a floppy disk while the
drive door is open.
:p.
These errors are called :hp2.critical errors:ehp2. because OS/2, &4OS2., or
your application program cannot proceed until the error is resolved.
:p.
When a critical error occurs, you will see a popup window asking you to
choose one of four error handling options. The message comes from
OS/2 or &4OS2., and will vary slightly depending upon whether you are in
full-screen or windowed mode. You can respond with a mouse click or menu
selection. The options and their meanings are similar in all cases&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.Return error code to program:ehp2.&per. Tell the program that
the operation failed. This option returns an error code to &4OS2. or to
the application program that was running when the error occurred. &4OS2.
generally stops the current command when an operation fails.
:pt.:hp2.End program/command/operation:ehp2.&per. Choose this option to
stop the program that was running when the error occurred and abort &4OS2..
:pt.:hp2.Retry command or operation:ehp2.&per. Choose this option if you have
corrected the problem.
:pt.:hp2.Display help:ehp2.&per. Display further information on the error.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=Conditional.Conditional Commands
:p.
When an internal command or external program finished, it returns a result
called the exit code. Conditional commands allow you to perform tasks based
upon the previous command's exit code. Many programs return a 0 if they are
successful and a non-zero value if they encounter an error.
:p.
If you separate two commands by :hp2.&amp.&amp.:ehp2. (AND), the second command
will be executed only if the first returns an exit code of 0. For
example, the following command will only erase files if the BACKUP
operation succeeds&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] backup c&colon.\ a&colon. &amp.&amp. del c&colon.\*.bak;*.lst
:exmp.:p.
If you separate two commands by :hp2.&splitvbar.&splitvbar.:ehp2. (OR), the
second command will be executed only if the first returns a non-zero exit
code. For example, if the following BACKUP operation fails, then ECHO
will display a message&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] backup c&colon.\ a&colon. &splitvbar.&splitvbar. echo Error in the backup!
:exmp.:p.
All internal commands return an exit code, but not all external
programs do. Conditional commands will behave unpredictably if you
use them with external programs which do not return an explicit
exit code. To determine whether a particular external program returns a
meaningful exit code use an :hp2.ECHO %?:ehp2. command immediately after the
program is finished. If the program's documentation does not discuss exit
codes you may need to experiment with a variety of conditions to see how the
exit code changes.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=Grouping.Command Grouping
:p.
Command grouping allows you to logically group a set of commands
together by enclosing them in parentheses. The parentheses are
similar in function to the BEGIN and END block statements in some
programming languages.
:p.
There are two primary uses for command grouping. One is to execute
multiple commands in a place where normally only a single command
is allowed. For example, suppose you want to execute two different
:link reftype=hd refid=REN.REN:elink. commands in all subdirectories of your
hard disk. You could do it like this&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] global ren *.wx1 *.wxo
    [c&colon.\] global ren *.tx1 *.txo
:exmp.:p.
But with command grouping you can do the same thing in one command
(enter this on one line)&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\]global (ren *.wx1 *.wxo &amp. ren *.tx1 *.txo)
:exmp.:p.
The two REN commands enclosed in the parentheses appear to
:link reftype=hd refid=GLOBAL.GLOBAL:elink. as if they were a single command,
so both commands are executed for every directory, but the directories are
only scanned once, not twice.
:p.
This kind of command grouping is most useful with the
:link reftype=hd refid=EXCEPT.EXCEPT:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=FOR.FOR:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=GLOBAL.GLOBAL:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=IF.IF:elink. commands. When you use this approach in
a batch file you must either place all of the commands in the group on one
line, or place the opening parenthesis at the end of a line and place the
commands on subsequent lines. For example, the first two of these
sequences will work properly, but the third will not:
:xmp.
    for %f in (1 2 3) (echo hello %f &amp. echo goodbye %f)
    for %f in (1 2 3) (
        echo hello %f
        echo goodbye %f
    )
    for %f in (1 2 3) (echo hello %f
    echo goodbye %f)
:exmp.:p.
The second common use of command grouping is to redirect input or
output for several commands without repeatedly using the
redirection symbols. For example, consider the following batch
file fragment which uses the ECHO command to create a file (with
:hp2.>:ehp2.), and to append to the file (with :hp2.>>:ehp2.)&colon.
:xmp.
    echo Data files %_date > filelist
    dir *.dat >> filelist
    echo. >> filelist
    echo Text files %_date >> filelist
    dir *.txt >> filelist
:exmp.:p.
Using command grouping, these commands can be written much more
simply. Enter this example on one line&colon.
:xmp.
    (echo Data files %_date &amp. dir *.dat &amp. echo. &amp. echo Text files
    %_date &amp. dir *.txt) > filelist
:exmp.:p.
The redirection, which appears outside the parentheses, applies to
all the commands within the parentheses. Because the redirection
is performed only once, the commands will run slightly faster than
if each command was entered separately. The same approach can be
used for input redirection and for piping.
:p.
You can also use command grouping in a batch file or at the prompt
to split commands over several lines. This last example is like
the redirection example above, but is entered at the prompt. Note the
"More?" prompt after each incomplete line. None of the commands are executed
until the command group is completed with the closing parenthesis. This
example does :hp2.not:ehp2. have to be entered on one line:
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] (echo Data files %_date
    More? dir *.dat
    More? echo.
    More? echo Text files %_date
    More? dir *.txt) > filelist
    [c&colon.\]
:exmp.:p.
A group of commands in parentheses is like a long command line. The total
length of the group may not exceed 2,047 characters, whether the commands are
entered from the prompt, an alias, or a batch file. The limit
:hp2.includes:ehp2. the space required to expand aliases and environment
variables used within the group. In addition, each line you type at the
normal prompt or the :hp2.More?:ehp2. prompt, and each individual
command within the line, must meet the usual length limit of 1,023 characters.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=Escape.Escape Character
:p.
&4OS2. recognizes a user-definable escape character. This character
gives the following character a special meaning; it is :hp2.not:ehp2. the
same as the ASCII ESC that is often used in ANSI and printer
control sequences.
:p.
The default escape character is a caret [:hp2.^:ehp2.].
:p.
If you don't like using the default escape character, you can pick
another character using the :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /E
command, the :link reftype=hd refid=Options1.Options 1 Page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
or the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_EscapeChar.EscapeChar:elink. directive in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. If you plan to share aliases
or batch files between &4OS2. and 4DOS, 4NT, or Take Command, see
:link reftype=hd refid=Compat.Special Character Compatibility:elink. for
details about choosing compatible escape characters for two or more products.
:p.
Ten special characters are recognized when they are preceded by
the escape character. The combination of the escape character and
one of these characters is translated to a single character, as
shown below. These are primarily useful for redirecting codes to the
printer; :hp2.^e:ehp2. is also useful to generate ANSI "escape
sequences" in your PROMPT, ECHO, or other output commands. The special
characters which can follow the escape character are&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.b:ehp2.:pd.backspace
:pt.:hp2.c:ehp2.:pd.comma
:pt.:hp2.e:ehp2.:pd.the ASCII ESC character (ASCII 27)
:pt.:hp2.f:ehp2.:pd.form feed
:pt.:hp2.k:ehp2.:pd.back quote
:pt.:hp2.n:ehp2.:pd.line feed
:pt.:hp2.q:ehp2.:pd.double quote
:pt.:hp2.r:ehp2.:pd.carriage return
:pt.:hp2.s:ehp2.:pd.space
:pt.:hp2.t:ehp2.:pd.tab character
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
If you follow the escape character with any other character, the
escape character is removed and the second character is copied
directly to the command line. This allows you to suppress the
normal meaning of special characters (such as :hp2.? * / \ &splitvbar. "
` > <:ehp2. and :hp2.&amp.:ehp2.). For example, to display a message
containing a :hp2.>:ehp2. symbol, which normally indicates redirection&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] echo 2 is ^> 4
:exmp.:p.
To send a form feed followed by the sequence ESC Y to
the printer, you can use this command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] echos ^f^eY > prn
:exmp.
The escape character has an additional use when it is the last character on
any line entered on the
:link reftype=hd refid=CommandLine.command line:elink.
or in a :hp1..BAT:ehp1. or :hp1.BTM:ehp1. batch file.
&4OS2. recognizes
this use of the escape character to signal line continuation&colon. the
command processor removes the escape character and appends the next line to
the current line before executing it.
This allows long command lines to be spread across multiple lines for readability.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h1 name=Commands.Commands
:p.
The best way to learn the &4OS2. commands is to
experiment with them. The lists below categorize the available
commands by topic and will help you find the ones that you need.
:p.
