:h2 name=BEEP.BEEP - Beep the speaker
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Beep the speaker or play simple music.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.BEEP [:ehp2.:hp3.frequency
duration:ehp3. :hp2....]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.frequency :ehp3.&colon. The beep frequency in Hertz (cycles per second).
:pt.:pd.:hp3.duration :ehp3.&colon. The beep length in 1/18th second intervals.
:eparml.:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
BEEP generates a sound through your computer's speaker. It is
normally used in batch files to signal that an operation has been
completed, or that the computer needs attention.
:p.
Because BEEP allows you to specify the frequency and duration of
the sound, you can also use it to play simple music or to create
different kinds of signals for the user.
:p.
You can include as many frequency and duration pairs as you wish.
No sound will be generated for frequencies less than 20 Hz,
allowing you to use BEEP as a way to create short delays. The default value
for :hp1.frequency:ehp1. is 440 Hz; the default value for
:hp1.duration:ehp1. is 2.
:p.
This batch file fragment runs a program called:hp1. DEMO:ehp1., then plays
a few notes and waits for you to press a key&colon.
:xmp.
    demo &amp. beep 440 4 600 2 1040 6
    pause Finished with the demo - hit a key...
:exmp.:p.
The following table gives the :hp1.frequency:ehp1. values for a five
octave range (middle C is 262 Hz)&colon.
:xmp.
    ͻ
     C        131    262    523    1046    2093 
     C#/Db    139    277    554    1108    2217 
     D        147    294    587    1175    2349 
     D#/Eb    156    311    622    1244    2489 
     E        165    330    659    1318    2637 
     F        175    349    698    1397    2794 
     F#/Gb    185    370    740    1480    2960 
     G        196    392    784    1568    3136 
     G#/Ab    208    415    831    1662    3322 
     A        220    440    880    1760    3520 
     A#/Bb    233    466    932    1866    3729 
     B        248    494    988    1973    3951 
    ͼ
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=CALL.CALL - Execute one batch file from another
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Execute one batch file from within another.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.CALL [/Q]:ehp2. :hp3.file:ehp3.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.file :ehp3.&colon. The batch file to execute.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./Q:ehp2.(uiet):pd.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=CANCEL.CANCEL:elink. and :link
reftype=hd refid=QUIT.QUIT:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
CALL allows batch files to call other batch files (batch file
nesting). The calling batch file is suspended while the called
(second) batch file runs. When the second batch file finishes, the
original batch file resumes execution at the next command. If you
execute a batch file from inside another batch file without using
CALL, the first batch file is terminated before the second one
starts.
:p.
The following batch file fragment compares an input line to "wp" and calls
another batch file if it matches&colon.
:xmp.
    input Enter your choice&colon. %%option
    if "%option" == "wp" call wp.bat
:exmp.:p.
&4OS2. supports batch file nesting up to ten levels deep.
:p.
The current ECHO state is inherited by a called batch file, except when the
:hp2./Q:ehp2.&per.
:p.
The called batch file should always either return (by executing its last
line, or using the :link reftype=hd refid=QUIT.QUIT:elink. command), or
terminate batch file processing with :link reftype=hd
refid=CANCEL.CANCEL:elink.&per. Do not restart or CALL the original batch file
from within the called file as this may cause an infinite loop or a stack
overflow.
:p.
CALL returns an exit code which matches the batch file return code.
You can test this exit code with the :link reftype=hd
refid=__QMARK.%_?:elink. or :link reftype=hd refid=_QMARK.%?:elink.
environment variable, and use it with :link reftype=hd
refid=Conditional.conditional commands:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./Q:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Quiet) Starts the new batch file with echo off,
regardless of the current batch file's echo state. This switch is provided
for compatibility with OS/2's :hp1.CMD.EXE:ehp1.&per.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=CANCEL.CANCEL - Terminate batch file processing
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Terminate batch file processing.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.CANCEL [:ehp2.:hp3.value:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.value :ehp3.&colon. The numeric exit code to return to &4OS2..
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=CALL.CALL:elink. and :link reftype=hd refid=QUIT.QUIT:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
The CANCEL command ends all batch file processing, regardless of
the batch file nesting level. Use QUIT to end a nested batch file
and return to the previous batch file.
:p.
You can CANCEL at any point in a batch file. If CANCEL is used
from within an alias it will end execution of both the alias and
any batch files which are running at the time.
:p.
The following batch file fragment compares an input line to "end"
and terminates all batch file processing if it matches&colon.
:xmp.
    input Enter your choice&colon. %%option
    if "%option" == "end" cancel
:exmp.:p.
If you specify a :hp1.value:ehp1., CANCEL will set the ERRORLEVEL or exit
code to that value (see the :link reftype=hd refid=IF.IF:elink. command, and
the :link reftype=hd refid=_QMARK.%?:elink. variable).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=CD.CD - Change the current directory
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display or change the current directory.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.CD [/N] [ :ehp2.:hp3.path:ehp3. :hp2.&splitvbar. - ]:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.   or
:pt.:pd.:hp2.CHDIR [/N] [ :ehp2.:hp3.path:ehp3. :hp2.&splitvbar. - ]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.path :ehp3.&colon. The target directory (or drive and directory).
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./N:ehp2.(o extended search)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=CDD.CDD:elink., :link reftype=hd
refid=MD.MD:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=PUSHD.PUSHD:elink., :link
reftype=hd refid=RD.RD:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=CDPATH.CDPATH:elink.,
and :link reftype=hd refid=DirNav.Directory Navigation:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
CD and CHDIR are synonyms. You can use either one.
:p.
CD lets you navigate through a drive's structure by changing the current
working directory. If you enter CD and a directory name, the named
directory becomes the new current directory. For example, to change to the
subdirectory :hp1.C&colon.\FINANCE\MYFILES:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] cd \finance\myfiles
    [c&colon.\finance\myfiles]
:exmp.:p.
Every disk drive on the system has its own current directory.
Specifying both a drive and a directory in the CD command will
change the current directory on the specified drive, but will not
change the default drive. For example, to change the default
directory on drive A&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] cd a&colon.\utility
    [c&colon.\]
:exmp.:p.
Notice that this command does not change to drive A&colon.&per. Use the CDD
command to change the current drive and directory at the same time.
:p.
When you use CD to change to a directory on a volume supporting long filenames, you must quote
the :hp1.path:ehp1. name if it contains whitespace or special
characters. See :link reftype=hd refid=Filenames.Filenames and File
Systems:elink. for additional details.
:p.
You can change to the parent directory with :hp2.CD ..:ehp2.; you can also
go up one additional directory level with each additional [:hp2..:ehp2.].
For example, :hp2.CD ....:ehp2. will go up three levels in the directory
tree (see :link reftype=hd refid=ParDir.Extended Parent Directory
Names:elink.). You can move to a sibling directory -- one that branches
from the same parent directory as the current subdirectory -- with a command
like :hp2.CD ..\newdir:ehp2.&per.
:p.
If you enter CD with no argument or with only a disk drive name, it
will display the current directory on the default or named drive.
:p.
If CD cannot change to the directory you have specified it will attempt to
search the :link reftype=hd refid=CDPATH.CDPATH:elink. and the :link
reftype=hd refid=ExtDirSearch.extended directory search:elink. database in order
to find a matching directory and switch to it. You can use :link
reftype=hd refid=Wildcards.wildcards:elink. in the :hp1.path:ehp1. to force
an extended directory search. See the section on :link reftype=hd
refid=DirNav.Directory Navigation:elink. for complete details on these and
other directory navigation features. To disable extended directory searches
for the current command (e.g. in a batch file) see the :hp2./N:ehp2. option
below.
:p.
CD saves the current directory before changing to a new directory.
You can switch back to the previous directory by entering :hp2.CD -:ehp2.
(there must be a space between the CD command and the hyphen). You
can switch back and forth between two directories by repeatedly
entering :hp2.CD -:ehp2.&per. The saved directory is the same for both the CD
and CDD commands. Drive changes and
:link reftype=hd refid=AutoDir.automatic directory changes:elink. also
modify the saved directory, so you can use :hp2.CD -:ehp2. to return to a
directory that you exited with an automatic directory change.
:p.
Directory changes made with CD are also recorded in the directory history
list and can be displayed in the :link reftype=hd refid=DirHist.directory
history window:elink., which allows you to return quickly to a recently-used
directory.
:p.
CD never changes the default drive. If you change directories on
one drive, switch to another drive, and then enter :hp2.CD -:ehp2., the
directory will be restored on the first drive but the current drive
will not be changed.
:p.
:hp2.Option:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./N:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(No extended search) This option prevents CD
from searching the :link reftype=hd refid=ExtDirSearch.extended directory
search:elink. database or displaying the related popup window. If
:hp2./N:ehp2. is used and the specified directory is not found via other
methods (i.e. without an extended search), CD will display an error.
This option is primarily intended for use in batch files where you do
not want CD to use "fuzzy" directory searching or display an extended
search popup window.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=CDD.CDD - Change the current drive and directory
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Change the current disk drive and directory.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.CDD [/A /N /S[drive ...]] [:ehp2.:hp3.path:ehp3. :hp2.&splitvbar. - ]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.path :ehp3.&colon. The target directory (or drive and directory).
:pt.:pd.:hp3.drive :ehp3.&colon. A drive or list of drives to include in the
extended directory search database.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.(ll drives):pd.:hp2./N:ehp2.(o extended search)
:pt.:hp2./S:ehp2.(earch tree):pd.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=CD.CD:elink., :link reftype=hd
refid=MD.MD:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=PUSHD.PUSHD:elink., :link
reftype=hd refid=RD.RD:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=CDPATH.CDPATH:elink.,
and :link reftype=hd refid=DirNav.Directory Navigation:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
CDD is similar to the CD command, except that it also changes the
default disk drive if one is specified. CDD will change to the
directory and drive you name. To change from the root directory on
drive A to the subdirectory :hp1.C&colon.\WP&colon.:ehp1.
:xmp.
    [a&colon.\] cdd c&colon.\wp
    [c&colon.\wp]
:exmp.:p.
You can change to the parent directory with :hp2.CDD ..:ehp2.; you can
also go up one additional directory level with each additional
[:hp2..:ehp2.]. For example, :hp2.CDD ....:ehp2. will go up three levels in
the directory tree (see :link reftype=hd refid=ParDir.Extended Parent
Directory Names:elink.).
:p.
CDD can also change to a network drive and directory specified with a UNC
name (see :link reftype=hd refid=Filesys.Filesystems:elink. for more
information about network directories).
:p.
When you use CDD to change to a directory on a volume supporting long filenames, you must quote
the :hp1.path:ehp1. name if it contains whitespace or special
characters. See :link reftype=hd refid=Filenames.Filenames and File
Systems:elink. for additional details.
:p.
If CDD cannot change to the directory you have specified it will attempt to
search the :link reftype=hd refid=CDPATH.CDPATH:elink. and the :link
reftype=hd refid=ExtDirSearch.extended directory search:elink. database in order
to find a matching directory and switch to it. You can also use :link
reftype=hd refid=Wildcards.wildcards:elink. in the :hp1.path:ehp1. to force
an extended directory search. See the section on :link reftype=hd
refid=DirNav.Directory Navigation:elink. for complete details on these and
other directory navigation features. To disable extended directory searches
for the current command (e.g. in a batch file) see the :hp2./N:ehp2. option
below.
:p.
CDD saves the current drive and directory before changing to a new
directory. You can switch back to the previous drive and directory
by entering :hp2.CDD -:ehp2. (there must be a space between the CDD
command and the hyphen). You can switch back and forth between two
drives and directories by repeatedly entering :hp2.CDD -:ehp2.&per. The saved
directory is the same for both the CD and CDD commands. Drive
changes and :link reftype=hd refid=AutoDir.automatic directory changes:elink. also modify
the saved directory, so you can use :hp2.CDD -:ehp2. to return to a
directory that you exited with a drive change or an automatic
directory change.
:p.
Directory changes made with CDD are also recorded in the directory history
list and can be displayed in the :link reftype=hd refid=DirHist.directory
history window:elink., which allows you to return quickly to a recently-used
directory.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(All drives) When CDD is used with this option, it
displays the current directory on all drives from C&colon. to the last drive
in the system. You cannot move to a new drive and directory and use
:hp2./A:ehp2. in the same command.
:pt.:hp2./N:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(No extended search) This option prevents CD
from searching the :link reftype=hd refid=ExtDirSearch.extended directory
search:elink. database or displaying the related popup window. If
:hp2./N:ehp2. is used and the specified directory is not found via other
methods (i.e. without an extended search), CD will display an error.
This option is primarily intended for use in batch files where you do
not want CD to use "fuzzy" directory searching or display an extended
search popup window.
:pt.:hp2./S:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Search tree) Builds or rebuilds the :link
reftype=hd refid=ExtDirSearch.Extended Directory Search:elink. database,
:hp1.JPSTREE.IDX:ehp1.&per. You cannot move to a new drive and directory and
use :hp2./S:ehp2. in the same command.
:p.
To include all local hard drives in the database use the command&colon.
:xmp.
    cdd /s
:exmp.:p.
To limit or add to the list of drives included in the database, list the
drives and network volume names after the :hp2./S:ehp2. switch. For
example, to include drives C, D, E, and the network volume \\server\dir1 in
the database, use this command&colon.
:xmp.
    cdd /s cde \\server\dir1
:exmp.:p.
All non-hidden directories on the listed drives will be indexed; you cannot
restrict the database to certain directories within a drive. Each time you
use :hp2./S:ehp2., everything in the previous directory database is replaced
by the new database that is created.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.


