:h2 name=CLS.CLS - Clear the screen
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Clear the video display and move the cursor to the
upper left corner; optionally change the default display and border colors.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.CLS [[BRIght] [BLInk] :ehp2.:hp3.fg:ehp3. :hp2.ON [BRIght] :ehp2.:hp3.bg:ehp3. :hp2.]
[BORder :ehp2.:hp3.bc:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.fg :ehp3.&colon. The new foreground color
:pt.:pd.:hp3.bg :ehp3.&colon. The new background color
:pt.:pd.:hp3.bc :ehp3.&colon. The new border color
:eparml.:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
CLS can be used to clear the screen without changing colors, or to
clear the screen and change the screen colors simultaneously.
These three examples show how to clear the screen to the default
colors, to bright white letters on a blue background, and to bright
yellow letters on a magenta background with a blue border&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] cls
    [c&colon.\] cls bright white on blue
    [c&colon.\] cls bri yel on mag bor blu
:exmp.:p.
CLS is often used in batch files to clear the screen before
displaying text.
:p.
See :link reftype=hd refid=Colors.Colors and Color Names:elink. for details about colors and
notes on the use of bright background colors.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=COLOR.COLOR - Change the display colors
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Change the default display colors.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.COLOR [BRIght] [BLInk]:ehp2.
:hp3.fg:ehp3. :hp2.ON [BRIght]:ehp2. :hp3.bg:ehp3.
:hp2.[BORder :ehp2.:hp3.bc:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.fg :ehp3.&colon. The new foreground color
:pt.:pd.:hp3.bg :ehp3.&colon. The new background color
:pt.:pd.:hp3.bc :ehp3.&colon. The new border color
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=CLS.CLS:elink., and :link reftype=hd
refid=Colors.Colors and Color Names:elink. for details about using colors.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
COLOR is normally used in batch files before displaying text.
For example, to set screen colors to bright white on blue, you can
use this command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] color bright white on blue
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=COPY.COPY - Copy files
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Copy data between disks, directories, files, or
physical hardware devices (such as your printer or serial port).
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.COPY [/A&colon.[[-]rhsda] /C /E /F /H /J /K
/M /N /P /Q /R /S /T /U /V /X /Z]:ehp2. :hp3.source:ehp3. :hp2.[+] ... [/A
/B]:ehp2. :hp3.destination:ehp3. :hp2.[/A /B]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.source :ehp3.&colon. A file or list of files or a device to copy :hp3.from:ehp3. .
:pt.:pd.:hp3.destination :ehp3.&colon. A file, directory, or device to copy :hp3.to:ehp3. .
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.(SCII):pd.:hp2./P:ehp2.(rompt)
:pt.:hp2./A&colon.:ehp2. (Attribute select)
:pt.:hp2./B:ehp2.(inary):pd.:hp2./Q:ehp2.(uiet)
:pt.:hp2./C:ehp2.(hanged):pd.:hp2./R:ehp2.(eplace)
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2. (no Error messages):pd.:hp2./S:ehp2.(ubdirectories)
:pt.:hp2./F:ehp2.(ail on EA error):pd.:hp2./T:ehp2.(otals)
:pt.:hp2./H:ehp2.(idden):pd.:hp2./U:ehp2.(update)
:pt.:hp2./J:ehp2. (CMD directory copy):pd.:hp2./V:ehp2.(erify)
:pt.:hp2./K:ehp2.(eep attributes):pd.:hp2./X:ehp2. (clear archive)
:pt.:hp2./M:ehp2.(odified):pd.:hp2./Z:ehp2. (overwrite)
:pt.:hp2./N:ehp2.(othing)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=ATTRIB.ATTRIB:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=MOVE.MOVE:elink., and :link reftype=hd refid=REN.REN:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.File Selection:ehp2.
:p.
Supports extended :link reftype=hd refid=wildcards.wildcards:elink., :link
reftype=hd refid=ranges.ranges:elink., :link reftype=hd
refid=MultFiles.multiple filenames:elink., and :link reftype=hd
refid=InclList.include lists:elink.&per. :link reftype=hd refid=Ranges.Date,
time, size:elink., or :link reftype=hd refid=ExclRanges.exclude:elink.
ranges anywhere on the line apply to all :hp1.source:ehp1. files.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
The COPY command accepts all traditional syntax and options and
adds many new features.
:p.
The simplest use of COPY is to make a copy of a file, like this
example which makes a copy of a file called :hp1.FILE1.ABC:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy file1.abc file2.def
:exmp.:p.
You can also copy a file to another drive and/or directory. The
following command copies :hp1.FILE1:ehp1. to the :hp1.\MYDIR:ehp1. directory on
drive E&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy file1 e&colon.\mydir
:exmp.:p.
You can copy several files at once by using
:link reftype=hd refid=wildcards.wildcards:elink.&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy *.txt e&colon.\mydir
:exmp.:p.
When you COPY files to or from a volume supporting long filenames, you must quote
the :hp1.path:ehp1. name if it contains whitespace or special
characters. See :link reftype=hd refid=Filenames.Filenames and File
Systems:elink. for additional details.
:p.
:hp2.Copying Files:ehp2.
:p.
You can copy several files at once by using :link reftype=hd
refid=Wildcards.wildcards:elink.&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy *.txt e&colon.\mydir
:exmp.:p.
You can also list several :hp1.source:ehp1. files in one command. The
following command copies 3 files from the current directory to the
:hp1.\MYDIR:ehp1. directory on drive E&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy file1 file2 file3 e&colon.\mydir
:exmp.:p.
:p.
COPY also understands :link reftype=hd refid=InclList.include lists:elink.,
so you can specify several different kinds of files in the same
command. This command copies the :hp1..TXT:ehp1., :hp1. .DOC:ehp1., and
:hp1..BAT :ehp1.files from the :hp1.E&colon.\MYDIR:ehp1. directory to the
root directory of drive A&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy e&colon.\mydir\*.txt;*.doc;*.bat a&colon.\
:exmp.:p.
If there is only one argument on the line, COPY assumes it is the
:hp1.source:ehp1., and uses the current drive and directory as the
:hp1.destination:ehp1.&per. For example, the following command copies all the
:hp1..DAT:ehp1. files on drive A to the current directory on drive C&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\data] copy a&colon.*.dat
:exmp.:p.
If there are two or more arguments on the line, separated by spaces,
then COPY assumes that the last argument is the :hp1.destination:ehp1. and
copies all :hp1.source:ehp1. files to this new location. If the
:hp1.destination:ehp1. is a drive, directory, or device name then the
:hp1.source:ehp1. files are copied individually to the new
location. If the :hp1.destination:ehp1. is a filename, the first
:hp1.source:ehp1. file is copied to the :hp1.destination:ehp1., and any
additional :hp1.source:ehp1. files are then appended to the new
:hp1.destination:ehp1. file.
:p.
For example, the first of these commands copies the :hp1..DAT:ehp1. files
from the current directory on drive A individually to :hp1.C&colon.\MYDIR:ehp1.
(which must already exist as a directory); the second appends all
the :hp1..DAT:ehp1. files together into one large file called :hp1.C&colon.\DATA:ehp1.
(assuming :hp1.C&colon.\DATA:ehp1. is not a directory)&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy a&colon.*.dat c&colon.\mydir\
    [c&colon.\] copy a&colon.*.dat c&colon.\data
:exmp.:p.
When you copy to a directory, if you add a backslash [:hp2.\:ehp2.] to the
end of the name as shown in the first example above, COPY will
display an error message if the name does not refer to an existing
directory. You can use this feature to keep COPY from treating a
mistyped :hp1.destination:ehp1. directory name as a filename and
attempting to append all your :hp1.source:ehp1. files to a
:hp1.destination:ehp1. :hp2.file:ehp2., when you really meant to copy them
individually to a :hp1.destination:ehp1. :hp2.directory:ehp2.&per.
:p.
To copy a file to a device such as the printer, use the device name as the
:hp1.destination:ehp1., for example&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy schedule.txt prn
:exmp.:p.
To copy text to or from the clipboard use :hp2.CLIP&colon.:ehp2. as the
device name. Using CLIP&colon. with non-text data will produce unpredictable
results. See :link reftype=hd refid=Redirection.Redirection:elink. for
additional information on CLIP&colon..
:p.
:hp2.Appending Files:ehp2.
:p.
A plus [:hp2.+:ehp2.] tells COPY to append two or more files to a single
:hp1.destination:ehp1. file. If you list several :hp1.source:ehp1. files
separated with [:hp2.+:ehp2.] and don't specify a :hp1.destination:ehp1., COPY
will use the name of the first :hp1.source:ehp1. file as the destination,
and append each subsequent file to the first file.
:p.
For example, the following command will append the contents of
:hp1.C&colon.\MEMO2:ehp1. and :hp1.C&colon.\MEMO3:ehp1. to :hp1.C&colon.\MEMO1:ehp1. and leave the
combined contents in the filenamed :hp1.C&colon.\MEMO1:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy memo1+memo2+memo3
:exmp.:p.
To append the same three files but store the result in
:hp1.BIGMEMO&colon.:ehp1.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy memo1+memo2+memo3 bigmemo
:exmp.:p.
To append :hp1.C&colon.\MEM\MEMO2:ehp1. and :hp1.C&colon.\MEM\MEMO3:ehp1. to
:hp1.D&colon.\DATA\MEMO1:ehp1., and leave the result in
:hp1.C&colon.\MEM\MEMO1:ehp1. &colon.

If no :hp1.destination:ehp1. is specified, the destination file will always
be created in the current directory even if the first :hp1.source:ehp1. file
is in another directory or on another drive. For example, this command will
append :hp1.C&colon.\MEM\MEMO2:ehp1. and :hp1.C&colon.\MEM\MEMO3:ehp1. to
:hp1.D&colon.\DATA\MEMO1:ehp1., and leave the result in
:hp1.C&colon.\MEM\MEMO1:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\mem] copy d&colon.\data\memo1+memo2+memo3
:exmp.:p.
You cannot append files to a device (such as a printer); if you try
to do so, COPY will ignore the [:hp2.+:ehp2.] signs and copy the files
individually. If you attempt to append several :hp1.source:ehp1. files to
a :hp1.destination:ehp1. directory or disk, COPY will append the files and
place the copy in the new location with the same name as the first
:hp1.source:ehp1. file.
:p.
:hp2.Advanced Features:ehp2.
:p.
If your :hp1.destination:ehp1. has wildcards in it, COPY will attempt to
match them with the :hp1.source:ehp1. names. For example, this command
copies the :hp1..DAT:ehp1. files from drive A to :hp1.C&colon.\MYDIR:ehp1. and gives
the new copies the extension :hp1..DX:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy a&colon.*.dat c&colon.\mydir\*.dx
:exmp.:p.
This feature can give you unexpected results if you use it with
multiple :hp1.source:ehp1. filenames. For example, suppose that drive A
contains :hp1.XYZ.DAT:ehp1. and :hp1.XYZ.TXT:ehp1.&per. The command
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy a&colon.\*.dat a&colon.\*.txt c&colon.\mydir\*.dx
:exmp.:p.
will copy :hp1.A&colon.XYZ.DAT:ehp1. to :hp1.C&colon.\MYDIR\XYZ.DX:ehp1.&per. Then it will copy
:hp1.A&colon.XYZ.TXT:ehp1. to :hp1.C&colon.\MYDIR\XYZ.DX:ehp1., overwriting the first file it
copied.
:p.
COPY also understands :link reftype=hd refid=InclList.include lists:elink., so you can
specify several different kinds of files in the same command. This
command copies the :hp1..TXT:ehp1., :hp1..DOC:ehp1., and :hp1..BAT:ehp1. files from the
:hp1.E&colon.\MYDIR:ehp1. directory to the root directory of drive A&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy e&colon.\mydir\*.txt;*.doc;*.bat a&colon.\
:exmp.:p.
You can use :link reftype=hd refid=Ranges.date, time, and size ranges:elink. to further
define the files that you want to copy. This example copies every
file in the :hp1.E&colon.\MYDIR:ehp1. directory, which was created or modified
yesterday, and which is also 10,000 bytes or smaller in size, to
the root directory of drive A&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy /[d-1] /[s0,10000] e&colon.\mydir\*.* a&colon.\
:exmp.:p.
You can also use file exclusion ranges to restrict the list of files that
would normally be selected with wildcards. This example copies every file
in the :hp1.E&colon.\MYDIR:ehp1. directory except backup (:hp1..BAK:ehp1. or
:hp1..BK!:ehp1.) files&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy /[!*.bak;*.bk!] e&colon.\mydir\*.* a&colon.\
:exmp.:p.
COPY will normally process :hp1.source:ehp1. files which do not have the
hidden or system attribute, and will ignore the read-only and archive
attributes. It will always set the archive attribute and clear the
read-only attribute of :hp1.destination:ehp1. files. In addition, if the
:hp1.destination:ehp1. is an existing file with the read-only attribute,
COPY will generate an "Access Denied" error and refuse to overwrite the
file. You can alter some of these behaviors with switches&colon.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./A&colon.:ehp2.:pd.Forces COPY to process :hp1.source:ehp1. files
with the attributes you specify after the ":hp2.&colon.:ehp2.", or to process
all :hp1.source:ehp1. files regardless of attributes (if :hp2./A&colon.:ehp2.
is used by itself).
:pt.:hp2./H:ehp2.:pd.Forces COPY to process hidden and system
:hp1.source:ehp1. files, as well as normal files. The hidden and system
attributes from each source file will be preserved when creating the
:hp1.destination:ehp1. files.
:pt.:hp2./K:ehp2.:pd.Retains the read-only attribute from each
:hp1.source:ehp1. file when creating the :hp1.destination:ehp1.file. See
:hp2./K:ehp2. below for a special note if you are running under Novell
Netware.
:pt.:hp2./Z:ehp2.:pd.Forces COPY to overwrite an existing read-only
:hp1.destination:ehp1. file.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
:p.
Use caution with :hp2./A&colon.:ehp2., :hp2./H:ehp2., or :hp2./K:ehp2. when
both the source and destination directories contain file descriptions. If
the source file specification matches the description file name (normally
:hp1.DESCRIPT.ION:ehp1.), and you use a switch which tells COPY to process
hidden files, the :hp1.DESCRIPT.ION:ehp1. file itself will be copied,
overwriting any existing file descriptions in the destination directory. For
example, if the :hp1.\DATA:ehp1. directory contains file descriptions this
command would overwrite any existing descriptions in the :hp1.\SAVE:ehp1.
directory&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\data] copy /h d*.* \save\
:exmp.:p.
(If you remove the hidden attribute from the :hp1.DESCRIPT.ION:ehp1. file
the same caution applies even if you do not use :hp2./A&colon.:ehp2.,
:hp2./H:ehp2., or :hp2./K:ehp2., as :hp1.DESCRIPT.ION:ehp1. is then treated
like any other file.)
:p.
If you copy a file from a FAT16 volume to a volume supporting long filenames,
and you do not give an explicit :hp1.destination:ehp1. name (:hp1.i.e.:ehp1.
you are moving the file to the current directory, or your :hp1.destination:ehp1.
name is made up entirely of wildcards), COPY will look for a &per.LONGNAME extended
attribute for the :hp1.source:ehp1. file. If it finds that attribute, it will
use the long filename for the destination file. If it does not, it will use the
short name.
:p.
Similarly, if you COPY files with long filenames from a volume supporting long
filenames to a FAT16 volume, &4OS2. will create the :hp1.destination:ehp1. files
with short, FAT16-compatible names and save the long filenames in the &per.LONGNAME
extended attribute. The short name is created by replacing special characters
with underscores, adding numeric digits to the filename (if necessary) to make
the new name unique, and truncating the name to fit with in the "8.3" FAT16
name structure.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:p.
The :hp2./A:ehp2.(SCII) and :hp2./B:ehp2.(inary) options apply to the preceding
filename and to all subsequent filenames on the command line until
the filename preceding the next :hp2./A:ehp2. or :hp2./B:ehp2., if any. The
other options (:hp2./A&colon.:ehp2., :hp2./C:ehp2., :hp2./E:ehp2.,
:hp2./H:ehp2., :hp2./K:ehp2., :hp2./M:ehp2., :hp2./N:ehp2., :hp2./P:ehp2.,
:hp2./Q:ehp2., :hp2./R:ehp2., :hp2./S:ehp2., :hp2./T:ehp2., :hp2./U:ehp2.,
:hp2./V:ehp2., :hp2./X:ehp2., :hp2./Z:ehp2.) apply to all filenames on
the command line, no matter where you put them. For example,
either of the following commands could be used to copy a font file
to the printer in binary mode&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] copy /b myfont.dat prn
    [c&colon.\] copy myfont.dat /b prn
:exmp.:p.
Some options do not make sense in certain contexts, in which case
COPY will ignore them. For example, you cannot prompt before
replacing an existing file when the :hp1.destination:ehp1. is a device
such as the printer -- there's no such thing as an "existing file"
on the printer. If you use conflicting output options, like :hp2./Q:ehp2.
and :hp2./P:ehp2., COPY will generally take a "conservative" approach and give
priority to the option which generates more prompts or more information.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(ASCII) If you use :hp2./A:ehp2. with a
:hp1.source:ehp1. filename, the file will be copied up to, but not
including, the first Ctrl-Z (Control-Z or ASCII 26) character in
the file (some application programs use the Ctrl-Z to mark the end of a
file). If you use :hp2./A:ehp2. with a :hp1.destination:ehp1. filename,
a Ctrl-Z will be added to the end of the file. :hp2./A:ehp2. is the default
when appending files, or when the :hp1.destination:ehp1. is a device like
NUL or PRN, rather than a disk file. Also see :hp2./B:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:hp2./A&colon.:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Attribute select) Select only those
files that have the specified attribute(s) set. Preceding the attribute
character with a hyphen [:hp2.-:ehp2.] will select files that do not have
that attribute set. The colon [:hp2.&colon.:ehp2.] after :hp2./A:ehp2. is
required. The attributes are&colon.
:parml tsize=8 compact break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  R:ehp2. Read-only
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  H:ehp2. Hidden
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  S:ehp2. System
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  D:ehp2. Subdirectory
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  A:ehp2. Archive
:eparml.:p.
If no attributes are listed at all (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., :hp2.COPY
/A&colon. ...:ehp2.), COPY will select all files and subdirectories including hidden
and system files. If attributes are combined, all the specified attributes
must match for a file to be selected. For example, /A&colon.RHS will select
only those files with all three attributes set.
:p.
See the cautionary note under :hp2.Advanced Features:ehp2. above before
using :hp2./A&colon.:ehp2. when both :hp1.source:ehp1. and
:hp1.destination:ehp1. directories contain file descriptions.
:p.
You must include the colon with this option to distinguish it from the
:hp2./A:ehp2.(SCII) switch, above.
:pt.:hp2./B:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Binary) If you use :hp2./B:ehp2. with a :hp1.source:ehp1. filename, the
entire file is copied; Ctrl-Z characters in the file do not affect the copy
operation. Using :hp2./B:ehp2. with a :hp1.destination:ehp1. filename
prevents addition of a Ctrl-Z to the end of the :hp1.destination:ehp1.
file. :hp2./B:ehp2. is the default for normal file copies. Also see
:hp2./A:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:hp2./C:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Changed files) Copy files only if the :hp1.destination:ehp1.
file exists and is older than the :hp1.source:ehp1. (see
also :hp2./U:ehp2.). This option is useful for updating
the files in one directory from those in another
without copying any newly created files.
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(no Error messages) Suppress all non-fatal error
messages, such as "File not found." Fatal error messages, such as "Drive
not ready," will still be displayed. This option is most useful in batch
files and aliases.
:pt.:hp2./F:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Fail on EA error) Fail if the source file has
extended attributes and the destination filesystem doesn't support extended
attributes.
:pt.:hp2./H:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Hidden) Copy all matching files including those with the
hidden and/or system attribute set.
:p.
See the cautionary note under :hp2.Advanced Features:ehp2. above before
using :hp2./H:ehp2. when both :hp1.source:ehp1. and :hp1.destination:ehp1.
directories contain file descriptions.
:pt.:hp2./J:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(CMD directory move) CMD copies the 
directory to the target when the command line aurgument is a directory. 
By default &4OS2. copies the files in the directory to the target. Using 
/J makes &4OS2. provide the CMD behavior. This can be set as the default
by :link reftype=hd refid=INI_CMDDirMvCpy.CMDDirMvCpy:elink.=yes in &4OS2INI..
:pt.:hp2./K:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Keep attributes) To maintain compatibility with
:hp1.CMD.EXE:ehp1., COPY normally maintains the hidden and system
attributes, sets the archive attribute, and removes the read-only attribute
on the destination file. :hp2./K:ehp2. tells COPY to also maintain the read-only
attribute on the :hp1.destination:ehp1. file. However, if the
:hp1.destination:ehp1. is on a Novell Netware volume, this option will fail
to maintain the read-only attribute. This is due to the way Netware handles
file attributes, and is not a problem in COPY.
:pt.:hp2./M:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Modified) Copy only those files with the archive
attribute set, :hp1.i.e.:ehp1., those which have been modified since the last
backup. The archive attribute of the :hp1.source:ehp1. will :hp2.not:ehp2.
be cleared after copying; to clear it use the :hp2./X:ehp2. switch, or use
:link reftype=hd refid=ATTRIB.ATTRIB:elink.&per.
:pt.:hp2./N:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Nothing) Do everything except actually perform
the copy. This option is useful for testing what the result of a complex
COPY command will be. :hp2./N:ehp2. does :hp2.not:ehp2. prevent creation of
:hp1.destination:ehp1. subdirectories when it is used with :hp2./s:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:hp2./P:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Prompt) Ask the user to confirm each
:hp1.source:ehp1. file. Your options at the prompt are explained in detail
under :link reftype=hd refid=Prompts.Page and File Prompts:elink.&per.
:pt.:hp2./Q:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Quiet) Don't display filenames or the total number of files
copied. This option is most often used in batch
files. See also :hp2./T:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:hp2./R:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Replace) Prompt the user before overwriting an existing
file.  Your options at the prompt are explained in
detail under :link reftype=hd refid=Prompts.Page and File Prompts:elink.&per.
:pt.:hp2./S:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Subdirectories) Copy the subdirectory tree
starting with the files in the :hp1.source:ehp1. directory plus each
subdirectory below that. The :hp1.destination:ehp1. must be a directory; if
it doesn't exist, COPY will attempt to create it. COPY will also attempt to
create needed subdirectories on the tree below the :hp1.destination:ehp1.,
including empty :hp3.source:ehp3. directories. If COPY /S creates one or
more destination directories, they will be added automatically to the
:link reftype=hd refid=ExtDirSearch.extended directory search:elink. database.
:p.
If you attempt to use COPY /S to copy a subdirectory tree into part of
itself, COPY will detect the resulting infinite loop, display an error
message, and exit.
:pt.:hp2./T:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Totals) Turns off the display of filenames, like :hp2./Q:ehp2.,
but does display the total number of files copied.
:pt.:hp2./U:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Update) Copy each :hp1.source:ehp1. file only
if it is newer than a matching :hp1.destination:ehp1. file or if a matching
:hp1.destination:ehp1. file does not exist (see also :hp2./C:ehp2.). This
option is useful for keeping one directory matched with another with a
minimum of copying.
:pt.:hp2./V:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Verify) Verify each disk write. This is the
same as executing the VERIFY ON command, but is only active during the
COPY. :hp2./V:ehp2. does :hp2.not:ehp2. read back the file and compare its
contents with what was written; it only verifies that the data written to
disk is physically readable.
:pt.:hp2./X:ehp2.&colon.:pd.Clears the archive attribute
from the source file after a successful copy. This option is most useful if
you are using COPY to maintain a set of backup files.
:pt.:hp2./Z:ehp2.&colon.:pd.Overwrites read-only
:hp1.destination:ehp1. files. Without this option, COPY will fail with an
"Access denied" error if the :hp1.destination:ehp1. file has its read-only
attribute set. This option allows COPY to overwrite read-only files without
generating any errors.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=DATE.DATE - Change the system date
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display and optionally change the system date.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.DATE [:ehp2.:hp3.mm:ehp3.
:hp2.-:ehp2.:hp3.dd:ehp3. :hp2.-:ehp2.:hp3.yy:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.mm :ehp3.&colon. The month (1 - 12).
:pt.:pd.:hp3.dd :ehp3.&colon. The day (1 - 31).
:pt.:pd.:hp3.yy :ehp3.&colon. The year (00 - 99, or a 4- digit year).
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=TIME.TIME:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
If you simply type DATE without any parameters, you will see the
current system date and time, and be prompted for a new date. Press ENTER
if you don't wish to change the date. If you type a new date, it will
become the current system date, which is included in the directory entry for
each file as it is created or altered&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] date
    Mon  Dec 22, 2017  9&colon.30&colon.06
    Enter new date (mm-dd-yy)&colon.
:exmp.:p.
You can also enter a new system date by typing the DATE command
plus the new date on the command line&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] date 10-16-17
:exmp.:p.
You can use hyphens, slashes, or periods to separate the month,
day, and year entries. The year can be entered as a 4-digit or 2-digit
value. Two-digit years between 80 and 99 are interpreted as 1980 - 1999;
values between 00 and 79 are interpreted as 2000 - 2079.
:p.
DATE adjusts the format it expects depending upon your country
settings. When entering the date, use the correct format for the
country setting currently in effect on your system.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=DEL.DEL - Delete one or more files
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Erase one file, a group of files, or entire
subdirectories.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.DEL [/A&colon.[[-]rhsda] /E /F /N /P /Q
/S /T /W /X /Y /Z] :ehp2.:hp3.file:ehp3. :hp2....:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.   or
:pt.:pd.:hp2.ERASE [/A&colon.[[-]rhsda] /E /F /N /P /Q /S /T /W /X /Y /Z]
:ehp2.:hp3.file:ehp3. :hp2....:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.file :ehp3.&colon. The file, subdirectory, or list of files or subdirectories to erase.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./A&colon.:ehp2. (ttribute select):pd.:hp2./S:ehp2.(ubdirectories)
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2. (no Error messages):pd.:hp2./T:ehp2.(otal)
:pt.:hp2./F:ehp2.(orce delete):pd.:hp2./W:ehp2.(ipe)
:pt.:hp2./N:ehp2.(othing):pd.:hp2./X:ehp2. (remove empty subdirectories)
:pt.:hp2./P:ehp2.(rompt):pd.:hp2./Y:ehp2.(es to all prompts)
:pt.:hp2./Q:ehp2.(uiet):pd.:hp2./Z:ehp2.(ap hidden and read-only files)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:hp2.File Selection:ehp2.
:p.
Supports extended :link reftype=hd refid=wildcards.wildcards:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=ranges.ranges:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=MultFiles.multiple filenames:elink., and :link reftype=hd refid=InclList.include lists:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
DEL and ERASE are synonyms, you can use either one.
:p.
Use the DEL and ERASE commands with caution; the files and
subdirectories that you erase may be impossible to recover without
specialized utilities and a lot of work.
:p.
To erase a single file, simply enter the filename&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] del letters.txt
:exmp.:p.
You can also erase multiple files in a single command. For
example, to erase all the files in the current directory with a
:hp1..BAK:ehp1. or :hp1..PRN:ehp1. extension&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] del *.bak *.prn
:exmp.:p.
When you use DEL on a volume supporting long filenames, you must quote any filenames
which contain whitespace or special characters. See :link reftype=hd
refid=Filenames.Filenames:elink. for additional details.
:p.
To exclude files from a DEL command, use a :link reftype=hd
refid=ExclRanges.file exclusion range:elink.&per. For example, to delete all
files in the current directory except those whose extension is
:hp1..TXT:ehp1., use a command like this&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] del /[!*.TXT] *.*
:exmp.:p.
When using exclusion ranges or other more complex options you may want to use
the :hp2./N:ehp2. switch first, to preview the effects of the DEL without
actually deleting any files.
:p.
If you enter a subdirectory name, or a filename composed only of
wildcards (* and/or ?), DEL asks for confirmation (:hp2.Y:ehp2. or
:hp2.N:ehp2.) unless you specified the :hp2./Y:ehp2. option. If you respond
with a :hp2.Y:ehp2., DEL will delete all the files in that subdirectory
(hidden, system, and read-only files are only deleted if you use the
:hp2./Z:ehp2. option).
:p.
DEL displays the amount of disk space recovered, unless the :hp2./Q:ehp2.
option is used (see below). It does so by comparing the amount of
free disk space before and after the DEL command is executed. This
amount may be incorrect if you are using a deletion tracking system
which stores deleted files in a hidden directory, or if, under a
multitasking system, another program performs a file operation
while the DEL command is executing.
:p.
Remember that DEL removes file descriptions along with files. Most
deletion tracking systems will not be able to save or recover a
file's description, even if they can save or recover the data in a
file.
:p.
When a file is deleted, its disk space is returned to the operating system
for use by other files. However, the contents of the file remain on the
disk until they are overwritten by another file. If you wish to obliterate
a file or wipe its contents clean, use DEL /W, which overwrites the file
with zeros before deleting it. Use this option with caution -- once a file
is obliterated, it is impossible to recover.
:p.
DEL returns a non-zero exit code if no files are deleted, or if
another error occurs. You can test this exit code with the
:link reftype=hd refid=_QMARK.%_?:elink. environment variable, and use it with
the :link reftype=hd refid=Conditional.conditional commands:elink.
:hp2.&amp.&amp.:ehp2. and :hp2.&splitvbar.&splitvbar.:ehp2.).
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./A&colon.:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Attribute select) Select only those files that have the
specified attribute(s) set. Preceding the attribute character with a
hyphen [:hp2.-:ehp2.] will select files that do not have that attribute set. The colon
[:hp2.&colon.:ehp2.] after :hp2./A:ehp2. is required. The attributes are&colon.
:parml tsize=8 compact break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  R:ehp2. Read-only
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  H:ehp2. Hidden
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  S:ehp2. System
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  D:ehp2. Subdirectory
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  A:ehp2. Archive
:eparml.:p.
If no attributes are listed at all (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., :hp2.DEL /A&colon. ...:ehp2.), DEL will select all
files and subdirectories including hidden and system files. If attributes are combined,
all the specified attributes must match for a file to be selected. For example,
/A&colon.RHS will select only those files with all three attributes set.
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(No error messages) Suppress all non-fatal
error messages, such as "File Not Found." Fatal error messages, such as
"Drive not ready," will still be displayed. This option is most useful in
batch files and aliases.
:pt.:hp2./F:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Force delete) This option forces deletion of the
file without saving it to the DELDIR directory (if DELDIR is not in use,
:hp2./F:ehp2. has no effect).
:pt.:hp2./N:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Nothing) Do everything except actually delete the
file(s). This is useful for testing what the result
of a DEL would be.
:pt.:hp2./P:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Prompt) Prompt the user to confirm each erasure. Your
options at the prompt are explained in detail under
:link reftype=hd refid=Prompts.Page and File Prompts:elink.&per.
:pt.:hp2./Q:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Quiet) Don't display filenames as they are deleted, or the
number of files deleted or bytes freed. See also :hp2./T:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:hp2./S:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Subdirectories) Delete the specified files in
this directory and all of its subdirectories. This can be used to delete
all the files in a subdirectory tree or even a whole disk. :hp8.It should
be used with caution!:ehp8.
:pt.:hp2./T:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Total) Don't display filenames as they are
deleted, but display the total number of files deleted plus the amount of
free disk space recovered. Unlike :hp2./Q:ehp2., the :hp2./T:ehp2. option
will not speed up deletions under DOS.
:pt.:hp2./W:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Wipe) Clear the file to zeros before deleting
it. Use this option to completely obliterate a file's contents from your
disk. Once you have used this option it is impossible to recover the file
even if you are using an undelete utility, because the contents of the file
are destroyed before it is deleted. :hp2./W:ehp2. overwrites the file only
once; it does :hp2.not:ehp2. adhere to security standards which require
multiple overwrites with varying data when destroying sensitive information.
:pt.:hp2./X:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Remove empty subdirectories) Remove empty subdirectories
after deleting (only useful when used with :hp2./S:ehp2.). If DEL deletes
one or more directories, they will be removed automatically from the :link
reftype=hd refid=ExtDirSearch.extended directory search:elink. database.
:pt.:hp2./Y:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Yes) The reverse of :hp2./P:ehp2. -- it assumes
a :hp2.Y:ehp2. response to everything, including deleting an entire
subdirectory tree. &4OS2. normally prompts before deleting files when the
name consists only of wildcards or a subdirectory name (see above);
:hp2./Y:ehp2. overrides this protection, and should be used with extreme
caution!
:pt.:hp2./Z:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Zap) Delete read-only, hidden, and system files as well
as normal files. Files with the read-only, hidden,
or system attribute set are normally protected from
deletion; :hp2./Z:ehp2. overrides this protection, and
should be used with caution. Because
:link reftype=hd refid=EXCEPT.EXCEPT:elink. works by hiding files, :hp2./Z:ehp2.
will override an EXCEPT command. However, files specified in a :link
reftype=hd refid=ExclRanges.file exclusion range:elink. will not be deleted
by DEL /Z.
:p.
For example, to delete the entire subdirectory tree starting with
C&colon.\UTIL, including hidden and read-only files, without prompting (use
this command with CAUTION!)&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] del /sxyz c&colon.\util\
:exmp.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=DELAY.DELAY - Pause for a specified length of time
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Pause for a specified length of time.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.DELAY [:ehp2.:hp3.seconds:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.seconds :ehp3.&colon. The number of seconds to delay.
:eparml.:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
DELAY is useful in batch file loops while waiting for something to
occur. To wait for 10 seconds&colon.
:xmp.
    delay 10
:exmp.:p.
DELAY is most useful when you need to wait a specific amount of time for an
external event, or check a system condition periodically. For example, this
batch file checks the battery status (as reported by your Advanced Power
Management drivers) every 15 seconds, and gives a warning when battery life
falls below 30%&colon.
:xmp.
    do forever
      iff %_apmlife lt 30 then
       beep 440 4 880 4 440 4 880 4
       echo Low Battery!!
      endiff
      delay 15
    enddo
:exmp.:p.
The seconds value can be as large as 4 million seconds (49 days).
:p.
For delays shorter than one second, use the :link reftype=hd
refid=BEEP.BEEP:elink. command with an inaudible frequency (below 20 Hz).
:p.
&4OS2. uses the minimum possible processor time during a DELAY, in order to
allow other applications full use of system resources.
:p.
You can cancel a delay by pressing :hp2.Ctrl-C:ehp2. or :hp2.Ctrl-Break:ehp2.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=DESCRIBE.DESCRIBE - Create or modify file descriptions
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Create, modify, or delete file and subdirectory
descriptions.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.DESCRIBE [/A&colon.[[-]rhsda]]:ehp2.
:hp3.file:ehp3. :hp2.[[/D]:ehp2.":hp3.description:ehp3. ":hp2.] ...:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.file :ehp3.&colon. The file, directory, or list of files and
directories to operate on.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.description :ehp3.&colon. The description to attach to the file.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./A&colon.:ehp2. (Attribute select):pd.:hp2./D:ehp2.(escription follows)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:hp2.File Selection:ehp2.
:p.
Supports extended :link reftype=hd refid=wildcards.wildcards:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=ranges.ranges:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=MultFiles.multiple filenames:elink., and :link reftype=hd refid=InclList.include lists:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
DESCRIBE adds descriptions to files and subdirectories. The
descriptions can be displayed by :link reftype=hd refid=DIR.DIR:elink. in
single-column mode and by :link reftype=hd
refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink.&per. Descriptions let you identify your files in
much more meaningful ways than you can in an eight-character filename.
:p.
You enter a description on the command line by typing the DESCRIBE
command, the filename, and the description in quotation marks, like
this&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] describe memo.txt "Memo to Bob about party"
:exmp.:p.
If you don't put a description on the command line, DESCRIBE will
prompt you for it&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] describe memo.txt
    Describe "memo.txt" &colon. Memo to Bob about party
:exmp.:p.
If you use wildcards or multiple filenames with the DESCRIBE
command and don't include the description text, you will be
prompted to enter a description for each file. If you do include
the description on the command line, all matching files will be
given the same description.
:p.
If you use DESCRIBE on a volume supporting long filenames, you must quote the :hp1.file:ehp1.
name if it contains whitespace or special characters. See :link
reftype=hd refid=Filenames.Filenames:elink. for additional details.
:p.
If you enter a quoted description on the command line, and the text
matches the name of a file in the current directory, the command
processor will treat the string as a quoted filename, not as
description text as you intended. To resolve this problem use the
:hp2./D:ehp2. switch immediately prior to the quoted description (with
no intervening spaces). For example, if the current directory contains
the files :hp1.DATA.TST:ehp1. and :hp1."Test File":ehp1., the first of
these commands will work as intended, but the second will not (in the
second example the string "test file" will be treated as a second file
name, when it is intended to be description text):
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] describe data.tst /D"test file"
    [c&colon.\] describe data.tst "test file"
:exmp.:p.
On volumes supporting long filenames you will not see file descriptions in a normal :link
reftype=hd refid=DIR.DIR:elink. display, because DIR must leave space
for the long filenames. To view the descriptions, use :hp2.DIR /Z:ehp2.
to display the directory in FAT16 format.
:p.
Each description can be up to 511 characters long. You can change this
limit with the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_DescriptionMax.DescriptionMax:elink.
directive in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. In order to fit your descriptions on a
single line in a standard DIR display, keep them to 4o characters or less
(longer descriptions are wrapped in the DIR output). DESCRIBE can edit
descriptions longer than DescriptionMax (up to a limit of 511 characters),
but will not allow you to lengthen the existing text.
:p.
The descriptions are stored in each directory in a hidden file
called :hp1.DESCRIPT.ION:ehp1.&per. Use the :link reftype=hd refid=ATTRIB.ATTRIB:elink. command to
remove the hidden attribute from this file if you need to copy or
delete it. :hp1.DESCRIPT.ION:ehp1. is always created as a hidden file,
but will not be re-hidden by &4OS2. if you remove the hidden
attribute.
:p.
You can change the description file name with the :link reftype=hd
refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /D command, or the :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_DescriptionName.DescriptionName:elink. directive in &4OS2INI., and
retrieve it with the :link reftype=hd refid=_DName._DName:elink. internal
variable. Use caution when changing the description file name, as changing
the name from the default will make it difficult to transfer file
descriptions to another system.
:p.
The description file is modified appropriately whenever you perform
an internal command which affects it (such as
:link reftype=hd refid=COPY.COPY:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=MOVE.MOVE:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=DEL.DEL:elink.,
or :link reftype=hd refid=REN.RENAME:elink.), but not if you use an external
program (such as XCOPY or a visual shell). You can disable description
processing on the :link reftype=hd refid=Options1.Options 1 page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
with the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_Descriptions.Descriptions:elink. directive
in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink., or with
:link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /D.
:p.
When you :link reftype=hd refid=COPY.COPY:elink. or :link reftype=hd
refid=MOVE.MOVE:elink. files between two directories, both of which have
descriptions, and you use switches which enable processing of hidden files
(or you have removed the hidden attribute from :hp1.DESCRIPT.ION:ehp1.), you
must use caution to avoid overwriting existing file descriptions in the
:hp1.destination:ehp1. directory with the :hp1.DESCRIPT.ION:ehp1. file from
the :hp1.source:ehp1. directory. See the notes under the :hp2.Advanced
Features:ehp2. sections of COPY and MOVE for additional details.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./A&colon.:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Attribute select) Select only those files that have the
specified attribute(s) set. Preceding the attribute character with a
hyphen [:hp2.-:ehp2.] will select files that do not have that attribute set. The colon
[:hp2.&colon.:ehp2.] after :hp2./A:ehp2. is required. The attributes
are&colon.
:parml tsize=8 compact break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  R:ehp2. Read-only
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  H:ehp2. Hidden
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  S:ehp2. System
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  D:ehp2. Subdirectory
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  A:ehp2. Archive
:eparml.:p.
If no attributes are listed at all (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1.,
:hp2.DESCRIBE /A&colon. ...:ehp2.), DESCRIBE will
select all files and subdirectories including hidden and system files. If
attributes are combined, all the specified attributes must match for a
file to be selected. For example, /A&colon.RHS will select only those files
with all three attributes set.
:pt.:hp2./D:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Description follows) The quoted string
immediately following this switch is a description, not a filename.
Use :hp2./D:ehp2. to avoid any ambiguity in the meaning of quoted
strings. See the :hp2.Usage:ehp2. section above for details.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

