:h2 name=DETACH.DETACH - Start a program in detached mode
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Start an OS/2 program in detached mode.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.DETACH :ehp2.:hp3.command:ehp3.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.command :ehp3.&colon. The name of a command to execute,
including an optional drive and path specification.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=START.START:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
When you start a program with DETACH, that program cannot use the
keyboard, mouse, or video display. It is "detached" from the
normal means of user input and output. However, you can redirect
the program's standard I/O to other devices if necessary, using
:link reftype=hd refid=RedirPipe.redirection:elink. symbols.
:p.
The :hp2.command:ehp2. can be an internal command, external command,
alias, or batch file. If it is not an external command, &4OS2. will
detach a copy of itself to execute the command.
:p.
For example, the following command will detach a copy of &4OS2. to
run the batch file :hp1.XYZ.BTM:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] detach xyz.btm
:exmp.:p.
Once the program has started, &4OS2. returns to the prompt
immediately. It does not wait for a detached program to finish.
:p.
There is no standard way to stop a detached program. If the program does not
terminate on its own you must reboot the system or use an appropriate task
manager or external utility to stop it.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=DIR.DIR - Display directories
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display information about files and subdirectories.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.DIR [/1 /2 /4 /A[[&colon.][-]rhsda] /B
/D /E /F /G /H /I"text" /J /K /L /M /N /O[[&colon.][-]adeginrsu] /P /Q /R /S
/T[&colon.acw] /U /V /W /Z] [:ehp2.:hp3.file:ehp3. :hp2....]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.file :ehp3.&colon. The file, directory, or list of files or
directories to display.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./1:ehp2. (one column):pd.:hp2./L:ehp2.(ower case)
:pt.:hp2./2:ehp2. (two columns):pd.:hp2./M:ehp2. (suppress footer)
:pt.:hp2./4:ehp2. (four columns):pd.:hp2./N:ehp2.(ew format)
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.(ttribute select):pd.:hp2./O:ehp2.(rder)
:pt.:hp2./B:ehp2.(are):pd.:hp2./P:ehp2.(ause)
:pt.:hp2./D:ehp2.(isable color coding):pd.:hp2./Q:ehp2. (suppress non-fatal errors)
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2. (use upper case):pd.:hp2./R:ehp2. (disable wRap)
:pt.:hp2./F:ehp2.(ull path):pd.:hp2./S:ehp2.(ubdirectories)
:pt.:hp2./G:ehp2. (allocated size):pd.:hp2./T:ehp2. (aTtribute) or (Time)
:pt.:hp2./H:ehp2.(ide dots):pd.:hp2./U:ehp2. (sUmmary information)
:pt.:hp2./I:ehp2. (match descriptions):pd.:hp2./V:ehp2.(ertical sort)
:pt.:hp2./J:ehp2.(ustify names):pd.:hp2./W:ehp2.(ide)
:pt.:hp2./K:ehp2. (suppress header):pd.:hp2./Z:ehp2. (use FAT format)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=ATTRIB.ATTRIB:elink., :link
reftype=hd refid=DESCRIBE.DESCRIBE:elink., :link reftype=hd
refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink., and :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.File Selection:ehp2.
:p.
Supports extended :link reftype=hd refid=wildcards.wildcards:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=ranges.ranges:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=MultFiles.multiple filenames:elink., and :link reftype=hd refid=InclList.include lists:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
DIR can be used to display information about files from one or more
of your disk directories, in a wide range of formats. Depending upon
the options chosen, you can display the filename, attributes, and
size; the time and date of the last change to the file; the file
description; and the file's compression ratio. You can also
display information in 1, 2, 4, 5, or more columns, sort the files
several different ways, use color to distinguish file types, and
pause after each full screen.
:p.
The various DIR displays are controlled through options or
switches. The best way to learn how to use the many options
available with the DIR command is to experiment. You will soon
know which options you want to use regularly. You can select those
options permanently by using the :link reftype=hd refid=ALIAS.ALIAS:elink.
command.
:p.
For example, to display all the files in the current directory, in 2
columns, sorted vertically (down one column then down the next), and with a
pause at the end of each page&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir /2/p/v
:exmp.:p.
To set up this format as the default, using an alias&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias dir=*dir /2/p/v
:exmp.:p.
When you use DIR on a volume supporting long filenames, you must quote any file
names which contain whitespace or special characters. See :link reftype=hd
refid=Filenames.Filenames:elink. for additional details.
:p.
The following sections group DIR's features together in several
categories. Many of the sections move from a general discussion to more
technical material. If you find some of the information in a category too
detailed for your needs, feel free to skip to the beginning of the next
section. The sections are&colon.
:p.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:hp2.
:pt.:pd.Selecting Files
:pt.:pd.Default DIR Output Format
:pt.:pd.Switching Formats
:pt.:pd.Multiple Column Displays
:pt.:pd.Color-Coded Directories
:pt.:pd.Redirected Output
:pt.:pd.Other Notes
:pt.:pd.Options
:ehp2.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
:p.
:hp2.Selecting Files:ehp2.
:p.
DIR can display information about a single file or about several, dozens,
hundreds, or thousands of files at once. To display information about a
single file, just add the name of the file to the DIR command line&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir january.wks
:exmp.:p.
The simplest way to view information about several files at once is to use
wildcards. DIR can work with traditional wildcard characters (:hp2.*:ehp2.
and :hp2.?:ehp2.) and
the extended :link reftype=hd refid=Wildcards.wildcards:elink.&per. For example
to display all of the :hp1..WKS:ehp1. files in the current directory&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir *.wks
:exmp.:p.
To display all :hp1..TXT:ehp1. files whose names begin with A, B, or C&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir [abc]*.txt
:exmp.:p.
If you don't specify a filename, DIR defaults to :hp2.*.*:ehp2. on
traditional FAT16 volumes, and :hp2.*:ehp2. on volumes supporting long
filenames. This default displays all non-hidden files and subdirectories in the
current directory.
:p.
If you link two or more filenames together with spaces, DIR will
display all of the files that match the first name and then all of
the files that match the second name. You may use a different
drive and path for each filename. This example lists all of the
:hp1..WKS:ehp1. and then all of the :hp1..WK1:ehp1. files in the current
directory&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir *.wks *.wk1
:exmp.:p.
If you use an :link reftype=hd refid=InclList.include list:elink. to link
multiple filenames, DIR will display the matching filenames in a single
listing. Only the first filename in an include list can have a
path; the other files must be in the same path. This example
displays the same files as the previous example, but the :hp1..WKS:ehp1.
and :hp1..WK1:ehp1. files are intermixed&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir *.wks;*.wk1
:exmp.:p.
:p.
You can include files in the current or named directory plus all of its
subdirectories by using the :hp2./S:ehp2. option. This example displays all
of the :hp1..WKS:ehp1. and :hp1..WK1:ehp1. files in the D&colon.\DATA
directory and each of its subdirectories&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir /s d&colon.\data\*.wks;*.wk1
:exmp.:p.
You can also select files by their attributes by using the :hp2./A:ehp2.
option. For example, this command displays the names of all of the
subdirectories of the current directory&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir /a&colon.d
:exmp.:p.
Finally, with the :hp2./I:ehp2. option, DIR can select files to display
based on their descriptions (see the :link reftype=hd
refid=DESCRIBE.DESCRIBE:elink. command for more information on file
descriptions). DIR will display a file if its description matches the text
after the :hp2./I:ehp2. switch. The search is not case-sensitive. You can
use :link reftype=hd refid=Wildcards.wildcards:elink. and extended wildcards
as part of the text. For example, to display any file described as a "Test
File" you can use this command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir /i"test file"
:exmp.:p.
If you want to display files that include the words "test file" anywhere in
their descriptions, use extended wildcards like this&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir /i"*test file*"
:exmp.:p.
To display only those files which do :hp2.not:ehp2. have descriptions,
use&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir /I"[]"
:exmp.:p.
In addition, you can use :link reftype=hd refid=TOC_Ranges.ranges:elink. to
select or exclude specific sets of files. For example, to display all files
modified in the last week, all files except those with a :hp1..BAK:ehp1.
extension, and all files over 500 KB in size&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir /[d-7]
    [c&colon.\] dir /[!*.bak]
    [c&colon.\] dir /[s500K]
:exmp.:p.
You can, of course, mix any of these file selection techniques in whatever
ways suit your needs.
:p.
:hp2.Default DIR Output Format:ehp2.
:p.
DIR's output varies based on the type of volume or drive on which the files
are stored. On a volume supporting long filenames, the default DIR format contains 4
columns&colon. the date of the last file modification or write, the
time of last write, the file size in bytes, and the filename. The name is
displayed as it is stored on the disk, in upper, lower, or mixed case. DIR
will wrap filenames from one line to the next if they are too long to fit the
width of the display. The standard output format is&colon.
:xmp.
     Volume in drive C is C - BOOTUP  Serial ...
     Directory of C&colon.\4OS2301\*.*

    10-24-16 12&colon.17     <DIR>  .
    10-24-16 12&colon.17     <DIR>  ..
    10-28-16  7&colon.57       967 4os2 3.txt
    10-21-16 18&colon.08     212,854 4OS2.EXE
    11-02-16 10&colon.08       45 4OS2.INI
:exmp.:p.
(See :hp2.Switching Formats:ehp2. below for information on changing the
standard long filename format to allow room for file descriptions.)
:p.
On FAT16 volumes which do not support long filenames, the default DIR format
contains 5 columns&colon. the filename, the file size in bytes, the date of
the last write, the time of the last write, and the file's description. File
names are listed in lower-case; directory names in upper case&colon.
:xmp.
     Volume in drive C is C - BOOTUP  Serial ...
     Directory of C&colon.\4OS230\*.*

    .           <DIR>     10-24-16  12&colon.17
    ..          <DIR>     10-24-16  12&colon.17
    TEST         <DIR>     11-01-16  16&colon.21
    4os23.txt         967  10-28-16   7&colon.57
    4os2.exe       212854  10-21-16  18&colon.08 4OS2 exe ...
    4os2.ini           45  11-02-16  10&colon.08 4OS2 conf ...
:exmp.:p.
DIR's output is normally sorted by name, with directories listed first. You
can change the sort order with the :hp2./O:ehp2. option. For example, these
two commands sort the output by date -- the first command lists the oldest
file first; the second command lists the oldest file last&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir /o&colon.d
    [c&colon.\] dir /o&colon.-d
:exmp.:p.
When displaying file descriptions, DIR wraps long lines to fit
on the screen. DIR displays a maximum of 40 characters of text in
each line of a description, unless your screen width allows a wider
display. If you disable description wrapping with the :hp2./R:ehp2.
option, the description is truncated at the right edge of the
screen, and a right arrow [:hp2.:ehp2.] is added at the end of the line to
alert you to the existence of additional description text.
:p.
Regardless of the volume type, DIR's default output is sorted. It displays
directory names first, with "<DIR>" inserted instead of a file size, and then
filenames. DIR assumes that sequences of digits should be sorted numerically
(for example, the file :hp1.DRAW2:ehp1. is listed before :hp1.DRAW03:ehp1.
because 2 is numerically smaller than 03), rather than strictly
alphabetically (where :hp1.DRAW2 :ehp1.would come second because "2" is
after "0" in alphanumeric order). You can change the sort order with the
:hp2./O:ehp2. option. When DIR displays filenames in a multi-column
format, it sorts filenames horizontally unless you use the :hp2./V:ehp2.
option to display vertically sorted output.
:p.
DIR's display can be modified in many ways to meet different needs. Most of
the following sections describes the various ways you can change DIR's output
format.
:p.
:hp2.Switching Formats:ehp2.
:p.
On volumes supporting long filenames, you can force DIR to use a FAT-like format
(filename first, followed by file information) with the :hp2./Z:ehp2. option. If
necessary, DIR /Z truncates long filenames on volumes supporting long filenames,
and adds a right arrow [:hp2.:ehp2.] to show that the name contains additional
characters.
:p.
The standard long filename output format does not provide enough space to show
descriptions along with filenames. Therefore, if you wish to view file
descriptions as part of the DIR listing on a volume supporting long filenames,
you :hp2.must:ehp2. use the :hp2./Z:ehp2. option.
:p.
If you use the :hp2./B:ehp2. option, DIR displays just filenames and omits
the file size, time stamp, and description for each file, for example&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir i* /b

    IBMCOM
    IBMI18N
    IBMINST
    IBMVESA
    IBMLVL.INI
    .....
:exmp.:p.
There are several ways to modify the display produced by :hp2./B:ehp2.&per. The
:hp2./F:ehp2. option is similar to :hp2./B:ehp2., but displays the full path
and name of each file, instead of just its name. To view the same
information for a directory and its subdirectories use :hp2./B:ehp2.
:hp2./S:ehp2. or :hp2./F:ehp2. :hp2./S:ehp2.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Multiple Column Displays:ehp2.
:p.
DIR has three options, :hp2./2:ehp2., :hp2./4:ehp2., and :hp2./W:ehp2., that
create multi-column displays. On volumes supporting long filenames, all three
of these options force the use of truncated names.
:p.
The :hp2./2:ehp2. option creates a 2-column display. On volumes supporting
long filenames, only the name of each file is displayed, with directory names
placed in square brackets to distinguish them from filenames. On FAT16 volumes,
support long filenames, or when :hp2./Z:ehp2. or :hp2./X:ehp2. is used (see
below), the display includes the name, file size, and time stamp for each
file.
:p.
The :hp2./4:ehp2. option is similar to :hp2./2:ehp2., but displays directory
information in 4 columns.    On drives which do not support long filenames, or
when :hp2./Z:ehp2. or :hp2./X:ehp2. is used (see below), the display shows
the filename and the file size in kilobytes (KB) or megabytes (MB), with
"<D>" in the size column for directories.
:p.
The :hp2./W:ehp2. option displays directory information in 5 or more
columns, depending upon your screen width. Each entry in a :hp2.DIR /W:ehp2.
display contains either the name of a file or the name of a
directory. Directory names are placed in square brackets to distinguish
them from filenames.
:p.
If you use one of these options on a volume supporting long filenames
and do not select an alternate display format with :hp2./Z:ehp2. or
:hp2./X:ehp2., the actual number of columns will be based on the longest
name to be displayed and your screen width, and may be less than the number
you requested (for example, you might see only three columns even though you
used :hp2./4:ehp2.). If the longest name is too long to fit in on a single
line the display will be reduced to one column, and each name will be
wrapped, with "extra" blank lines added so that each name takes the same
number of lines.
:p.
:hp2.Color-Coded Directories:ehp2.
:p.
The DIR command can display each filename and the associated file
information in a different color, depending upon the file's extension.
:p.
To choose the display colors, you must either use the :link reftype=hd
refid=SET.SET:elink. command to create an environment variable called
:link reftype=hd refid=COLORDIR_Var.COLORDIR:elink., use the
:link reftype=hd refid=CommandsOption.Commands page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
or a text editor to set the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_ColorDir.ColorDir:elink.
directive in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. If you do not
use the COLORDIR variable or the ColorDir directive, DIR will use the default
screen colors for all files.
:p.
If you use both the COLORDIR variable and the ColorDir directive, the
environment variable will override the settings in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. You may find it useful to
use the COLORDIR variable for experimenting, then to set permanent directory
colors with the ColorDir directive.
:p.
The format for both the COLORDIR environment variable and the ColorDir
directive in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. is&colon.
:xmp.
    ext ... &colon.ColorName; ...
:exmp.:p.
where "ext" is a file extension (which may include wildcards) or one of the
following file types&colon.
:xmp.
    DIRS        Directories
    RDONLY      Read-only files
    HIDDEN      Hidden files
    SYSTEM      System files
    ARCHIVE     Files modified since the last backup
:exmp.:p.
and "ColorName" is any valid color name (see :link reftype=hd
refid=Colors.Colors and Color Names:elink.).
:p.
Unlike most color specifications, the background portion of the color name
may be omitted for directory colors. If you don't specify a background
color, DIR will use the current screen background color.
:p.
For example, to display the :hp1..COM:ehp1. and :hp1..EXE:ehp1. files in red
on the current background, the :hp1..C:ehp1. and :hp1..ASM:ehp1. files in
bright cyan on the current background, and the read-only files in blinking
green on white (this should be entered on one line)&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] set colordir=com exe&colon.red; c asm&colon.bright cyan;
       rdonly&colon.blink green on white
:exmp.:p.
Extended :link reftype=hd refid=Wildcards.wildcards:elink. can be used in
directory color specifications. For example, to display :hp1..BAK:ehp1.,
:hp1..BAX:ehp1., and :hp1..BAC:ehp1. files in red&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] set colordir=BA[KXC]&colon.red
:exmp.:p.
:hp2. Redirected Output:ehp2.
:p.
The output of the DIR command, like that of most other internal commands, can
be redirected to a file, printer, serial port, or other device. However, you
may need to take certain DIR command options into account when you redirect
DIR's output.
:p.
DIR wraps both long filenames and file descriptions at the width of your
display. Its redirected output will also wrap at the screen width. Use the
:hp2./R:ehp2. option if you wish to disable wrapping of long descriptions.
:p.
If you redirect a color-coded directory to a file, DIR will remove the color
data as it sends the directory information to a file. It will usually do the
same if you redirect output to a character device such as a printer or serial
port. However, it is not always possible for DIR to tell whether or not a
device is a character device. If you notice that non-colored lines are being
sent to the output device and colored lines are appearing on your screen, you
can use the :hp2./D:ehp2. option to temporarily disable color-coding when
you redirect DIR's output.
:p.
To redirect DIR output to the clipboard, use CLIP&colon. as the output
device name, for example&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir *.exe > clip&colon.
:exmp.:p.
:hp2.Other Notes:ehp2.
:p.
If you have selected a specific country code for your system, DIR will
display the date in the format for that country. The default date format is
U.S. (mm-dd-yy). The separator character in the file time will also be
affected by the country code. Thousands and decimal separators in numeric
displays are affected by the country code, and by the :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_ThousandsChar.ThousandsChar:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_DecimalChar.DecimalChar:elink. settings selected
on the :link reftype=hd refid=Options1.Options 1 page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.
or in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:p.
Options on the command line apply only to the filenames which
follow the option, and options at the end of the line apply to the
preceding filename only. This allows you to specify different
options for different groups of files, yet retains compatibility
with the traditional DIR command when a single filename is
specified.
:lm margin=4.:parml compact tsize=8 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./1:ehp2.&colon.:pd.Single column display -- display the filename,
size, date, and time; also displays the description on drives which do not
support long filenames. This is the default. If :hp2./T:ehp2. is used the
attributes are displayed instead of the description. This option is most
useful if you wish to override a default :hp2./2:ehp2., :hp2./4:ehp2., or
:hp2./W:ehp2. setting stored in an alias.
.br
:pt.:hp2./2:ehp2.&colon.:pd.Two column display -- display just the name (on
volumes supporting long filenames), or display the filename, size, date, and time on other
drives. See :hp2.Multiple Column Displays:ehp2. above for more details.
.br
:pt.:hp2./4:ehp2.&colon.:pd.Four column display -- display just the name (on
volumes supporting long filenames); or display the filename and size, in K (kilobytes) or M
(megabytes), with files between 1 and 9.9 megabytes in size displayed in
tenths (:hp1.i.e.:ehp1. "2.4M"). See :hp2.Multiple Column Displays:ehp2.
above for more details.
.br
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Attribute select) Select only those files that have the
specified attribute(s) set. Preceding the attribute character with a
hyphen [:hp2.-:ehp2.] will select files that do not have that attribute set. The colon
[:hp2.&colon.:ehp2.] after :hp2./A:ehp2. is optional. The attributes
are&colon.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  R:ehp2. Read-only
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  H:ehp2. Hidden
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  S:ehp2. System
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  D:ehp2. Subdirectory
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  A:ehp2. Archive
:p.
If no attributes are listed at all (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., :hp2.DIR /A ...:ehp2.), DIR will display
all files and subdirectories including hidden and system files. If attributes
are combined, all the specified attributes must match for a file to be included in the
listing. For example, :hp2./A&colon.RHS:ehp2. will display only those files
with all three attributes set.
.br
:pt.:hp2./B:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Bare) Suppress the header and summary lines,
and display file or subdirectory names only, in a single column. This option
is most useful when you want to redirect a list of names to a file or
another program. If you use :hp2./B:ehp2. with :hp2./S:ehp2., DIR will show
the full path of each file (the same display as :hp2./F:ehp2.) instead of
simply its name and extension.
.br
:pt.:hp2./D:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Disable color coding) Temporarily disable directory color
coding. May be required when color-coded directories are used and DIR output is
redirected to a character device like the printer (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., PRN
or LPT1) or serial port (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., COM1 or COM2). :hp2./D:ehp2. is not required
when DIR output is redirected to a file.
.br
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2.&colon.:pd.Display filenames in the traditional upper case;
also see :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /U and the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_UpperCase.UpperCase:elink. directive in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
.br
:pt.:hp2./F:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Full path) Display each filename with its
drive letter and path in a single column, without other information. If you
use :hp2./F:ehp2. with :hp2./X:ehp2. on a volume which supports long
filenames, the "short" version of the entire path is displayed.
.br
:pt.:hp2./G:ehp2.&colon.:pd.Display the allocated disk space instead of the
actual size of each file.
.br
:pt.:hp2./H:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Hide dots) Suppress the display of the "." and
".." directories.
.br
:pt.:hp2./I:ehp2.&colon.:pd.Display filenames by matching text in their
descriptions. The text can include wildcards and extended wildcards. The
search text must be enclosed in quotation marks. You can select all
filenames that have a description with :hp2./I"[?]*":ehp2., or all
filenames that do not have a description with :hp2./I"[]":ehp2.&per.
:p.
The :hp2./I:ehp2. option may be used to select files even if descriptions are
not displayed (for example, if :hp2./2:ehp2. is used). However,
:hp2./I:ehp2. will be ignored if :hp2./O&colon.c:ehp2. is used.
.br
:pt.:hp2./J:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Justify names) Justify (align) filename
extensions and display them in the traditional format.
.br
:pt.:hp2./K:ehp2.&colon.:pd.Suppress the header (disk and directory name)
display.
.br
:pt.:hp2./L:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Lower case) Display file and directory names in lower case;
also see :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /U and the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_UpperCase.UpperCase:elink. directive in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
.br
:pt.:hp2./M:ehp2.&colon.:pd.Suppress the footer (file and byte count totals)
display.
.br
:pt.:hp2./N:ehp2.&colon.:pd.Use the HPFS/JFS display format, even if the files are
stored on a volume which does not support long filenames. See also :hp2./Z:ehp2.&per.
.br
:pt.:hp2./O:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Order) Set the sorting order. You may use any
combination of the following sorting options; if multiple options are used,
the listing will be sorted with the first sort option as the primary key,
the next as the secondary key, and so on&colon.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  -:ehp2. Reverse the sort order for the next option.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  a:ehp2. Sort in ASCII order, not numerically, when there are digits in the name.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  d:ehp2. Sort by date and time (oldest first); for volumes supporting long filenames, also see :hp2./T:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  e:ehp2. Sort by extension.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  g:ehp2. Group subdirectories first, then files.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  i:ehp2. Sort by file description (ignored if :hp2./O&colon.c:ehp2. is used).
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  n:ehp2. Sort by filename (this is the default).
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  r:ehp2. Reverse the sort order for all options.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  s:ehp2. Sort by size.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  u:ehp2. Unsorted.
:p.
:pt.:hp2./P:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Pause) Wait for a key to be pressed after each screen page
before continuing the display. Your options at the prompt are explained in detail under
:link reftype=hd refid=Prompts.Page and File Prompts:elink.&per.
.br
:pt.:hp2./Q:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Suppress non-fatal errors) This option suppresses error 
messages.
.br
:pt.:hp2./R:ehp2.:pd.(disable wRap) Forces long descriptions to be displayed
on a single line, rather than wrapped onto two or more lines. Use :hp2./R:ehp2. when
output is redirected to a character device, such as a serial port or the printer;
or when you want descriptions truncated, rather than wrapped, in the on-screen display.
.br
:pt.:hp2./S:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Subdirectories) Display file information from
the current directory and all of its subdirectories. DIR will only display
headers and summaries for those directories which contain files that match
the filename(s), ranges, and attributes that you specify on the command line.
.br
:pt.:hp2./T:ehp2.:pd.(aTtribute display) Display the filenames, attributes, and
descriptions. The descriptions will be wrapped onto the next line, if
necessary, unless you also use the :hp2./R:ehp2. (truncate) option. If you use
both :hp2./T:ehp2. and :hp2./R:ehp2., descriptions are truncated after 34 characters
on an 80-column display. The attributes are displayed in the format RHSA, with
the following meanings&colon.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  R:ehp2. Read-only
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  H:ehp2. Hidden
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  D:ehp2. Directory
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  S:ehp2. System
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  A:ehp2. Archive
:p.
On volumes supporting long filenames, if you wish to add another option after :hp2./T:ehp2., you
must start the next option with a forward slash (:hp2./:ehp2.). If you don't, &4OS2. will
interpret the :hp2./T:ehp2. as the time display switch and the
following character as a valid or invalid time selector. For example&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir /tz     incorrect, will display error
    [c&colon.\] dir /t/z    correct
:exmp.
:pt.:hp2./T&colon.acw:ehp2.:pd.(Time display) Specify which of the date and time
fields on a volume supporting multiple timestamps should be displayed and used
for sorting&colon.
.br
:pt.:pd.  :hp2.a:ehp2. Last access date and time.
:pt.:pd.  :hp2.c:ehp2. Creation date and time.
:pt.:pd.  :hp2.w:ehp2. Last write date and time (default).
.br
:pt.:hp2./U:ehp2.:pd.(sUmmary information) Only display the number of
files, the total file size, and the total amount of disk space
used. Information on individual files is not displayed.
.br
:pt.:hp2./V:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Vertical sort) Display the filenames sorted
vertically rather than horizontally (use with the :hp2./2:ehp2.,
:hp2./4:ehp2. or :hp2./W:ehp2. options).
.br
:pt.:hp2./W:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Wide) Display filenames only, horizontally
across the screen. On FAT16 volumes, :hp2./W:ehp2. displays as many columns as
it can fit into the command processor window, using 16 characters in each
column. Otherwise (i.e., when long filenames are displayed) the number of
columns depends upon the width of the longest name in the listing. See
:hp2.Multiple Column Displays:ehp2. above for more details.
.br
:pt.:hp2./Z:ehp2.&colon.:pd.Display the directory for a volume supporting
long filenames in the FAT16 format, with the filename at the left and the
description at the right. Long names will be truncated to 12 characters unless
:hp2./X:ehp2. is also used; if the name is longer than 12 characters, it will
be followed by a right arrow [:hp2.:ehp2.] to show that one or more characters
have been truncated.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

