:h2 name=DIRHISTORY.DIRHISTORY - Display, read, or modify the directory history list
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display, add to, clear, or read the
directory history list.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.DIRHISTORY [/A:ehp2. :hp3.directory:ehp3.
:hp2./F /P /R:ehp2. :hp3.filename:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.directory :ehp3.&colon. The name of a directory to be added to
the directory history.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.filename :ehp3.&colon. The name of a file containing entries to
be added to the directory history.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.(dd):pd.:hp2./P:ehp2.(ause)
:pt.:hp2./F:ehp2.(ree):pd.:hp2./R:ehp2.(ead)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=HISTORY.HISTORY:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
Every time you change to a new directory or drive, &4OS2. records the current
directory in an internal directory history list. See :link reftype=hd
refid=DirHist.Directory History:elink. for information on directory history
window, which allows you to use the list to return to a previous
directory. Also see :link reftype=hd refid=DirNav.Directory
Navigation:elink.&per.
:p.
The DIRHISTORY command lets you view and manipulate the directory history
list directly. If no parameters are entered, DIRHISTORY will display the
current directory history list&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dirhistory
:exmp.:p.
With the options explained below, you can clear the list, add new directories
to the list without changing to them, save the list in a file, or read a new
list from a file.
:p.
The number of directories saved in the directory history list depends upon the
length of each directory name. The list size can be specified at startup
from 256 to 32767 characters by using the :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_DirHistory.DirHistory:elink. directive in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:p.
Your directory history list can be stored either locally (a separate history
list for each copy of the command processor) or globally (all copies of the
command processor share the same list). See :link reftype=hd
refid=DirHist.Directory History:elink. for the discussion of local and
global directory history lists.
:p.
You can save the directory history list by redirecting the output of
DIRHISTORY to a file. This example saves the history to a file called
:hp1.DIRHIST:ehp1. and reads it back again&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dirhistory > dirhist
      .....
    [c&colon.\] dirhistory /r dirhist
:exmp.:p.
Because the directory history stores each name only once, you don't have to
delete its contents before reading back the file unless you want to delete
the directories that were visited by the intervening commands.
:p.
If you need to save your directory history at the end of each day's work, you
might use commands like this in your :hp1.4START.BTM:ehp1. file&colon.
:xmp.
    if exist c&colon.\dirhist dirhistory /r c&colon.\dirhist

    alias shut*down `dirhistory > c&colon.\dirhist`
:exmp.:p.
This restores the previous history list if it exists, then defines an alias
which will allow you to save the history before shutting off the system.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml compact tsize=8 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Add) Add a directory to the directory history
list.
:pt.:hp2./F:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Free) Erase all entries in the directory
history list.
:pt.:hp2./P:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Prompt) Wait for a key after displaying each
page of the list. Your options at the prompt are explained in :link
reftype=hd refid=Prompts.Page and File Prompts:elink.&per.
:pt.:hp2./R:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Read) Read the directory history from the
specified file and append it to the list currently held in memory.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=DIRS.DIRS - Display the directory stack
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display the current directory stack.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.DIRS:ehp2.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=PUSHD.PUSHD:elink., :link
reftype=hd refid=POPD.POPD:elink., and :link reftype=hd
refid=DirNav.Directory Navigation:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
The PUSHD command adds the current default drive and directory to
the directory stack, a list that &4OS2. maintains in memory. The
POPD command removes the top entry of the directory stack and makes
that drive and directory the new default. The DIRS command
displays the contents of the directory stack, with the most recent
entries on top (:hp1.i.e.:ehp1., the next POPD will retrieve the first
entry that DIRS displays).
:p.
The directory stack holds 511 characters, enough for 20 to 40
typical drive and directory entries.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=DO.DO - Create loops in batch files
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Create loops in batch files.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.DO [:ehp2.:hp3.n:ehp3. :hp2.&splitvbar.
FOREVER]:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.   or
:pt.:pd.:hp2.DO :ehp2.:hp3.varname:ehp3.:hp2. = :ehp2.:hp3.start:ehp3.
:hp2.TO :ehp2.:hp3.end:ehp3. :hp2.[BY :ehp2.:hp3.n:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.   or
:pt.:pd.:hp2.DO [WHILE &splitvbar. UNTIL] :ehp2.:hp3.condition:ehp3.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.DO:ehp2. :hp3.varname:ehp3. :hp2.IN [@]:ehp2.:hp3.set:ehp3.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.   commands:ehp3.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.[ITERATE]:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.[LEAVE]:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.   commands:ehp3.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.ENDDO:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.varname :ehp3.&colon. The environment variable that will hold
the loop counter, filename, or line from a file.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.n, start, end :ehp3.&colon. Integers between 0 and
2,147,483,647 inclusive, or an internal variables or variable functions that
evaluate to such a value.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.condition :ehp3.&colon. A test to determine if the loop should
be executed.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.set :ehp3.&colon. A set of values for the variable.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.commands :ehp3.&colon. One or more commands to execute each
time through the loop. If you use multiple commands, they must be separated
by command separators or be placed on separate lines.
:eparml.:p.
:hp2.File Selection:ehp2.
:p.
Supports extended :link reftype=hd refid=wildcards.wildcards:elink., :link
reftype=hd refid=ranges.ranges:elink.,
and :link reftype=hd refid=InclList.include lists:elink. for the
:hp1.set:ehp1.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
DO can only be used in batch files. It cannot be used in aliases.
:p.
DO can be used to create 4 different kinds of loops. The first,
introduced by :hp2.DO n:ehp2., is a counted loop. The batch file lines
between DO and ENDDO are repeated :hp1.n:ehp1. times. For example&colon.
:xmp.
    do 5
      beep
    enddo
:exmp.:p.
You can also specify "forever" for :hp1.n:ehp1. if you wish to create an
endless loop (you can use LEAVE or :link reftype=hd refid=GOTO.GOTO:elink.
to exit such a loop; see below for details).
:p.
The second type of loop is similar to a "for loop" in programming
languages like BASIC. DO creates an environment variable,
:hp1.varname:ehp1., and sets it equal to the value :hp1.start:ehp1. (if
:hp1.varname:ehp1. already exists in the environment, it will be
overwritten). DO then begins the loop process by comparing the
value of :hp1.varname:ehp1. with the value of :hp1.end. :ehp1. If :hp1.varname:ehp1. is
less than or equal to :hp1.end:ehp1., DO executes the batch file lines up
to the ENDDO. Next, DO adds 1 to the value of :hp1.varname:ehp1., or adds
the value :hp1.n:ehp1. if BY :hp1.n:ehp1. is specified, and repeats the compare
and execute process until :hp1.varname:ehp1. is greater than
:hp1.end:ehp1.&per. This example displays the even numbers from 2 through
20&colon.
:xmp.
    do i = 2 to 20 by 2
      echo %i
    enddo
:exmp.:p.
DO can also count down, rather than up. If :hp1.n:ehp1. is negative,
:hp1.varname:ehp1. will decrease by :hp1.n:ehp1. with each loop, and the loop
will stop when :hp1.varname:ehp1. is :hp2.less:ehp2. than :hp1.end:ehp1.&per. For
example, to display the even numbers from 2 through 20 in reverse order,
replace the first line of the example above with&colon.
:xmp.
    do i = 20 to 2 by -2
:exmp.:p.
The third type of loop is called a "while loop" or "until loop."
DO evaluates the :hp1.condition:ehp1., which can be any of the tests
supported by the :link reftype=hd refid=IF.IF:elink. command, and executes the lines between
DO and ENDDO as long as the condition is true. The loop ends when
the condition becomes false.
:p.
WHILE tests the condition at the start of the loop. Therefore, if the
condition is false when the loop starts, the statements within the loop will
never be executed, and the batch file will continue with the statement after
the ENDDO.
:p.
UNTIL tests the condition at the end of the loop. Therefore, if the
condition is false when the loop starts, the statements within the loop will
still be executed at least once.
:p.
The fourth type of loop executes the lines between DO and ENDDO once for
every member of a :hp1.set:ehp1. (this is similar to the set used in the
:link reftype=hd refid=FOR.FOR:elink. command). Normally, the
:hp1.set:ehp1. is a list of files specified with wildcards. For
example&colon.
:xmp.
    do x in *.txt
:exmp.:p.
will execute the loop once for every :hp1..TXT:ehp1. file in the current
directory; each time through the loop the variable :hp2.x:ehp2. will be set
to the name of the next file that matches the file specification.
:p.
If, between DO and ENDDO, you create a new file that :hp1.could:ehp1. be
included in the list of files, it may or may not appear in an iteration of
the DO loop. Whether the new file appears depends upon its physical location
in the directory structure, a condition over which &4OS2. has no control.
:p.
You can also execute the loop once for each line of text in a file by placing
an [:hp2.@:ehp2.] in front of the filename. If you have a file called
:hp1.DRIVES.TXT:ehp1. that contains a list of drives on your computer, one
drive name per line, you can execute the loop once for each drive this
way&colon.
:xmp.
    do x in @drives.txt
:exmp.:p.
To execute the loop once for each line of text in the clipboard, use
:hp2.CLIP&colon.:ehp2. as the filename (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1. DO X IN
@CLIP&colon.). CLIP&colon. will not return any data unless the clipboard
contains text. See :link reftype=hd refid=Redirection.Redirection:elink. for
additional information on CLIP&colon..
:p.
Two special commands, ITERATE and LEAVE, can only be used inside a
DO / ENDDO loop. ITERATE ignores the remaining lines inside the
loop and returns to the beginning of loop for another iteration
(unless DO determines that the loop is finished). LEAVE exits from
the current DO loop and continues with the line following ENDDO.
Both ITERATE and LEAVE are most often used in an :link reftype=hd refid=IF.IF:elink. or
:link reftype=hd refid=IFF.IFF:elink. command&colon.
:xmp.
    do while "%var" != "%var1"
      ...
      if "%var" == "%val2" leave
    enddo
:exmp.:p.
You can nest DO loops up to 15 levels deep.
:p.
The DO and ENDDO commands must be on separate lines, and cannot be placed
within a :link reftype=hd refid=Grouping.command group:elink., or on the
same line as other commands (this is the reason DO cannot be used in
aliases). However, commands within the DO loop can use command groups or
the :link reftype=hd refid=MultCmds.command separator:elink. in the normal
way.
:p.
You can exit from all DO / ENDDO loops by using GOTO to a line
past the last ENDDO. However, :hp8.be sure to read the cautionary notes:ehp8.
about GOTO and DO under the :link reftype=hd refid=GOTO.GOTO:elink. command
before using a GOTO in any other way inside any DO loop.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=DPATH.DPATH - Set the data search path
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Specify the subdirectories which applications will
search to find files that are not in the current directory.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.DPATH [:ehp2.:hp3.directory:ehp3.
:hp2.[;:ehp2.:hp3.directory...:ehp3. :hp2.]]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.directory :ehp3.&colon. The full name of a directory to
include in the DPATH (data path) setting.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=PATH.PATH:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=SET.SET:elink., and :link reftype=hd refid=ESET.ESET:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
When most OS/2 applications try to open a data file,
they look for the file in the current directory first. If they
fail to find the file there, they may search each of the directories in
the DPATH setting in the order that they are included. Internal
commands like TYPE do not search the DPATH directories for files.
:p.
For example, the following DPATH command directs applications to
look for files in this order&colon. the current directory, the :hp1.INIT:ehp1.
directory on C, and the :hp1.CONFIG:ehp1. directory on D&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dpath c&colon.\init;d&colon.\config
:exmp.:p.
The listing of directories to be searched can be set or viewed with
DPATH. The list is stored as an environment string with the
variable name DPATH, and can also be set or viewed with the
:link reftype=hd refid=SET.SET:elink. command and edited with the :link reftype=hd refid=ESET.ESET:elink. command.
:p.
Directory names in the DPATH must be separated with semicolons
[:hp2.;:ehp2.]. &4OS2. will :hp2.not:ehp2. shift directory names in
the DPATH to upper case as it does with those in the PATH setting. If
you want the names in the DPATH to be in upper case you must
enter them that way.
:p.
If you enter DPATH with no parameters, &4OS2. displays the current DPATH
search list.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=DRAWBOX.DRAWBOX - Draw a box
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Draw a box on the screen.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.DRAWBOX :ehp2.:hp3.ulrow ulcol lrrow
lrcol style:ehp3. :hp2.[BRIght] [BLInk] fg ON [BRIght] bg [FILl [BRIght]
:ehp2.:hp3.bgfill:ehp3. :hp2.] [ZOOm] [SHAdow]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.ulrow :ehp3.&colon. Row for upper left corner
:pt.:pd.:hp3.ulcol :ehp3.&colon. Column for upper left corner
:pt.:pd.:hp3.lrrow :ehp3.&colon. Row for lower right corner
:pt.:pd.:hp3.lrcol :ehp3.&colon. Column for lower right corner
:pt.:pd.:hp3.style :ehp3.&colon. Box drawing style&colon.
.* FIX FIX FIX sub-indentation
:pt.:pd.       :hp2.0:ehp2.    No lines (box is drawn with blanks)
:pt.:pd.       :hp2.1:ehp2.    Single line
:pt.:pd.       :hp2.2:ehp2.    Double line
:pt.:pd.       :hp2.3:ehp2.    Single line on top and bottom, double on sides
:pt.:pd.       :hp2.4:ehp2.    Double line on top and bottom, single on sides
:pt.:pd.:hp3.fg :ehp3.&colon. Foreground character color
:pt.:pd.:hp3.bg :ehp3.&colon. Background character color
:pt.:pd.:hp3.bgfill :ehp3.&colon. Background fill color (for the inside of the box)
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=DRAWHLINE.DRAWHLINE:elink. and :link reftype=hd refid=DRAWVLINE.DRAWVLINE:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
DRAWBOX is useful for creating attractive screen displays in batch
files.
:p.
For example, to draw a box around the edge of an 80x25 screen with bright
white lines on a blue background&colon.
:xmp.
    drawbox 0 0 24 79 1 bri whi on blu fill blu
:exmp.:p.
See :link reftype=hd refid=Colors.Colors and Color Names:elink. for details about colors and
notes on the use of bright background colors.
:p.
If you use ZOOM, the box appears to grow in steps to its final
size. The speed of the zoom operation depends upon the speed of your
computer and video system.
:p.
If you use SHADOW, a drop shadow is created by changing the
characters in the row under the box and the 2 columns to the right
of the box to normal intensity text with a black background (this
will make characters displayed in black disappear entirely).
:p.
The row and column values are zero-based, so on a standard 25 line
by 80 column display, valid rows are 0 - 24 and valid columns are
0 - 79.
:p.
DRAWBOX checks for valid row and column values, and displays a
"Usage" error message if any values are out of range.
:p.
Unlike DRAWHLINE and DRAWVLINE, DRAWBOX does :hp2.not:ehp2. automatically
connect boxes to existing lines on the screen with the proper
connector characters. If you want to draw lines inside a box and
have the proper connectors drawn automatically, draw the box first,
then use DRAWHLINE and DRAWVLINE to draw the lines.
:p.
DRAWBOX uses the standard line and box drawing characters in the
U.S. English extended ASCII character set. If your system is
configured for a different country or language, or a font which does not
include these characters, the box may not appear on your screen as you expect.

