:h2 name=ECHO.ECHO and ECHOERR - Display a message / set echo state
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display a message, enable or disable batch file or
command-line echoing, or display the echo status.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.ECHO [ON &splitvbar. OFF &splitvbar.
:ehp2.:hp3.message:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.ECHOERR:ehp2. :hp3.message:ehp3.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.message :ehp3.&colon. Text to display.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=ECHOS.ECHOS:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=SCREEN.SCREEN:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=SCRPUT.SCRPUT:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. and :link reftype=hd refid=TEXT.TEXT:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
&4OS2. has a separate echo capability for batch files and for the
command line. The command-line ECHO state is independent of the
batch file ECHO state; changing ECHO in a batch file has no effect
on the display at the command prompt, and vice versa.
:p.
To see the current echo state, use the ECHO command with no
arguments. This displays either the batch file or command-line
echo state, depending upon where the ECHO command is performed.
:p.
In a batch file, if you turn ECHO on, each line of the file is
displayed before it is executed. If you turn ECHO off, each line
is executed without being displayed. ECHO can also be used in a
batch file to display a message on the screen. Regardless of the
ECHO state, a batch file line that begins with the [:hp2.@:ehp2.]
character will not be displayed. To turn off batch file echoing,
without displaying the ECHO command, use this line&colon.
:xmp.
    @echo off
:exmp.:p.
ECHO commands in a batch file will send messages to the screen
while the batch file executes, even if ECHO is set OFF. For
example, this line will display a message in a batch file&colon.
:xmp.
    echo Processing your print files...
:exmp.:p.
If you want to echo a blank line from within a batch file, enter&colon.
:xmp.
    echo.
:exmp.:p.
You cannot use the command separator character [:hp2.&amp.:ehp2.],
or the redirection symbols [:hp2.&splitvbar. > <:ehp2.]
in an ECHO message, unless you enclose them in quotes (see
:link reftype=hd refid=Quoting.Argument Quoting:elink.) or precede them with
the :link reftype=hd refid=Escape.escape character:elink.&per.
:p.
ECHO defaults to ON in batch files. The current ECHO state is
inherited by called batch files. You can change the default
setting to ECHO OFF with the :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /V0
command, the :link reftype=hd refid=Options1.Options 1 page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
or the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_BatchEcho.BatchEcho:elink. directive in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:p.
If you turn the command-line ECHO on, each command will be
displayed before it is executed. This will let you see the command
line after expansion of all aliases and variables. The command-line ECHO is
most useful when you are learning how to use advanced
features. This example will turn command-line echoing on&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] echo on
:exmp.:p.
ECHO defaults to OFF at the command line.
:p.
ECHOERR acts like ECHO but sends its output to the standard error device
(usually the screen) instead of the standard output device. If the standard
output of a batch file is redirected to a file or another device with
:hp2.>:ehp2., ECHOERR will still generate a screen message. See :link
reftype=hd refid=RedirPipe.Redirection and Piping:elink. for more information
about the standard output and standard error devices and redirection.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=ECHOS.ECHOS and ECHOSERR - Display a message without CR/LF
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display a message without a trailing
carriage return and line feed.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.ECHOS:ehp2. :hp3.message:ehp3.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.ECHOSERR:ehp2. :hp3.message:ehp3.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=ECHO.ECHO:elink., :link reftype=hd
refid=SCREEN.SCREEN:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=SCRPUT.SCRPUT:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=TEXT.TEXT:elink., and :link reftype=hd
refid=VSCRPUT.VSCRPUT:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
ECHOS is useful for text output when you don't want to add a
carriage return / linefeed pair at the end of the line. For
example, you can use ECHOS when you need to redirect control
sequences to your printer; this example sends the sequence :hp2.Esc
P:ehp2. to the printer on LPT1&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] echos :hp2.^:ehp2.eP > lpt1&colon.
:exmp.:p.
You cannot use the command separator character [:hp2.&amp.:ehp2.]
or the redirection symbols [:hp2.&splitvbar. > <:ehp2.]
in an ECHOS message, unless you enclose them in quotes (see
:link reftype=hd refid=Quoting.Argument Quoting:elink.) or precede them with the :link reftype=hd refid=Escape.escape character:elink.&per.
:p.
ECHOS does not translate or modify the message text. For example,
carriage return characters are not translated to CR/LF pairs. ECHOS sends
only the characters you enter (after :link reftype=hd refid=Escape.escape character:elink. and back quote
processing). The only character you cannot put into an ECHOS message is the
NUL character (ASCII 0).
:p.
ECHOSERR acts like ECHOS but sends its output to the standard error device
(usually the screen) instead of the standard output device. If the standard
output of a batch file is redirected to a file or another device with
:hp2.>:ehp2., ECHOSERR will still generate a screen message. See :link
reftype=hd refid=RedirPipe.Redirection and Piping:elink. for more
information about the standard output and standard error devices and
redirection.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=ENDLOCAL.ENDLOCAL - Restore the saved environment
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Restore the saved disk drive, directory,
environment, alias list, and special characters.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.ENDLOCAL:ehp2.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=SETLOCAL.SETLOCAL:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
The SETLOCAL command in a batch file saves the current disk drive,
default directory, all environment variables, the alias
list, and the command separator, :link reftype=hd refid=Escape.escape character:elink., parameter character,
decimal separator, and thousands separator. ENDLOCAL restores everything
that was saved by the previous SETLOCAL command.
:p.
For example, this batch file fragment saves everything, removes all aliases
so that user aliases will not affect batch file commands, changes the disk
and directory, changes the command separator, runs a program, and then
restores the original values&colon.
:xmp.
    setlocal
    unalias *
    cdd d&colon.\test
    setdos /c~
    program ~ echo Done!
    endlocal
:exmp.:p.
SETLOCAL and ENDLOCAL can only be used in batch files, not in
aliases or from the command line.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=ESET.ESET - Edit environment variables and aliases
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Edit environment variables and aliases.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.ESET [/A] :ehp2.:hp3.variable name:ehp3.
:hp2....:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.variable name :ehp3.&colon. The name of an environment variable or alias to edit.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.(lias)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=ALIAS.ALIAS:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=UNALIAS.UNALIAS:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=SET.SET:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=UNSET.UNSET:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
ESET allows you to edit environment variables and aliases using
line editing commands (see :link reftype=hd refid=Editing.Command-Line
Editing:elink.).
:p.
For example, to edit the executable file search path&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] eset path
    path=:hp5.c:ehp5.&colon.\;c&colon.\dos;c&colon.\util
:exmp.:p.
To create and then edit an alias&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias d = dir /d/j/p
    [c&colon.\] eset d
    d=:hp5.d:ehp5.ir /d/j/p
:exmp.:p.
ESET will search for environment variables first and then aliases.
If you have an environment variable and an alias with the same
name, ESET will edit the environment variable and ignore the alias
unless you use the :hp2./A:ehp2. option.
:p.
Environment variable and alias names are normally limited to 80
characters. Their values are normally limited to 1,023 characters. However,
if you use special techniques to create a longer environment variable, ESET
will edit it provided the variable contains no more than 2,047 characters of
text.
:p.
If you have enabled global aliases (see :link reftype=hd
refid=ALIAS.ALIAS:elink.), any changes made to an alias with ESET will
immediately affect all other copies of &4OS2. which are using the same alias
list.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Alias) Edit the named alias even if an
environment variable of the same name exists. If you have an alias and
an environment variable with the same name, you must use this switch to be
able to edit the alias.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=EXCEPT.EXCEPT - Exclude files from a command
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Perform a command on all available files except those
specified.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.EXCEPT (:ehp2.:hp3.file:ehp3. :hp2.)
:ehp2.:hp3.command:ehp3.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.file :ehp3.&colon. The file or files to exclude from the
command.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.command :ehp3.&colon. The command to execute, including all
appropriate arguments and switches.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=ATTRIB.ATTRIB:elink. and :link
reftype=hd refid=ExclRanges.File Exclusion Ranges:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.File Selection:ehp2.
:p.
Supports extended :link reftype=hd refid=wildcards.wildcards:elink., :link
reftype=hd refid=ranges.ranges:elink., :link reftype=hd
refid=MultFiles.multiple filenames:elink., and :link reftype=hd
refid=InclList.include lists:elink.&per. Ranges :hp2.must:ehp2. appear
immediately after the EXCEPT keyword.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
EXCEPT provides a means of executing a command on a group of files
and/or subdirectories, and excluding a subgroup from the operation.
The :hp1.command:ehp1. can be an internal command or alias, an external
command, or a batch file.
:p.
You may use wildcards to specify the files to exclude from the
command. The first example erases all the files in the current
directory except those beginning with :hp1.MEMO:ehp1., and those whose
extension is :hp1..WKS:ehp1.&per. The second example copies all the files and
subdirectories on drive C to drive D except those in :hp1.C&colon.\MSC:ehp1. and
:hp1.C&colon.\DOS:ehp1., using the COPY command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] except (memo*.* *.wks) erase *.*
    [c&colon.\] except (c&colon.\msc c&colon.\dos) copy c&colon.\*.* d&colon.\ /s
:exmp.:p.
Date, time, and size ranges can be used immediately after the word
EXCEPT to further qualify which files should be excluded from the
:hp1.command:ehp1.&per. If the :hp1.command:ehp1. is an internal command that
supports ranges, an independent range can also be used in the
:hp1.command:ehp1. itself.
:p.
When you use EXCEPT on a volume supporting long filenames, you must quote any file
names inside the parentheses which contain whitespace or special characters.
For example, to copy all files except those in the :hp1."Program
Files":ehp1. directory to drive E&colon.\&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] except ("Program Files") copy /s *.* e&colon.\
:exmp.:p.
EXCEPT prevents operations on the specified file(s) by setting
the hidden attribute, performing the command, and then clearing the
hidden attribute. If the command is aborted in an unusual way, you
may need to use the ATTRIB command to remove the hidden attribute
from the file(s).
:p.
:hp8.Caution&colon.:ehp8. EXCEPT will not work with programs or commands that ignore the
hidden attribute or which work explicitly with hidden files,
including :link reftype=hd refid=DEL.DEL:elink. /Z, and the :hp2./H:ehp2. (process hidden files)
switch available in some &4OS2. file processing commands.
:p.
:link reftype=hd refid=ExclRanges.File exclusion ranges:elink. provide a
faster and more flexible method of excluding files from internal commands,
and do not manipulate file attributes, as EXCEPT does. However, exclusion
ranges can only be used with &4OS2. internal commands; you must use EXCEPT for
external commands.
:p.
:link reftype=hd refid=Ranges.Date, time, and size ranges:elink. can be used
immediately after the word EXCEPT to further qualify which files should be
excluded from the :hp1.command:ehp1.&per. If the :hp1.command:ehp1. is an
internal command that supports ranges, an independent range can also be used
in the :hp1.command:ehp1. itself. You can also use a :link reftype=hd
refid=ExclRanges.file exclusion range:elink.
within the EXCEPT command; however, this will select files to be
:hp2.excluded:ehp2. from EXCEPT, and therefore :hp2.included:ehp2. in
execution of the :hp1.command:ehp1.&per.
:p.
You can use :link reftype=hd refid=Grouping.command grouping:elink. to
execute multiple :hp1.commands:ehp1. with a single EXCEPT. For example, the
following command copies all files in the current directory whose extensions
begin with :hp1..DA:ehp1., except the :hp1..DAT:ehp1. files, to the
:hp1.D&colon.\SAVE:ehp1. directory, then changes the first two characters of
the extension of the copied files to :hp1..SA:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\data] except (*.dat) (copy *.da* d&colon.\save &amp. ren *.da* *.sa*)
:exmp.:p.
If you use :link reftype=hd refid=FileComp.filename completion:elink.
to enter the filenames inside the
parentheses, type a space after the open parenthesis before
entering a partial filename or pressing :hp2.Tab:ehp2.&per. Otherwise, the
command-line editor will treat the open parenthesis as the first
character of the filename to be completed.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=EXIT.EXIT - Exit &4OS2.
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Return from &4OS2..
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.EXIT [:ehp2.:hp3.value:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.value :ehp3.&colon. The numeric exit code to return.
:eparml.:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
EXIT terminates the current copy of &4OS2.. Use it to return to an
application when you have "shelled out" to work at the prompt, or
to end an OS/2 command-line session.
:p.
To close the session, or to return to the application that started
&4OS2., type&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] exit
:exmp.:p.
If you specify a value, EXIT will return that value to the program
that started &4OS2.. For example&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] exit 255
:exmp.:p.
The :hp1.value:ehp1. is a number you can use to inform the program of some
result, such as the success or failure of a batch file. It can range from
0 - 4,294,967,295. This feature is most useful for systems which use batch
files to automate their operation, such as bulletin boards, or custom
application programs like databases that shell to &4OS2. to perform
certain tasks.

