:h2 name=FFIND.FFIND - Search for files
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Search for files by name or contents.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.FFIND [/A[&colon.][[-]rhsda] /B /C
/D[:ehp2.:hp3.list:ehp3. :hp2.] /E /I /K /L /M /O[[&colon.][-]acdeginrsu] /P
/R /S /T"xx" /V /X["xx xx ..."]:ehp2. :hp3.file...:ehp3.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.list :ehp3.&colon. A list of disk drive letters (without colons).
:pt.:pd.:hp3.file :ehp3.&colon. The file, directory, or list of files or directories to display.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.(ttribute select):pd.:hp2./M:ehp2. (no footers)
:pt.:hp2./B:ehp2.(are):pd.:hp2./O:ehp2.(rder)
:pt.:hp2./C:ehp2.(ase-sensitive):pd.:hp2./P:ehp2.(ause)
:pt.:hp2./D:ehp2.(rive):pd.:hp2./R:ehp2.(everse)
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2. (upper case display):pd.:hp2./S:ehp2.(ubdirectories)
:pt.:hp2./I:ehp2.(gnore wildcards):pd.:hp2./T"xx":ehp2. (text search string)
:pt.:hp2./K:ehp2. (no headers):pd.:hp2./V:ehp2.(erbose)
:pt.:hp2./L:ehp2.(ine numbers):pd.:hp2./X["xx"]:ehp2. (hex display/search string)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:hp2.File Selection:ehp2.
:p.
Supports extended :link reftype=hd refid=wildcards.wildcards:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=ranges.ranges:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=MultFiles.multiple filenames:elink., and :link reftype=hd refid=InclList.include lists:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
FFIND is a flexible search command that looks for files based on their names
and their contents. depending upon the options you choose, FFIND can display
filenames, matching text, or a combination of both in a variety of formats.
:p.
If you want to search for files by name, FFIND works much like the DIR
command. For example, to generate a list of all the :hp1..BTM:ehp1. files
in the current directory, you could use the command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] ffind *.btm
:exmp.:p.
The output from this command is a list of full pathnames, followed by the
number of files found.
:p.
If you want to limit the output to a list of :hp1.*.BTM:ehp1. files which
contain the string :hp1.color:ehp1., you could use this command instead&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] ffind /t"color" *.btm
:exmp.:p.
The output from this command is a list of files that contain the
string :hp1.color:ehp1. along with the first line in each file that contains
that string. By default, FFIND uses a case-insensitive search, so the command
above will include files that contain :hp1.COLOR:ehp1., :hp1.Color:ehp1.,
:hp1.color:ehp1., or any other combination of upper-case and lower-case
letters.
:p.
If you would rather see the :hp2.last:ehp2. line of each file that contains
the search string, use the :hp2./R:ehp2. option, which forces FFIND to
search from the end of each file to the beginning. This option will also
speed up searches somewhat if you are looking for text that will normally be
at the end of a file, such as a signature line&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] ffind /r /t"Sincerely," *.txt
:exmp.:p.
You can use extended wildcards in the search string to increase the
flexibility of FFIND's search. For example, the following command will find .TXT
files which contain either the string :hp1.June:ehp1. or :hp1.July:ehp1.&per. It will also find
:hp1.Juny:ehp1. and :hp1.Jule:ehp1.&per. The :hp2./C:ehp2. option makes the search case-sensitive&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] ffind /c /t"Ju[nl][ey]" *.txt
:exmp.:p.
If you want to search for text that contains wildcard characters
(:hp2.*:ehp2., :hp2.?:ehp2., :hp2.[:ehp2., or :hp2.]:ehp2.), you can use the
:hp2./I:ehp2. option to force FFIND to interpret these as normal
characters instead of wildcards. The following command, for example, finds
all :hp1..TXT:ehp1. files that contain a question mark&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] ffind /i /t"?" *.txt
:exmp.:p.
At times, you may need to search for data that cannot be represented by
ASCII characters. You can use FFIND's :hp2./X:ehp2. option to represent the
search string in hexadecimal format (this option also changes the output to
show hexadecimal offsets rather than text lines). With :hp2./X:ehp2., the
search must be represented by pairs of hexadecimal digits separated by
spaces; a search of this type is always case-sensitive (in the example below,
41 63 65 is the hex code for "Ace")&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] ffind /x"41 63 65" *.txt
:exmp.:p.
You can use FFIND's other options to further specify the files for which you
are searching and to modify the way in which the output is displayed.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Attribute select) Select only those files that
have the specified attribute(s) set. Preceding the attribute character with a
hyphen [:hp2.-:ehp2.] will select files that do not have that attribute
set. The colon [:hp2.&colon.:ehp2.] after :hp2./A:ehp2. is optional. The
attributes are&colon.
:parml tsize=8 compact break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   R:ehp2. Read-only
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   H:ehp2. Hidden
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   S:ehp2. System
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   D:ehp2. Subdirectory
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   A:ehp2. Archive
:eparml.:p.
If no attributes are listed at all (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., :hp2.FFIND /A ...:ehp2.), FFIND will select all
files and subdirectories including hidden and system files. If
attributes are combined, all the specified attributes must match for a
file to be selected. For example, /A&colon.RHS will select only those files
with all three attributes set.
:pt.:hp2./B:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Bare) Display filenames only and omit the text that matches
the search. This option is only useful in combination with :hp2./T:ehp2. or :hp2./X:ehp2.,
which normally force FFIND to display filenames and matching text.
:pt.:hp2./C:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Case-sensitive) Perform a case-sensitive search. This option
is only valid with :hp2./T:ehp2., which defaults to a case-insensitive search. It
is not needed with a :hp2./X:ehp2. hexadecimal search, which is always case-sensitive.
:pt.:hp2./D:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Drive) Search all files on one or more drives. If you use :hp2./D:ehp2.
without a list of drives, FFIND will search the drives specified in the
list of files. If no drive letters are listed, FFIND will search all of the
current drive. You can include a list of drives or a range of drives
to search as part of the :hp2./D:ehp2. option. For example, to search drives C&colon.,
D&colon., E&colon., and G&colon., you can use either of these commands&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] ffind /dcdeg ...
    [c&colon.\] ffind /dc-eg ...
:exmp.:p.
Drive letters listed after :hp2./D:ehp2. will be ignored when processing
:hp1.file:ehp1. names which also include a drive letter. For example, this
command displays all the :hp1..BTM:ehp1. files on C&colon. and E&colon., but
only the :hp1..BAT:ehp1. files on D&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] ffind /s /dce *.btm d&colon.\*.bat
:exmp.:p.
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2.&colon.:pd.Display filenames in the traditional upper case;
also see :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /U and the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_UpperCase.UpperCase:elink. directive in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:pt.:hp2./I:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Ignore wildcards) Only meaningful when used in
conjunction with the :hp2./T"text":ehp2. option. Suppresses the recognition
of wildcard characters in the search text. This option is useful if you
need to search for characters that would normally be interpreted as
wildcards&colon. :hp2.*:ehp2., :hp2.?:ehp2., :hp2.[:ehp2., and :hp2.]:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:hp2./K:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(No headers) Suppress the display of the header or filename for
each matching text line.
:pt.:hp2./L:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Line numbers) Include the line number for each text line
displayed. FFIND numbers lines beginning with 1, unless :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_ListRowStart.ListRowStart:elink. is set to 0 in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. A new line is
counted for every CR or LF character (FFIND determines automatically
which character is used for line breaks in each file), or when line
length reaches 511 characters, whichever comes first.
:pt.:hp2./M:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(No footers) Suppress the footer (the number of files and number
of matches) at the end of FFIND's display.
:pt.:hp2./O:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Order) Set the sorting order. You may use any combination
of the following sorting options; if multiple options are used, the listing will be
sorted with the first sort option as the primary key, the next as the secondary key,
and so on&colon.
.br
:parml tsize=8 compact break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  -:ehp2. Reverse the sort order for the next option.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  a:ehp2. Sort in ASCII order, not numerically, when there are digits in the name.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  d:ehp2. Sort by date and time (oldest first); for volumes supporting long filenames, also see :hp2./T:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  e:ehp2. Sort by extension.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  g:ehp2. Group subdirectories first, then files.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  i:ehp2. Sort by file description (ignored if :hp2./C:ehp2. or :hp2./O&colon.c:ehp2. is used).
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  n:ehp2. Sort by filename (this is the default).
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  r:ehp2. Reverse the sort order for all options.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  s:ehp2. Sort by size.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  u:ehp2. Unsorted.
:eparml.:p.
:pt.:hp2./P:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Pause) Wait for a key to be pressed after each screen page
before continuing the display. Your options at the prompt are explained in
detail under :link reftype=hd refid=Prompts.Page and File Prompts:elink.&per.
:pt.:hp2./R:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Reverse) Only meaningful when used in
conjuction with the :hp2./T"text":ehp2. or :hp2./X :ehp2. options. Searches
each file from the end backwards to the beginning. This option is useful if
you want to display the last occurrence of the search string in each file
instead of the first (the default). It can also speed up searches for
information that is normally at the end of a file, such as a signature.
:pt.:hp2./S:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Subdirectories) Display matches from the
current directory and all of its subdirectories.
:pt.:hp2./T"xx":ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Text search) Specify the text search string. :hp2./T:ehp2. must be
followed by a text string in double quotes (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., :hp2./t"color":ehp2.). FFIND
will perform a case-insensitive search unless you also use the :hp2./C:ehp2.
option. For a hexadecimal search and/or hexadecimal display of the
location where the search string is found, see :hp2./X:ehp2.&per.  You can specify a search
string with either /T or /X, but not both.
:pt.:hp2./V:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Verbose) Show every matching line. FFIND's default
behavior is to show only the first matching line then and then go on to
the next file. This option is only valid with :hp2./T:ehp2. or :hp2./X:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:hp2./X:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Hexadecimal display / search) Specify hexadecimal display
and an optional hexadecimal search string.
:p.
If :hp2./X:ehp2. is followed by one or more pairs of hexadecimal digits in quotes
(:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., :hp1./x"44 63 65":ehp1.), FFIND will search for that exact sequence of
characters or data bytes without regard to the meaning of those bytes
as text. If those bytes are found, the offset is displayed (in both decimal
and hexadecimal). A search of this type will always be case-sensitive.
:p.
If :hp2./X:ehp2. is not followed by a hexadecimal search string it must be
used in conjunction with :hp2./T:ehp2., and will change the output format to
display offsets (in both decimal and hexadecimal) rather than actual text
lines when the search string is found. For example, this command uses
:hp2./T:ehp2. to display the first line in each :hp1..BTM:ehp1. file
containing the word :hp1.hello:ehp1.&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] ffind /t"hello" *.btm
    ---- c&colon.\test.btm&colon.
    echo hello

      1 line in 1 file
:exmp.:p.
If you use the same command with :hp2./X:ehp2., the offset is displayed
instead of the text&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] ffind /t"hello" /x *.btm
    ---- c&colon.\test.btm&colon.
    Offset&colon. 26 (1Ah)

      1 line in 1 file
:exmp.:p.
You can specify a search string with either :hp2./T:ehp2. or :hp2./X:ehp2.,
but not both.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=FOR.FOR - Repeat a command
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Repeat a command for several values of a variable.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd. :hp2.FOR [/A&colon.[[-]rhsda] /D /F
[":ehp2.:hp3.options:ehp3. :hp2."] /H /L /R
[:ehp2.:hp3.path:ehp3. :hp2.]]:ehp2. :hp3.%var:ehp3. :hp2.IN
([@]:ehp2.:hp3.set:ehp3. :hp2.|:ehp2. :hp3.start, step, end:ehp3. :hp2.)
[DO]:ehp2. :hp3.command:ehp3. :hp2....:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.options :ehp3.&colon. Parsing options for a "file parsing" :hp2.FOR:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.path :ehp3.&colon. The starting directory for a "recursive" :hp2.FOR:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.%var :ehp3.&colon. The variable to be used in the command ("FOR variable").
:pt.:pd.:hp3.set :ehp3.&colon. A set of values for the variable.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.start :ehp3.&colon. The starting increment for a "counted" :hp2.FOR:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.step :ehp3.&colon. The increment value for a "counted" :hp2.FOR:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.end :ehp3.&colon. The limit value for a "counted" :hp2.FOR:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.command :ehp3.&colon. A command or group of commands to be executed for each value of the variable.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./A&colon.:ehp2. (Attribute select):pd.:hp2./L:ehp2. (counted loop)
:pt.:hp2./F:ehp2.(ile parsing):pd.:hp2./R:ehp2.(ecursive)
:pt.:hp2./H:ehp2.(ide dots):pd.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:hp2.File Selection:ehp2.
:p.
Supports extended :link reftype=hd refid=wildcards.wildcards:elink., :link
reftype=hd refid=ranges.ranges:elink., :link reftype=hd
refid=MultFiles.multiple filenames:elink., and :link reftype=hd
refid=InclList.include lists:elink.&per. Ranges :hp2.must:ehp2. appear
immediately after the FOR keyword.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
FOR begins by creating a set. It then executes a command for every
member of the set. The command can be an internal command, an
alias, an external command, or a batch file. The members of the set can be
a list of filenames, text strings, a group of numeric values, or text read
from a list of files.
:p.
When the :hp1.set:ehp1. is made up of text or several separate filenames
(not an include list), the elements must be separated by spaces, tabs,
commas, or the switch character (normally a slash [:hp2./:ehp2.]).
:p.
FOR includes a large number of options, some of which duplicate functions
available in other &4OS2. commands, and/or do not follow conventions you may
find in our other commands. Most of these extra options are included for
compatibility with Windows NT 4.0's :hp1.CMD.EXE:ehp1.&per. However, we make
them available in &4OS2., 4DOS, and 4NT so that aliases and batch files which
use them can work under all three products.
:p.
The first three sections below (:hp2.Working with Files:ehp2., :hp2.Working
with Text:ehp2., and :hp2.Retrieving Text from Files:ehp2.) describe the
traditional FOR command and the enhancements to it which are part of
&4OS2.. The sections on :hp2.Parsing Text from Files:ehp2. and :hp2.Counted
FOR Loops:ehp2. describe features added for compatibility of our line of
text mode products with Windows NT 4.0. The section entitled :hp2.Other
Notes:ehp2. contains information you may need if you use any aspect of the
FOR command extensively.
:p.
:hp2.Working with Files:ehp2.
:p.
Normally, the :hp1.set:ehp1. is a list of files specified with wildcards. For
example, if you use this line in a batch file&colon.
:xmp.
    for %x in (*.txt) do list %x
:exmp.:p.
then LIST will be executed once for each file in the current
directory with the extension :hp1..TXT:ehp1.&per. The FOR variable
:hp1.%x:ehp1. is set equal to each of the filenames in turn, then the LIST
command is executed for each file. (You could do the same thing more easily
with a simple LIST *.TXT. We used FOR here so you could get a feel
for how it operates, using a simple example. Many of the examples in this
section are constructed in the same way.)
:p.
The :hp1.set:ehp1. can include multiple files or an include list, like
this&colon.
:xmp.
    for %x in (d&colon.\*.txt;*.doc;*.asc) do type %x
:exmp.:p.
FOR supports :link reftype=hd refid=Wildcards.wildcards and extended
wildcards:elink., as well as extended parent directory names
(:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., :hp2....\*.txt:ehp2. to process all of the :hp1..TXT:ehp1.
files that are contained in the directory 2 levels above the current
directory).
:p.
When you use FOR on a volume supporting long filenames, you must quote any filenames within the
:hp1.set:ehp1. which contain whitespace or special characters. The same
restriction applies to names returned in the FOR variable, if you pass them
to &4OS2. internal commands, or other commands which require quoting filenames
with whitespace. FOR does not quote returned names automatically, even if
you included quotes in the :hp1.set:ehp1.&per. See :link reftype=hd
refid=Filenames.Filenames:elink. for additional details on
filename quoting.
:p.
If the :hp1.set:ehp1. includes filenames, the file list can be further refined
by using :link reftype=hd refid=Ranges.date, time, size:elink. and :link
reftype=hd refid=ExclRanges.file exclusion:elink. ranges. The range or
ranges must be placed immediately after the word FOR. Ranges will be
ignored if no wildcards are used inside the parentheses. For
example, this set is made up of all of the :hp1..TXT:ehp1. files that were
created or updated on October 4, 2017&colon.
:xmp.
    for /[d10-4-17,+0] %x in (*.txt) do ...
:exmp.:p.
If the :hp1.command:ehp1. is an internal command that supports ranges, an
independent range can also be used in the :hp1.command:ehp1. itself.
:p.
You can also refine the list by limiting it with the :hp2./A&colon.:ehp2.
option to select only files that have specific attributes.
:p.
By default, FOR works only with files in the current directory or a specified
directory. With the :hp2./R:ehp2. option, FOR will also search for files in
subdirectories. For example, to work with all of the :hp1..TXT:ehp1. files
in the current directory and its subdirectories&colon.
:xmp.
    for /r %x in (*.txt) do ...
:exmp.:p.
If you specify a directory name immediately after :hp2./R:ehp2., FOR will
start in that directory and then search each of its subdirectories. This
example works with all of the :hp1..BAK:ehp1. files on drive D&colon.
:xmp.
    for /r d&colon.\ %x in (*.bak) do ...
:exmp.:p.
When you use wildcards to specify the :hp1.set:ehp1., FOR scans the
directory and finds each file which matches the wildcard name(s) you
specified. If, during the processing of the FOR command, you create a file
that could be included in the :hp1.set:ehp1., it may or may not appear in a
future iteration of the same FOR command. Whether the new file appears
depends upon its physical location in the directory structure. For example,
if you use FOR to execute a command for all :hp1..TXT:ehp1. files, and the
command also creates one or more new :hp1..TXT:ehp1. files, those new files
may or may not be processed during the current FOR command, depending upon
where they are placed in the physical structure of the directory. This is
an operating system constraint over which &4OS2. have no control. Therefore,
in order to achieve consistent results you should construct FOR commands
which do not create files that could become part of the :hp1.set:ehp1. for
the current command.
:p.
:hp2.Working with Text:ehp2.
:p.
The :hp1.set:ehp1. can also be made up of text instead of filenames. For
example, to create three files named file1, file2, and file3, each
containing a blank line&colon.
:xmp.
    for %suffix in (1 2 3) do echo. > file%suffix
:exmp.:p.
You could also use the names of environment variables as the text. This
example displays the name and content of several variables from the
environment (see :link reftype=hd refid=Environment.Environment Variables
and Functions:elink. for details on the use of square brackets when
expanding environment variables). Enter this on one line&colon.
:xmp.
    for %var in (path prompt comspec) do echo %var=%[%var]
:exmp.:p.
:hp2.Retrieving Text from Files:ehp2.
:p.
FOR can extract text from files in two different ways. The first method
extracts each line from each file in the :hp1.set:ehp1. and places it in the
variable. To use this method, place an [:hp2.@:ehp2.] at the beginning of
the :hp1.set:ehp1., in front of the filename(s).
:p.
For example, if you have a file called :hp1.DRIVES.TXT:ehp1. that contains a
list of drives on your computer, one drive name per line (with a "&colon."
after each drive letter), you can print the free space on each drive this
way&colon.
:xmp.
    for %d in (@drives.txt) do free %d > prn
:exmp.:p.
Because the [:hp2.@:ehp2.] is also a valid filename character, FOR first
checks to see if the file exists with the [:hp2.@:ehp2.] in its name
(:hp1.i.e.:ehp1., a file named :hp1.@DRIVES.TXT:ehp1. ). If so, the filename is
treated as a normal argument. If it doesn't exist, FOR uses the
filename (without the [:hp2.@:ehp2.]:hp2.):ehp2. as the file from which to
retrieve text.
:p.
If you use @CON as the filename, FOR will read from standard input (a
redirected input file) or a pipe; see :link reftype=hd
refid=RedirPipe.Redirection and Piping:elink. for more information). If you
use @CLIP&colon. as the filename, FOR will read any text available from the
OS/2 clipboard (see :link reftype=hd refid=Redirection.Redirection:elink.
for details).
:p.
:hp2.Parsing Text from Files:ehp2.
:p.
The second method of working with text from files is to have FOR parse each
line of each file for you. To begin a "file-parsing" FOR, you must use the
:hp2./F:ehp2. option and then include one or more filenames in the
:hp1.set:ehp1.&per. When you use this form of FOR, the variable must be a
single letter, for example, :hp1.%a:ehp1.&per.
:p.
This method of parsing, included for compatibility with Windows NT 4.0's
:hp1.CMD.EXE:ehp1., can be cumbersome and inflexible. For a more powerful
method, use FOR with :hp2.@filename:ehp2. as the :hp1.set:ehp1. to retrieve
each line from the file, as described in the previous section. Then use
variable functions like :link reftype=hd refid=_@INSTR.@INSTR:elink., :link
reftype=hd refid=_@LEFT.@LEFT:elink., :link reftype=hd
refid=_@RIGHT.@RIGHT:elink., and :link reftype=hd refid=_@WORD.@WORD:elink.
to parse the line.
:p.
By default, FOR will extract the first word or :hp1.token:ehp1. from each
line and return it in the variable. For example, to display the first word
on each line in the file :hp1.FLIST.TXT:ehp1.&colon.
:xmp.
    for /f %a in (flist.txt) do echo %a
:exmp.:p.
You can control the way FOR /F parses each line by specifying one or more
parsing options in a quoted string immediately after the :hp2./F:ehp2.&per. The
available options are&colon.
:lm margin=4.:parml compact tsize=10 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.skip=n:ehp2.&colon.:pd.FOR /F will skip "n" lines at the beginning of each
file before parsing the remainder of the file.
:pt.:hp2.tokens=n, m, ...:ehp2. &colon.:pd.By default, FOR /F returns just
the first word or "token" from each parsed line in the variable you
named. You can have it return more than one token in the variable, or
return tokens in several variables, with this option.
:p.
This option is followed by a list of numbers separated by
commas. The first number tells FOR /F which token to return in the first
variable, the second number tells it which to return in the second variable,
etc. The variables follow each other alphabetically starting with the
variable you name on the FOR command line. This example returns the first
word of each line in each text file in :hp1.%d:ehp1., the second in
:hp1.%e:ehp1., and the third in :hp1.%f:ehp1.&colon.
:xmp.
    for /f "tokens=1,2,3" %d in (*.txt) do ...
:exmp.:p.
You can also indicate a range of tokens by separating the numbers with a
hyphen [:hp2.-:ehp2.]. This example returns the first word of each line in
:hp1.%p:ehp1., the second through fifth words in :hp1.%q:ehp1., and the
eighth word in :hp1.%r:ehp1.&colon.
:xmp.
    for /f "tokens=1,2-5,8" %p in (*.txt) do ...
:exmp.:p.
To return the rest of the line in a variable, use a range that ends with a
number higher than the last token in any line, such as 999. This final
example returns the first word of each line in :hp1.%a:ehp1. and the
remainder of each line (assuming that no line has more than 999 words!) in
:hp1.%b:ehp1.&colon.
:xmp.
    for /f "tokens=1,2-999" %a in (*.txt) do ...
:exmp.:p.
:pt.:hp2.eol=c:ehp2. &colon.:pd.If FOR /F finds the character "c" in the
line, it will assume that the character and any text following it are part
of a comment and ignore the rest of the line.
:pt.:hp2.delims=xxx...:ehp2. &colon.:pd.By default, FOR /F sees spaces and
tabs as word or token delimiters. This option replaces those delimiters
with all of the characters following the equal sign to the end of the
string. This option must therefore be the last one used in the quoted
options string.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
You can also use FOR /F to parse a single string instead of each line of a
file by using the string, in quotes, as the :hp1.set:ehp1.&per. For example,
this command will assign variable A to the string "this", B to "is", etc.,
then display "this" (enter the command on one line)&colon.
:xmp.
    for /f "tokens=1,2,3,4" %a in ("this is a test") do echo %a
:exmp.:p.
:hp2."Counted" FOR Loop:ehp2.
:p.
The "counted FOR" loop is included only for compatibility with Windows NT
4.0's :hp1.CMD.EXE:ehp1.&per. In most cases, you will find the :link reftype=hd
refid=DO.DO:elink. command more useful for performing counted loops.
:p.
In a counted FOR command, the :hp1.set:ehp1. is made up of numeric values
instead of text or filenames. To begin a counted FOR command, you must use
the :hp2./L:ehp2. option and then include three values, separated by commas,
in the :hp1.set:ehp1.&per. These are the :hp1.start:ehp1., :hp1.step:ehp1., and
:hp1.end:ehp1. values. During the first iteration of the FOR loop, the
variable is set equal to the :hp1.start:ehp1. value. Before each iteration,
the variable is increased by the :hp1.step:ehp1. value. The loop ends when
the variable exceeds the :hp1.end:ehp1. value. This example will print the
numbers from 1 to 10&colon.
:xmp.
    for /l %val in (1,1,10) do echo %val
:exmp.:p.
This example will print the odd numbers from 1 to 10 (1, 3, 5, 7, and
9)&colon.
:xmp.
    for /l %val in (1,2,10) do echo %val
:exmp.:p.
The step value can be negative. If it is, the loop will end when the
variable is less than the end value.
:p.
:hp2.Other Notes:ehp2.
:p.
You can use either :hp1.%:ehp1. or :hp1.%%:ehp1. in front of the variable
name. Either form will work, whether the FOR command is typed from the
command line or is part of an alias or batch file (some of the
traditional command processors require a single :hp1.%:ehp1. if FOR is
used at the command line, but require :hp1.%%:ehp1. if FOR is used in a batch
file). The variable name can be up to 80 characters long. The word DO is
optional.
:p.
If you use a single-character FOR variable name, that name is given
priority over any environment variable which starts with the same
letter, in order to maintain compatibility with the traditional FOR
command. For example, the following command tries to add a&colon. and
b&colon. to the end of the PATH, but will not work as intended&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] for %p in (a&colon. b&colon.) do path %path;%p
:exmp.:p.
The "%p" in "%path" will be interpreted as the FOR variable :hp1.%p:ehp1.
followed by the text "ath", which is not what was intended. To get
around this, use a different letter or a longer name for the FOR
variable, or use square brackets around the variable name (see
:link reftype=hd refid=Environment.Environment:elink.).
:p.
The following example uses FOR with variable functions to delete
the :hp1..BAK:ehp1. files for which a corresponding :hp1..TXT:ehp1. file
exists in the current directory&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\docs] for %file in (*.txt) do del %@name[%file].bak
:exmp.:p.
The above command would not work properly on a volume supporting long filenames, because the
returned FILE variable might contain whitespace. To correct this problem,
you would need two sets of quotes, one for DEL and one for %@NAME&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\docs] for %file in (*.txt) do del "%@name["%file"].bak"
:exmp.:p.
You can use :link reftype=hd refid=Grouping.command grouping:elink. to
execute multiple commands for each element in the :hp1.set:ehp1.&per. For
example, the following command copies each :hp1..WKQ:ehp1. file in the
current directory to the :hp1.D&colon.\WKSAVE:ehp1. directory, then changes
the extension of each file in the current directory to :hp1..SAV:ehp1.&per. This
should be entered on one line&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\text] for %file in (*.wkq) do (copy "%file" d&colon.\wksave\ &amp.
         ren "%file" *.sav)
:exmp.:p.
In a batch file you can use GOSUB to execute a subroutine for every
element in the :hp1.set:ehp1.&per. Within the subroutine, the FOR variable can be
used just like any environment variable. This is a convenient way
to execute a complex sequence of commands for every element in the
:hp1.set:ehp1. without CALLing another batch file.
:p.
One unusual use of FOR is to execute a collection of batch files or
other commands with the same parameter. For example, you might
want to have three batch files all operate on the same data file. The
FOR command could look like this&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] for %cmd in (filetest fileform fileprnt) do %cmd datafile
:exmp.:p.
This line will expand to three separate commands&colon.
:xmp.
    filetest datafile
    fileform datafile
    fileprnt datafile
:exmp.:p.
The variable that FOR uses (the :hp2.%CMD:ehp2. in the example above) is
created in the environment and then erased when the FOR command is
done. (For compatibility with :hp1.CMD.EXE:ehp1., a single-character FOR
variable is created in a special way that does not overwrite an existing
environment variable with the same name.) When using a multi-character
variable name you must be careful not to use the name of one of your
environment variables as a FOR variable. For example, a command that begins
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] for %path in ...
:exmp.:p.
will write over your current path setting, then erase the path
variable completely when FOR is done.
:p.
FOR statements can be nested.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml compact tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./A&colon.:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Attribute select) Select only those
files that have the specified attribute(s) set. :hp2./A&colon.:ehp2. will
be used only when processing wildcard filenames in the set. It will be
ignored for filenames without wildcards or other items in the set. Preceding
the attribute character with a hyphen [-] will select files that do not have
that attribute set. The colon [&colon.] after :hp2./A:ehp2. is required. The
attributes are&colon.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  R:ehp2. Read-only
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  H:ehp2. Hidden
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  S:ehp2. System
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  D:ehp2. Subdirectory
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  A:ehp2. Archive
.br
:pt.:pd.If no attributes are listed (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., :hp2.FOR /A&colon. ...:ehp2.),
FOR will process all files including hidden and system files. If attributes
are combined, all the specified attributes must match for a file to be
included. For example, :hp2./A&colon.RHS:ehp2. will include only
those files with all three attributes set.
:p.
For example, to process only those files with the
archive attribute set&colon.
:xmp.
    for /a&colon.a %f in (*.*) echo %f needs a backup!
:exmp.
:pt.:hp2./F:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(File parsing) Return one or more words or
tokens from each line of each file in the set. The :hp2./F:ehp2. option can
be followed by one or more options in a quoted string which control how the
parsing is performed. See the details under :hp2.Parsing Text From
Files:ehp2., above.
:pt.:hp2./H:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Hide dots) Suppress the assignment of the "."
and ".." directories to the FOR variable.
:pt.:hp2./L:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(counted loop) Interpret the three values in the
:hp1.set:ehp1. as the :hp1.start:ehp1., :hp1.step:ehp1., and :hp1.end:ehp1.
values of a counted loop. See the details under :hp2."Counted" FOR
Loop:ehp2., above.
:pt.:hp2./R:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Recursive) Look in the current directory and
all of its subdirectories for files in the :hp1.set:ehp1.&per. If the
:hp2./R:ehp2. is followed by a directory name, look for files in that
directory and all of its subdirectories.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=FREE.FREE - Display total and free disk space
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display the total disk space, total bytes used, and
total bytes free on the specified (or default) drive(s).
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.FREE [:ehp2.:hp3.drive&colon.:ehp3.
:hp2....]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.drive :ehp3.&colon. One or more drives to include in the report.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=MEMORY.MEMORY:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
FREE provides the same disk information as the external command
CHKDSK, but without the wait, since it does not check the integrity
of the file and directory structure of the disk.
:p.
A colon [:hp2.&colon.:ehp2.] is required after each drive letter. This
example displays the status of drives A and C&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] free a&colon. c&colon.

     Volume in drive A&colon. is unlabeled    Serial number is 213A&colon.15D5
        1,213,952 bytes total disk space
        1,115,136 bytes used
           98,816 bytes free

     Volume in drive C&colon. is DEVELOPMENT  Serial number is 2944&colon.15D9
      242,496,000 bytes total disk space
      236,851,712 bytes used
        5,644,288 bytes free
:exmp.:p.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=GLOBAL.GLOBAL - Execute a command all subdirectories
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Execute a command in the current directory and its
subdirectories.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.GLOBAL [/H /I /P /Q] :ehp2.:hp3.command:ehp3.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.command :ehp3.&colon. The command to execute, including arguments and switches.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./H:ehp2.(idden directories):pd.:hp2./P:ehp2.(rompt)
:pt.:hp2./I:ehp2.(gnore exit codes):pd.:hp2./Q:ehp2.(uiet)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
GLOBAL performs the command first in the current directory and then
in every subdirectory under the current directory. The command can
be an internal command, an alias, an external command, or a batch
file.
:p.
This example copies the files in every directory on drive A to the
directory :hp1.C&colon.\TEMP:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    [a&colon.\] global copy *.* c&colon.\temp
:exmp.:p.
If you use the :hp2./P:ehp2. option, GLOBAL will prompt for each
subdirectory before performing the command. You can use this
option if you want to perform the command in most, but not all
subdirectories of the current directory.
:p.
You can use :link reftype=hd refid=Grouping.command grouping:elink. to execute multiple
:hp1.commands:ehp1. in each subdirectory. For example, the following
command copies each :hp1..TXT:ehp1. file in the current directory and all
of its subdirectories to drive A. It then changes the extension of
each of the copied files to :hp1..SAV:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] global (copy *.txt a&colon. &amp. ren *.txt *.sav)
:exmp.:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./H:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Hidden directories) Forces GLOBAL to look for hidden
directories. If you don't use this switch, hidden
directories are ignored.
:pt.:hp2./I:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Ignore exit codes) If this option is not
specified, GLOBAL will terminate if the command returns a non-zero exit
code. Use :hp2./I:ehp2. if you want the command to continue in additional
subdirectories even if it returns an error in one subdirectory. Even
if you use :hp2./I:ehp2., GLOBAL will normally halt execution if the command
processor receives a :hp2.Ctrl-C:ehp2. or :hp2.Ctrl-Break:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:hp2./P:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Prompt) Forces GLOBAL to prompt with each directory name
before it performs the command. Your options at the
prompt are explained in detail under :link reftype=hd refid=Prompts.Page and File Prompts:elink.&per.
:pt.:hp2./Q:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Quiet) Do not display the directory names as each directory
is processed.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=GOSUB.GOSUB - Execute a subroutine in a batch file
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Execute a subroutine in the current batch file.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.GOSUB :ehp2.:hp3.label:ehp3.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.label :ehp3.&colon. The batch file label at the beginning of the subroutine.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=CALL.CALL:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=GOTO.GOTO:elink. and :link reftype=hd refid=RETURN.RETURN:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
GOSUB can only be used in batch files.
:p.
&4OS2. allows subroutines in batch files. A subroutine must start
with a :hp1.label:ehp1. (a colon [:hp2.&colon.:ehp2.] followed by a one-word label
name) which appears on a line by itself. Case differences are
ignored when matching labels. Labels may be one or more words long. The
subroutine must end with a RETURN statement.
:p.
The subroutine is invoked with a GOSUB command from another part of
the batch file. After the :link reftype=hd refid=RETURN.RETURN:elink.,
processing will continue with the command following the GOSUB command. For
example, the following batch file fragment calls a subroutine which displays
the directory and returns&colon.
:xmp.
    echo Calling a subroutine
    gosub subr1
    echo Returned from the subroutine
    quit
    &colon.subr1
    dir /a/w
    return
:exmp.:p.
&4OS2. begins its search for the :hp1.label:ehp1. on the next line of the
batch file (after the GOSUB command). If the label is not found between the
current position and the end of the file, GOSUB will restart the search at
the beginning of the file. If the label does not exist, the
batch file is terminated with the error message "Label not found."
:p.
GOSUB saves the :link reftype=hd refid=IFF.IFF:elink. and :link reftype=hd
refid=DO.DO:elink. states, so IFF and DO statements inside a subroutine
won't interfere with statements in the part of the batch file from which the
subroutine was called.
:p.
Subroutines can be nested.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=GOTO.GOTO - Branch within a batch file
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Branch to a specified line inside the current batch
file.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.GOTO [/I] :ehp2.:hp3.label:ehp3.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.label :ehp3.&colon. The batch file label to branch to.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./I:ehp2.(FF and DO continue):pd.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=GOSUB.GOSUB:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
GOTO can only be used in batch files.
:p.
After a GOTO command in a batch file, the next line to be executed
will be the one immediately after the :hp1.label:ehp1.&per. The :hp1.label:ehp1.
must begin with a colon [:hp2.&colon.:ehp2.] and appear on a line by itself.
The colon is required on the line where the label is defined, but
is not required in the GOTO command itself. Case differences are
ignored when matching labels. Labels may be one or more words long.
:p.
This batch file fragment checks for the existence of the file
:hp1.CONFIG.SYS:ehp1.&per. If the file exists, the batch file jumps to
C_EXISTS and copies all the files from the current directory to the
root directory on A&colon.&per. Otherwise, it prints an error message and
exits.
:xmp.
    if exist config.sys goto C_EXISTS
    echo CONFIG.SYS doesn't exist - exiting.
    quit
    &colon.C_EXISTS
    copy *.* a&colon.\
:exmp.:p.
:p.
GOTO begins its search for the :hp1.label:ehp1. on the next line of the
batch file (after the GOTO command). If the label is not found between the
current position and the end of the file, GOTO will restart the search at
the beginning of the file. If the label does not exist, the batch file
is terminated with the error message "Label not found."
:p.
To avoid errors in the processing of nested statements and
loops, GOTO cancels all active :link reftype=hd refid=IFF.IFF:elink. statements and
:link reftype=hd refid=DO.DO:elink. / ENDDO loops unless you use :hp2./I:ehp2.&per. This means that a
normal GOTO (without :hp2./I:ehp2.) may not branch to any label that is
between an IFF and the corresponding ENDIFF or between a DO and the
corresponding ENDDO.
:p.
For compatibility with Windows NT's :hp1.CMD.EXE:ehp1., the command
:xmp.
    GOTO &colon.EOF
:exmp.:p.
will end processing of the current batch file if the label &colon.EOF does
not exist. However, this is less efficient than using the :link reftype=hd
refid=QUIT.QUIT:elink. or :link reftype=hd refid=CANCEL.CANCEL:elink.
command to end a batch file.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./I:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(IFF and DO continue) Prevents GOTO from canceling IFF
statements and DO loops. Use this option only if you are absolutely certain
that your GOTO command is branching entirely within any current IFF
statement :hp2.and:ehp2. any active DO / ENDDO block. Using :hp2./I:ehp2.
under any other conditions will cause an error later in your batch file.
:p.
You cannot branch into another IFF statement, another DO loop, or a
different IFF or DO nesting level, whether you use the :hp2./I:ehp2. option
or not. If you do, you will eventually receive an "unknown command" error
(or execution of the UNKNOWN_CMD alias) on a subsequent ENDDO, ELSE,
ELSEIFF, or ENDIFF statement.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=HELP.HELP - Display help
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display help for internal commands. Help for
external commands is also available in some cases.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.HELP [:ehp2.:hp3.topic:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.topic :ehp3.&colon. A help topic, internal command, or
external command.
:eparml.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=HelpSys.The &4OS2. Help System:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
Online help is available for &4OS2.. The &4OS2. help system uses the OS/2 help
facility.
:p.
See the :hp1.Introduction and Installation Guide:ehp1. for a more thorough
explanation of the online help available.
:p.
If you type the command HELP by itself (or press :hp2.F1:ehp2. when the
command line is empty), the table of contents is displayed. If you
type HELP plus a topic name, that topic is displayed. For example&colon.
:xmp.
    help copy
:exmp.:p.
displays information about the COPY command and its options.
:p.
You can configure the HELP command to display OS/2's command-line help
along with the &4OS2.'s (the default), display only the &4OS2. help, or display
some other combination of help "books". For details, see the :link
reftype=hd refid=INI_HelpBook.HelpBook:elink. directive and your
:hp1.Introduction and Installation Guide:ehp1.&per.
:p.
For help on system errors enter the message number in the HELP
command, for example:
:xmp.
    help 3
    help sys0003
:exmp.:p.
&4OS2. will invoke OS/2's HELPMSG program to process these requests, and
HELPMSG will display any available information on the message number
given.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=HISTORY.HISTORY - Manage the history list
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display, add to, clear, or read the history
list.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.HISTORY [/A :ehp2.:hp3.command:ehp3.
:hp2./F /P /R :ehp2.:hp3.filename:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.command :ehp3.&colon. A command to be added to the history list.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.filename :ehp3.&colon. The name of a file containing entries to
be added to the history list.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.(dd):pd.:hp2./P(:ehp2.ause)
:pt.:hp2./F:ehp2.(ree):pd.:hp2./R:ehp2.(ead)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=DIRHISTORY.DIRHISTORY:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=LOG.LOG:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
&4OS2. keeps a list of the commands you have entered on the command
line. See :link reftype=hd refid=CmdHist.Command History and Recall:elink.
for information on command recall, which allows you to use the history list
to repeat or edit commands you have previously executed.
:p.
The HISTORY command lets you view and manipulate the command
history list directly. If no parameters are entered, HISTORY will
display the current command history list&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] history
:exmp.:p.
With the options explained below, you can clear the list, add new
commands to the list without executing them, save the list in a
file, or read a new list from a file.
:p.
The number of commands saved in the history list depends upon the
length of each command line. The history list size can be
specified at startup from 256 to 32767 characters (see the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_History.History:elink. directive). The default size
is 1024 characters.
:p.
Your history list can be stored either locally (a separate history
list for each copy of &4OS2.) or globally (all copies of &4OS2. share
the same list). For full details see the discussion of local and
global history lists under
:link reftype=hd refid=CmdHist.Command History and Recall:elink.&per.
:p.
You can use the HISTORY command as an aid in writing batch files by
redirecting the HISTORY output to a file and then editing the file
appropriately. However, it may be easier to use the LOG /H command for
this purpose.
:p.
You can disable the history list or specify a minimum command-line length to
save with on the
:link reftype=hd refid=CommandLine1Option.Command Line 1 page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
or with the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_HistMin.HistMin:elink. directive in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:p.
You can save the history list by redirecting the output of HISTORY to a
file. This example saves the command history to a file called
:hp1.HISTFILE:ehp1. and reads it back again immediately. If you leave out
the HISTORY /F command on the second line, the contents of the file will be
appended to the current history list instead of replacing it&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] history > histfile
    [c&colon.\] history /f
    [c&colon.\] history /r histfile
:exmp.:p.
If you need to save your history at the end of each day's work, you might use
commands like this in your :hp1.AUTOEXEC.BAT:ehp1. or other startup
file&colon.
:xmp.
    if exist c&colon.\histfile history /r c&colon.\histfile
    alias shut*down `history > c&colon.\histfile`
:exmp.:p.
This restores the previous history list if it exists, then defines an alias
which will allow you to save the history before shutting off the system.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Add) Add a command to the history list. This
performs the same function as the :hp2.Ctrl-K:ehp2. key at the
command line (see :link reftype=hd refid=CmdHist.Command History and
Recall:elink.).
:pt.:hp2./F:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Free) Erase all entries in the command history
list.
:pt.:hp2./P:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Prompt) Wait for a key after displaying each
page of the list. Your options at the prompt are explained in
detail under :link reftype=hd refid=Prompts.Page and File Prompts:elink.&per.
:pt.:hp2./R:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Read) Read the command history from the
specified file and append it to the history list currently held in
memory. Each line in the file must fit within the
:link reftype=hd refid=CmdLength.command-line length limit:elink.).
:p.
If you are creating a HISTORY /R file by hand, and need to create an entry
that spans multiple lines in the file, you can do so by terminating each line,
except the last, with an :link reftype=hd refid=Escape.escape
character:elink.&per. However, you cannot use this method to exceed the
command-line length limit.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=IF.IF - Execute a command if a condition is true
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Execute a command if a condition or set of
conditions is true.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.IF [NOT]
:ehp2.:hp3.condition:ehp3. :hp2.[.AND. &splitvbar. .OR. &splitvbar. .XOR.
[NOT] :ehp2.:hp3.condition:ehp3. :hp2....]:ehp2. :hp3.command:ehp3.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.condition :ehp3.&colon. A test or set of tests to determine if
the command should be executed.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.command :ehp3.&colon. The command to execute if the condition
is true.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=IFF.IFF:elink., :link reftype=hd
refid=_@IF.@IF:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
IF is normally used only in aliases and batch files. It is always
followed by one or more :hp1.conditions:ehp1. and then a
:hp1.command:ehp1.&per. First, the :hp1.conditions:ehp1. are evaluated. If
they are true, the :hp1.command:ehp1. is executed. Otherwise, the
:hp1.command:ehp1. is ignored. If you add a NOT before a
:hp1.condition:ehp1., the :hp1.command:ehp1. is executed only when the
:hp1.condition:ehp1. is false.
:p.
You can link :hp1.conditions:ehp1. with :hp2..AND.:ehp2., :hp2..OR.:ehp2.,
or :hp2..XOR.:ehp2., and you can group conditions with parentheses (see
:hp2.Combining Tests:ehp2. below). You can also nest IF statements.
:p.
The :hp1.conditions:ehp1. can test strings, numbers, the existence of a file
or subdirectory, the exit code returned by the preceding external command, and
the existence of aliases and internal commands.
:p.
The :hp1.command:ehp1. can be an alias, an internal command, an external
command, or a batch file. The entire IF statement, including all
:hp1.conditions:ehp1. and the :hp1.command:ehp1., must fit on one line.
:p.
Some examples of IF conditions and commands are included below; additional
examples can be found in the :hp1.EXAMPLES.BTM:ehp1. file which came with
&4OS2..
:p.
You can use :link reftype=hd refid=Grouping.command grouping:elink. to
execute multiple :hp1.commands:ehp1. if the :hp1.condition:ehp1. is
true. For example, the following command tests if any :hp1..TXT:ehp1. files
exist. If they do, they are copied to drive A&colon. and their extensions
are changed to :hp1..TXO:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    if exist *.txt (copy *.txt a&colon. &amp. ren *.txt *.txo)
:exmp.:p.
(Note that the IFF command provides a more structured method of executing
multiple commands if a condition or set of conditions is true.)
:p.
When an IF test fails, the remainder of the command is
discarded, and the command processor normally continues with the next
command on the line, or the next line. This behavior is not compatible with
:hp1.CMD.EXE:ehp1., which discards all remaining commands on the line when
an IF test fails, including those after a command separator or pipe
character. To change the behavior so that IF affects all commands on the
line, as in :hp1.CMD.EXE:ehp1., set :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_DuplicateBugs.DuplicateBugs:elink. to Yes in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIModify.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:p.
For example, if DuplicateBugs is set to Yes (the default), the following
command will display nothing, because the second :link reftype=hd
refid=ECHO.ECHO:elink. command is discarded along with the first when the
:hp3.condition:ehp3. fails. If DuplicateBugs is set to No, it will display
"hello"&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] if 1 == 2 echo Wrong! &amp. echo hello
:exmp.:p.
:hp2.Conditions:ehp2.
:p.
The conditional tests listed in the following sections are available in both
the IF and IFF commands. They fit into two categories&colon. string and
numeric tests, and status tests. The tests can use environment variables,
internal variables and variable functions, filenames, literal
text, and numeric values as their arguments.
:p.
:hp2.String and Numeric Tests:ehp2.
:p.
Six test conditions can be used to test character strings. The
same conditions are available for both numeric and normal text
strings (see below for details). In each case you enter the test
as&colon.
:xmp.
    :hp1.string1:ehp1. operator :hp1.string2:ehp1.
:exmp.:p.
The :hp2.operator:ehp2. defines the type of test (equal, greater than or
equal, and so on). You should always use spaces on both sides of the
:hp2.operator:ehp2. The operators are&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.EQ:ehp2. or :hp2.==:ehp2.:pd.:hp1.string1:ehp1. equal to :hp1.string2:ehp1.
:pt.:hp2.NE:ehp2. or !:hp2.=:ehp2.:pd.:hp1.string1:ehp1. not equal to :hp1.string2:ehp1.
:pt.:hp2.LT:ehp2.:pd.:hp1.string1:ehp1. less than :hp1.string2:ehp1.
:pt.:hp2.LE:ehp2.:pd.:hp1.string1:ehp1. less than or equal to :hp1.string2:ehp1.
:pt.:hp2.GE:ehp2.:pd.:hp1.string1:ehp1. greater than or equal to :hp1.string2:ehp1.
:pt.:hp2.GT:ehp2.:pd.:hp1.string1:ehp1. greater than :hp1.string2:ehp1.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
When IF compares two character strings, it will use either a
:hp2.numeric:ehp2. comparison or a :hp2.string:ehp2. comparison. A numeric
comparison treats the strings as numeric values and tests them
arithmetically. A string comparison treats the strings as text.
:p.
The difference between numeric and string comparisons is best
explained by looking at the way two values are tested. For
example, consider comparing the values 2 and 19. Numerically, 2 is
smaller, but as a string it is "larger" because its first digit is
larger than the first digit of 19. So the first of these
:hp1.conditions:ehp1. will be true, and the second will be false&colon.
:xmp.
    if 2 lt 19 ...
    if "2" lt "19" ...
:exmp.:p.
IF determines which kind of test to do by examining the first
character of each string. If both strings begin with a numeric
character (a digit, sign, or decimal separator), a numeric comparison
is used. (If a string begins with a decimal separator it is not considered
numeric unless the next character is a digit, and there are no more decimal
separators within the string. For example, ".07" is numeric, but ".a"
and ".07.01" are not.) If either value is non-numeric, a string comparison
is used. To force a string comparison when both values are or may be
numeric, use double quotes around the values you are testing, as shown
above. Because the double quote is not a numeric character, IF performs a
string comparison.
:p.
Case differences are ignored in string comparisons. If two strings
begin with the same text but one is shorter, the shorter string is
considered to be "less than" the longer one. For example, "a" is
less than "abc", and "hello_there" is greater than "hello".
:p.
When you compare text strings, you should always enclose the
arguments in double quotes in order to avoid syntax errors which
may occur if one of the argument values is empty.
:p.
Numeric comparisons work with both integer and decimal values. The
values to be compared must contain only numeric digits, decimal
points, and an optional sign (:hp2.+:ehp2. or :hp2.-:ehp2.).
The number may contain up to 16 digits to the left of the decimal point, and
8 digits to the right.
:p.
:link reftype=hd refid=IntVars.Internal variables:elink. and :link
reftype=hd refid=VarFuncs.variable functions:elink. are very powerful when
combined with string and numeric comparisons. They allow you to test the
state of your system, the characteristics of a file, date and time
information, or the result of a calculation. You may want to review the
variables and variable functions when determining the best way to
set up an IF test.
:p.
This batch file fragment runs a program called :hp1.MONOPROG:ehp1. if a
monochrome monitor is attached to the system&colon.
:xmp.
    if "%_monitor" == "mono" monoprog
:exmp.:p.
This batch file fragment tests for a string value&colon.
:xmp.
    input "Enter your selection &colon. " %%cmd
    if "%cmd" == "WP" goto wordproc
    if "%cmd" NE "GRAPHICS" goto badentry
:exmp.:p.
This example calls :hp1.GO.BTM:ehp1. if the first two characters in the
file :hp1.MYFILE:ehp1. are "GO"&colon.
:xmp.
    if "%@left[2,%@line[myfile,0]]" == "GO" call go.btm
:exmp.:p.
:hp2.Status Tests:ehp2.
:p.
These conditions test the system or command processor status. You
can use internal variables and variable functions to test many
other parts of the system status.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=4 break=all.
:pt.:hp2.DEFINED variable:ehp2.:pd.If the variable exists in the
environment, the condition is true. This is equivalent to testing whether
the variable is not empty, for example the following two commands are
equivalent&colon.
:xmp.
    if defined abc echo Hello
    if "%abc" != "" echo Hello
:exmp.
:pt.:hp2.ERRORLEVEL [operator] n:ehp2.:pd.This test retrieves the exit code
of the preceding external program. By convention, programs return an exit
code of 0 when they are successful and a number between 1
and 255 to indicate an error (depending upon the program you are running, the
maximum return value may be larger). The condition can be any
of the operators listed above (:hp2.EQ:ehp2., :hp2.!=:ehp2., :hp2.GT:ehp2.,
etc.). If no operator is specified, the default is :hp2.GE:ehp2.&per. The
comparison is done numerically.
:p.
Not all programs return an explicit exit code. For programs which do not,
the behavior of ERRORLEVEL is undefined.
:pt.:hp2.EXIST filename:ehp2.:pd.If the file exists, the condition is
true. You can use wildcards in the filename, in which case the condition is
true if any file matching the wildcard name exists.
:p.
Do not use IF EXIST to test for existence of a directory
(use IF ISDIR instead). Due to variations in operating system internals, IF
EXIST will not return consistent results when used to test for the existence
of a directory.
:pt.:hp2.ISALIAS aliasname:ehp2.:pd.If the name is defined as an alias, the
condition is true.
:pt.:hp2.ISDIR &splitvbar. DIREXIST path:ehp2.:pd.If the subdirectory exists,
the condition is true.
:pt.:hp2.ISINTERNAL command:ehp2.:pd.If the specified command is an active
internal command, the condition is true. Commands can be activated and
deactivated with the :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /I command.
:pt.:hp2.ISLABEL label:ehp2.:pd.If the specified label exists in the current
batch file, the condition is true. Labels may be one or more words long.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
This batch file fragment tests for the existence of
:hp1.A&colon.\JAN.DOC:ehp1. before copying it to drive C (this avoids an
error message if the file does not exist)&colon.
:xmp.
    if exist a&colon.\jan.doc copy a&colon.\jan.doc c&colon.\
:exmp.:p.
This example tests the exit code of the previous program and stops
all batch file processing if an error occurred&colon.
:xmp.
    if errorlevel == 0 goto success
    echo "External Error -- Batch File Ends!"
    cancel
:exmp.:p.
:hp2.Combining Tests:ehp2.
:p.
You can negate the result of any test with :hp2.NOT:ehp2., and combine
tests of any type with :hp2..AND.:ehp2., :hp2..OR.:ehp2., and
:hp2..XOR.:ehp2.
:p.
When two tests are combined with :hp2..AND.:ehp2., the result is true if
both individual tests are true. When two tests are combined with
:hp2..OR.:ehp2., the result is true if either (or both) individual tests
are true. When two tests are combined with :hp2..XOR.:ehp2., the result
is true only if one of the tests is true and the other is false.
:p.
This example runs a program called :hp1.HIGHRES:ehp1. if either an EGA or
VGA video adapter is in use. Enter this on one line&colon.
:xmp.
    if "%_video" == "EGA" .or. "%_video" == "vga" highres
:exmp.:p.
Test conditions are always scanned from left to right. There is no implied
order of precedence, as there is in some programming languages. You can,
however, force a specific order of testing by grouping conditions with
parentheses, for example (enter this on one line)&colon.
:xmp.
    if (%a == 1 .or. (%b == 2 .and. %c == 3)) echo something
:exmp.:p.
Parentheses can only be used when the portion of the condition inside the
parentheses contains at least one ".and.", ".or.", or ".xor.". Parentheses
on a simple condition which does not combine two or more tests will be taken
as part of the string to be tested, and will probably make the test
fail. For example, the first of these IF tests would fail; the second would
succeed:
:xmp.
    if (a == a) ...
    if (a == a .and. b == b) ...
:exmp.:p.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=IFF.IFF - IF / THEN / ELSE conditional command execution
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Perform IF / THEN / ELSE conditional
execution of commands.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.IFF [NOT] :ehp2.:hp3.condition:ehp3.
:hp2.[.AND. &splitvbar. .OR. &splitvbar. .XOR. [NOT]:ehp2.
:hp3.condition:ehp3. :hp2. ...] THEN :ehp2.:hp3.commands:ehp3.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.[ &amp. ELSEIFF :ehp2.:hp3.condition:ehp3. :hp2. THEN:ehp2.
:hp3.commands:ehp3.:hp2. ] ...:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.[ &amp. ELSE:ehp2.:hp3.commands:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.&amp. ENDIFF:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.condition :ehp3.&colon. A test to determine if the command(s) should be executed.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.commands :ehp3.&colon. One or more commands to execute if the condition(s) is
true. If you use multiple commands, they must be separated by command separators or be
placed on separate lines of a batch file.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=IF.IF:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=_@IF.@IF:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
IFF is similar to the IF command, except that it can perform one
set of :hp1.commands:ehp1. when a condition or set of :hp1.conditions:ehp1. is
true and different :hp1.commands:ehp1. when the :hp1.conditions:ehp1. are
false.
:p.
IFF can also execute multiple commands when the :hp1.conditions:ehp1. are true
or false; IF normally executes only one command. IFF imposes no
limit on the number of commands and is generally a "cleaner" and
more structured command than IF.
:p.
IFF is always followed by one or more :hp1.conditions:ehp1.&per. If they are
true, the :hp1.commands:ehp1. that follow the word THEN are
executed. Additional :hp1.conditions:ehp1. can be tested with ELSEIFF. If
none of these :hp1.conditions:ehp1. are true, the :hp1.commands:ehp1. that
follow the word ELSE are executed. After the selected :hp1.commands:ehp1.
(if any) are executed, processing continues after the word ENDIFF.
:p.
If you add a NOT before the condition, the THEN :hp1.commands:ehp1. are
executed only when the :hp1.condition:ehp1. is false and the ELSE
:hp1.commands:ehp1. are executed only when the :hp1.condition:ehp1. is true.
:p.
The :hp1.commands:ehp1. may be separated by command separators, or may be
on separate lines of a batch file. You should include a command
separator or a line break after a THEN, before an ELSEIFF, and
before and after an ELSE.
:p.
You can link :hp1.conditions:ehp1. with :hp2..AND.:ehp2., :hp2..OR.:ehp2.,
or :hp2..XOR.:ehp2., and you can group conditions with parentheses. You can
nest IFF statements up to 15 levels deep. The
:hp1.conditions:ehp1. can test strings or numbers, the existence of a file
or subdirectory, the errorlevel returned from the preceding
external command, and the existence of alias names and internal
commands.
:p.
See the :link reftype=hd refid=IF.IF:elink. command for a list of the possible
:hp1.conditions:ehp1., and details on using :hp2..AND.:ehp2., :hp2..OR.:ehp2.,
:hp2..XOR.:ehp2., and parentheses.
:p.
The :hp1.commands:ehp1. can include any internal command, alias, external
command, or batch file.
:p.
The following batch file fragment tests the
monitor type (monochrome or color), and sets the appropriate colors
and prompt (enter the "prompt" lines on one line of the batch
file)&colon.
:xmp.
    iff "%_monitor" == "color" then
      color bright white on blue &amp. cls
      prompt=$e[s$e[1;1f$e[41;1;37m$e[K Path&colon. $p$e[u$e[44;37m$n$g
    else
      prompt=$e[s$e[1;1f$e[0;7m$e[K Path&colon. $p$e[u$e[0m$n$g
    endiff
:exmp.:p.
The alias in this second example checks to see if the argument is a
subdirectory. If so, the alias deletes the subdirectory's files
and removes it (enter this on one line)&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias prune `iff isdir %1 then &amp. del /sxz %1
       &amp. else &amp. echo Not a directory! &amp. endiff`
:exmp.:p.
:hp8.Be sure to read the cautionary notes:ehp8. about GOTO and IFF under
the :link reftype=hd refid=GOTO.GOTO:elink. command before using a GOTO inside an IFF
statement.
:p.
If you :link reftype=hd refid=Piping.pipe:elink. data to an IFF, the data
will be passed to the command(s) following the IFF, not to IFF itself.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=INKEY.INKEY - Get a character from the keyboard
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Get a single keystroke from the user and
store it in an environment variable.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.INKEY [/C /D /K"keys" /P /Wn /X]
[:ehp2.:hp3.prompt:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2. :hp3.%%varname:ehp3.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.prompt :ehp3.&colon. Optional text that is displayed as a prompt.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.varname :ehp3.&colon. The variable that will hold the user's keystroke.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./C:ehp2.(lear buffer):pd.:hp2./P:ehp2.(assword)
:pt.:hp2./D:ehp2.(igits only):pd.:hp2./W:ehp2.(ait)
:pt.:hp2./K:ehp2.(valid keystrokes):pd.:hp2./X:ehp2. (no carriage return)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=INPUT.INPUT:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
INKEY optionally displays a prompt. Then it waits for a specified
time or indefinitely for a keystroke, and places the keystroke into
an environment variable. It is normally used in batch files and
aliases to get a menu choice or other single-key input. Along with
the INPUT command, INKEY allows great flexibility in reading input
from within a batch file or alias.
:p.
If :hp1.prompt:ehp1. text is included in an INKEY command, it is displayed
while INKEY waits for input.
:p.
The following batch file fragment prompts for a character and
stores it in the variable :hp1.NUM:ehp1.&colon.
:xmp.
    inkey Enter a number from 1 to 9&colon. %%num
:exmp.:p.
INKEY reads standard input for the keystroke, so it will accept
keystrokes from a redirected file or from the :link reftype=hd
refid=KEYSTACK.KEYSTACK:elink.&per. You can supply a list of valid
keystrokes with the :hp2./K:ehp2. option.
:p.
Standard keystrokes with ASCII values between 1 and 255 are stored
directly in the environment variable. Extended keystrokes (for
example, function keys and cursor keys) are stored as a string in
decimal format, with a leading @ (for example, the :hp2.F1:ehp2. key is
@59). The :hp2.Enter:ehp2. key is stored as an extended keystroke, with
the code @28. See the :link reftype=hd refid=RefTab.Reference Tables:elink.
for a list of the ASCII and extended key codes.
:p.
To test for a non-printing ASCII keystroke returned by INKEY use the
:link reftype=hd refid=_@ASCII.@ASCII:elink. function to get the numeric
value of the key. For example, to test for :hp2.Esc:ehp2., which has an
ASCII value of 27&colon.
:xmp.
    inkey Enter a key&colon. %%key
    if "%@ascii[%key]" == "27" echo Esc pressed
:exmp.:p.
If you press :hp2.Ctrl-C:ehp2. or :hp2.Ctrl-Break:ehp2. while INKEY is waiting
for a key, execution of an alias will be terminated, and execution
of a batch file will be suspended while you are asked whether to
cancel the batch job. A batch file can handle :hp2.Ctrl-C:ehp2. and
:hp2.Ctrl-Break:ehp2. itself with the :link reftype=hd refid=ON.ON:elink.
BREAK command.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./C:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Clear buffer) Clears the keyboard buffer before INKEY
accepts keystrokes. If you use this option, INKEY will ignore any
keystrokes which you type, either accidentally or intentionally, before it
is ready to accept input.
:pt.:hp2./D:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Digits only) Prevents INKEY from accepting any keystroke
except a digit from 0 to 9.
:pt.:hp2./K"keys":ehp2.&colon.:pd.Specify the permissible keystrokes. The list
of valid keystrokes should be enclosed in double
quotes. For alphabetic keys the validity test is
not case-sensitive. You can specify extended keys
by enclosing their names in square brackets (within
the quotes), for example&colon.
:xmp.
    inkey /k"ab[Alt-F10]" Enter A, B, Alt-F10 %%var
:exmp.:p.
See :link reftype=hd refid=KeyNames.Keys and Key Names:elink. for a complete
listing of the key names you can use within the square brackets, and a
description of the key name format.
:p.
If an invalid keystroke is entered, &4OS2. will echo
the keystroke if possible, beep, move the cursor
back one character, and wait for another keystroke.
:pt.:hp2./P:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Password) Prevents INKEY from echoing the character.
:pt.:hp2./W:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Wait) Timeout period, in seconds, to wait for a response.
If no keystroke is entered by the end of the timeout
period, INKEY returns with the variable unchanged. This allows you to
continue the batch file if the user does not respond in a given period of
time. You can specify :hp2./W0:ehp2. to return immediately if
there are no keys waiting in the keyboard buffer.
:p.
For example, the following batch file fragment waits up to 10 seconds for a
character, then tests to see if a "Y" was entered&colon.
:xmp.
    set net=N
    inkey /K"YN" /w10 Load network (Y/N)? %%net
    iff "%net" == "Y" then
    rem Commands to load the network go here
    endiff
:exmp.
:pt.:hp2./X:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(No carriage return) Prevents INKEY from
displaying a carriage return and line feed after the user's entry.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=INPUT.INPUT - Get a string from the keyboard
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Get a string from the keyboard and save it in an
environment variable.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.INPUT [/C /D /E /Ln /N /P /Wn /X]
[:ehp2.:hp3.prompt:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2. :hp3.%%varname:ehp3.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.prompt :ehp3.&colon. Optional text that is displayed as a prompt.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.varname :ehp3.&colon. The variable that will hold the user's input.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./C:ehp2.(lear buffer):pd.:hp2./N:ehp2.(o colors)
:pt.:hp2./D:ehp2.(igits only):pd.:hp2./P:ehp2.(assword)
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2.(dit):pd.:hp2./W:ehp2.(ait)
:pt.:hp2./L:ehp2.(ength):pd.:hp2./X:ehp2. (no carriage return)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=INKEY.INKEY:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
INPUT optionally displays a prompt. Then it waits for a specified
time or indefinitely for your entry. It places any characters you
type into an environment variable. INPUT is normally used in batch
files and aliases to get multi-key input. Along with the INKEY
command, INPUT allows great flexibility in reading user input from
within a batch file or alias.
:p.
If :hp1.prompt:ehp1. text is included in an INPUT command, it is displayed
while INPUT waits for input. Standard command-line editing keys
may be used to edit the input string as it is entered. If you use
the :hp2./P:ehp2. password option, INPUT will echo asterisks instead of
the keys you type.
:p.
All characters entered up to, but not including, the carriage
return are stored in the variable.
:p.
The following batch file fragment prompts for a string and stores
it in the variable FNAME&colon.
:xmp.
    input Enter the filename&colon. %%fname
:exmp.:p.
INPUT reads standard input, so it will accept text from a redirected file.
:p.
If you press :hp2.Ctrl-C:ehp2. or :hp2.Ctrl-Break:ehp2. while INPUT is waiting
for input, execution of an alias will be terminated, and execution
of a batch file will be suspended while you are asked whether to
cancel the batch job. A batch file can handle :hp2.Ctrl-C:ehp2.
and :hp2.Ctrl-Break:ehp2. itself with the :link reftype=hd
refid=ON.ON:elink. BREAK command.
:p.
You should not :link reftype=hd refid=Piping.pipe:elink. text to INPUT. If
you do, INPUT will set the variable to the first line it receives, but it
will set the variable in the "child" process used to handle the right hand
side fo the pipe. This variable will not be available in the original copy
of &4OS2. used to start the pipe.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./C:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Clear buffer) Clears the keyboard buffer before
INPUT accepts keystrokes. If you use this option, INPUT will ignore any
keystrokes which you type, either accidentally or intentionally, before
INPUT is ready.
:pt.:hp2./D:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Digits only) Prevents INKEY from accepting any
keystroke except a digit from 0 to 9.
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Edit) Allows you to edit an existing value. If
there is no existing value for :hp1.varname:ehp1., INPUT proceeds as
if :hp2./E:ehp2. had not been used, and allows you to enter a new value.
:pt.:hp2./Ln:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Length) Sets the maximum number of characters
which INPUT will accept to :hp1.n:ehp1.&per. If you attempt to enter
more than this number of characters, INPUT will beep and prevent further
input (you will still be able to edit the characters typed before the limit
was reached).
:pt.:hp2./N:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(No colors) Disables the use of input colors defined in the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_InputColors.InputColors:elink. directive in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.,
and forces INPUT to use the default display colors.
:pt.:hp2./P:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Password) Tells INPUT to echo asterisks, instead of the
characters you type.
:pt.:hp2./Wn:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Wait) Timeout period, in seconds, to wait for a
response. If no keystroke is entered by the end of the timeout
period, INPUT returns with the variable unchanged. This allows you to
continue the batch file if the user does not respond in a given period of
time. If you enter a key before the timeout period, INPUT will wait
indefinitely for the remainder of the line. You can specify :hp2./W0:ehp2.
to return immediately if there are no keys waiting in the keyboard buffer.
:pt.:hp2./X:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(No carriage return) Prevents INPUT from displaying
a carriage return and line feed after the user's entry.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=KEYBD.KEYBD - Set the keyboard toggles
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Set the state of the keyboard
toggles&colon. Caps Lock, Num Lock, and Scroll Lock.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.KEYBD [/C:ehp2.:hp3.n:ehp3.
:hp2./N:ehp2.:hp3.n:ehp3. :hp2./S:ehp2.:hp3.n:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.n :ehp3.&colon. 0 to turn off the toggle, or 1 to turn on the
toggle.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./C:ehp2.(aps lock):pd.:hp2./S:ehp2.(croll lock)
:pt.:hp2./N:ehp2.(um lock):pd.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
Most keyboards have 3 toggle keys, the Caps Lock, Num Lock, and
Scroll Lock. The toggle key status is usually displayed by three
lights at the top right corner of the keyboard.
:p.
This command lets you turn any toggle key on or off. It is most
useful in batch files and aliases if you want the keys set a
particular way before collecting input from the user.
:p.
For example, to turn off the Num Lock and Caps Lock keys, you can
use this command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] keybd /c0 /n0
:exmp.:p.
If you use the KEYBD command with no switches, it will display the
present state of the toggle keys.
:p.
The toggle key state is typically the same for all sessions, and changes
made with KEYBD in one session will therefore affect all other sessions.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./C:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Caps lock) Turn the Caps Lock key on or off.
:pt.:hp2./N:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Num lock) Turn the Num Lock key on or off.
:pt.:hp2./S:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Scroll lock) Turn the Scroll Lock key on or off.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=KEYS.KEYS - Enable or disable the history list
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Enable, disable, or display the history list.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.KEYS [ON &splitvbar. OFF &splitvbar. LIST]:ehp2.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=HISTORY.HISTORY:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
This command is provided for compatibility with the KEYS command in
:hp1.CMD.EXE:ehp1., which controls the history list in OS/2. The same
functions are available by setting the :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_HistMin.HistMin:elink. directive in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink., and
by using the :link reftype=hd refid=HISTORY.HISTORY:elink. command.
:p.
The history list collects the commands you type for later recall,
editing, and viewing. You can view the contents of the list
through the history list window or by typing any of the following
commands&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] history
    [c&colon.\] history /p
    [c&colon.\] keys list
:exmp.:p.
The first command displays the entire history list. The second
displays the entire list and pauses at the end of each full screen. The
third command produces the same output as the first, except that each line
is numbered.
:p.
You can disable the collection and storage of commands in the
history list by typing&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] keys off
:exmp.:p.
You can turn the history back on with the command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] keys on
:exmp.:p.
If you issue the KEYS command without any parameters, &4OS2.
will show you the current status of the history list.
:p.
KEYS also affects the way &4OS2. reads input from the keyboard. KEYS
OFF will force &4OS2. into line input mode; KEYS ON will return input
to the usual character by character method. See the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_LineInput.LineInput:elink. directive, or the
:hp2./L:ehp2. option of the
:link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. command, for details on line
input mode.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=KEYSTACK.KEYSTACK - Feed keystrokes to a program or command
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Feed keystrokes to a program or command
automatically.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.KEYSTACK [!] [/Wn]
[:ehp2.":hp3.abc:ehp3. ":hp2.] [:ehp2.:hp3.keyname:ehp3. :hp2.[n]] ...:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp2.! :ehp2.&colon. Signal to clear the Keystack and the keyboard
buffer.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.abc :ehp3.&colon. Literal characters to be placed in the
Keystack.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.keyname :ehp3.&colon. Name or code for a key to be placed in the
Keystack.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.n :ehp2.&colon. Number of times to repeat the named key.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./W:ehp2.(ait):pd.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=KeystackUse.Using the Keystack:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
KEYSTACK takes a series of keystrokes and feeds them to a program or command
as if they were typed at the keyboard. When the program has used all of the
keystrokes in the keystack buffer, it will begin to read the keyboard for
input, as it normally would.
:p.
KEYSTACK sends the keystrokes to the current active window. If you want to
send keystrokes to another program (rather than have them function with &4OS2.
itself), you must start the program or :link reftype=hd
refid=ACTIVATE.ACTIVATE:elink. its window so it can receive the
keystrokes. The KEYSTACK command must be executed :hp2.after:ehp2. you
start or ACTIVATE the program which is to receive the keystrokes.
:p.
KEYSTACK is most often used for programs started from batch files. In order
for &4OS2.'s KEYSTACK to work in a batch file, you must start the program with
the :link reftype=hd refid=START.START:elink. command, then use the KEYSTACK
command. If you start the program directly - without using START - the
batch file will wait for the application to complete before continuing and
running the KEYSTACK command, and the keystrokes will be placed in the
buffer too late.
:p.
If you use KEYSTACK in an alias executed from the prompt, the considerations
are essentially the same, but depend on whether :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_ExecWait.ExecWait:elink. is set. If ExecWait is :hp2.not:ehp2.
set, you can use KEYSTACK immediately after an application is
started. However, :hp2.if:ehp2. ExecWait is set, the KEYSTACK command will
not be executed until the program has finished, and the keystrokes will be
placed in the buffer too late.
:p.
You may not be able to use KEYSTACK effectively if you have programs running
in the background which change the active window (for example, by popping up
a dialog box). If a window pops up in the midst of your KEYSTACK sequence,
keystrokes stored in the KEYSTACK buffer may go to that window, and not to
the application you intended.
:p.
KEYSTACK will only work if the program :hp1.KEYSTACK.EXE:ehp1. is
in the same directory :hp1.4OS2.EXE:ehp1., or a directory listed in your
:link reftype=hd refid=PATH_Var.PATH:elink.&per. If
:hp1.KEYSTACK.EXE:ehp1. cannot be found, the KEYSTACK command will display
an error message. KEYSTACK can send keystrokes to Presentation Manager
applications and to OS/2 character-mode applications running in a window. It
cannot send keystrokes to DOS applications, or to character-mode
applications running in a full-screen session.
:p.
Characters entered within double quotes (:hp1."abc":ehp1.) will be sent "as
is" to the application. The only items allowed outside double quotes are
key names, the :hp2.!:ehp2. and :hp2./W:ehp2. options, and a repeat count.
:p.
See :link reftype=hd refid=KeyNames.Keys and Key Names:elink. for
a complete listing of key names and a description of the key name and
numeric key code format. If you want to send the same key name or numeric
code several times, you can follow it with a repeat count in square
brackets. For example, to send the Enter key 4 times, you can use this
command:
:xmp.
    keystack enter [4]
:exmp.:p.
The repeat count works only with individual keystrokes, or numeric keystroke
or character values. It cannot be used with quoted strings.
:p.
An exclamation mark [:hp2.!:ehp2.] will clear all pending keystrokes
in the KEYSTACK buffer.
:p.
For example, to start a program that needs a single space to skip its opening
screen you could use the command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\comm] keystack 32 &amp. progname
:exmp.:p.
This places a space (ASCII code 32) in the buffer, then runs the
program. When the program looks for a keystroke to end the display of the
opening screen the keystroke is already in the buffer, and the opening
screen is removed immediately.
:p.
You can store a maximum of 1023 characters in the &4OS2. KEYSTACK
buffer. The count is determined by the number of characters on the KEYSTACK
command line, not by the actual number of characters sent to the application.
:p.
Each time the KEYSTACK command is executed, it will clear any remaining
keystrokes stored by a previous KEYSTACK command.
:p.
You may need to experiment with your programs and insert delays (see the
:hp2./W:ehp2. option) to find a keystroke sequence that works for a
particular program.
:p.
:hp2.Advanced Options:ehp2.
:p.
KEYSTACK treats the number 0 as a special case; it is used with programs that
flush the keyboard buffer. When KEYSTACK processes a key value of 0, it
tells the program the buffer is clear, so subsequent keystrokes will be
accepted normally. Some programs will require several "0"s before they will
accept input; you may need to experiment to determine the correct number.
:p.
For example, the following batch file starts a spreadsheet program and loads
the file specified on the command line when the batch file is invoked (the
KEYSTACK command should be entered on one line)&colon.
:xmp.
    pushd c&colon.\finance
    keystack 0 Enter 0 Enter 0 Enter 0 Enter 0
     Enter "/FR" 0 "%1" Enter
    spread
    popd
:exmp.:p.
The sequence of "0 Enter" pairs tells the program that the keyboard buffer is
empty, then passes a carriage return, repeating this sequence five
times. (You must determine the actual sequence required by your software
through experimentation. Few programs require as long a startup sequence as
is shown here.) This gets the program to a point where an empty spreadsheet
is displayed. The rest of the KEYSTACK line issues a File Retrieve command
(/FR), simulates an empty keyboard buffer once more, enters the filename
passed on the batch command line (%1), and finally enters a carriage return
to end the filename.
:p.
Here's the same command defined as an alias (enter this on one line)&colon.
:xmp.
    alias sload `pushd c&colon.\finance &amp. keystack 0 Enter 0 Enter 0
     Enter 0 Enter 0 Enter "/FR" 0 "%1" Enter &amp. spread &amp. popd`
:exmp.:p.
KEYSTACK mimics the BIOS by stacking both an ASCII code and a scan code for
each key. It does so by calculating the code for each character, whether it
is entered as part of a quoted string, as a key name, or as an ASCII value
less than 128. However, if you are stacking keys for a program which
distinguishes between keys with the same symbol, like the plus on the
keyboard and the gray plus, you will have to calculate the codes for the
keys on the numeric keypad yourself. Calculate the value ((256 * scan code)
+ ASCII code) and enter that numeric value as an argument for KEYSTACK.
:p.
For example, for the Enter key on the numeric keypad, the scan code is 224
and the ASCII code is 13, so to stack both values use ((256 * 224) + 13) or
KEYSTACK 57357. Try this approach if a "normal" KEYSTACK command does not
work (for example, if you use "KEYSTACK Enter" for the Enter key and the
program doesn't see the correct character). To stack such combined key
codes you must use the numeric value, not the key name. See
:link reftype=hd refid=RefTab.Reference Tables:elink. for ASCII and scan
codes.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml compact tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./W:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Wait) Delay the next keystroke in the
KEYSTACK buffer by a specified number of clock "ticks". A clock tick is
approximately 1/18 second. The number of clock ticks to delay should be
placed immediately after the :hp2.W:ehp2., and must be between 1 and 65535
(65535 ticks is about 1 hour). You can use the :hp2./W:ehp2. option as many
times as desired and at any point in the string of keystrokes except within
double quotes. Some programs may need the delays provided by :hp2./W:ehp2.
in order to receive keystrokes properly from KEYSTACK. The only way to
determine what delay is needed is to experiment. Sometimes a combination of
a delay and an "empty buffer" signal (a 0) are required. For example, to
start the program CADX and send it an :hp2.F7:ehp2., a delay of
one second, an indication that the keyboard buffer is empty, and a carriage
return&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] keystack F7 /W18 0 Enter &amp. cadx
:exmp.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=LIST.LIST - Display a file
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display a file, with forward and backward
paging and scrolling.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.LIST [/A&colon.[[-]rhsda] /H /I /R /S
/T /W /X] :ehp2.:hp3.file:ehp3. :hp2....:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.file :ehp3.&colon. A file or list of files to display.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./A&colon.:ehp2. (Attribute select):pd.:hp2./S:ehp2.(tandard input)
:pt.:hp2./H:ehp2.(igh bit off):pd.:hp2./T:ehp2. (search for Text)
:pt.:hp2./I:ehp2.(gnore wildcards):pd.:hp2./W:ehp2.(rap)
:pt.:hp2./R:ehp2.(everse):pd.:hp2./X:ehp2. (heX display mode)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=TYPE.TYPE:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.File Selection:ehp2.
:p.
Supports extended :link reftype=hd refid=wildcards.wildcards:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=ranges.ranges:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=MultFiles.multiple filenames:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=InclList.include lists:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
LIST provides a fast and flexible way to view a file, without the overhead
of loading and using a text editor.
:p.
For example, to display a file called :hp1.MEMO.DOC:ehp1.&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] list memo.doc
:exmp.:p.
LIST is most often used for displaying ASCII text files. It can be used for
other files which contain non-alphabetic characters, but you may need to use
hex mode (see below) to read these files.
:p.
LIST uses the cursor pad to scroll through the file. The following
keys have special meanings&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=15 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.Home:ehp2.:pd.Display the first page of the file.
:pt.:hp2.End:ehp2.:pd.Display the last page of the file.
:pt.:hp2.Esc:ehp2.:pd.Exit the current file.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-PgUp:ehp2.:pd.Display previous file.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-PgDn:ehp2.:pd.Display next file.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-C:ehp2.:pd.Quit LIST.
:pt.:hp2.PgUp:ehp2.:pd.Scroll up one page.
:pt.:hp2.PgDn or Space:ehp2.:pd.Scroll down one page.
:pt.:hp2.&uarrow.:ehp2.:pd.Scroll up one line.
:pt.:hp2.&darrow.:ehp2.:pd.Scroll down one line.
:pt.:hp2.:ehp2.:pd.Scroll left 8 columns.
:pt.:hp2.:ehp2.:pd.Scroll right 8 columns.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl :ehp2.:pd.Scroll left 40 columns.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl :ehp2.:pd.Scroll right 40 columns.
:pt.:hp2.F1:ehp2.:pd.Display online help
:pt.:hp2.B:ehp2.:pd.Go back one file to the previous file in the current
group of files.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-F:ehp2.:pd.Prompt and search for a string, searching backward
from the end of the file.
:pt.:hp2.F:ehp2.:pd.Prompt and search for a string.
:pt.:hp2.G:ehp2.:pd.Go to a specific line, or, in hex mode, to a specific
hexadecimal offset.
:pt.:hp2.H:ehp2.:pd.Toggle the "strip high bit" (:hp2./H:ehp2.) option.
:pt.:hp2.I:ehp2.:pd.Display information on the current file (the full name,
size, date, and time).
:pt.:hp2.N:ehp2.:pd.Find next matching string.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-N:ehp2.:pd.Find previous match in the file.
:pt.:hp2.P:ehp2.:pd.Print the current page or the entire file.
:pt.:hp2.W:ehp2.:pd.Toggle the "line wrap" (:hp2./W:ehp2.) option.
:pt.:hp2.X:ehp2.:pd.Toggle the hex-mode display (:hp2./X:ehp2.) option.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
Text searches performed with :hp2.F:ehp2., :hp2.N:ehp2., :hp2.Ctrl-F:ehp2.,
and :hp2.Ctrl-N:ehp2. are not case-sensitive. However, if the display is
currently in hexadecimal mode and you press :hp2.F:ehp2. or
:hp2.Ctrl-F:ehp2., you will be prompted for whether you want
to search in hexadecimal mode. If you answer :hp2.Y:ehp2., you should
then enter the search string as a sequence of 2-digit hexadecimal
numbers separated by spaces, for example :hp2.41 63 65:ehp2. (these are
the ASCII values for the string "Ace"; see :link reftype=hd
refid=ASCII.ASCII:elink. for a complete list of ASCII codes). Hexadecimal
searches :hp2.are:ehp2. case-sensitive, and search for exactly the string
you enter.
:p.
When the search string is found LIST displays the line containing the string
at the top of the screen, and highlights the string it found. Any
additional occurrences of the string on the same display page are also
highlighted. Highlighting is intended for use with text files; in binary
files the search string will be found, but may not be highlighted properly.
:p.
You can use :link reftype=hd refid=Wildcards.wildcards:elink. in the search
string. For example, you can search for the string "to*day" to find the
next line which contains the word "to" followed by the word "day"
later on the same line, or search for the numbers "101" or "401" with the
search string "[14]01". If you begin the search string with a back-quote
[:hp2.`:ehp2.], or enclose it in back-quotes, wildcard characters in the
string will be treated as normal text with no special wildcard meaning.
:p.
LIST saves the search string used by :hp2.F:ehp2., :hp2.N:ehp2.,
:hp2.Ctrl-F:ehp2., and :hp2.Ctrl-N:ehp2. so you can
LIST multiple files and search for the same string simply by
pressing :hp2.N:ehp2. in each file, or repeat your search the next time
you use LIST.
:p.
You can use the :hp2./T:ehp2. switch to specify search text for the first
:hp1.file:ehp1.&per. When you do so, LIST begins a search as soon as the file
is loaded. Use :hp2./I:ehp2. to ignore wildcards in the initial search
string, and :hp2./R:ehp2. to make the initial search go backwards from the
end of the file. When you LIST multiple files with a single LIST command,
these switches affect only the first file; they are ignored for the second
and subsequent files.
:p.
You can use the :hp2.G:ehp2. key to go to a specific line number in the
file (or to a specified hexadecimal offset in hex mode). LIST numbers
lines beginning with 1, unless :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_ListRowStart.ListRowStart:elink. is set to 0. A new line is counted for
every CR or LF character (LIST determines automatically which character
is used for line breaks in each file), or when line length reaches 511
characters, whichever comes first.
:p.
LIST normally allows long lines in the file to extend past the
right edge of the screen. You can use the horizontal scrolling
keys (see above) to view text that extends beyond the screen width. If
you use the :hp2.W:ehp2. command or :hp2./W:ehp2. switch to wrap the display,
each line is wrapped when it reaches the right edge of the screen,
and the horizontal scrolling keys are disabled.
:p.
To view text from the clipboard, use :hp2.CLIP&colon.:ehp2. as the file to
be listed. CLIP&colon. will not return any data unless the clipboard
contains text. See :link reftype=hd refid=Redirection.Redirection:elink. for
additional information on CLIP&colon..
:p.
If you print the file which LIST is displaying, the print format
will match the display format. If you have switched to hexadecimal
or wrapped mode, that mode will be used for the printed output as
well. If you print in wrapped mode, long lines will be wrapped at
the width of the display. If you print in normal display mode
without line wrap, long lines will be wrapped or truncated by the
printer, not by LIST.
:p.
Printed output normally goes to device LPT1. If you wish to send
the printed output to another device, use the
:link reftype=hd refid=CommandsOption.Commands page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
or the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_Printer.Printer:elink. directive in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:p.
If you specify a directory name instead of a filename as an argument, LIST
will display each of the files in that directory.
:p.
Most of the LIST keystrokes can be reassigned with :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=INIKeyMap.key mapping:elink. directives.
:p.
You can set the colors used by LIST on the
:link reftype=hd refid=CommandsOption.Commands page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
or the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_ListColors.ListColors:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ListStatBarColors.ListStatBarColors:elink.
directives in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. If ListColors
is not used, the LIST display will use the current default colors. If
ListStatBarColors is not used, the status bar will use the reverse of the LIST
display colors.
:p.
By default, LIST sets tab stops every 8 columns. You can change this
behavior on the :link reftype=hd refid=DisplayOption.Display page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
or with the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_TabStops.TabStops:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. directive.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml compact tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Attribute select) Select only those files that have the
specified attribute(s) set. Preceding the attribute character with a
hyphen [:hp2.-:ehp2.] will select files that do not have that attribute set. The colon
[:hp2.&colon.:ehp2.] after /A is required. The attributes are&colon.
.br
:parml tsize=8 compact break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  R:ehp2. Read-only
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  H:ehp2. Hidden
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  S:ehp2. System
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  D:ehp2. Subdirectory
:pt.:pd.:hp2.  A:ehp2. Archive
:eparml.:p.
If no attributes are listed at all (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., :hp2.LIST /A&colon. ...:ehp2.), LIST will select all
files and subdirectories including hidden and system files. If
attributes are combined, all the specified attributes must match for a
file to be selected. For example, /A&colon.RHS will select only those files
with all three attributes set.
.br
:pt.:hp2./H:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(High bit off) Strip the high bit from each character
before displaying. This is useful when displaying
files created by some word processors that turn on
the high bit for formatting purposes. You can
toggle this option on and off from within LIST with
the :hp2.H:ehp2. key.
.br
:pt.:hp2./I:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Ignore wildcards) Only meaningful when used in
conjunction with the :hp2./T "text":ehp2. option. Directs LIST to interpret
characters such as :hp2.*:ehp2., :hp2.?:ehp2., :hp2.[:ehp2., and
:hp2.]:ehp2. as literal characters instead of wildcard
characters. :hp2./I:ehp2. affects only the initial search started by
:hp2./T:ehp2., not subsequent searches started from within LIST.
.br
:pt.:hp2./R:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Reverse) Only meaningful when used in
conjuction with the :hp2./T "text" :ehp2.option. Directs LIST to search for
text from the end of the file instead of from the beginning of the
file. Using this switch can speed up searches for text that is normally
near the end of the file, such as a signature. :hp2./R:ehp2. affects only
the initial search started by :hp2./T:ehp2., not subsequent searches started
from within LIST.
.br
:pt.:hp2./S:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Standard input) Read from standard input rather than a
file. This allows you to redirect command output
and view it with LIST. Normally, LIST will detect input from a redirected
command and adjust automatically. However, you may find circumstances when
:hp2./S:ehp2. is required. For example, to use LIST to
display the output of DIR you could use either of these commands&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir &splitvbar. list
    [c&colon.\] dir &splitvbar. list /s
:exmp.
.br
:pt.:hp2./T:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Text) Search for text in the first
:hp1.file:ehp1.&per. This option is the same as pressing :hp2.F:ehp2., but it
allows you to specify the search text on the command line. The text must be
contained in quotation marks if it contains spaces, punctuation, or wildcard
characters. For example, to search for the string &4OS2. in the file
:hp1.README.DOC:ehp1., you can use this command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] list /t4os2 readme.doc
:exmp.:p.
The search text may include :link reftype=hd refid=Wildcards.wildcards
and extended wildcards:elink.&per. For example, to search for the words Hello
and John on the same line in the file :hp1.LETTER.DAT:ehp1.&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] list /t"Hello*John" letter.dat
:exmp.:p.
When you LIST multiple files with a single LIST command, :hp2./T:ehp2. only
initiates a search in the first file. It is ignored for the second and
subsequent files. Also see :hp2./I:ehp2. and :hp2./R:ehp2.&per.
.br
:pt.:hp2./W:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Wrap) Wrap the text at the right edge of the
screen. This option is useful when displaying files that don't have a
carriage return at the end of each line. The horizontal scrolling keys do
not work when the display is wrapped. You can toggle this option on and off
from within LIST with the :hp2.W:ehp2. key.
.br
:pt.:hp2./X:ehp2.:pd.(heX mode)&colon. Display the file in hexadecimal
(hex) mode. This option is useful when displaying executable files and other
files that contain non-text characters. Each byte of the file is shown as a
pair of hex characters. The corresponding text is displayed to the right of
each line of hexadecimal data. You can toggle this mode on and off from
within LIST with the :hp2.X:ehp2. key.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=LOADBTM.LOADBTM - Switch a batch file's mode
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Switch a batch file to or from BTM mode.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.LOADBTM [ON &splitvbar. OFF]:ehp2.
:eparml.:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
&4OS2. recognizes two kinds of :link reftype=hd refid=Batch.batch
files:elink.&colon. :hp1..BAT:ehp1. or :hp1..CMD:ehp1., and
:hp1..BTM:ehp1.&per. Batch files executing in BTM mode run two to ten times
faster than in BAT or CMD mode. Batch files automatically start in the mode
indicated by their extension.
:p.
The LOADBTM command turns BTM mode on and off. It can be used to
switch modes in either a :hp1..BAT:ehp1. / :hp1..CMD:ehp1., or
:hp1..BTM:ehp1. file. If you use LOADBTM with no argument, it will display
the current batch mode&colon. LOADBTM ON or LOADBTM OFF.
:p.
Using LOADBTM to repeatedly switch modes within a batch file is not
efficient. In most cases the speed gained by running some parts of the file
in BTM mode will be more than offset by the speed lost through repeated
loading of the file each time BTM mode is invoked.
:p.
LOADBTM can only be used within a batch file. It is most often
used to convert a :hp1..BAT:ehp1. or :hp1..CMD:ehp1. file to BTM mode
without changing its extension.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=LOG.LOG - Save a log of commands
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Save a log of commands to a disk file.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.LOG [/H /W :ehp2.:hp3.file:ehp3. :hp2.]
[ON &splitvbar. OFF &splitvbar. :ehp2.:hp3.text:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.file :ehp3.&colon. The name of the file to hold the log.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.text :ehp3.&colon. An optional message that will be added to the log.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./H(:ehp2.istory log):pd.:hp2./W:ehp2.(rite to).
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=HISTORY.HISTORY:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
LOG keeps a record of all internal and external commands you use, whether
they are executed from the prompt or from a batch file. Each entry includes
the current system date and time, along with the actual command after any
alias or variable expansion. You can use the log file as a record of your
daily activities.
:p.
LOG with the :hp2./H:ehp2. option keeps a similar record called a "history
log". The history log records only commands entered at the prompt; it does
not record batch file commands. In addition, the history log does not
record the date and time for each command, and it records commands before
aliases and variables are expanded.
:p.
The two logging options are independent. You can have both a regular log
and a history log enabled simultaneously.
:p.
By default, LOG writes to the file :hp1.4OS2LOG:ehp1. in the root directory
of the boot drive. The default filename for the history log is
:hp1.4OS2HLOG:ehp1.&per. You can set the default log file names on the
:link reftype=hd refid=Options2.Options 2 page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
or with the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_LogName.LogName:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_HistLogName.HistLogName:elink. directives in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:p.
Entering LOG or LOG /H with no parameters displays the name of the log file
and the log status (ON or OFF)&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] log
    LOG (C&colon.\4OS2LOG) is OFF
:exmp.:p.
To enable or disable logging, add the word "ON" or "OFF" after the
LOG command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] log on
:exmp.:p.
or
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] log /h on
:exmp.:p.
Entering LOG or LOG /H with :hp1.text:ehp1. writes a message to the log
file, even if logging is set OFF. This allows you to enter
headers in the log file&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] log "Started work on the database system"
:exmp.:p.
The LOG file format looks like this&colon.
:xmp.
    [date time] command
:exmp.:p.
where the date and time are formatted according to the country code set
for your system.
:p.
The LOG /H output can be used as the basis for writing batch files. Start
LOG /H, then execute the commands that you want the batch
file to execute. When you are finished, turn LOG /H off. The
resulting file can be turned into a batch file that performs the
same commands with little or no editing.
:p.
You can have both a regular log (with time and date stamping) and a
history log (without the time stamps) enabled simultaneously.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml compact tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./H:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(History log) This option makes the other options
on the command line (after the :hp2./H:ehp2.) apply to the history log. For
example, to turn on history logging and write to the file
:hp1.C&colon.\LOG\HLOG:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] log /h /w c&colon.\log\hlog
:exmp.
:pt.:hp2./W:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Write) This switch specifies a different filename for the
LOG or LOG /H output. It also automatically
performs a LOG ON command. For example, to turn
logging on and write the log to :hp1.C&colon.\LOG\LOGFILE:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] log /w c&colon.\log\logfile
:exmp.
.br
Once you select a new filename with the LOG /W or LOG /H/W command, LOG
will use that file until you issue another LOG /W or LOG /H/W command, or
until you reboot your computer. Turning LOG or LOG /H off or on does not
change the filename.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=MD.MD - Create a subdirectory
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Create a subdirectory.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.MD [/N /S]:ehp2.
:hp3.path:ehp3. :hp2....:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.   or
:pt.:pd.:hp2.MKDIR [/N /S]:ehp2. :hp3.path:ehp3. :hp2....:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.path :ehp3.&colon. The name of one or more directories to create.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./N:ehp2.(o update):pd.:hp2./S:ehp2.(ubdirectories)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=RD.RD:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
MD and MKDIR are synonyms. You can use either one.
:p.
MD creates a subdirectory anywhere in the directory tree. To
create a subdirectory from the root, start the :hp1.path:ehp1. with a
backslash [:hp2.\:ehp2.]. For example, this command creates a
subdirectory called :hp1.MYDIR:ehp1. in the root directory&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] md \mydir
:exmp.:p.
If no path is given, the new subdirectory is created in the current
directory. This example creates a subdirectory called :hp1.DIRTWO:ehp1.
in the current directory&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\mydir] md dirtwo
:exmp.:p.
To create a directory from the parent of the current directory
(that is, to create a sibling of the current directory), start the
pathname with two periods and a backslash [:hp2...\:ehp2.].
:p.
When creating a directory on a volume supporting long filenames, you must quote any
:hp1.path:ehp1. which contains whitespace or special characters. See
:link reftype=hd refid=Filenames.Filenames:elink. for
additional details on filename quoting.
:p.
If MD creates one or more directories, they will be added automatically to
the :link reftype=hd refid=ExtDirSearch.extended directory search:elink. database
unless the :hp2./N:ehp2. option is specified.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./N:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(No Update) Do not update the
:link reftype=hd refid=ExtDirSearch.extended directory search:elink. database,
:hp1.JPSTREE.IDX:ehp1. This is useful when creating a temporary directory
which you do not want to appear in the extended search database.
:pt.:hp2./S:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Subdirectories) MD creates one directory at a
time unless you use the :hp2./S:ehp2. option. If you need to create
the directory :hp1.C&colon.\ONE\TWO\THREE:ehp1. and none of the
named directories exist, you can use :hp2./S:ehp2. to have MD create all of
the necessary subdirectories for you in a single command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] md /s \one\two\three
:exmp.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=MEMORY.MEMORY - Display memory statistics
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display the amount and status of system RAM.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.MEMORY:ehp2.
:eparml.:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
MEMORY lists the total physical and resident RAM in your system,
the largest free block of RAM, the swap file size,
the total and free environment and alias space, and the total
history space. If you use a non-standard swap file location, the swap
file size will be displayed as 0 unless you set the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_SwapFilePath.SwapFilePath:elink. directive.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=MOVE.MOVE - Move files
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Move files to a new directory and drive.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.MOVE [/A&colon.[[-]rhsda] /C /D /E /F
/H /J /M /N /P /Q /R /S /T /U /V]:ehp2. :hp3.source:ehp3. :hp2....:ehp2.
:hp3.destination:ehp3.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.source :ehp3.&colon. A file or list of files to move.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.destination :ehp3.&colon. The new location for the files.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./A&colon.:ehp2. (Attribute select):pd.:hp2./N:ehp2.(othing)
:pt.:hp2./C:ehp2.(hanged):pd.:hp2./P:ehp2.(rompt)
:pt.:hp2./D:ehp2.(irectory):pd.:hp2./Q:ehp2.(uiet)
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2. (No error messages):pd.:hp2./R:ehp2.(eplace)
:pt.:hp2./F:ehp2.(orce delete):pd.:hp2./S:ehp2.(ubdirectory tree)
:pt.:hp2./H:ehp2.(idden and system):pd.:hp2./T:ehp2.(otal)
:pt.:hp2./J:ehp2.(CMD directory move):pd.:hp2./U:ehp2.(pdate)
:pt.:hp2./M:ehp2.(odified files):pd.:hp2./V:ehp2.(erify)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=COPY.COPY:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=REN.RENAME:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.File Selection:ehp2.
:p.
Supports extended :link reftype=hd refid=wildcards.wildcards:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=ranges.ranges:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=MultFiles.multiple filenames:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=InclList.include lists:elink.&per. Date, time, or size
ranges anywhere on the line apply to all :hp1.source:ehp1. files.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
The MOVE command moves one or more files from one directory to
another, whether the directories are on the same drive or not. It
has the same effect as copying the files to a new location and then
deleting the originals. Like COPY and RENAME, MOVE works with
single files, multiple files, and sets of files specified with an
include list.
:p.
The simplest MOVE command moves a single :hp1.source:ehp1. file to a new
location and, optionally, gives it a new name. These two examples
both move one file from drive :hp1.C&colon.:ehp1. to the root directory on drive
:hp1.A&colon.:ehp1.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] move myfile.dat a&colon.\
    [c&colon.\] move myfile.dat a&colon.\savefile.dat
:exmp.:p.
In both cases, :hp1.MYFILE.DAT:ehp1. is removed from drive :hp1.C&colon.:ehp1. after it
has been copied to drive :hp1.A&colon.:ehp1.&per. If a file called :hp1.MYFILE.DAT:ehp1.
in the first example, or :hp1.SAVEFILE.DAT:ehp1. in the second example,
already existed on drive :hp1.A&colon.:ehp1., it would be overwritten. (This
demonstrates the difference between MOVE and RENAME. MOVE will
move files between drives and will overwrite the destination file
if it exists; RENAME will not.)
:p.
When you move a single file, the :hp1.destination:ehp1. can be a directory
name or a filename. If it is a directory name, and you add a backslash
[:hp2.\:ehp2.] to the end of the name, MOVE will display an error message if
the name does not refer to an existing directory. You can use this feature
to keep MOVE from treating a mistyped :hp1.destination:ehp1. directory name
as a filename, and attempting to move the :hp1.source:ehp1. file to that
name.
:p.
If you move multiple files, the :hp1.destination:ehp1. :hp2.must:ehp2. be a
directory name. MOVE will move each file into the :hp1.destination:ehp1.
directory with its original name. If the :hp1.destination:ehp1. is not a
directory, MOVE will display an error message and exit. For example, if
:hp1.C&colon.\FINANCE\MYFILES:ehp1. is not a directory, this command will
display an error; otherwise, the files will be moved to that directory&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] move *.wks *.txt c&colon.\finance\myfiles
:exmp.:p.
The :hp2./D:ehp2. option can be used for single or multiple file moves; it
checks to see whether the :hp1.destination:ehp1. is a directory, and will
prompt to see if you want to create the :hp1.destination:ehp1. directory if
it doesn't exist.
:p.
If MOVE creates one or more destination directories, they will be added
automatically to the
:link reftype=hd refid=ExtDirSearch.extended directory search:elink. database.
:p.
You cannot move a file to a character device like the printer, or
to itself.
:p.
:hp8.Be careful when you use MOVE with the :link reftype=hd refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink.
command.:ehp8. If you SELECT multiple files and the destination is not a
directory (for example, because of a misspelling), MOVE will assume
it is a filename. In this case each file will be moved in turn to
the destination file, overwriting the previous file, and then the
original will be erased before the next file is moved. At the end
of the command, all of the original files will have been erased and
only the last file will exist as the destination file.
:p.
You can avoid this problem by using square brackets with SELECT instead of
parentheses (be sure that you don't allow the command line to get
too long -- watch the character count in the upper left corner
while you're selecting files). MOVE will then receive one list of
files to move instead of a series of individual filenames, and it
will detect the error and halt. You can also add a backslash
[:hp2.\:ehp2.] to the end of the :hp1.destination:ehp1. name to ensure that
it is the name of a subdirectory (see above).
:p.
:hp2.Advanced Features and Options:ehp2.
:p.
MOVE first attempts to rename the file(s), which is the fastest way
to move files between subdirectories on the same drive. If that
fails (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., because the :hp1.destination:ehp1. is on a different
drive or already exists), MOVE will copy the file(s) and then delete the
originals.
:p.
If MOVE must physically copy the files and delete the originals,
rather than renaming them (see above), then some disk space may be
freed on the :hp1.source:ehp1. drive. The free space may be the result of
moving the files to another drive, or of overwriting a larger
:hp1.destination:ehp1. file with a smaller :hp1.source:ehp1. file. MOVE
displays the amount of disk space recovered unless the :hp2./Q:ehp2. option
is used (see below). It does so by comparing the amount of free disk space
before and after the MOVE command is executed. However, this
amount may be incorrect if you are using a deletion tracking system
which retains deleted files for later recovery, or if another program
performs a file operation while the MOVE command is executed.
:p.
When physically copying files, MOVE preserves the hidden, system,
and read-only attributes of the :hp1.source:ehp1. files, and sets the
archive attribute of the :hp1.destination:ehp1. files. However, if the
files can be renamed, and no copying is required, then the file attributes
are not changed.
:p.
Use caution with the :hp2./A&colon.:ehp2. and :hp2./H:ehp2. switches (both
of which can allow MOVE to process hidden files) when you are physically
moving files, and both the :hp1.source:ehp1. and :hp1.destination:ehp1.
directories contain file descriptions. If the :hp1.source:ehp1. file
specification matches the description file name (normally
:hp1.DESCRIPT.ION:ehp1.), and you tell MOVE to process hidden files, the
:hp1.DESCRIPT.ION:ehp1. file itself will be moved, overwriting any existing
file descriptions in the :hp1.destination:ehp1. directory. For example, if
the :hp1.C&colon.\DATA:ehp1. directory contains file descriptions, this
command would overwrite any existing descriptions in the
:hp1.D&colon.\SAVE:ehp1. directory:
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\data] move /h d*.* d&colon.\save\
:exmp.:p.
(If you remove the hidden attribute from the :hp1.DESCRIPT.ION:ehp1. file
the same caution applies even if you do not use :hp2./A&colon.:ehp2. or
:hp2./H:ehp2., as :hp1.DESCRIPT.ION:ehp1. is then treated like any other
file.)
:p.
If you move a file from a FAT16 volume to a volume supporting long filenames,
and you do not give an explicit :hp1.destination:ehp1. name (:hp1.i.e.:ehp1.
you are moving the file to the current directory, or your :hp1.destination:ehp1.
name is made up entirely of wildcards), MOVE will look for a &per.LONGNAME extended
attribute for the :hp1.source:ehp1. file. If it finds that attribute, it will
use the long filename for the destination file. If it does not, it will use the
short name.
:p.
Similarly, if you MOVE files with long filenames from a volume supporting long
filenames to a FAT16 volume, &4OS2. will create the :hp1.destination:ehp1. files
with short, FAT-compatible names and save the long filenames in the &per.LONGNAME
extended attribute. The short name is created by replacing special characters
with underscores, adding numeric digits to the filename (if necessary) to make
the new name unique, and truncating the name to fit with in the "8.3" FAT16
name structure.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./A&colon.:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Attribute select) Select only those files that have the
specified attribute(s) set. Preceding the attribute character with a
hyphen [:hp2.-:ehp2.] will select files that do not have that attribute set. The colon
[:hp2.&colon.:ehp2.] after :hp2./A:ehp2. is required. The attributes are&colon.
:parml tsize=8 compact break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   R:ehp2. Read-only
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   H:ehp2. Hidden
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   S:ehp2. System
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   D:ehp2. Subdirectory
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   A:ehp2. Archive
:eparml.:p.
If no attributes are listed at all (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., :hp2.MOVE /A&colon. ...:ehp2.), MOVE will select all
files and subdirectories including hidden and system files. If
attributes are combined, all the specified attributes must match for a
file to be selected. For example, /A&colon.RHS will select only those files
with all three attributes set.
:p.
See the cautionary note under :hp2.Advanced Features and Options:ehp2. above
before using :hp2./A&colon.:ehp2. when both :hp1.source:ehp1. and
:hp1.destination:ehp1. directories contain file descriptions.
:pt.:hp2./C:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Changed files) Move files only if the :hp1.destination:ehp1.
file exists and is older than the :hp1.source:ehp1. (see also
:hp2./U:ehp2.). This option is useful for updating the files in one
directory from those in another without moving any newly-created files.
:pt.:hp2./D:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Directory) Requires that the :hp1.destination:ehp1. be a
directory. If the :hp1.destination:ehp1. does not exist, MOVE will prompt
to see if you want to create it. If the :hp1.destination:ehp1. exists as a
file, MOVE will fail with an "Access denied" error. Use this option to
avoid having MOVE accidentally interpret your :hp1.destination:ehp1. name as
a filename when it's really a mistyped directory name.
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(No error messages) Suppress all non-fatal error
messages, such as "File Not Found." Fatal error messages, such as "Drive
not ready," will still be displayed. This option is most useful in batch
files and aliases.
:pt.:hp2./F:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Force delete) This option forces deletion of the
:hp1.source:ehp1. file without saving it to the DELDIR directory (if DELDIR
is not in use, :hp2./F:ehp2. has no effect). :hp2./F:ehp2. is only
effective when MOVE must copy the :hp1.source:ehp1. file(s) and delete the
originals (:hp1.i.e.:ehp1., if the :hp1.destination:ehp1. is on a different
drive or the destination file already exists). If the files are simply
renamed, :hp2./F:ehp2. has no effect.
:pt.:hp2./H:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Hidden) Move all files, including hidden and
system files. See the cautionary note under :hp2.Advanced Features and
Options:ehp2. above before using :hp2./H:ehp2. when both :hp1.source:ehp1. and
:hp1.destination:ehp1. directories contain file descriptions.
:pt.:hp2./J:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(CMD directory move) CMD moves the 
directory to the target when the command line aurgument is a directory. 
By default &4OS2. moves the files in the directory to the target. Using 
/J makes &4OS2. provide the CMD behavior. This can be set as the default
by :link reftype=hd refid=INI_CMDDirMvCpy.CMDDirMvCpy:elink.=yes in &4OS2INI..
:pt.:hp2./M:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Modified files) Move only files that have the
archive bit set. The archive bit will remain set after the MOVE; to clear it
use :link reftype=hd refid=ATTRIB.ATTRIB:elink.&per.
:pt.:hp2./N:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Nothing) Do everything except actually move the file(s).
This option is most useful for testing what a
complex MOVE command will do.
:pt.:hp2./P:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Prompt) Prompt the user to confirm each move. Your options
at the prompt are explained in detail under :link reftype=hd refid=Prompts.Page and File Prompts:elink.&per.
:pt.:hp2./Q:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Quiet) Don't display filenames, the total number of files
moved, or the amount of disk space recovered, if
any. This option is most often used in batch files.
See also :hp2./T:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:hp2./R:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Replace) Prompt for a :hp2.Y:ehp2. or :hp2.N:ehp2. response before
overwriting an existing :hp1.destination:ehp1. file.
:pt.:hp2./S:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Subdirectories) Move an entire subdirectory tree to
another location. MOVE will attempt to create the
:hp1.destination:ehp1. directories if they don't exist, and
will remove empty subdirectories after the move. When :hp2./D:ehp2. is used
with :hp2./S:ehp2., you will be prompted if the first :hp1.destination:ehp1.
directory does not exist, but subdirectories below that will be
created automatically by MOVE. If MOVE /S creates one or more destination
directories, they will be added automatically to the
:link reftype=hd refid=ExtDirSearch.extended directory search:elink. database.
:p.
If you attempt to use :hp2./S:ehp2. to move a subdirectory tree into part of
itself, MOVE will detect the resulting infinite loop, display an error
message, and exit.
:pt.:hp2./T:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Total) Don't display filenames as they are moved, but
display the total number of files moved and the
amount of free disk space recovered, if any.
:pt.:hp2./U:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Update) Move each :hp1.source:ehp1. file only
if it is newer than a matching :hp1.destination:ehp1. file or if a matching
:hp1.destination:ehp1. file does not exist (also see :hp2./C:ehp2.). This
option is useful for moving new or changed files from one directory to
another.
:pt.:hp2./V:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Verify) Verify each disk write. This is the
same as executing the VERIFY ON command, but is only active during the
MOVE. :hp2./V:ehp2. does :hp2.not:ehp2. read back the file and compare its
contents with what was written; it only verifies that the data written to
disk is physically readable.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=ON.ON - Handle Ctrl-Break and errors in batch files
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Execute a command in a batch file when a
specific condition occurs.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.ON BREAK [:ehp2.:hp3.command:ehp3.
:hp2.]:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.   or
:pt.:pd.:hp2.ON ERROR [:ehp2.:hp3.command:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.   or
:pt.:pd.:hp2.ON ERRORMSG [:ehp2.:hp3.command:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
:eparml.:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
ON can only by used in batch files.
:p.
ON sets a "watchdog" that remains in effect for the duration of the
current batch file. Whenever a BREAK or ERROR condition occurs
after ON has been executed, the corresponding :hp1.command:ehp1. is
automatically executed.
:p.
ON BREAK will execute the :hp1.command:ehp1. if the user presses
:hp2.Ctrl-C:ehp2. or :hp2.Ctrl-Break:ehp2.&per.
:p.
ON ERROR and ON ERRORMSG will execute the :hp1.command:ehp1. after any
command processor or operating system error (including :link reftype=hd
refid=CritErr.critical errors:elink.). That is, they will detect errors
such as a disk write error, and &4OS2. errors such as a COPY command that
fails to copy any files, or the use of an unacceptable command option.
:p.
ON ERROR executes the :hp1.command:ehp1. immediately after the error occurs,
without displaying any command processor error message (operating system
errors may still be displayed in some cases). ON ERRORMSG displays the
appropriate error message, then executes the :hp1.command:ehp1.&per. If both
are specified, ON ERROR will take precedence, and the ON ERRORMSG setting
will be ignored. The remainder of this section discusses both settings
together, using the term "ON ERROR[MSG]".
:p.
ON BREAK and ON ERROR[MSG] are independent of each other. You can use
either one, or both, in any batch file.
:p.
Each time ON BREAK or ON ERROR[MSG] is used, it defines a new
:hp1.command:ehp1. to be executed for a break or error, and any old
:hp1.command:ehp1. is discarded. If you use ON BREAK or ON ERROR[MSG]
with no following :hp1.command:ehp1., that type of error handling is
disabled. Error handling is also automatically disabled when the batch file
exits.
:p.
ON BREAK and ON ERROR[MSG] only affect the current batch file. If you
CALL another batch file, the first batch file's error handling is
suspended, and the CALLed file must define its own error handling. When
control returns to the first batch file, its error handling is reactivated.
:p.
The :hp1.command:ehp1. can be any command that can be used on a batch file
line by itself. Frequently, it is a :link reftype=hd refid=GOTO.GOTO:elink.
or :link reftype=hd refid=GOSUB.GOSUB:elink. command. For example, the
following fragment traps any user attempt to end the batch file by pressing
:hp2.Ctrl-C:ehp2. or :hp2.Ctrl-Break:ehp2.&per. It scolds the user for trying
to end the batch file and then continues displaying the numbers from 1 to
1000&colon.
:xmp.
    on break gosub gotabreak
    do i = 1 to 1000
      echo %i
    enddo
    quit
    &colon.gotabreak
    echo Hey! Stop that!!
    return
:exmp.:p.
You can use a :link reftype=hd refid=Grouping.command group:elink. as the :hp1.command:ehp1. if you
want to execute multiple commands, for example&colon.
:xmp.
    on break (echo Oops, got a break! &amp. quit)
:exmp.:p.
ON BREAK and ON ERROR[MSG] always assume that you want to continue
executing the batch file. After the :hp1.command:ehp1. is executed,
control automatically returns to the next command in the batch file
(the command after the one that was interrupted by the break or
error). The only way to avoid continuing the batch file after a
break or error is for the :hp1.command:ehp1. to transfer control to
another point with :link reftype=hd refid=GOTO.GOTO:elink., end the batch
file with :link reftype=hd refid=QUIT.QUIT:elink. or :link reftype=hd
refid=CANCEL.CANCEL:elink., or start another batch file (without CALLing it).
:p.
When handling an error condition with ON ERROR[MSG], you may find it
useful to use :link reftype=hd refid=IntVars.internal variables:elink.,
particularly :link reftype=hd refid=__QMARK.%_?:elink. and :link reftype=hd
refid=_SYSERR.%_SYSERR:elink., to help determine the cause of the error.
:p.
The ON ERROR[MSG] command will :hp2.not:ehp2. be invoked if an error occurs
while reading or writing a redirected input file, output file, or pipe.
:p.
:hp8.Caution&colon.:ehp8. If a break or error occurs while the
:hp1.command:ehp1. specified in ON BREAK or ON ERROR[MSG] is executing, the
:hp1.command:ehp1. will be restarted. This means you must use caution to
avoid or handle any possible errors in the commands invoked by ON ERROR[MSG],
since such errors can cause an infinite loop.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=OPTION.OPTION - Modify the command processor configuration
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Modify the command processor configuration
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.OPTION [//:ehp2.:hp3.optname:ehp3.
:hp2.=:ehp2.:hp3.value:ehp3. :hp2....]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.optname :ehp3.&colon. An INI file directive to set or modify.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.value :ehp3.&colon. A new value for that directive.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
When run without parameters, OPTION displays a settings notebook which allows
you to modify many of the configuration options stored in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:p.
See
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.
for more information.
:p.
:hp2.Setting Individual Options:ehp2.
:p.
If you follow the OPTION command with one or more sequences of a double slash
mark [:hp2.//:ehp2.] followed by an :hp2.option=value:ehp2. setting, the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.
will not be presented. Instead, the new settings will take effect
immediately, and will be in effect for the current session only. This
example turns off batch file echo and changes the input colors to bright
cyan on black (enter this all on one line)&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] option //BatchEcho = No //InputColors = bri cya on bla
:exmp.:p.
Option values may contain whitespace. However, you cannot enter an option
value which contains the "//" string.
:p.
This feature is most useful for testing settings quickly, and in aliases or
batch files which depend on certain options being in effect.
:p.
Changes made with :hp2.//:ehp2. are temporary. They will not be saved in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink., even if you subsequently load the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.
and click :hp2.Save:ehp2.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=PATH.PATH - Set the executable file search path
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display or alter the list of directories
that &4OS2. will search for executable files, batch files, and files with
executable extensions that are not in the current directory.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.PATH [:ehp2.:hp3.directory:ehp3.
:hp2.[;:ehp2.:hp3.directory:ehp3. :hp2....]]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.directory :ehp3.&colon. The full name of a directory to include in the path setting.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=ESET.ESET:elink. and :link reftype=hd refid=SET.SET:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
When &4OS2. is asked to execute an external command (a :hp1..COM:ehp1.,
:hp1..EXE:ehp1., :hp1..BTM:ehp1., :hp1..BAT:ehp1., or :hp1..CMD:ehp1. file or executable
extension), it first looks for the file in the current directory.
If it fails to find an executable file there, it then searches each
of the :hp1.directories:ehp1. specified in the PATH setting.
:p.
For example, after the following PATH command, &4OS2. will search for
an executable file in four directories&colon. the current directory,
then the root directory on drive C, then the :hp1.DOS:ehp1. subdirectory
on C, and then the :hp1.UTIL:ehp1. subdirectory on C&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] path c&colon.\;c&colon.\dos;c&colon.\util
:exmp.:p.
The list of :hp1.directories:ehp1. to search can be set or viewed with the
PATH command. The list is stored as an environment string, and can
also be set or viewed with SET, and edited with ESET.
:p.
Directory names in the path must be separated by semicolons
[:hp2.;:ehp2.]. Each directory name is shifted to upper case to maintain
compatibility with programs which can only recognize upper case
directory names in the path. If you modify your path with the
:link reftype=hd refid=SET.SET:elink. or :link reftype=hd refid=ESET.ESET:elink. command, you may include directory
names in lower case. These may cause trouble with some programs,
which assume that all path entries have been shifted to upper case.
:p.
If you enter PATH with no parameters, the current path is
displayed&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] path
    PATH=C&colon.\;C&colon.\DOS;C&colon.\UTIL
:exmp.:p.
Entering PATH and a semicolon clears the search path so that only
the current directory is searched for executable files (this is the
default at system startup).
:p.
Some applications also use the PATH to search for their data files.
:p.
&4OS2. normally searches the path for files with the extensions
:hp1..COM:ehp1., :hp1..EXE:ehp1., :hp1..BTM:ehp1., :hp1..CMD:ehp1., and :hp1..BAT:ehp1.
(in that order). However, if you include an explicit file extension on
a command name (for example, :hp1.WP.EXE:ehp1.), the search will find
files with that name and extension in the current directory and every
directory in the path. It will not locate other executable files with
the same base name (:hp1.e.g., WP.COM).:ehp1.
:p.
The standard list of extensions for which to search can be modified by
setting :link reftype=hd refid=INI_PathExt.PathExt:elink. to Yes in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink., then setting the :link reftype=hd
refid=PATHEXT.PATHEXT:elink. variable.
:p.
If you have an entry in the path which consists of a single period
[:hp2..:ehp2.], the current directory will :hp2.not:ehp2. be searched first,
but instead will be searched when &4OS2. reaches the ":hp2..:ehp2." in the
path. This allows you to delay the search of the current directory for
executable files and files with executable extensions. In rare
cases, this feature may not be compatible with applications which
use the path to find their files; if you experience a problem, you
will have to remove the "." from the path while using any such
application.
:p.
To create a path longer than the command-line length limit, use
PATH repeatedly to append additional directories to the path&colon.
:xmp.
    path [first list of directories]
    path %path;[second list of directories]
    ...
:exmp.:p.
You cannot use this method to extend the path beyond 2042 characters
(the internal buffer limit, with room for "PATH "). It is usually more efficient to
use aliases to load application programs than to create a long
PATH. See :link reftype=hd refid=ALIAS.ALIAS:elink. for details.
:p.
If you specify an invalid directory in the path, it will be skipped
and the search will continue with the next directory in the path.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=PAUSE.PAUSE - Suspend batch file or alias execution
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Suspend batch file or alias execution.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.PAUSE [:ehp2.:hp3.text:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.text :ehp3.&colon. The message to be displayed as a user prompt.
:eparml.:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
A PAUSE command will suspend execution of a batch file or alias,
giving you the opportunity to change disks, turn on the printer,
etc.
:p.
PAUSE waits for any key to be pressed and then continues execution.
You can specify the :hp1.text:ehp1. that PAUSE displays while it waits for
a keystroke, or let it use the default message&colon.
:xmp.
    Press any key when ready...
:exmp.:p.
For example, the following batch file fragment prompts the user
before erasing files&colon.
:xmp.
    pause Press Ctrl-C to abort, any other key to erase all .LST files
    erase *.lst
:exmp.:p.
If you press :hp2.Ctrl-C:ehp2. or :hp2.Ctrl-Break:ehp2. while PAUSE is waiting
for a key, execution of an alias will be terminated, and execution
of a batch file will be suspended while you are asked whether to
cancel the batch job. In a batch file you can handle :hp2.Ctrl-C:ehp2.
and :hp2.Ctrl-Break:ehp2. yourself with the :link reftype=hd refid=ON.ON:elink. BREAK command.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=POPD.POPD - Restore the disk drive and directory
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Return to the disk drive and directory at
the top of the directory stack..
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.POPD [*]:ehp2.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=DIRS.DIRS:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=PUSHD.PUSHD:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=DirNav.Directory Navigation:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
Each time you use the PUSHD command, it saves the current disk
drive and directory on the internal directory stack. POPD restores
the last drive and directory that was saved with PUSHD and removes
that entry from the stack. You can use these commands together to
change directories, perform some work, and return to the starting
drive and directory.
:p.
Directory changes made with POPD are recorded in the directory history
list and can be displayed in the :link reftype=hd refid=DirHist.directory
history window:elink.&per. See
:link reftype=hd refid=DirNav.Directory Navigation:elink. for complete details
on this and other directory navigation features.
:p.
This example saves and changes the current disk drive and directory
with PUSHD, and then restores it. The current directory is shown
in the prompt&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] pushd d&colon.\database\test
    [d&colon.\database\test] pushd c&colon.\wordp\memos
    [c&colon.\wordp\memos] pushd a&colon.\123
    [a&colon.\123] popd
    [c&colon.\wordp\memos] popd
    [d&colon.\database\test] popd
    [c&colon.\]
:exmp.:p.
You can use the DIRS command to see the complete list of saved
drives and directories (the directory stack).
:p.
The POPD command followed by an asterisk [:hp2.*:ehp2.] clears the
directory stack without changing the current drive and directory.
:p.
If the directory on the top of the stack is not on the current
drive, POPD will switch to the drive and directory on the top of
the stack without changing the default directory on the current
drive.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=PROMPT.PROMPT - Change the command-line prompt
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Change the command-line prompt.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.PROMPT [:ehp2.:hp3.text:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.text :ehp3.&colon. Text to be used as the new command-line prompt.
:eparml.:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
You can change and customize the command-line prompt at any time. The
prompt can include normal text, and system information such as
the current drive and directory, the time and date, and the amount
of memory available. You can create an informal "Hello, Bob!"
prompt or an official-looking prompt full of impressive information. The
prompt :hp1.text:ehp1. can contain special commands in the form
:hp2.$?:ehp2., where :hp2.?:ehp2. is one of the characters listed below&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=6 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.b:ehp2.:pd.The vertical bar character [:hp2.&splitvbar.:ehp2.].
:pt.:hp2.c:ehp2.:pd.The open parenthesis [:hp2.(:ehp2.].
:pt.:hp2.d:ehp2.:pd.Current date, in the format&colon. :hp1.Fri
2-12-17:ehp1. (the month, day, and year are formatted according to your
current country settings).
:pt.:hp2.D:ehp2.:pd.Current date, in the format&colon. :hp1.Fri Dec 12,
2017:ehp1.&per.
:pt.:hp2.e:ehp2.:pd.The ASCII ESC character (decimal 27).
:pt.:hp2.f:ehp2.:pd.The close parenthesis [:hp2.):ehp2.].
:pt.:hp2.g:ehp2.:pd.The :hp2.>:ehp2. character.
:pt.:hp2.h:ehp2.:pd.Backspace over the previous character.
:pt.:hp2.i:ehp2.:pd.Display the OS/2 prompt header line, which reminds you
of how to return to the OS/2 desktop, or get help.
:pt.:hp2.l:ehp2.:pd.The :hp2.<:ehp2. character.
:pt.:hp2.m:ehp2.:pd.Time in hours and minutes using 24-hour format&colon. :hp1.16&colon.07:ehp1.
:pt.:hp2.M:ehp2.:pd.Time in hours and minutes using the default country format and
retaining "a" or "p", :hp1.e.g. 4&colon.07p:ehp1.&per.
:pt.:hp2.n:ehp2.:pd.Current drive letter.
:pt.:hp2.p:ehp2.:pd.Current directory (lower case).
:pt.:hp2.P:ehp2.:pd.Current directory (upper case on FAT16 volumes; directory
names shown in mixed case as stored on the disk on volumes supporting case retention).
:pt.:hp2.q:ehp2.:pd.The :hp2.=:ehp2. character.
:pt.:hp2.r:ehp2.:pd.The numeric exit code of the last external command.
:pt.:hp2.s:ehp2.:pd.The space character.
:pt.:hp2.t:ehp2.:pd.Current 24-hour time, in the format :hp1.hh&colon.mm&colon.ss:ehp1.&per.
:pt.:hp2.T:ehp2.:pd.Current 12-hour time, in the format :hp1.hh&colon.mm&colon.ss[a&splitvbar.p]:ehp1.&per.
:pt.:hp2.v:ehp2.:pd.Operating system version number, in the format :hp1.3.10:ehp1.&per.
:pt.:hp2.xd&colon.:ehp2.:pd.Current directory on drive :hp1.d&colon.:ehp1.,
in lower case, including the drive letter (uses the actual case of the
directory name as stored on the disk for volumes supporting case retention).
:pt.:hp2.Xd&colon.:ehp2.:pd.Current directory on drive :hp1.d&colon.:ehp1.,
in upper case, including the drive letter.
:pt.:hp2.z:ehp2.:pd.Current shell nesting level; the primary command
processor is shell 0.
:pt.:hp2.+:ehp2.:pd.Display one :hp2.+:ehp2. character for each directory
on the PUSHD directory stack.
:pt.:hp2.$:ehp2.:pd.The $ character.
:pt.:hp2._:ehp2.:pd.CR/LF (go to beginning of a new line).
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
For example, to set the prompt to the current date and time, with a
">" at the end&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] prompt $D $t $g
    Fri  Jun 6, 2017 10&colon.29&colon.19 >
:exmp.:p.
To set the prompt to the current date and time, followed by the
current drive and directory in upper case on the next line, with a
">" at the end&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] prompt $d $t$_$P$g
    Fri  Dec 2, 2014 10&colon.29&colon.19
    [c&colon.\]
:exmp.:p.
The &4OS2. prompt can be set in :hp1.CONFIG.SYS:ehp1. (see
below), and the prompt for any command processor can be set in
:link reftype=hd refid=AutoBatch.4START:elink., or in any batch file that
runs when &4OS2. starts.
:p.
The &4OS2. default prompt is :hp2.[$n]:ehp2. (drive name in square brackets)
on floppy drives, and :hp2.[$p]:ehp2. (current drive and directory in
square brackets) on all other drives. When OS/2 is installed, it
inserts a SET PROMPT statement in :hp1.CONFIG.SYS:ehp1. to set the prompt
to :hp2.$i[$p]:ehp2.&per. This prompt will override the &4OS2. defaults. The
:hp2.$i:ehp2. adds a header line to the default prompt to remind you of
certain OS/2 keystrokes. You must delete this statement if you
want to use the default &4OS2. prompt.
:p.
If you enter PROMPT with no arguments, the prompt will be reset to
its default value. The PROMPT command sets the environment
variable PROMPT, so to view the current prompt setting use the
command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] set prompt
:exmp.:p.
(If the prompt is not set at all, the PROMPT environment variable
will not be used, in which case the SET command above will give a
"Not in environment" error.)
:p.
Along with literal text, special characters, and ANSI sequences
you can include the text of any :link reftype=hd refid=environment.environment:elink.
variable, :link reftype=hd refid=IntVars.internal variable:elink.,
or :link reftype=hd refid=VarFuncs.variable function:elink. in a
prompt. For example, if you want to include the size of the largest free
memory block in the command prompt, plus the current drive and directory,
you could use this command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] prompt (%%@dosmem[K]K) $p$g
    (601K) [c&colon.\data]
:exmp.:p.
Notice that the @DOSMEM function is shown with two leading percent
signs [:hp2.%:ehp2.]. If you used only one percent sign, the @DOSMEM
function would be expanded once when the PROMPT command was
executed, instead of every time the prompt is displayed. As a
result, the amount of memory would never change from the value it
had when you entered the PROMPT command. You can also use back
quotes to delay expanding the variable function until the prompt is
displayed&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] prompt `(%@dosmem[K]K) $p$g`
:exmp.:p.
You can use this feature along with the :link reftype=hd
refid=_@EXEC.@EXEC:elink. variable function to create a complex prompt which
not only displays information but executes commands. For example, to
execute an alias which checks battery status each time the prompt is
displayed (enter the alias on one line)&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias cbatt `if %_apmlife lt 30 beep 440 4 880 4 440
     4 880 4`
    [c&colon.\] prompt `%@exec[@cbatt]$p$g`
:exmp.:p.
You can include ANSI escape sequences in the PROMPT
:hp1.text:ehp1.&per. See :link reftype=hd refid=ANSI.ANSI:elink. for complete
details on ANSI commands. This example uses ANSI sequences to set a prompt
that displays the shell level, date, time and path in color on the top line of
the screen (enter the command as one line)&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] prompt $e[s$e[1;1f$e[41;1;37m$e[K[$z] $d
       Time&colon. $t$h$h$h Path&colon. $p$e[u$e[0;32m$n$g
:exmp.:p.
A few older batch files use the PROMPT command to transmit
:hp1.ANSI.SYS:ehp1. control sequences to the screen (for example, to redefine
function keys). This technique will not work with &4OS2., because it
doesn't display a prompt within batch files; hence, the characters in the
PROMPT string are never sent to :hp1.ANSI.SYS:ehp1.&per. To send ANSI sequences
in &4OS2., use the :link reftype=hd refid=ECHO.ECHO:elink. command,
substituting an :link reftype=hd refid=Escape.escape character:elink.
followed by an :hp2.e:ehp2. for :hp2.$e:ehp2. in the PROMPT string.
:p.
You may find it helpful to define a different prompt in secondary
shells, perhaps including :hp2.$z:ehp2. in the prompt to display the shell
level. To do so, place a PROMPT command in your :hp1.4START:ehp1. file
and use :link reftype=hd refid=IF.IF:elink. or :link reftype=hd
refid=IFF.IFF:elink. statements to set the appropriate prompt for different
shells.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=PUSHD.PUSHD - Save the disk drive and directory
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Save the current disk drive and directory,
optionally changing to a new drive and directory.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.PUSHD [:ehp2.:hp3.path:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.path :ehp3.&colon. The name of the new default drive and directory.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=CD.CD:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=CDD.CDD:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=DIRS.DIRS:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=POPD.POPD:elink., and :link reftype=hd refid=DirNav.Directory
Navigation:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
PUSHD saves the current drive and directory on a "last in, first
out" directory stack. The POPD command returns to the last drive
and directory that was saved by PUSHD. You can use these commands
together to change directories, perform some work, and return to
the starting drive and directory. The DIRS command displays the
contents of the directory stack.
:p.
To save the current drive and directory, without changing
directories, use the PUSHD command by itself, with no :hp1.path:ehp1.&per.
:p.
If a :hp1.path:ehp1. is specified as part of the PUSHD command, the
current drive and directory are saved and PUSHD changes to the
specified drive and directory. If the :hp1.path:ehp1. includes a
drive letter, PUSHD changes to the specified directory on the new
drive without changing the current directory on the original drive.
:p.
This example saves the current directory and changes to
:hp1.C&colon.\WORDP\MEMOS:ehp1., then returns to the original directory&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] pushd \wordp\memos
    [c&colon.\wordp\memos] popd
    [c&colon.\]
:exmp.:p.
When you use PUSHD to change to a directory on a volume supporting long filenames, you
must quote the :hp1.path:ehp1. name if it contains whitespace or special
characters. See :link reftype=hd refid=Filenames.Filenames:elink. for
additional details.
:p.
PUSHD can also change to a network drive and directory specified with a UNC
name (see :link reftype=hd refid=Filesys.Filesystems:elink. for a
description of UNC names).
:p.
If PUSHD cannot change to the directory you have specified it will attempt to
search the :link reftype=hd refid=CDPATH.CDPATH:elink. and the
:link reftype=hd refid=ExtDirSearch.extended directory search:elink.
database. You can also use wildcards in the :hp1.path:ehp1. to force an
extended directory search. See the :link reftype=hd refid=DirNav.Directory
Navigation:elink. section for complete details on these and other directory
navigation features.
:p.
Directory changes made with PUSHD are also recorded in the
:link reftype=hd refid=DirHist.directory history list:elink. and can be
displayed in the directory history window.
:p.
The directory stack can hold up to 511 characters, or about 20 to
40 entries (depending upon the length of the names). If you exceed
this limit, the oldest entry is removed before adding a new entry.
:p.
The :hp2./N:ehp2. option available in :link reftype=hd
refid=CD.CD:elink. and :link reftype=hd refid=CDD.CDD:elink. to disable
extended directory searches is not available in PUSHD. To disable
extended searches when using PUSHD, save the current directory with
PUSHD (without parameters) and then use CDD /N to change directories,
for example&colon.
:xmp.
   pushd
   cdd /n testdir
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=QUIT.QUIT - Terminate a batch file
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Terminate the current batch file.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.QUIT [:ehp2.:hp3.value:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.value :ehp3.&colon. The numeric exit code to return to &4OS2. or
to the previous batch file.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=CANCEL.CANCEL:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
QUIT provides a simple way to exit a batch file before reaching the
end of the file. If you QUIT a batch file called from another
batch file, you will be returned to the previous file at the line
following the original CALL.
:p.
QUIT only ends the current batch file. To end all batch file
processing, use the CANCEL command.
:p.
If you specify a :hp1.value:ehp1., QUIT will set the ERRORLEVEL or exit
code to that value.
If you do not specify a :hp1.value:ehp1., the current ERRORLEVEL value
will be retained.
For information on exit codes see the :link reftype=hd
refid=IF.IF:elink. command, and the :link reftype=hd refid=_QMARK.%?:elink.
variable.
:p.
You can also use QUIT to terminate an alias. If you QUIT an alias
while inside a batch file, QUIT will end both the alias and the
batch file and return you to the command prompt or to the calling
batch file.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=RD.RD - Remove subdirectories
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Remove one or more subdirectories.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.RD :ehp2.:hp3.path:ehp3. :hp2....:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.   or
:pt.:pd.:hp2.RMDIR :ehp2.:hp3.path:ehp3. :hp2....:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.path :ehp3.&colon. The name of one or more subdirectories to remove.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=MD.MD:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.File Selection:ehp2.
:p.
Supports extended :link reftype=hd refid=wildcards.wildcards:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=ranges.ranges:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=MultFiles.multiple filenames:elink., and :link reftype=hd refid=InclList.include lists:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
RD and RMDIR are synonyms. You can use either one.
:p.
RD removes directories from the directory tree. For example, to
remove the subdirectory :hp1.MEMOS:ehp1. from the subdirectory :hp1.WP:ehp1., you
can use this command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] rd \wp\memos
:exmp.:p.
Before using RD, you must delete all files and subdirectories (and
their files) in the :hp1.path:ehp1. you want to remove. Remember to
remove hidden and read-only files as well as normal files (you can
use DEL /Z to delete hidden and read-only files).
:p.
You can use wildcards in the :hp1.path:ehp1.&per.
:p.
When removing a directory on a volume supporting long filenames, you must quote any :hp1.path:ehp1.
which contains whitespace or special characters. See :link reftype=hd
refid=Filenames.Filenames:elink. for additional details.
:p.
If RD removes one or more directories, they will be deleted automatically
from the :link reftype=hd refid=ExtDirSearch.extended directory search:elink.
database.
:p.
You cannot remove the root directory, the current directory
(:hp2..:ehp2.), any directory above the current directory in the directory
tree, or any directory in use by another process in a multitasking
system.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=REBOOT.REBOOT - Reboot the system
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Do a system reboot.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.REBOOT [/S /V]:ehp2.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./S:ehp2.(hutdown):pd.:hp2./V:ehp2.(erify)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
REBOOT will log off or shut down the operating system, or completely restart
your computer. It normally performs a warm reboot, which is comparable to
pressing Ctrl-Alt-Delete. A reboot is necessary to activate any changes to
your :hp1.CONFIG.SYS:ehp1. file.
:p.
The following example prompts you to verify the reboot, then does a
warm boot&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] reboot /v
:exmp.:p.
REBOOT defaults to performing a warm boot, with no prompting.
:p.
REBOOT flushes the disk buffers, resets the drives, and waits one
second before rebooting, to allow disk caching programs to finish
writing any cached data. &4OS2. issues commands to shut down OS/2
before rebooting.
:p.
REBOOT uses the DOS.SYS device driver to reboot your
system. DOS.SYS is loaded via a DEVICE= statement in your
:hp1.CONFIG.SYS:ehp1. file. If DOS.SYS is not loaded, REBOOT will not
work.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./S:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Shutdown) Shut down the system, but do not
reboot. This option is equivalent to clicking the "Shutdown" choice on the
Workplace Shell popup menu.
:pt.:hp2./V:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Verify) Prompt for confirmation (:hp2.Y:ehp2.
or :hp2.N:ehp2.) before rebooting or taking the action specified by other
REBOOT options.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=REM.REM - Put a comment in a batch file
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Put a comment in a batch file.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.REM [:ehp2.:hp3.comment:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.comment :ehp3.&colon. The text to include in the batch file.
:eparml.:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
The REM command lets you place a remark or comment in a batch file. Batch
file comments are useful for documenting the purpose of a batch file and the
procedures you have used.
:p.
REM must be followed by a space or tab character and then your
comment. Comments can be up to 1023 characters long. &4OS2. will normally
ignore everything on the line after the REM command, including
quote characters, redirection symbols, and other commands (see
below for the exception to this rule).
:p.
If ECHO is ON, the comment is displayed. Otherwise, it is ignored. If ECHO
is ON and you don't want to display the line, preface the REM command with
an at sign [:hp2.@:ehp2.].
:p.
You can also place a comment in a batch file by starting the comment line
with two colons [:hp2.&colon.&colon.:ehp2.]. In essence this creates a
batch file "label" without a valid label name. Such comments are processed
slightly faster than those entered with REM, because they do not require the
command processor to handle a command.
:p.
You can use REM to create a zero-byte file if you use a redirection
symbol after the REM command. No text is permitted between
the REM command and the redirection symbol. For example, to
create the zero-byte file :hp1.C&colon.\FOO:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] rem > foo
:exmp.:p.
(This capability is included for compatibility with
:hp1.CMD.EXE:ehp1.&per. A simpler method for creating a zero-byte file
with &4OS2. is to use :hp2.>filename:ehp2. as a command, with no actual
command before the [:hp2.>:ehp2.] redirection character.)

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=REN.REN - Rename files or subdirectories
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Rename files or subdirectories.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.REN [/A&colon.[[-]rhsda] /E /N /P /Q /S
/T]:ehp2. :hp3.old_name:ehp3. :hp2...&per. :ehp2.:hp3.new_name:ehp3.
:pt.:pd.   or
:pt.:pd.:hp2.RENAME [/A&colon.[[-]rhsda] /E /N /P /Q /S /T]:ehp2.
:hp3.old_name:ehp3. :hp2....:ehp2. :hp3.new_name:ehp3.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.old_name :ehp3.&colon. Original name of the file(s) or subdirectory.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.new_name :ehp3.&colon. New name to use, or new path on the same drive.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./A&colon.:ehp2. (Attribute select):pd.:hp2./Q:ehp2.(uiet)
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2. (No error messages):pd.:hp2./S:ehp2.(ubdirectory)
:pt.:hp2./N:ehp2.(othing):pd.:hp2./T:ehp2.(otal)
:pt.:hp2./P:ehp2.(rompt)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=COPY.COPY:elink. and :link reftype=hd refid=MOVE.MOVE:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.File Selection:ehp2.
:p.
Supports extended :link reftype=hd refid=wildcards.wildcards:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=ranges.ranges:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=MultFiles.multiple filenames:elink., and :link reftype=hd refid=InclList.include lists:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
REN and RENAME are synonyms. You may use either one.
:p.
REN lets you change the name of a file or a subdirectory, or move
one or more files to a new subdirectory on the same drive. (If you
want to move files to a different drive, use MOVE.)
:p.
In its simplest form, you give REN the :hp1.old_name:ehp1. of an
existing file or subdirectory and then a :hp1.new_name:ehp1.&per. The
:hp1.new_name:ehp1. must not already exist -- you can't give two files the
same name (unless they are in different directories). The first
example renames the file :hp1.MEMO.TXT:ehp1. to :hp1.MEM.TXT:ehp1.&per. The
second example changes the name of the :hp1.\WORD:ehp1. directory to
:hp1.\WP:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] rename memo.txt mem.txt
    [c&colon.\] rename \word \wp
:exmp.:p.
If you use REN to rename a directory, the :link reftype=hd
refid=ExtDirSearch.extended directory search:elink. database will be
automatically updated to reflect the change.
:p.
When you rename files on a volume supporting long filenames, you must quote any file
names which contain whitespace or special characters. See :link reftype=hd
refid=Filenames.Filenames:elink. for additional details.
:p.
You can also use REN to rename a group of files that you specify
with wildcards, as multiple files, or in an include list. When you
do, the :hp1.new_name:ehp1. must use one or more wildcards to show what
part of each filename to change. Both of the next two examples
change the extensions of multiple files to :hp1..SAV:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] ren config.sys autoexec.bat 4start.btm *.sav
    [c&colon.\] ren *.txt *.sav
:exmp.:p.
REN can move files to a different subdirectory on the same drive. When it
is used for this purpose, REN requires one or more filenames for the
:hp1.old_name:ehp1. and a directory name for the :hp1.new_name:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] ren memo.txt \wp\memos\
    [c&colon.\] ren oct.dat nov.dat \data\save\
:exmp.:p.
The final backslash in the last two examples is optional. If you
use it, you force REN to recognize the last argument as the name of
a directory, not a file. The advantage of this approach is that if
you accidentally mistype the directory name, REN will report an
error instead of renaming your files in a way that you didn't
intend.
:p.
Finally, REN can move files to a new directory and change their
name at the same time if you specify both a path and filename for
:hp1.new_name:ehp1.&per. In this example, the files are renamed with an
extension of :hp1..SAV:ehp1. as they are moved to a new directory&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] ren *.dat \data\save\*.sav
:exmp.:p.
You cannot rename a subdirectory to a new location on the directory tree.
:p.
REN does not change a file's attributes. The :hp1.new_name:ehp1. file(s)
will have the same attributes as :hp1.old_name:ehp1.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./A&colon.:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Attribute select) Select only those
files that have the specified attribute(s) set. Preceding the attribute
character with a hyphen [:hp2.-:ehp2.] will select files that do not have
that attribute set. The colon [:hp2.&colon.:ehp2.] after :hp2./A:ehp2. is
required. The attributes are&colon.
:parml tsize=8 compact break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   R:ehp2. Read-only
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   H:ehp2. Hidden
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   S:ehp2. System
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   D:ehp2. Subdirectory
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   A:ehp2. Archive
:eparml.:p.
If no attributes are listed at all (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., :hp2.REN /A&colon. ...:ehp2.), REN will select all
files and subdirectories including hidden and system files. If
attributes are combined, all the specified attributes must match for a
file to be selected. For example, /A&colon.RHS will select only those files
with all three attributes set.
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(No error messages) Suppress all non-fatal error
messages, such as "File Not Found." Fatal error messages, such as "Drive
not ready," will still be displayed. This option is most useful in batch
files.
:pt.:hp2./N:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Nothing) Do everything except actually rename
the file(s). This option is useful for testing what a REN command will
actually do.
:pt.:hp2./P:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Prompt) Prompt the user to confirm each rename
operation. Your options at the prompt are explained in detail
under :link reftype=hd refid=Prompts.Page and File Prompts:elink.&per.
:pt.:hp2./Q:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Quiet) Don't display filenames or the number of
files renamed. This option is most often used in batch files. See also
:hp2./T:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:hp2./S:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Subdirectory) Normally, you can rename a subdirectory
only if you do not use any wildcards in the :hp1.new_name:ehp1.&per. This
prevents subdirectories from being renamed inadvertently when a group of
files is being renamed with wildcards. :hp2./S:ehp2. will let you
rename a subdirectory even when you use wildcards. :hp2./S :ehp2.does
:hp2.not:ehp2. cause REN to process files in the current directory and all
subdirectories as it does in some other file processing commands. To rename
files throughout a directory tree, use a :link reftype=hd
refid=GLOBAL.GLOBAL:elink. REN.
:pt.:hp2./T:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Total) Don't display filenames as they are renamed, but
report the number of files renamed. See also
:hp2./Q:ehp2.&per.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=RETURN.RETURN - Return from a subroutine in a batch file
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Return from a GOSUB (subroutine) in a batch
file.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.RETURN [:ehp2.:hp3.value:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.value :ehp3.&colon. The exit code from 0 to 255 to return to the
command processor or to the previous batch file.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=GOSUB.GOSUB:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
&4OS2. allows subroutines in batch files.
:p.
A subroutine begins with a label (a colon followed by a word) and
ends with a RETURN command.
:p.
The subroutine is invoked with a GOSUB command from another part of
the batch file. When a RETURN command is encountered the
subroutine terminates, and execution of the batch file continues on
the line following the original GOSUB. If RETURN is encountered without a
GOSUB, the command processor will display a "Missing GOSUB" error.
:p.
The following batch file fragment calls a subroutine which displays
the files in the current directory&colon.
:xmp.
    echo Calling a subroutine
    gosub subr1
    echo Returned from the subroutine
    quit

    &colon.subr1
    dir /a/w
    return
:exmp.:p.
If you specify a :hp1.value:ehp1., RETURN will set the ERRORLEVEL or exit
code to that value. For information on exit codes see the :link reftype=hd
refid=IF.IF:elink. command, and the %:link reftype=hd refid=QMARK.?:elink.
variable.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=SCREEN.SCREEN - Position the cursor and display text
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Position the cursor on the screen and optionally
display a message.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.SCREEN :ehp2.:hp3.row column:ehp3.
:hp2.[:ehp2.:hp3.text:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.row :ehp3.&colon. The new row location for the cursor.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.column :ehp3.&colon. The new column location for the cursor.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.text :ehp3.&colon. Optional text to display at the new cursor location.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=ECHO.ECHO:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=SCRPUT.SCRPUT:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=TEXT.TEXT:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=VSCRPUT.VSCRPUT:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
SCREEN allows you to create attractive screen displays in batch
files. You use it to specify where a message will appear on the
screen. You can use SCREEN to create menus and other similar displays. The
following batch file fragment displays a menu&colon.
:xmp.
    @echo off
    cls
    screen 3 10  Select a number from 1 to 4&colon.
    screen 6 20  1 - Word Processing
    screen 7 20  2 - Spreadsheet
    screen 8 20  3 - Telecommunications
    screen 9 20  4 - Quit
:exmp.:p.
SCREEN does not change the screen colors. To display text in specific
colors, use SCRPUT or VSCRPUT. SCREEN always leaves the cursor at the
end of the displayed text.
:p.
The :hp1.row:ehp1. and :hp1.column:ehp1. values are zero-based, so on a standard
25 line by 80 column display, valid :hp1.rows:ehp1. are 0 - 24 and valid
:hp1.columns:ehp1. are 0 - 79. You can also specify the :hp1.row:ehp1. and
:hp1.column:ehp1. as offsets from the current cursor position. Begin the
value with a plus sign [:hp2.+:ehp2.] to move the cursor down the
specified number of rows or to the right the specified number of
columns, or with a minus sign [:hp2.-:ehp2.] to move the cursor up or to
the left. This example prints a string 3 lines above the current
position, in absolute column 10&colon.
:xmp.
    screen -3 10 Hello, World!
:exmp.:p.
If you specify 999 for the :hp1.row:ehp1., SCREEN will center the text
vertically on the display. If you specify 999 for the :hp1.column:ehp1.,
SCREEN will center the text horizontally. This example prints a message at
the center of the display&colon.
:xmp.
    screen 999 999 Hello, World
:exmp.:p.
SCREEN checks for a valid :hp1.row:ehp1. and :hp1.column:ehp1., and displays a
"Usage" error message if either value is out of range.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=SCRPUT.SCRPUT - Display text in color
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Position text on the screen and display it in color.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.SCRPUT :ehp2.:hp3.row col:ehp3.
:hp2.[BRIght] [BLInk]:ehp2. :hp3.fg:ehp3. :hp2.ON
[BRIght] :ehp2.:hp3.bg text:ehp3.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.row :ehp3.&colon. Starting row
:pt.:pd.:hp3.col :ehp3.&colon. Starting column
:pt.:pd.:hp3.fg :ehp3.&colon. Foreground character color
:pt.:pd.:hp3.bg :ehp3.&colon. Background character color
:pt.:pd.:hp3.text :ehp3.&colon. The text to display
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=ECHO.ECHO:elink., :link reftype=hd
refid=SCREEN.SCREEN:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=TEXT.TEXT:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=VSCRPUT.VSCRPUT:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
SCRPUT allows you to create attractive screen displays in batch
files. You use it to specify where a message will appear on the
screen and what colors will be used to display the message text. You can
use SCRPUT to create menu displays, logos, etc.
:p.
SCRPUT works like SCREEN, but requires you to specify the display
colors. See :link reftype=hd refid=Colors.Colors and Color Names:elink. for
details about colors and notes on the use of bright background colors.
:p.
The :hp1.row:ehp1. and :hp1.column:ehp1. are zero-based, so on a standard 25
line by 80 column display, valid rows are 0 - 24 and valid columns are 0
- 79. SCRPUT checks for a valid :hp1.row:ehp1. and :hp1.column:ehp1., and
displays a "Usage" error message if either value is out of range.
:p.
You can also specify the :hp1.row:ehp1. and :hp1.column:ehp1. as
offsets from the current cursor position. Begin the value with a plus sign
[:hp2.+:ehp2.] to move down the specified number of rows or to the right
the specified number of columns, or with a minus sign [:hp2.-:ehp2.] to
move up or to the left.
:p.
If you specify 999 for the :hp1.row:ehp1., SCRPUT will center the text
vertically on the display. If you specify 999 for the :hp1.column:ehp1.,
SCRPUT will center the text horizontally.
:p.
SCRPUT does not move the cursor when it displays the text.
:p.
The following batch file fragment displays part of a menu, in color&colon.
:xmp.
    cls white on blue
    scrput 6 20 bri red on blu 1 - Word Processing
    scrput 7 20 bri yel on blu 2 - Spreadsheet
    scrput 8 20 bri gre on blu 3 - Communications
    scrput 9 20 bri mag on blu 4 - Quit
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=SELECT.SELECT - Select files for a command
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Interactively select files for a command.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.SELECT [/A[[&colon.][-][rhsda]] /D /E /H
/I"text" /J /L /O[&colon.][-]adeginrsu /T&colon.acw /Z]
[:ehp2.:hp3.command:ehp3.:hp2. ] ..&per. (:ehp2.:hp3.files:ehp3.
:hp2....)...:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.command :ehp3.&colon. The command to execute with the selected
files.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.files :ehp3.&colon. The files from which to select. File
names may be enclosed in either parentheses or square brackets. The
difference is explained below.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.(ttribute select):pd.:hp2./J:ehp2.(ustify names)
:pt.:hp2./D:ehp2.(isable color coding):pd.:hp2./L:ehp2.(ower case)
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2. (use upper case):pd.:hp2./O:ehp2.(rder)
:pt.:hp2./H:ehp2.(ide dots):pd.:hp2./T:ehp2.(ime)
:pt.:hp2./I:ehp2. (match descriptions):pd.:hp2./Z:ehp2. (use FAT format)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:hp2.File Selection:ehp2.
:p.
Supports extended :link reftype=hd refid=wildcards.wildcards:elink., :link
reftype=hd refid=ranges.ranges:elink., :link reftype=hd
refid=MultFiles.multiple filenames:elink., and :link reftype=hd
refid=InclList.include lists:elink.&per. Ranges :hp2.must:ehp2. appear
immediately after the SELECT keyword.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
SELECT allows you to select files for internal and external
commands by using a full-screen "point and shoot" display. You can
have SELECT execute a command once for each file you select, or
have it create a list of files for a command to work with. The
:hp1.command:ehp1. can be an internal command, an alias, an external
command, or a batch file.
:p.
If you use parentheses around the :hp1.files:ehp1., SELECT executes the
:hp1.command:ehp1. once for each file you have selected. During each
execution, one of the selected files is passed to the :hp1.command:ehp1.
as an argument. If you use square brackets around :hp1.files:ehp1., the
SELECTed files are combined into a single list, separated by
spaces. The command is then executed once with the entire list
presented as part of its command-line arguments.
:p.
:hp2.Using the SELECT File List:ehp2.
:p.
When you execute the SELECT command, the file list is displayed in a
full-screen format which includes a top-line status bar and shows the command
to be executed, the number of files marked, and the number of Kbytes in those
files.
:p.
SELECT uses the cursor up, cursor down, PgUp, and PgDn keys to scroll through
the file list. You can also use character matching to find specific files,
just as you can in any :link reftype=hd
refid=PopUp.popup window:elink.&per. While the file list is displayed you can
enter any of the following keys to select or unselect files, display files,
execute the command, or exit&colon.
:parml compact tsize=25 break=none.
:pt.:hp2.+:ehp2. or :hp2.space:ehp2.:pd.Select a file, or unselect a marked file.
:pt.:hp2.-:ehp2.:pd.Unselect a marked file.
:pt.:hp2.*:ehp2.:pd.Reverse all of the current marks (except those on
subdirectories). If no files have been marked you can use :hp2.* :ehp2. to
mark all of the files.
:pt.:hp2./:ehp2.:pd.Unselect all files.
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-L:ehp2.:pd.View the current highlighted file with
:link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink. When you exit from LIST, the SELECT
screen will be restored.
:pt.:hp2.Enter:ehp2.:pd.Execute the command with the marked files, or with
the currently highlighted file if no files have been marked.
:pt.:hp2.Esc:ehp2.:pd.Skip the files in the current display and go on to the
next file specification inside the parentheses or brackets (if any).
:pt.:hp2.Ctrl-C:ehp2. or :hp2.Ctrl-Break:ehp2.:pd.Cancel the current SELECT
command entirely.
:eparml.
.br
On FAT16 volumes the file list is shown in standard FAT16 directory format, with
names at the left an descriptions at the right. On volumes supporting long filenames
the format is similar but more space is allowed for the name, and the
description is not shown. In this format long names are truncated if they do
not fit in the allowable space. For a short-name format (including
descriptions) on long filename drives, use the :hp2./Z:ehp2. switch.
:p.
When displaying descriptions in the short filename format, SELECT adds a
right arrow [:hp2.:ehp2.] at the end of the line if the description is too
long to fit on the screen. This symbol will alert you to the existence of
additional description text. You can use the left and right arrow keys to
scroll the description area of the screen horizontally and view the
additional text.
:p.
You can display the filenames in color by using the SET command to create an
environment variable called :link reftype=hd refid=COLORDIR_Var.COLORDIR:elink.,
or using the :link reftype=hd refid=CommandsOption.Commands page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.
or a text editor to set the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_ColorDir.ColorDir:elink.
directive in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. If you do not
use the COLORDIR variable or the ColorDir directive, SELECT will use the default
screen colors for all files. See the discussion of color-coded directories under
:link reftype=hd refid=DIR.DIR:elink. for more details. To disable directory
color coding within SELECT, use the :hp2./D:ehp2. option.
:p.
You can set the default colors used by SELECT on the
:link reftype=hd refid=CommandsOption.Commands page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.
or with the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_SelectColors.SelectColors:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_SelectStatBarColors.SelectStatBarColors:elink.
directives in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. If SelectColors is not used, the
SELECT display will use the current default colors. If SelectStatBarColors
is not used, the status bar will use the reverse of the SELECT colors.
:p.
:hp2.Creating SELECT Commands:ehp2.
:p.
In the simplest form of SELECT, you merely specify the command and
then the list of files from which you will make your selection(s). For
example&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] select copy (*.com *.exe) a&colon.\
:exmp.:p.
will let you select from among the :hp1..COM:ehp1. files on the current
drive and will then invoke the COPY command to copy each file you select to
drive A&colon.&per. After the :hp1..COM:ehp1. files are done, the operations
will be repeated for the :hp1..EXE:ehp1. files.
:p.
If you want to select from a list of all the :hp1..COM:ehp1. and
:hp1..EXE:ehp1. files mixed together, create an :link reftype=hd
refid=InclList.include list:elink. inside the parentheses by inserting a
semicolon&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] select copy (*.com;*.exe) a&colon.\
:exmp.:p.
Finally, if you want the SELECT command to send a single list of
files to COPY, instead of invoking COPY once for each file you
select, put the filenames in square brackets instead of
parentheses&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] select copy [*.com;*.exe] a&colon.\
:exmp.:p.
If you use brackets, you have to be sure that the resulting command
(the word COPY, the list of files, and the destination drive in
this example) does not exceed the command line length limit of 1,023
characters. The current line length is displayed by SELECT while you are
marking files to help you to conform to this limit.
:p.
The parentheses or brackets enclosing the filename(s) can appear
anywhere within the command; SELECT assumes that the first set of
parentheses or brackets it finds is the one containing the list of
files from which you wish to make your selection.
:p.
When you use SELECT on a volume supporting long filenames, you must quote any filenames inside
the parentheses which contain whitespace or special characters. See :link
reftype=hd refid=Filenames.Filenames:elink. for additional details. For
example, to copy selected files from the :hp1."Program Files":ehp1.
directory to the :hp1.E&colon.\SAVE:ehp1. directory&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] select copy ("Program Files\*.*") e&colon.\save\
:exmp.:p.
Filenames passed to the :hp1.command:ehp1. will be quoted automatically if
they contain whitespace or special characters.
:p.
The list of files from which you wish to select can be further refined by
using :link reftype=hd refid=Ranges.date, time, size:elink., and :link
reftype=hd refid=ExclRanges.file exclusion:elink. ranges. The range(s) must
be placed immediately after the word SELECT. If the :hp1.command:ehp1. is
an internal command that supports ranges, an independent range can also be
used in the :hp1.command:ehp1. itself.
:p.
You cannot use command grouping to make SELECT execute several commands,
because SELECT will assume that the parentheses are marking the list of
files from which to select, and will display an error message or give
incorrect results if you try to use parentheses for command grouping
instead. (You :hp2.can:ehp2. use a SELECT command :hp2.inside:ehp2. command
grouping parentheses, you just can't use command grouping to specify a group
of commands for SELECT to execute.)
:p.
:hp2.Advanced Topics:ehp2.
:p.
If you don't specify a command, the selected filename(s) will
become the command. For example, this command defines an alias
called UTILS that selects from the executable files in the
directory :hp1.C&colon.\UTIL:ehp1., and then executes them in the order
marked&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias utils select (c&colon.\util\*.com;*.exe;*.btm;*.bat)
:exmp.:p.
If you want to use :link reftype=hd refid=FileComp.filename completion:elink. to enter the
filenames inside the parentheses, type a space after the opening
parenthesis. Otherwise, the command-line editor will treat the open
parenthesis as the first character of the filename.
:p.
With the :hp2./I:ehp2. option, you can select files based on their
descriptions. SELECT will display files if their description
matches the text after the :hp2./I:ehp2. switch. The search is not case
sensitive. You can use wildcards and extended wildcards as part
of the text.
:p.
When sorting filenames and extensions for the SELECT display, &4OS2.
normally assumes that sequences of digits should be sorted
numerically (for example, the file DRAW2 would come before DRAW03
because 2 is numerically smaller than 03), rather than strictly
alphabetically (where DRAW2 would come second because "2" comes
after "0"). You can defeat this behavior and force a strict
alphabetic sort with the :hp2./O&colon.a:ehp2. option.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml compact tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Attribute select) Select only those files that have the
specified attribute(s) set. Preceding the attribute character with a
hyphen [:hp2.-:ehp2.] will select files that do not have that attribute set. The colon
[:hp2.&colon.:ehp2.] after :hp2./A:ehp2. is optional. The attributes
are&colon.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   R:ehp2. Read-only
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   H:ehp2. Hidden
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   S:ehp2. System
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   D:ehp2. Subdirectory
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   A:ehp2. Archive
.br
:pt.:pd.If no attributes are listed at all (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., :hp2.SELECT /A ...:ehp2.), SELECT
will display all files and subdirectories including hidden and system files.
If attributes are combined, all the specified attributes must match for a file to
be included in the listing. For example, :hp2./A&colon.RHS:ehp2. will display
only those files with all three attributes set.
.br
:pt.:hp2./D:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Disable color coding) Temporarily turn off directory color
coding within SELECT.
.br
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2.:pd.(use upper case) Display filenames upper case; also
see :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /U
and the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_UpperCase.UpperCase :elink. directive in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
.br
:pt.:hp2./H:ehp2.:pd.(Hide dots) Suppress the display of the "." and ".."
directories.
.br
:pt.:hp2./I:ehp2.:pd.(match descriptions) Display filenames by matching text in
their descriptions. The text can include wildcards and extended
wildcards. The search text must be enclosed in quotation marks. You can
select all filenames that have a description with :hp2./I"[?]*",:ehp2. or
all filenames that do not have a description with :hp2./I"[]":ehp2.&per.
.br
:pt.:hp2./J:ehp2.:pd.(Justify names) Justify (align) filename extensions and
display them in the traditional format.
.br
:pt.:hp2./L:ehp2.:pd.(Lower case) Display file and directory names in lower
case; also see :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /U and the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_UpperCase.UpperCase:elink. directive in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
.br
:pt.:hp2./O:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Order) Set the sort order for the files. The
order can be any combination of the following options&colon.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   -:ehp2. Reverse the sort order for the next option.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   a:ehp2. Sort in ASCII order, not numerically, when there are digits in the name.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   d:ehp2. Sort by date and time (oldest first); for volume supporting multiple timestamps also see :hp2./T:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   e:ehp2. Sort by extension.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   g:ehp2. Group subdirectories first, then files.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   i:ehp2. Sort by file description.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   n:ehp2. Sort by filename (this is the default).
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   r:ehp2. Reverse the sort order for all options.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   s:ehp2. Sort by size.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   u:ehp2. Unsorted.
.br
:pt.:hp2./T:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Time display) Specify which of the date and
time fields on a volume supporting multiple timestamps should be displayed and used for sorting&colon.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   a:ehp2. last access date and time
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   c:ehp2. creation date and time
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   w:ehp2. last write date and time (default)
.br
:pt.:hp2./Z:ehp2.&colon.:pd.Display the directory for a volume supporting
long filenames in the FAT16 format, with the filename at the left and the
description at the right. Long names will be truncated to 12 characters unless
:hp2./X:ehp2. is also used; if the name is longer than 12 characters, it will
be followed by a right arrow [:hp2.:ehp2.] to show that one or more characters
have been truncated.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=SET.SET - Create or modify environment variables
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display, create, modify, or delete
environment variables.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.SET [/P /R:ehp2. :hp3.file:ehp3.
:hp2....] [:ehp2.:hp3.name:ehp3. :hp2.[=][:ehp2.:hp3.value:ehp3. :hp2.]]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.file :ehp3.&colon. One or more files containing variable
definitions.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.name :ehp3.&colon. The name of the environment variable to
define or modify.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.value :ehp3.&colon. The new value for the variable.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./P:ehp2.(ause):pd.:hp2./R:ehp2.(ead from file)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=ESET.ESET:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=UNSET.UNSET:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
Every program and command inherits an :link reftype=hd refid=Environment.environment:elink.,
which is a list of variable :hp1.names:ehp1., each of which is followed by
an equal sign and some text. Many programs use entries in the
environment to modify their own actions.
:p.
If you simply type the SET command with no options or arguments, it
will display all the names and values currently stored in the
environment. Typically, you will see an entry called COMSPEC, an
entry called PATH, an entry called CMDLINE, and whatever other
environment variables you and your programs have established&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] set
    COMSPEC=C&colon.\4OS2\$OS2.EXE
    PATH=C&colon.\;C&colon.\OS2;C&colon.\OS2\SYSTEM;C&colon.\UTIL
    CMDLINE=C&colon.\4OS2\4START.CMD
:exmp.:p.
To add a variable to the environment, type SET, a space, the
variable name, an equal sign, and the text&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] set mine=c&colon.\finance\myfiles
:exmp.:p.
The variable name is converted to upper case by &4OS2.. The text after the
equal sign will be left just as you entered it. If the variable already
exists, its value will be replaced with the new text that you entered.
:p.
Normally you should not put a space on either side of the equal
sign. A space before the equal sign will become part of the
:hp1.name:ehp1. ; a space after the equal sign will become part of the
:hp1.value:ehp1.&per.
:p.
If you use SET to create a variable with the same name as one of
the &4OS2. :link reftype=hd refid=IntVars.internal variables:elink., you will disable the
internal variable. If you later execute a batch file or alias that
depends upon that internal variable, it may not operate correctly.
:p.
To display the contents of a single variable, type SET plus the
variable name&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] set mine
:exmp.:p.
You can edit environment variables with the ESET command. To
remove variables from the environment, use UNSET, or type SET plus
a variable name and an equal sign&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] set mine=
:exmp.:p.
The variable :hp1.name:ehp1. is limited to a maximum of 80 characters.
The name and :hp1.value:ehp1. together cannot be longer than 1,023 characters.
:p.
In &4OS2. the size of the environment is set automatically, and
increased as necessary as you add variables.
:p.
&4OS2. supports the "pseudo-variables" :hp2.BeginLIBPath:ehp2. and
:hp2.EndLIBPath:ehp2. introduced in OS/2 Warp. If you use either of these
as a variable name, &4OS2. will pass the library path information from the SET
command to the operating system, but the variables will not appear in the
environment. Additionally, &4OS2. supports the "pseudo-variable"
:hp2.LIBPATHSTRICT:ehp2. introduced in OS/2 Warp Convenience Package. See your
OS/2 documentation for more information about these "variables".
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./P:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Pause) Wait for a key to be pressed after each
screen page before continuing the display. Your options at the prompt are
explained in detail under :link reftype=hd refid=Prompts.Page and File
Prompts:elink.&per.
:pt.:hp2./R:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Read) Read environment variables from a
file. This is much faster than loading variables from a batch file with
multiple SET commands. Each entry in the file must fit within the
1,023-byte command-line length limit for &4OS2.. The file is in the same
format as the SET display (:hp1.i.e.:ehp1., :hp3.name:ehp3.
=:hp3.value:ehp3. ), so SET /R can accept as input a file generated by
redirecting SET output. For example, the following commands will save the
environment variables to a file, and then reload them from that file&colon.
:xmp.
    set > varlist
    set /r varlist
:exmp.:p.
You can load variables from multiple files by listing the filenames
individually after the :hp2./R:ehp2.&per. You can add comments to a variable
file by starting the comment line with a colon [:hp2.&colon.:ehp2.].
:p.
If you are creating a SET /R file by hand, and need to create an entry that
spans multiple lines in the file, you can do so by terminating each line,
except the last, with an :link reftype=hd refid=Escape.escape
character:elink.&per. However, you cannot use this method to exceed the
command-line length limit.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=SETDOS.SETDOS - Set the &4OS2. configuration
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display or set the &4OS2. configuration.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.SETDOS [/A? /B? /C? /D? /E? /Fn.n /G??
/I+&splitvbar.-:ehp2. :hp3.command:ehp3. :hp2./L? /M? /N? /P? /R? /S?&colon.?
/U? /V? /X[+&splitvbar.-]n /Y?]:ehp2.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./B:ehp2.(right background):pd.:hp2./N:ehp2.(o clobber)
:pt.:hp2./C:ehp2.(ompound):pd.:hp2./P:ehp2.(arameter character)
:pt.:hp2./D:ehp2.(escriptions):pd.:hp2./R:ehp2.(ows)
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2.(scape character):pd.:hp2./S:ehp2.(hape of cursor)
:pt.:hp2./F:ehp2.(ormat for @EVAL):pd.:hp2./U:ehp2.(pper case)
:pt.:hp2./G:ehp2. (numeric separators):pd.:hp2./V:ehp2.(erbose)
:pt.:hp2./I:ehp2.(nternal commands):pd.:hp2./X:ehp2. (expansion, special characters)
:pt.:hp2./L:ehp2.(ine):pd.:hp2./Y:ehp2. (debug batch file)
:pt.:hp2./M:ehp2.(ode for editing):pd.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
SETDOS allows you to customize certain aspects of &4OS2. to suit your
personal tastes or the configuration of your system. Each of these
options is described below.
:p.
You can display the value of all SETDOS options by entering the
SETDOS command with no parameters.
:p.
Most of the SETDOS options can be initialized when &4OS2. executes
the :link reftype=hd refid=INIConfig.configuration directives:elink. in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink., and can also be set on the
:link reftype=hd refid=CommandLine1Option.Command Line 1:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=CommandLine2Option.Command Line 2:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=Options1.Options 1:elink., or
:link reftype=hd refid=Options2.Options 2:elink. pages of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.&per.
The name of the corresponding directive is listed with each option below; if
none is listed, that option cannot be set using the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.
or in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. You can also define
the SETDOS options in your :hp1.AUTOEXEC.BAT:ehp1., :hp1.4START:ehp1., or other
startup file
(see :link reftype=hd refid=AutoBatch.Automatic Batch Files:elink.), in aliases,
or at the command line.
:p.
Secondary shells automatically inherit most configuration settings
currently in effect in the previous shell. If values have been
changed by SETDOS since &4OS2. started, the new values will be passed
to the secondary shell.
:p.
SETDOS /I settings are not inherited by secondary shells. If you
want to use SETDOS /I- to disable commands in all shells, place the
SETDOS command(s) in your :hp1.4START:ehp1. file, which is executed when
any shell starts.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml compact tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./B:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Bright background) This option determines
whether &4OS2. configures your video adapter for blinking text
(:hp2./B0:ehp2., the default) or bright background colors (:hp2./B1:ehp2.),
or leave the video bright / blink configuration unchanged
(:hp2./B2:ehp2.). See :link reftype=hd refid=Colors.Colors and Color
Names:elink. for a detailed discussion of this option. Also see the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_BrightBG.BrightBG:elink. directive.
.br
:pt.:hp2./C:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Compound character) This option sets the
character used for separating multiple commands on
the same line. The default is the ampersand [:hp2.&amp.:ehp2.]. You cannot
use any of the redirection characters (:hp2.&splitvbar.
> <:ehp2.), or the blank, tab, comma, or equal sign as the command
separator. The command separator is saved by :link reftype=hd
refid=SETLOCAL.SETLOCAL:elink. and restored by :link reftype=hd
refid=ENDLOCAL.ENDLOCAL:elink.&per. This example changes the separator
to a tilde [:hp2.~:ehp2.]&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] setdos /c~
:exmp.:p.
If you want to share batch files or aliases among 4DOS, &4OS2., 4NT, and
Take Command, see the :link reftype=hd refid=PLUS.%+:elink. variable, which
retrieves the current command separator, and :link reftype=hd
refid=Compat.Special Character Compatibility:elink. for
details on using compatible command separators for all the products
you use. Also see the :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_CommandSep.CommandSep:elink. directive.
.br
:pt.:hp2./D:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Descriptions) This option controls whether
file processing commands like :link reftype=hd refid=COPY.COPY:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=DEL.DEL:elink., :link reftype=hd
refid=MOVE.MOVE:elink., and :link reftype=hd refid=REN.REN:elink.
process file descriptions along with the files they
belong to. :hp2./D1:ehp2. turns description processing on,
which is the default. :hp2./D0:ehp2. turns description
processing off. Also see the :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_Descriptions.Descriptions:elink. directive.
:p.
You can also use :hp2./D:ehp2. to set the name of the hidden file in each
directory that contains file descriptions. To do so, follow :hp2./D:ehp2.
with the filename in quotes&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] setdos /d"files.bbs"
:exmp.:p.
:hp8.Use this option with caution:ehp8. because changing the name
of the description file will make it difficult to transfer file descriptions
to another system. This option is provided for bulletin board system
operators and others who have special needs.
:p.
Also see the :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_DescriptionName.DescriptionName:elink. directive.
.br
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Escape character) This option sets the
character used to suppress the normal meaning of the following
character. Any character following the :link reftype=hd refid=Escape.escape
character:elink. will be passed unmodified to the command. The default
:link reftype=hd refid=Escape.escape character:elink. is a caret [:hp2.^:ehp2.]. You cannot use any of the
redirection characters (:hp2.&splitvbar. > <:ehp2.) or the blank, tab,
comma, or equal sign as the escape character. The escape character is saved
by :link reftype=hd refid=SETLOCAL.SETLOCAL:elink. and restored by
:link reftype=hd refid=ENDLOCAL.ENDLOCAL:elink.&per. Certain characters
(:hp2.b:ehp2., :hp2.c:ehp2., :hp2.e:ehp2., :hp2.f:ehp2., :hp2.k:ehp2.,
:hp2.n:ehp2., :hp2.q:ehp2., :hp2.r:ehp2., :hp2.s:ehp2., and :hp2.t:ehp2.)
have special meanings when immediately preceded by the escape character.
:p.
If you want to share batch files or aliases among 4DOS, &4OS2., 4NT, and
Take Command, see the :link reftype=hd refid=EQUALS.%=:elink. variable, which
retrieves the current escape character, and :link reftype=hd
refid=Compat.Special Character Compatibility:elink. for details on using
compatible escape characters for all the products you use. Also see the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_EscapeChar.EscapeChar:elink. directive.
.br
:pt.:hp2./F:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Format for @EVAL) This option lets
you set default decimal precision for the :link reftype=hd refid=_@EVAL.@EVAL:elink. variable
function. The maximum precision is 16 digits to the left of the decimal
point and 8 digits to the right of the decimal point.

The general form of this option is :hp2./Fx.y:ehp2., where :hp2.x:ehp2. sets
the minimum number of digits to the right of the decimal place and
:hp2.y:ehp2. sets the maximum number of digits. You can use :hp2.=x,y:ehp2.
instead of :hp2.=x.y:ehp2. if the comma is your decimal separator. Both
values can range from 0 to 8; if :hp2.x:ehp2. is greater than :hp2.y:ehp2.,
it is ignored. You can specify either or both values: /F2.5, /F2, and /F.5
are all valid entries.
:p.
See :link reftype=hd refid=_@EVAL.@EVAL:elink. if you want to set the
precision for a single computation.
:p.
Also see the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_EvalMax.EvalMax:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_EvalMin.EvalMin:elink. directives.
.br
:pt.:hp2./G:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Numeric separators) This option sets the
decimal and thousands separator characters. The format is :hp2./Gxy
:ehp2.where :hp2.x:ehp2. is the new decimal separator and :hp2.y:ehp2. is
the new thousands separator. Both characters must be included. The only
valid settings are :hp2./G.,:ehp2. (period is the decimal separator, comma
is the thousands separator); :hp2./G,.:ehp2. (the reverse); or
:hp2./G0:ehp2. to remove any custom setting and use the default separators
associated with your current country code (this is the default).
:p.
The decimal separator is used for :link reftype=hd
refid=_@EVAL.@EVAL:elink., numeric :link reftype=hd refid=IF.IF:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=IFF.IFF:elink. tests, version numbers, and other
similar uses. The thousands separator is used for numeric output, and is
skipped when performing calculations in @EVAL.
.br
:pt.:hp2./I:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Internal) This option allows you to disable or
enable internal commands. To disable a command, precede the command name
with a minus [:hp2.-:ehp2.]. To re-enable a command, precede it with a plus
[:hp2.+:ehp2.]. For example, to disable the internal LIST command to force
&4OS2. to use an external command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] setdos /i-list
:exmp.
.br
:pt.:hp2./L:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Line) This option controls how &4OS2. gets its
input from the command line. :hp2./L0:ehp2. tells &4OS2. to
use character input (the default). :hp2./L1:ehp2. tells it
to use line input (like :hp1.CMD.EXE:ehp1. ). :hp2./L1:ehp2. will
disable command-line editing, history recall,
:link reftype=hd refid=FileComp.filename completion:elink., and
the directory history window, and will reduce the &4OS2. input length limit
from 1023 characters to 255 characters. It should only be used if it is
needed for compatibility with a specific program. If you have a program
that requires line input, you can use the following line in an alias or
batch file to change the line input option just for that single
program&colon.
:xmp.
    setdos /L1 &amp. program %&amp. &amp. setdos /L0
:exmp.:p.
See :hp1.README.DOC:ehp1. for information on programs which require
this option. Also see the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_LineInput.LineInput:elink. directive.
.br
:pt.:hp2./M:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Mode) This option controls the initial line
editing mode. To start in overstrike mode at the beginning of each command
line, use :hp2./M0:ehp2. (the default). To start in insert mode, use
:hp2./M1:ehp2.&per. Also see the :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_EditMode.EditMode:elink. directive.
.br
:pt.:hp2./N:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(No clobber) This option controls output
:link reftype=hd refid=Redirection.redirection:elink.). :hp2./N0:ehp2. means
existing files will be overwritten by output redirection
(with :hp2.>:ehp2.) and that appending (with :hp2.>>:ehp2.) does not require
the file to exist already. This is the default. :hp2./N1:ehp2. means
existing files may not be overwritten by output redirection, and that when
appending the output file must exist. A :hp2./N1:ehp2. setting can be
overridden with the [:hp2.!:ehp2.] character. If you use :hp2./N1:ehp2.,
you may have problems with a few unusual programs that shell out
to run a command with redirection, and expect to be able to overwrite an
existing file. Also see the :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_NoClobber.NoClobber:elink. directive.
.br
:pt.:hp2./P:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Parameter character) This option sets the
character used after a percent sign to specify all or all remaining
command-line arguments in a :link reftype=hd refid=Batch.batch file:elink. or
:link reftype=hd refid=ALIAS.alias:elink. (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1.,
:hp2.%&amp.:ehp2. or :hp2.%n&amp.:ehp2.&per. The default is the dollar sign
[:hp2.$:ehp2.]. The parameter character is saved by :link reftype=hd
refid=SETLOCAL.SETLOCAL:elink. and restored by :link reftype=hd
refid=ENDLOCAL.ENDLOCAL:elink.&per.
:p.
If you want to share batch files or aliases among 4DOS, &4OS2., 4NT, and
Take Command, see :link reftype=hd refid=Compat.Special Character
Compatibility:elink. for details on selecting compatible parameter
characters for all the products you use. Also see the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ParameterChar.ParameterChar:elink. directive.
.br
:pt.:hp2./R:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Rows) This option sets the number of screen
rows used by the video display. Normally &4OS2. detects the screen size, but
if you have a non-standard display you may need to set it explicitly. This
option does not affect screen scrolling (which is controlled by your video
driver). It also does not :hp2.set:ehp2. the screen size; it is used only
to specify the screen height for :link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink., paged output options
(:hp1.i.e.:ehp1., :link reftype=hd refid=TYPE.TYPE:elink. /P), and error
checking in the screen output commands. Also see
the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_ScreenRows.ScreenRows:elink. directive.
.br
:pt.:hp2./S:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Shape) This option sets the cursor shape. The
format is :hp2./So&colon.i:ehp2. where :hp2.o:ehp2. is the cursor size
for overstrike mode and :hp2.i:ehp2. is the cursor size for insert mode. The
size is entered as a percentage of the total character height. The default
values are 10&colon.100 (a 10% underscore cursor for overstrike mode,
and a 100% block cursor for insert mode). Because of the way video drivers
remap the cursor shape, you may not get a smooth progression in the cursor
size from 0% - 100%. To disable the cursor, enter
:hp2./S0&colon.0:ehp2.&per.
:p.
If either value is -1, &4OS2. will not attempt to modify the cursor shape at
all. You can use this feature to give another program full control of the
cursor shape. You can retrieve the current cursor shape values with the
:link reftype=hd refid=_CI.%_CI:elink. and :link reftype=hd
refid=_CO.%_CO:elink. internal variables.
:p.
Also see the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_CursorOver.CursorOver:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_CursorIns.CursorIns:elink. directives.
.br
:pt.:hp2./U:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Upper) This option controls the default case
(upper or lower) for file and directory names displayed by internal commands
like COPY and DIR. :hp2./U0:ehp2. displays filenames in lower case (the
default). :hp2./U1:ehp2. displays filenames in the traditional upper
case. The :hp2./U:ehp2. setting is ignored for case-retentive filesystems.
Filenames in these filesystems are always displayed in the case in which they
are stored.
:p.
Also see the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_UpperCase.UpperCase:elink. directive.
.br
:pt.:hp2./V:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Verbose) This option controls the default for
command echoing in batch files. :hp2./V0:ehp2. disables echoing of batch
file commands unless :link reftype=hd refid=ECHO.ECHO:elink. is explicitly
set ON. :hp2./V1:ehp2., the default setting, enables echoing of batch file
commands unless ECHO is explicitly set OFF. Also see the :link reftype=hd
refid=BatchEcho.BatchEcho:elink. directive.
:p.
:hp2./V2:ehp2. forces echoing of all batch file commands, even if ECHO is
set OFF or the line begins with an "@". This allows you to turn echoing on
for a batch file without editing the batch file and removing the ECHO OFF
command(s) within it. :hp2./V2:ehp2. is intended for debugging, and can be
set with SETDOS, but not using the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.
or the BatchEcho directive in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:p.
For more information on batch file debugging see :link reftype=hd
refid=BatchDebug.Debugging Batch Files:elink. and :hp2./Y:ehp2. below.
.br
:pt.:hp2./X[+&splitvbar.-]n:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(eXpansion and special
characters) This option enables and disables alias and environment variable
expansion, and controls whether special characters have their usual meaning
or are treated as text. It is most often used in batch files to process text
strings which may contain special characters.
:p.
The features enabled or disabled by :hp2./X:ehp2. are numbered. All
features are enabled when &4OS2. starts, and you can re-enable all features at
any time by using :hp2./X0:ehp2.&per. To disable a particular feature, use
:hp2./X-n:ehp2., where :hp2.n:ehp2. is the feature number from the list
below. To re-enable the feature, use :hp2./X+n:ehp2.&per. To enable or disable
multiple individual features, list their numbers in sequence after the
:hp2.+:ehp2. or :hp2.-:ehp2. (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1. :hp2./X-345:ehp2. to disable
features 3, 4, and 5).
:p.
The features are&colon.
.br
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.   1:pd.All alias expansion.
:pt.   2:pd.Nested alias expansion only.
:pt.   3:pd.All variable expansion (environment variables and batch and alias parameters).
:pt.   4:pd.Nested variable expansion only.
:pt.   5:pd.Multiple commands, conditional commands, and piping.
:pt.   6:pd.Redirection.
:pt.   7:pd.Quoting (double quotes and back quotes) and square brackets.
:pt.   8:pd.Escape character.
:eparml.
:p.
If nested alias expansion is disabled, the first alias of a command is
expanded but any aliases it invokes are not expanded. If nested variable
expansion is disabled, each variable is expanded once, but variables
containing the names of other variables are not expanded further.
:p.
For example, to disable all features except alias expansion while you are
processing a text file containing special characters&colon.
:xmp.
    setdos /x-35678
    ... [perform text processing here]
    setdos /x0
:exmp.
.br
:pt.:hp2./Y&colon.:ehp2.:pd.(debug batch file) :hp2./Y1:ehp2. enables the
built-in batch file debugger. The debugger allows you to "single-step"
through a batch file line by line, with the file displayed in a popup window
as it executes. For complete details on using the debugger see
:link reftype=hd refid=BatchDebug.Debugging Batch Files:elink. (this topic
also covers additional debugging techniques which do not require stepping
through each line individually).
:p.
To start the debugger, insert a SETDOS /Y1 command at the beginning of the
portion of the batch file you want to debug, and a SETDOS /Y0 command at the
end.
:p.
You cannot use the batch debugger with :link reftype=hd
refid=REXX.REXX:elink. files or :link reftype=hd
refid=EXTPROC.EXTPROC:elink. files. It can only be used with normal &4OS2.
batch files.
:p.
You can also invoke SETDOS /Y1 from the prompt, but because the debugger is
automatically turned off whenever the command processor returns to the
prompt, you must enter the SETDOS command and the batch file name on the
same line. For example&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] setdos /y1 &amp. mybatch.btm
:exmp.:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=SETLOCAL.SETLOCAL - Save the environment
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Save a copy of the current disk drive,
directory, environment, alias list, and special characters.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.SETLOCAL:ehp2.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=ENDLOCAL.ENDLOCAL:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
SETLOCAL is used in batch files to save the default disk drive and
directory, the environment, the alias list, and the command separator,
:link reftype=hd refid=Escape.escape character:elink., parameter character, decimal separator, and thousands
separator. You can then change their values and later restore the original
values with ENDLOCAL.
:p.
For example, this batch file fragment saves everything, removes all
aliases so that user aliases will not affect batch file commands,
changes the disk and directory, changes the command separator, runs a
program, and then restores the original values&colon.
:xmp.
    setlocal
    unalias *
    cdd d&colon.\test
    setdos /c~
    program ~ echo Done!
    endlocal
:exmp.:p.
SETLOCAL and ENDLOCAL are not nestable within a batch file. However, you
can have multiple, separate SETLOCAL / ENDLOCAL pairs within a batch file,
and nested batch files can each have their own SETLOCAL / ENDLOCAL. You
cannot use SETLOCAL in an alias or at the command line.
:p.
An ENDLOCAL is performed automatically at the end of a batch file
if you forget to do so. If you invoke one batch file from another
without using CALL, the first batch file is terminated, and an
automatic ENDLOCAL is performed; the second batch file inherits
the settings as they were prior to any SETLOCAL.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=SHIFT.SHIFT - Shift batch file parameters
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Allows the use of more than 127 parameters
in a batch file.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.SHIFT [:ehp2.:hp3.n:ehp3.
:hp2.&splitvbar. /:ehp2.:hp3.n:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.n :ehp3.&colon. Number of positions to shift.
:eparml.:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
SHIFT is provided for compatibility with older batch files, where
it was used to access more than 10 parameters. &4OS2. supports 128
parameters (%0 to %127), so you may not need to use SHIFT for batch
files running exclusively under JP Software command processors.
:p.
SHIFT moves each of the batch file parameters :hp1.n:ehp1. positions to
the left. The default value for :hp1.n:ehp1. is 1. SHIFT 1 moves the
parameter in %1 to position %0, the parameter in %2 becomes %1,
etc. You can reverse a SHIFT by giving a negative value for :hp1.n:ehp1.
(:hp1.i.e.:ehp1., after SHIFT -1, the former %0 is restored, %0 becomes
%1, %1 becomes %2, etc.).
:p.
SHIFT also affects the parameters :hp2.%n$.:ehp2. (command-line tail)
and :hp2.%#:ehp2. (number of command arguments).
:p.
For example, create a batch file called :hp1.TEST.BAT:ehp1.&colon.
:xmp.
    echo %1 %2 %3 %4
    shift
    echo %1 %2 %3 %4
    shift 2
    echo %1 %2 %3 %4
    shift -1
    echo %1 %2 %3 %4
:exmp.:p.
Executing :hp1.TEST.BAT:ehp1. produces the following results&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] test one two three four five six seven
    one two three four
    two three four five
    four five six seven
    three four five six
:exmp.:p.
If you add a slash before the value :hp1.n:ehp1., the value determines the
position at which to begin the shift. For example&colon.
:xmp.
    shift /2
:exmp.:p.
leaves parameters %0 and %1 unchanged, and moves the value of %3 to position
%2, %4 to %3, etc. The value after the slash cannot be negative, and shifts
performed with the slash cannot be undone later in the batch file.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=SHRALIAS.SHRALIAS - Load or unload SHRALIAS.EXE
:i1 id=SHALIAS global.SHRALIAS
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Retains global command history, directory
history, and alias lists in memory when the command processor is not running.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.SHRALIAS [/U]:ehp2.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./U:ehp2.(nload):pd.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
When you close all &4OS2. sessions, the memory for the global command history,
global directory history, and global alias list is released. If you want
the lists to be retained in memory even when no command processor session is
running, you need to execute SHRALIAS.
:p.
The SHRALIAS command starts and initializes :hp1.SHRALIAS.EXE:ehp1., a small
program which remains active and retains global lists when &4OS2. is not
running. In order to start the program, SHRALIAS must be able to find
:hp1.SHRALIAS.EXE:ehp1. either in the same directory as &4OS2., or in a
directory in your PATH. You cannot run :hp1.SHRALIAS.EXE:ehp1. directly, it
must be run by the SHRALIAS command.
:p.
Once SHRALIAS has been executed, the global lists will be retained in memory
until you use :hp2.SHRALIAS /U:ehp2. to unload the lists, or until you shut
down your operating system.
:p.
SHRALIAS will not work unless you have at least one copy of &4OS2. running
with global alias, command history, and directory history lists enabled. If
the required global lists are not found, SHRALIAS will display an error.
:p.
If you start SHRALIAS from a temporary &4OS2. session which exits after
starting SHRALIAS (for example, by executing SHRALIAS in your OS/2
:hp1.STARTUP.CMD:ehp1. file), the command processor session may terminate
and discard the shared lists before SHRALIAS can attach to them. In this
case :hp1.SHRALIAS.EXE:ehp1. will not be loaded. If you experience this
problem, add a short delay with the DELAY command after SHRALIAS is loaded
and before your session exits.
:p.
For more information about global history and alias lists, see :hp2.Local and
Global Command History:ehp2. under
:link reftype=hd refid=CmdHist.Command History and Recall:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=GlobalDirHistory.Local and Global Directory
History:elink., and :hp2.Local and Global Aliases:ehp2. under the
:link reftype=hd refid=ALIAS.ALIAS:elink. command.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml compact tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./U:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Unload) Shuts down :hp1.SHRALIAS.EXE.:ehp1. If
SHRALIAS is not loaded again, the memory used by global command history,
directory history, and alias lists will be released when the last copy of
&4OS2. exits.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=START.START - Start a program in another session
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Start a program in another session or window.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.START [":ehp2.:hp3.program
title:ehp3. :hp2."] [/B[G] /C /DOS[=:ehp2.:hp3.optfile:ehp3. :hp2.] /F[G] /FS
/I /ICON=:ehp2.:hp3.iconfile:ehp3. :hp2./INV /K /L /LA /LD /LH /MAX /MIN /N
/PGM:ehp2. :hp3.progname:ehp3. :hp2./PM /POS=x,y,width,height /WAIT /WIN
/WIN3[=:ehp2.:hp3.optfile:ehp3. :hp2.]
/WIN3S[=:ehp2.:hp3.optfile:ehp3. :hp2.]] [:ehp2.:hp3.command:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.program title :ehp3.&colon. Title to appear on title bar.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.optfile :ehp3.&colon. Option settings file.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.iconfile :ehp3.&colon. Name of icon (:hp1..ICO:ehp1. ) file.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.progname :ehp3.&colon. Program name (not the session name).
:pt.:pd.:hp3.path :ehp3.&colon. Startup directory.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.command :ehp3.&colon. Command to be executed.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./B[G]:ehp2. (background session):pd.:hp2./LH:ehp2. (local history list)
:pt.:hp2./C:ehp2.(lose when done):pd.:hp2./MAX:ehp2.(imized)
:pt.:hp2./DOS:ehp2. (DOS session):pd.:hp2./MIN:ehp2.(imized)
:pt.:hp2./F[G]:ehp2. (foreground session):pd.:hp2./N:ehp2.(o command processor)
:pt.:hp2./FS:ehp2. (full screen):pd.:hp2./PGM:ehp2. (program name)
:pt.:hp2./I:ehp2.(nherit environment):pd.:hp2./PM:ehp2. (PM application)
:pt.:hp2./ICON:ehp2. (:hp1..ICO:ehp1. file adds /N):pd.:hp2./POS:ehp2.(ition of window)
:pt.:hp2./INV:ehp2.(isible):pd.:hp2./WAIT:ehp2. (for session to finish)
:pt.:hp2./K:ehp2.(eep when done):pd.:hp2./WIN:ehp2.(dowed session)
:pt.:hp2./L:ehp2.(ocal lists):pd.:hp2./WIN3:ehp2. (Windows enhanced mode)
:pt.:hp2./LA:ehp2. (local aliases):pd.:hp2./WIN3S:ehp2. (Windows standard mode)
:pt.:hp2./LD:ehp2. (local dir history):pd.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=DETACH.DETACH:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
START is used to begin a new OS/2 session, and optionally run a program in
that session. If you use START with no parameters, it will begin a new
command-line session. If you add a :hp1.command:ehp1., START will begin a new
session or window and execute that command.
:p.
The :hp1.program title:ehp1., if it is included, will appear on the title
bar, and on the Presentation Manager window list. The :hp1.program
title:ehp1. must be enclosed in quotation marks and cannot exceed 60
characters. If the :hp1.program title:ehp1. is omitted, the program name
will be used as the title.
:p.
START always assumes that the first quoted string on the command line is the
:hp1.program title:ehp1.; if there is a second quoted string it is assumed
to be the :hp1.command:ehp1.&per. As a result, if the name of the program you
are starting is a long filename containing whitespace (and must therefore be
quoted), you cannot simply place it on the command line. If you do, as the
first quoted string it will be interpreted as the :hp1.program title:ehp1.,
not the :hp1.command:ehp1.&per. To address this, use the /PGM switch to
indicate explicitly that the quoted string is the program name, or include a
title before the program name. For example, to start the program
":hp1.C&colon.\Program Files\Proc.Exe:ehp1." you could use either of the
first two commands below, but the third command would not work&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] start /PGM "C&colon.\Program Files\Proc.Exe"
    [c&colon.\] start "test" "C&colon.\Program Files\Proc.Exe"
    [c&colon.\] start "C&colon.\Program Files\Proc.Exe"
:exmp.:p.
START offers a large number of switches to control the session you
start. In most cases you need only a few switches to accomplish
what you want. The list below summarizes the most commonly used
START options, and how you can use them to control the way a
session is started&colon.
:lm margin=8.:p.
:hp2./MAX:ehp2., :hp2./MIN:ehp2., and :hp2./POS:ehp2. allow you to start a
character-mode windowed session in a maximized window, a
minimized window, or a window with a specified position and
size. The default is to let the operating environment choose
the position and size of the window.
:p.
:hp2./C:ehp2. allows you to close the session when the command is
finished (the default for DOS and OS/2 Presentation Manager sessions);
:hp2./K:ehp2. allows you to keep the session open and go to a prompt
(the default for OS/2 character mode sessions).
:p.
:hp2./BG:ehp2. and :hp2./FG:ehp2. allow you to start the session in the
background(does not respond to keystrokes until selected) or
foreground (responds to keystrokes until deselected). :hp2./FG:ehp2.
is the default if :hp2./DOS:ehp2., :hp2./FS:ehp2., :hp2./WIN:ehp2., or :hp2./PM:ehp2. is
used; otherwise, :hp2./BG:ehp2. is the default.
:p.
:hp2./FS:ehp2. and :hp2./WIN:ehp2. control whether a character-mode session
is started in full-screen or windowed mode. The default is to
start a session of the same type as the current session, if
the application can be run in such a session.
:lm margin=1.:p.
START determines the application type automatically and starts the
session in the appropriate mode.
:p.
START gives you some flexibility in determining the session mode.
For example, if the :hp1.command:ehp1. is the name of a batch file (either
a :hp1..BTM:ehp1. or :hp1..CMD:ehp1. file), you can use the :hp2./FS:ehp2.
or :hp2./WIN:ehp2. options to run the batch file as part of a new session in
either full-screen or windowed mode.
:p.
However, you cannot start a session in a mode that is inappropriate
for the application type. A DOS application cannot be run as part
of a Presentation Manager session, for example, even if you use the
:hp2./PM:ehp2. switch. Invalid or conflicting options will be ignored.
&4OS2. will always attempt to run the command in the appropriate type of
session.
:p.
If the program is a DOS application or :hp1..BAT:ehp1. file, &4OS2. will
start a new DOS session to run it. The DOS session will close itself
automatically as soon as the program or batch file ends, unless
:hp2./K:ehp2. is used. If you want the session to wait for a keystroke
before it closes itself, you can use this syntax (assuming 4DOS is your
command processor for OS/2 DOS sessions&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] start /DOS command ^^ pause
:exmp.:p.
(Because the caret [:hp2.^:ehp2.] is the default &4OS2. escape character,
two carets must be used in order to pass one on to 4DOS as a
command separator.)
:p.
If you want to start a DOS command-line session in OS/2, you can use the
command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] start /DOS
:exmp.:p.
You can specify settings for DOS and Windows sessions by using a
settings options file, and loading it with the :hp2./DOS=:ehp2.,:hp2.
/WIN3=:ehp2., or :hp2./WIN3S=:ehp2. option. This allows you to start DOS and
Windows sessions with specific settings without creating a desktop
object and modifying the settings manually. Before using this
capability you should read the description of it under :hp2./DOS=:ehp2.
(below) very carefully, since :hp8.errors in the settings file can
occasionally hang your system:ehp8..
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./BG:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(BackGround session) The session is started as a
background session. :hp2./BG:ehp2. may be abbreviated to
:hp2./B:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:hp2./C:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Close) The session or window is closed when the application
ends.
:pt.:hp2./DOS[=filename]:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(DOS session) Start a DOS session.
:p.
If you include the :hp2.=filename:ehp2., OS/2 will load DOS
settings from the specified file. When you use :hp2./DOS:ehp2. you can also
alter the DOS settings for a session with environment variables of the form
:hp2.DosSetting.name=value:ehp2., without using a settings file.
:p.
Starting a session with specific DOS settings is an undocumented feature
which was implemented within OS/2 with little error checking. It is
included in START because it substantially eases a complex task,
but :hp8.you must experiment carefully to ensure that the settings you
select will work properly on the systems on which you plan to use
them:ehp8.&per. Incorrect settings may be ignored, but they may also hang your
session or stop the entire system. Be sure your experiments are not
conducted while critical tasks are in process.
:p.
Each line in the file must have a name, an equal sign [:hp2.=:ehp2.], and a
value. The names are those shown in OS/2's DOS Settings dialog box. Do not
use spaces on either side of the equal sign.
:p.
The names in the DOS Settings dialog box will vary depending upon the device
drivers and other settings in your :hp1.CONFIG.SYS:ehp1. file, though many are
available on all systems. You must ensure that the names you use are valid
for the systems on which you use them. For example, if you replace IBM's
:hp1.COM.SYS:ehp1. and :hp1.VCOM.SYS:ehp1. with different communications
drivers, the COM_ settings will probably not be valid for the new
drivers. If you have a settings file which contains settings defined by a
particular driver, and use it on a system where the corresponding driver is
not loaded, the results are undefined.
:p.
The values in your settings file must be numeric for settings which show a
numeric value under DOS Settings (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., DOS_FILES=30), and must
be text strings for settings shown with a string (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1.,
DOS_SHELL=C&colon.\4DOS.COM C&colon.\4DOS /P). Strings should be entered
without trailing blanks. For values shown as multiple choice on the DOS
Settings page you must specify a numeric value, typically :hp2.0:ehp2. for
Off and :hp2.1:ehp2. for On (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., DOS_HIGH=1). Items with
choices other than Off and On may use different values, or may not work at
all; experimentation is usually required to find out what works. Attempting
to use strings for choice items (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., DOS_HIGH=ON) will not
work, and can hang your system.  This is due to the internal operation of
OS/2, and is not a problem in &4OS2..
:p.
A typical DOS settings file might look like this&colon.
:xmp.
    DOS_FILES=30
    DOS_HIGH=1
    DOS_SHELL=C&colon.\4DOS\4DOS.COM C&colon.\4DOS /P
    MOUSE_EXCLUSIVE_ACCESS=0
    VIDEO_FASTPASTE=1
:exmp.:p.
You can include comments in a settings file by beginning any line with a
colon [:hp2.&colon.:ehp2.].
:p.
When you use :hp2./DOS:ehp2. you can also alter the DOS settings for a
session with environment variables, without using a DOS settings file. When
the :hp2.=filename:ehp2. portion of the switch is not used, OS/2 will scan the
environment looking for variables of the form
:hp2.DosSetting.name=value:ehp2.&per. Each such variable entry will be used to
set the DOS setting with the specified name to the specified value. All of
the cautions and restrictions given above for settings stored in a file
apply equally to settings stored in environment variables.
:p.
Settings stored in environment variables are "global" and apply to all
sessions started with :hp2.START /DOS:ehp2., except when an explicit
settings file is specified with :hp2.=filename:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:hp2./FG:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(ForeGround session) Start the session as the foreground
session. :hp2./FG:ehp2. may be abbreviated to :hp2./F:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:hp2./FS:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Full Screen) Start the session as a full-screen
session.
:pt.:hp2./I:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Inherit environment) Inherit the default environment
specified in :hp1.CONFIG.SYS:ehp1., if any, rather than the
current environment.
:pt.:hp2./ICON=:ehp2.:hp1.filename:ehp1. &colon.:pd.Use the specified icon
file. If you don't use :hp2./ICON:ehp2., the displayed icon will be the one
found or assigned by OS/2. :hp2./ICON:ehp2. adds :hp2./N:ehp2. to the command
Otherwise it fails.
:pt.:hp2./INV:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Invisible) Start the session or window as invisible. No
icon will appear and the session will only be accessible through the Task Manager or Window List.
:pt.:hp2./K:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Keep session or window at end) The session or window
continues after the application program ends. Use
the :link reftype=hd refid=EXIT.EXIT:elink. command to end the session.
:pt.:hp2./L:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Local lists) Start &4OS2. with local alias,
history, and directory history lists. This option combines the effects of
:hp2./LA:ehp2., :hp2./LD:ehp2., and :hp2./LH:ehp2. (below).
:pt.:hp2./LA:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Local Alias list) Start &4OS2. with a local alias
list.See :link reftype=hd refid=ALIAS.ALIAS:elink. for information on local
and global aliases.
:pt.:hp2./LD:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Local Directory history) Start &4OS2. with a local
directory history list. See :link reftype=hd refid=GlobalDirHistory.Local and Global Directory History:elink.
for more information.
:pt.:hp2./LH:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Local History list) Start &4OS2. with a local history list.
See :link reftype=hd refid=CmdHist.Command History and Recall:elink. for
information on local and global history lists.
:pt.:hp2./MAX:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Maximized) Start the session or window maximized.
:pt.:hp2./MIN:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Minimized) Start the session or window minimized.
:pt.:hp2./N:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(No command processor) Start an OS/2 program
directly, without a command processor. The :hp1.command:ehp1. cannot be an
internal command or batch file. This is the default for PM applications.
:pt.:hp2./PGM:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Program name) The string following this option is the
program name. If you do not use :hp2./PGM:ehp2., the first quoted string on
the line will be used as the session and task list title, and not as the
program name.
:pt.:hp2./PM:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Presentation Manager) Start a program in the
Presentation Manager session.
:pt.:hp2./POS:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Position) Start the window at the specified
screen position. The syntax is :hp2./POS=x, y, width, height:ehp2. where the
values are specified in pixels or pels. :hp2.x:ehp2. and :hp2.y:ehp2. refer
to the position of the :hp2.top:ehp2. left corner of the window relative to
the :hp2.bottom:ehp2. left corner of the screen.
:pt.:hp2./WAIT:ehp2.&colon.:pd.Wait for the new session or window to finish
before continuing. Cannot be used with :hp2./WIN3:ehp2. or :hp2./WIN3S:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:hp2./WIN:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Windowed) Start the session in a window.
:pt.:hp2./WIN3[=filename]:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Windows enhanced mode) Run the program
in an enhanced-mode Windows 3.x session. The session will run seamless (on the OS/2
desktop). To start a Windows application in full-screen mode, use :hp2./FS:ehp2. rather
than :hp2./WIN3:ehp2.&per. You can include an equal sign and the name of an options file to
set options for the specific session and application (see :hp2./DOS=:ehp2. above for
details).
:pt.:hp2./WIN3S[=filename]:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Windows standard mode)
Equivalent to :hp2./WIN3:ehp2., but runs the program in standard mode rather
than enhanced mode.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=SWITCH.SWITCH - Select commands based on a value
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Select commands to execute based on a value.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.SWITCH:ehp2. :hp3.expression:ehp3.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.CASE:ehp2. :hp3.value1:ehp3. :hp2.[.OR.:ehp2.
:hp3.value2:ehp3. :hp2.] ...:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.    commands:ehp3.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.CASE:ehp2. :hp3.value3:ehp3.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.    commands:ehp3.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.DEFAULT:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.    commands:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.ENDSWITCH:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.expression :ehp3.&colon. An environment variable, internal
variable, variable function, text string, or a combination of these
elements, that is used to select a group of commands.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.value1, value2,:ehp3. :hp1.etc. :ehp1.&colon. A value to test,
or multiple values connected with :hp2..OR.:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.commands :ehp3.&colon. One or more commands to execute if the
expression matches the :hp1.value:ehp1.&per. If you use multiple commands, they
must be separated by command separators or placed on separate lines.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=IF.IF:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=IFF.IFF:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
SWITCH can only be used in batch files. It allows you to select a command
or group of commands to execute based on the possible values of a variable
or a combination of variables and text.
:p.
The SWITCH command is always followed by an :hp1.expression:ehp1. created
from environment variables, internal variables, variable functions, and text
strings, and then by a sequence of CASE statements matching the possible
:hp1.values:ehp1. of the :hp1.expression:ehp1.&per. If one of the
:hp1.values:ehp1. in a CASE statement matches the :hp1.expression:ehp1., the
commands following that CASE statement are executed, and all subsequent CASE
statements and the commands which follow them are ignored. If no matches are
found, the commands following the optional DEFAULT statement are executed. If
there are no matches and there is no DEFAULT statement, no commands are
executed by SWITCH.
:p.
After all of the commands following the CASE or DEFAULT statement are
executed, the batch file continues with the commands that follow ENDSWITCH.
:p.
You must include a command separator or new line after the
:hp1.expression:ehp1., before each CASE or DEFAULT statement, before each
command, and before ENDSWITCH. You can link :hp1.values:ehp1. in a CASE
statement with :hp2..OR.:ehp2. (but not with :hp2..AND.:ehp2. or
:hp2..XOR.:ehp2.).
:p.
For example, the following batch file fragment displays one message if the
user presses :hp2.A:ehp2., another if user presses :hp2.B:ehp2. or
:hp2.C:ehp2., and a third if the user presses any other key&colon.
:xmp.
    inkey Enter a keystroke&colon. %%key
    switch %key
    case A
      echo It's an A
    case B .or. C
      echo It's either B or C
    default
      echo It's not A, B, or C
    endswitch
:exmp.:p.
In the example above, the value of a single environment variable was used for
the :hp1.expression:ehp1.&per. You will probably find that this is the best
method to use in most situations. However, you can use other kinds of
expressions if necessary. The first example below selects a command to
execute based on the length of a variable, and the second bases the action
on a quoted text string stored in an environment variable&colon.
:xmp.
    switch %@len[%var1]
    case 0
      echo Missing var1
    case 1
      echo Single character
    ...
    endswitch

    switch "%string1"
    case "This is a test"
      echo Test string
    case "The quick brown fox"
      echo It's the fox
    ...
    endswitch
:exmp.:p.
The SWITCH and ENDSWITCH commands must be on separate lines, and cannot be
placed within a :link reftype=hd refid=Grouping.command group:elink., or on
the same line as other commands (this is the reason SWITCH cannot be used in
aliases). However, commands within the SWITCH block can use command groups
or the :link reftype=hd refid=MultCmds.command separator:elink. in the
normal way.
:p.
SWITCH commands can be nested. You can exit from all SWITCH / ENDSWITCH
processing by using :link reftype=hd refid=GOTO.GOTO:elink. to a line past
the last ENDSWITCH.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=TEE.TEE - "Tee" pipe fitting
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Copy standard input to both standard output
and a file.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.TEE [/A] :ehp2.:hp3.file:ehp3.
:hp2....:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.file :ehp3.&colon. One or more files that will receive the
"tee-d" output.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.(ppend):pd.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=Y.Y:elink. and the :link reftype=hd
refid=RedirPipe.redirection:elink. options.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
TEE is normally used to "split" the output of a program so that you
can see it on the display and also save it in a file. It can also
be used to capture intermediate output before the data is altered
by another program or command.
:p.
TEE gets its input from standard input (usually the piped output of
another command or program), and sends out two copies&colon. one goes to
standard output, the other to the :hp1.file:ehp1. or :hp1.files:ehp1. that you
specify. TEE is not likely to be useful with programs which do not
use standard output, because these programs cannot send output
through a pipe.
:p.
For example, to search the file :hp1.DOC:ehp1. for any lines containing
the string "4OS2", make a copy of the matching lines in :hp1.4.DAT:ehp1.,
sort the lines, and write them to the output file :hp1.4O.DAT:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] find "4OS2" doc &splitvbar. tee 4.dat &splitvbar. sort > 4o.dat
:exmp.:p.
If you are typing at the keyboard to produce the input for TEE, you
must enter a :hp2.Ctrl-Z:ehp2. to terminate the input.
:p.
When using TEE with a pipe under &4OS2., the programs on the two ends
of the pipe run simultaneously, not sequentially as in 4DOS.
:p.
See :link reftype=hd refid=Piping.Piping:elink. for more information on
pipes.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Append) Append the output to the file(s) rather
than overwriting them.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=TEXT.TEXT - Display text in a batch file
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display a block of text in a batch file.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.TEXT:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.    .
:pt.:pd.    .
:pt.:pd.    .
:pt.:pd.:hp2.ENDTEXT:ehp2.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=ECHO.ECHO:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=SCREEN.SCREEN:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=SCRPUT.SCRPUT:elink.,
and :link reftype=hd refid=VSCRPUT.VSCRPUT:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
TEXT can only be used in batch files.
:p.
The TEXT command is useful for displaying menus or multi-line
messages. TEXT will display all subsequent lines in the batch file
until terminated by ENDTEXT. Both TEXT and ENDTEXT must be entered
as the only command on the line.
:p.
To redirect the entire block of text, use redirection on the TEXT
command itself, but not on the actual text lines or the ENDTEXT
line. No environment variable expansion or other processing is
performed on the lines between TEXT and ENDTEXT; they are displayed
exactly as they are stored in the batch file.
:p.
You can change screen colors by inserting ANSI escape sequences
anywhere in the text block. You can also use a
:link reftype=hd refid=CLS.CLS:elink. or :link reftype=hd
refid=COLOR.COLOR:elink. command to set the screen color before executing
the TEXT command.
:p.
The following batch file fragment displays a simple menu&colon.
:xmp.
    @echo off &amp. cls
    screen 2 0
    text
    Enter one of the following&colon.
      1 - Spreadsheet
      2 - Word Processing
      3 - Utilities
      4 - Exit
    endtext
    inkey /k"1243" Enter your selection: %%key
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=TIME.TIME - Set the system time
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display or set the current system time.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.TIME [:ehp2.:hp3.hh:ehp3.
:hp2.[&colon.:ehp2.:hp3.mm:ehp3. :hp2.[&colon.:ehp2.:hp3.ss:ehp3. :hp2.]]]
[AM &splitvbar. PM]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.hh :ehp3.&colon. The hour (0 - 23).
:pt.:pd.:hp3.mm :ehp3.&colon. The minute (0 - 59).
:pt.:pd.:hp3.ss :ehp3.&colon. The second (0 - 59).
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=DATE.DATE:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
If you don't enter any parameters, TIME will display the current
system time and prompt you for a new time. Press :hp2.Enter:ehp2. if you
don't wish to change the time; otherwise, enter the new time&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] time
    Mon  Dec 22, 2017  9&colon.30&colon.06
    New time (hh&colon.mm&colon.ss)&colon.
:exmp.:p.
TIME defaults to 24-hour format, but you can optionally enter the
time in 12-hour format by appending "a", "am", "p", or "pm" to the
time you enter.
:p.
For example, to enter the time as 9&colon.30 am&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] time 9&colon.30 am
:exmp.:p.
OS/2 adds the system time and date to the directory entry for every
file you create or modify. If you keep both the time and date
accurate, you will have a record of when you last updated each
file.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=TIMER.TIMER - Start or stop a stopwatch
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.TIMER is a system stopwatch.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.TIMER [ON] [/1 /2 /3 /S]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.ON :ehp3.&colon. Force the stopwatch to restart.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./1:ehp2. (stopwatch #1):pd.:hp2./3:ehp2. (stopwatch #3)
:pt.:hp2./2:ehp2. (stopwatch #2):pd.:hp2./S:ehp2.(plit)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
The TIMER command turns a system stopwatch on and off. When you
first run TIMER, the stopwatch starts&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] timer
    Timer 1 on&colon. 12&colon.21&colon.46
:exmp.:p.
When you run TIMER again, the stopwatch stops and the elapsed time
is displayed&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] timer
    Timer 1 off&colon. 12&colon.21&colon.58   Elapsed time&colon. 0&colon.00&colon.12.06
:exmp.:p.
There are three stopwatches available (1, 2, and 3) so you can time
multiple overlapping events. By default, TIMER uses stopwatch #1.
:p.
The smallest interval TIMER can measure depends upon the operating
system you are using, your hardware, and the interaction between
the two. However, it should never be greater than .06 second. The
largest interval is 23 hours, 59 minutes, 59.99 seconds.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml compact tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./1:ehp2.&colon.:pd.Use timer #1 (the default).
.br
:pt.:hp2./2:ehp2.&colon.:pd.Use timer #2.
.br
:pt.:hp2./3:ehp2.&colon.:pd.Use timer #3.
.br
:pt.:hp2./S:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Split) Display a split time without stopping
the timer. To display the current elapsed time but leave the timer
running&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] timer /s
    Timer 1 elapsed&colon. 0&colon.06&colon.40.63
:exmp.
:pt.:hp2.ON:ehp2.&colon.:pd.Start the timer regardless of its previous state (on
or off). Otherwise the TIMER command toggles the timer state (unless :hp2./S:ehp2.
is used).
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=TITLE.TITLE - Window title
:i1 id=TITLE global.TITLE
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Change the window title.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.TITLE:ehp2. [:hp3.title:ehp3.]
:pt.:pd.   or
:pt.:pd.:hp2.TITLE [:ehp2.:hp3./c /d:ehp3.:hp2.]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.title :ehp3.&colon. The new window title.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3./c :ehp3.&colon. Set window title to the standard 4os2 window title ('4os2 Window' / '4os2 Full Screen').
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3./d :ehp3.&colon. Set window title to current directory name.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=ACTIVATE.ACTIVATE:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=WINDOW.WINDOW:elink. and :link reftype=hd refid=INI_TitleIsCurDir.TitleIsCurDir:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
TITLE changes the window title text that appears in the caption bar at the top of the
&4OS2. window.
:p.
If the TITLE command is issued from within a script, the change will not
take effect until script execution terminates. To change the window title
text displayed during script execution, use the
:link reftype=hd refid=WINDOW.WINDOW:elink. command.
:p.
Do not enclose the title text in quotes unless you want the quotes to
appear as part of the actual title.
:p.
TITLE /c or /d can be used to override the TitleIsCurDir :hp1.&period.INI:ehp1. File setting for the current session.
:p.
To change the title of the current window to "JP Software / 4OS2"&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] title JP Software / 4OS2
:exmp.
:p.
Note that the :hp3./c :ehp3. and :hp3./d :ehp3. switches change the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_TitleIsCurDir.TitleIsCurDir:elink.
setting for the current session and all child sessions.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=TOUCH.TOUCH - Change date and time stamps
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Change a file's date and time stamps.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.TOUCH [/C /D[acw][mm-dd-yy] /E /F /Q
/T[acw][hh&colon.mm]]:ehp2. :hp3.file:ehp3. :hp2....:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.file :ehp3.&colon. One or more files whose date and/or time
stamps are to be changed.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./C:ehp2.(reate file):pd.:hp2./F:ehp2.(orce read-only files)
:pt.:hp2./D:ehp2.(ate):pd.:hp2./Q:ehp2.(uiet)
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2. (no Error messages):pd.:hp2./T:ehp2.(ime)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.File Selection:ehp2.
:p.
Supports extended :link reftype=hd refid=wildcards.wildcards:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=ranges.ranges:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=MultFiles.multiple filenames:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=InclList.include lists:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
TOUCH is used to change the date and/or time of a file. You can use it to
be sure that particular files are included or excluded from an internal
command, backup program, compiler MAKE utility, or other program that
selects files based on their time and date stamps, or to set a group of
files to the same date and time for consistency.
:p.
:hp8.TOUCH should be used with caution:ehp8., and in most cases should only
be used on files you create. Many programs depend on file dates
and times to perform their work properly. In addition, many software
manufacturers use file dates and times to signify version
numbers. Indiscriminate changes to date and time stamps can lead to
confusion or incorrect behavior of other software.
:p.
TOUCH normally works with existing files, and will display an error if the
:hp1.file:ehp1. you specify does not exist, or has the read-only attribute
set. To create the :hp1.file:ehp1. if it does not already exist, use the
:hp2./C:ehp2. switch. To force a date and time change for read-only files,
use the :hp2./F:ehp2. switch.
:p.
TOUCH displays the date, time, and full name of each file whose timestamp is
modified. To disable this output, use :hp2./Q:ehp2.&per.
:p.
If you don't specify a date or a time, TOUCH will default to the current date
and time from your system clock. For example, to set the time stamp of all
:hp1..C:ehp1. files in the current directory to the current date and
time&colon.
:xmp.
    [d&colon.\source] touch *.c
     6-12-17 11&colon.13&colon.58  D&colon.\SOURCE\MAIN.C
     6-12-17 11&colon.13&colon.58  D&colon.\SOURCE\INIT.C
     ...
:exmp.:p.
If you specify a date but not a time, the time will default to the current
time from your system clock. Similarly, if you specify a time but not a
date, the date will be obtained from the system clock.
:p.
On volumes supporting multiple timestamps, TOUCH sets the "modified" or "last write" date and time by
default. By adding the appropriate character to the /D or /T switch, you
can set the other date and time stamps that are maintained for each
file&colon.
:lm margin=4.:parml compact tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.a:ehp2.:pd.last access date and time.
:pt.:hp2.c:ehp2.:pd.creation date and time
:pt.:hp2.w:ehp2.:pd.last write date and time (default)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./C:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Create file) Create the :hp1.file:ehp1. (as a
zero-byte file) if it does not already exist. You cannot use wildcards with
:hp2./C:ehp2., but you can create multiple :hp1.files:ehp1. by listing them
individually on the command line.
:pt.:hp2./D:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Date) Specify the date that will be set for the
selected files. If the date is not specified, TOUCH will use the current
date. For files on volumes supporting multiple timestamps, you can use
:hp2./Da:ehp2., :hp2./Dc:ehp2., or :hp2./Dw:ehp2., followed by the date, to
explicitly specify the last access, creation, or last write date stamp. The
date must be entered using the proper format for your current country settings.
:pt.:hp2./E:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(No error messages) Suppress all non-fatal error
messages, such as "File not found." Fatal error messages, such as "Drive not
ready," will still be displayed. This option is most useful in batch files.
:pt.:hp2./F:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Force read-only files) Remove the read-only
attribute from each file before changing the date and time, and restore it
afterwards. Without :hp2./F:ehp2., attempting to change the date and time
on a read-only file will usually cause an error.
:pt.:hp2./Q:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Quiet) Do not display the new date and time and
the full name for each file.
:pt.:hp2./T:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Time) Specify the time that will be set for the
selected files, in hh&colon.mm format. If the time is not specified, TOUCH
will use the current time. For files on volumes supporting multiple timestamps,
you can use :hp2./Ta:ehp2., :hp2./Tc:ehp2., or :hp2./Tw:ehp2., followed by the
time, to explicitly specify the last access, creation, or last write time stamp.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=TREE.TREE - Directory tree
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display a graphical directory tree.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.TREE [/A /B /F /H /P /S
/T[&colon.acw]]:ehp2. :hp3.dir:ehp3. :hp2....:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.dir :ehp3.&colon. The directory to use as the start of the
tree. If more than one directory is specified, TREE will display a directory
tree for each.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./A&colon.:ehp2.(SCII):pd.:hp2./P:ehp2.(ause)
:pt.:hp2./B&colon.:ehp2.(are):pd.:hp2./S:ehp2. (file Size)
:pt.:hp2./F&colon.:ehp2.(iles):pd.:hp2./T:ehp2.(ime and date)
:pt.:hp2./H&colon.:ehp2.(idden directories):pd.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:hp2.File Selection:ehp2.
:p.
Supports extended :link reftype=hd refid=wildcards.wildcards:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=ranges.ranges:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=MultFiles.multiple filenames:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=InclList.include lists:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
The TREE command displays a graphical representation of the directory tree
using standard or extended ASCII characters. For example, to display the
directory structure on drive C&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] tree c&colon.\
:exmp.:p.
You can print the display, save it in a file, or view it with
:link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink. by using standard
:link reftype=hd refid=RedirPipe.redirection:elink. symbols. Be sure to
review the :hp2./A :ehp2.option before attempting to print the TREE
output. The options, discussed below, specify the amount of information
included in the display.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./A:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(ASCII) Display the tree using standard ASCII
characters. You can use this option if you want to save the directory tree
in a file for further processing or print the tree on a printer which does
not support the graphical symbols that TREE normally uses.
:pt.:hp2./B:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Bare) Display the full pathname of each
directory, without any of the line-drawing characters.
:pt.:hp2./F:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Files) Display files as well as directories. If
you use this option, the name of each file is displayed beneath the name of
the directory in which it resides.
:pt.:hp2./H:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Hidden) Display hidden as well as normal
directories. If you combine :hp2./H:ehp2. and :hp2./F:ehp2., hidden files
are also displayed.
:pt.:hp2./P:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Pause) Wait for a key to be pressed after each
screen page before continuing the display. Your options at the prompt are
explained in detail under :link reftype=hd refid=Prompts.Page and File
Prompts:elink.&per.
:pt.:hp2./S:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Size) Display the size of each file. This
option is only useful when combined with :hp2./F:ehp2.&per.
:pt.:hp2./T:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Time and date) Display the time and date for
each directory. If you combine :hp2./T:ehp2. and :hp2./F:ehp2., the time
and date for each file will also be displayed. For volumes supporting multiple
timestamps, the time and date of the last write will be shown by default. You
can select a specific time and date stamp by using the following variations of
:hp2./T:ehp2.&colon. 
:parml tsize=8 compact break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:hp2./T&colon.a:ehp2. last access date and time.
:pt.:pd.:hp2./T&colon.c:ehp2. creation date and time.
:pt.:pd.:hp2./T&colon.w:ehp2. last write date and time (default).
:eparml.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=TYPE.TYPE - Display file(s)
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display the contents of the specified file(s).
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.TYPE [/A&colon.[[-]rhsda] /L /P]:ehp2.
:hp3.file:ehp3. :hp2....:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.file :ehp3.&colon. The file or list of files that you want to display.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./A&colon.:ehp2. (Attribute select):pd.:hp2./P:ehp2.(ause)
:pt.:hp2./L:ehp2.(ine numbers):pd.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.File Selection:ehp2.
:p.
Supports extended :link reftype=hd refid=wildcards.wildcards:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=ranges.ranges:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=MultFiles.multiple filenames:elink., and :link reftype=hd refid=InclList.include lists:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
The TYPE command displays a file. It is normally only useful for
displaying ASCII text files. Executable files (:hp1..COM:ehp1. and
:hp1..EXE:ehp1. ) and many data files may be unreadable when displayed with
TYPE because they include non-alphanumeric characters.
:p.
To display the files :hp1.MEMO1:ehp1. and :hp1.MEMO2:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] type /p memo1 memo2
:exmp.:p.
You can press :hp2.Ctrl-S:ehp2. to pause TYPE's display and then any key
to continue.
:p.
To display text from the clipboard, use :hp2.CLIP&colon.:ehp2. as the file
name. CLIP&colon. will not return any data unless the clipboard
contains text. See :link reftype=hd refid=Redirection.Redirection:elink. for
additional information on CLIP&colon..
:p.
You will probably find LIST to be more useful for displaying files. However,
the TYPE /L command used with :link reftype=hd
refid=Redirection.redirection:elink. is useful if you want to add line
numbers to a file, for example&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] type /l myfile > myfile.num
:exmp.:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./A&colon.:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Attribute select) Select only those files that have the
specified attribute(s) set. Preceding the attribute character with a
hyphen [:hp2.-:ehp2.] will select files that do not have that attribute set. The colon
[:hp2.&colon.:ehp2.] after :hp2./A:ehp2. is required. The attributes are&colon.
:parml tsize=8 compact break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   R:ehp2. Read-only
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   H:ehp2. Hidden
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   S:ehp2. System
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   D:ehp2. Subdirectory
:pt.:pd.:hp2.   A:ehp2. Archive
:eparml.:p.
If no attributes are listed at all (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., :hp2.TYPE /A&colon. ...:ehp2.), TYPE will select all
files and subdirectories including hidden and system files. If
attributes are combined, all the specified attributes must match for a
file to be selected. For example, /A&colon.RHS will select only those files
with all three attributes set.
:pt.:hp2./L:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Line numbers) Display a line number preceding
each line of text.
:pt.:hp2./P:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Pause) Prompt after displaying each page. Your
options at the prompt are explained in detail under :link reftype=hd
refid=Prompts.Page and File Prompts:elink.&per.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=UNALIAS.UNALIAS - Remove aliases
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Remove aliases from the alias list.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.UNALIAS [/Q /R:ehp2.
:hp3.file:ehp3. :hp2.] [:ehp2.:hp3.alias:ehp3. :hp2....]:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.   or
:pt.:pd.:hp2.UNALIAS *:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.alias :ehp3.&colon. One or more aliases to remove from memory.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.file :ehp3.&colon. One or more files to read for alias
definitions.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./Q:ehp2.(uiet):pd.:hp2./R:ehp2.(ead file)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=ALIAS.ALIAS:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=ESET.ESET:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
&4OS2. maintains a list of the aliases that you have defined. The
UNALIAS command will remove aliases from that list. You can remove
one or more aliases by name, or you can delete the entire alias
list by using the command :hp2.UNALIAS *:ehp2.&per.
:p.
For example, to remove the alias DDIR&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] unalias ddir
:exmp.:p.
To remove all the aliases&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] unalias *
:exmp.:p.
If you keep aliases in a file that can be loaded with the
:link reftype=hd refid=ALIAS.ALIAS:elink. /R command, you can remove the
aliases by using the UNALIAS /R command with the same filename&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] unalias /r alias.lst
:exmp.:p.
This is much faster than removing each alias individually in a batch file,
and can be more selective than using UNALIAS *.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./Q:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Quiet) Prevents UNALIAS from displaying an error message if
one or more of the aliases does not exist. This option is most useful in
batch files, for removing a group of aliases when some of the aliases may not
have been defined.
:pt.:hp2./R:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Read) Read the list of aliases to remove from a
file. The file format should be the same format as that used by the
:link reftype=hd refid=ALIAS.ALIAS:elink. /R command. You can use multiple
files with one UNALIAS /R command by placing the names on the command line,
separated by spaces&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] unalias /r alias1.lst alias2.lst
:exmp.:p.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=UNSET.UNSET - Remove environment variables
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Remove variables from the environment.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.UNSET  [/Q /R:ehp2.
:hp3.file:ehp3. :hp2.]:ehp2. :hp3.name:ehp3. :hp2....:ehp2.
:pt.:pd.   or
:pt.:pd.:hp2.UNSET *:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.name :ehp3.&colon. One or more variables to remove.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.file :ehp3.&colon. One or more files containing variables
definitions.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./M:ehp2.(uiet):pd.:hp2./R:ehp2.(ead from file)
:pt.:hp2./Q:ehp2.(uiet):pd.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=ESET.ESET:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=SET.SET:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
UNSET removes one or more variables from the environment. For example, to
remove the variable CMDLINE&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] unset cmdline
:exmp.:p.
If you use the command :hp2.UNSET *:ehp2., all of the environment variables
will be deleted&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] unset *
:exmp.:p.
UNSET can be used in a batch file, in conjunction with the SETLOCAL and
ENDLOCAL commands, to clear the environment of variables that may cause
problems for applications run from that batch file.
:p.
For more information on environment variables, see the :link reftype=hd
refid=SET.SET:elink. command and the general discussion of the
:link reftype=hd refid=Environment.environment:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp8.Use caution:ehp8. when removing environment variables, and especially
when using UNSET *. Many programs will not work properly without
certain environment variables; for example, &4OS2. uses PATH and DPATH.
:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./Q:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Quiet) Prevents UNSET from displaying an error
message if one or more of the variables does not exist. This option is most
useful in batch files, for removing a group of variables when some of the
variables may not have been defined.
:pt.:hp2./R:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Read) Read environment variables to UNSET from
a file. This much faster than using multiple UNSET commands in a batch
file, and can be more selective than UNSET *. The file format should be the
same format as that used by the :link reftype=hd refid=SET.SET:elink. /R
command.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=VERIFY.VERIFY - Enable or disable disk write verification
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Enable or disable disk write verification
or display the verification state.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.VERIFY [ON &splitvbar. OFF]:ehp2.
:eparml.:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
OS/2 maintains an internal verify flag. When the flag is on, OS/2 attempts
to verify each disk write by making sure that the data written to the disk
can be read back successfully into the computer. It does :hp2.not:ehp2.
compare the data in memory with the data actually placed on disk to fully
verify the disk write process.
:p.
If used without any parameters, VERIFY will display the state of the verify
flag&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] verify
    VERIFY is OFF
:exmp.:p.
VERIFY is off when the system boots up. Once it is turned on with
the VERIFY ON command, it stays on until you use the VERIFY OFF command or
until you reboot.
:p.
Verification will slow your disk write operations slightly (the effect is
not usually noticeable).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=VOL.VOL - Display disk volume labels
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display disk volume label(s).
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.VOL [:ehp2.:hp3.drive&colon.:ehp3.
:hp2.] ...:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.drive :ehp3.&colon. The drive or drives to search for labels.
:eparml.:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
Each disk may have a volume label, created when the disk is
formatted or with the external LABEL command. Also, every floppy
disk formatted with DOS version 4.0 or above, OS/2, or Windows NT
has a volume serial number.
:p.
The VOL command will display the volume label and, if available,
the volume serial number of a disk volume. If the disk doesn't
have a volume label, VOL will report that it is "unlabeled." If
you don't specify a drive, VOL displays information about the
current drive&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] vol
    Volume in drive C&colon. is MYHARDDISK
:exmp.:p.
If available, the volume serial number will appear after the drive
label or name.
:p.
To display the disk labels for drives A and B&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] vol a&colon. b&colon.
    Volume in drive A&colon. is unlabeled
    Volume in drive B&colon. is BACKUP_2
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=VSCRPUT.VSCRPUT - Display text vertically and in color
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Display text vertically in the specified color.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.VSCRPUT:ehp2. :hp3.row col:ehp3.
:hp2.[BRIght] [BLInk]:ehp2. :hp3.fg:ehp3. :hp2.ON [BRIght]:ehp2.
:hp3.bg text:ehp3.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.row :ehp3.&colon. Starting row number.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.col :ehp3.&colon. Starting column number.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.fg :ehp3.&colon. Foreground text color.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.bg :ehp3.&colon. Background text color.
:pt.:pd.:hp3.text :ehp3.&colon. The text to display.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=SCRPUT.SCRPUT:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
VSCRPUT writes text vertically on the screen rather than
horizontally. Like the SCRPUT command, it uses the colors you
specify to write the text. VSCRPUT can be used for simple graphs
and charts generated by batch files. VSCRPUT always leaves the cursor
at the end of the displayed text. See :link reftype=hd refid=Colors.Colors
and Color Names:elink. for details about colors and notes on the use of
bright background colors.
:p.
The :hp1.row:ehp1. and :hp1.column:ehp1. are zero-based, so on a standard 25
line by 80 column display, valid rows are 0 - 24 and valid columns are 0
- 79. VSCRPUT checks for a valid :hp1.row:ehp1. and :hp1.column:ehp1., and
displays a "Usage" error message if either value is out of range.
:p.
You can also specify the :hp1.row:ehp1. and :hp1.column:ehp1. as offsets
from the current cursor position. Begin the value with a plus sign
[:hp2.+:ehp2.] to move down the specified number of rows or to the right
the specified number of columns before displaying text, or with a
minus sign [:hp2.-:ehp2.] to move up or to the left.
:p.
If you specify 999 for the :hp1.row:ehp1., VSCRPUT will center the text
vertically on the display. If you specify 999 for the :hp1.column:ehp1.,
VSCRPUT will center the text horizontally.
:p.
VSCRPUT does not move the cursor when it displays the text.
:p.
The following batch file fragment displays an X and Y axis and labels
them&colon.
:xmp.
    cls bright white on blue
    drawhline 20 10 40 1 bright white on blue
    drawvline 2 10 19 1 bright white on blue
    scrput 21 20 bright red on blue X axis
    vscrput 8 9 bright red on blue Y axis
:exmp.:p.
VSCRPUT checks for a valid :hp1.row:ehp1. and :hp1.column:ehp1., and
displays a "Usage" error message if either value is out of range.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=WINDOW.WINDOW - Change the window state or title
:i1 id=WINDOW global.WINDOW
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Minimize or maximize the current window,
restore the default window size, or change the window title.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.WINDOW [MIN &splitvbar. MAX &splitvbar.
RESTORE &splitvbar. /POS=x,y,width,height &splitvbar.
":ehp2.:hp3.title:ehp3. :hp2."]:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.title :ehp3.&colon. A new title for the window.
:eparml.:lm margin=13.:parml compact tsize=32 break=none.
:pt.:hp2./POS:ehp2.(ition):pd.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=TITLE.TITLE:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
The WINDOW command is used to control the appearance and title of the current
window. WINDOW can only be used to specify one change to the current window
at a time; to perform more than one operation, you must use multiple WINDOW
commands (see examples below).
:p.
WINDOW MIN reduces the window to an icon, WINDOW MAX
enlarges it to its maximum size, and WINDOW RESTORE returns the
window to its default size and location on the desktop.
:p.
You can use the :hp2./POS:ehp2. option to set the location and size of the
window on the desktop. The x and y values of the :hp2./POS:ehp2.
option select the window's origin while the width and height values
determine its size.
:p.
If you specify a new title, the title text must be enclosed in
double quotes. The quotes will not appear as part of the actual
title. The title text is limited to 60 characters.
:p.
If you specify a new title from the &4OS2. prompt, the WINDOW command will
behave the same as the :link reftype=hd refid=TITLE.TITLE:elink. command.
:p.
If you specify a new title from within a script or a nested &4OS2. shell,
the setting is temporary. When the script terminates or the shell is exited,
the title will revert to the value it had before it was changed by the WINDOW command.
:p.
For example, to maximize the current window and change it's title, you must
perform two WINDOW commands:
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] window max
    [c&colon.\] window "JP Software / 4OS2"
:exmp.:p.
:hp2.Options:ehp2.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2./POS:ehp2.&colon.:pd.(Position) Set the window position and size on the
screen. The syntax is :hp2./POS=x, y, width, height:ehp2. where the
values are specified in pixels or pels. :hp2.x:ehp2. and :hp2.y:ehp2. refer
to the position of the :hp2.top:ehp2. left corner of the window relative to
the :hp2.bottom:ehp2. left corner of the screen.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=Y.Y - "Y" pipe fitting
:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp3.Purpose&colon.:ehp3.:pd.Copy standard input to standard output, and
then copy the specified file(s) to standard output.
.br
:pt.:hp3.Format&colon.:ehp3.:pd.:hp2.Y:ehp2. :hp3.file:ehp3. :hp2....:ehp2.
.br
:pt.:pd.:hp3.file :ehp3.&colon. The file or list of files to send to
standard output.
:eparml.:p.
See also&colon. :link reftype=hd refid=TEE.TEE:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Usage:ehp2.
:p.
The Y command copies input from standard input (usually the
keyboard) to standard output (usually the screen). Once the input
ends, the named files are appended to standard output.
:p.
For example, to get text from standard input, append the files
:hp1.MEMO1:ehp1. and :hp1.MEMO2:ehp1. to it, and send the output to :hp1.MEMOS:ehp1. &colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] y memo1 memo2 > memos
:exmp.:p.
The Y command is most useful if you want to add redirected data to
the beginning of a file instead of appending it to the end. For
example, this command copies the output of DIR, followed by the
contents of the file DIREND, to the file DIRALL&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] dir &splitvbar. y dirend > dirall
:exmp.:p.
If you are typing at the keyboard to produce input text for Y, you
must enter a :hp2.Ctrl-Z:ehp2. to terminate the input.
:p.
When using Y with a pipe you must take into account that the programs on the
two ends of the pipe run simultaneously, not sequentially.
:p.
See :link reftype=hd refid=Piping.Piping:elink. for more information.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h1 name=Aliases.Aliases
:p.
Much of the power of &4OS2. comes together in :hp2.aliases:ehp2., which
give you the ability to create your own commands. An alias is a name that
you select for a command or group of commands. Simple aliases substitute a
new name for an existing command. More complex aliases can redefine the
default settings of internal or external commands, operate as very fast
in-memory batch files, and perform commands based on the results of other
commands.
:p.
This section will show you some examples of the power of aliases. See the
:link reftype=hd refid=ALIAS.ALIAS:elink. command for complete details about
writing your own aliases.
:p.
The simplest type of alias gives a new name to an existing command. For
example, you could create a command called ROOT which uses
:link reftype=hd refid=CD.CD:elink. to switch to the root directory this
way&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias root = cd \
:exmp.:p.
After the alias has been defined this way, every time you type the command
ROOT, you will actually execute the command CD \.
:p.
Aliases can also create customized versions of commands. For example, the
:link reftype=hd refid=DIR.DIR:elink. command can sort a directory in
various ways. You can create an alias called DE that means "sort the
directory by filename extension, and pause after each page while displaying
it" like this&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias de = dir /oe /p
:exmp.:p.
Aliases can be used to execute sequences of commands as well. The following
command creates an alias called W which saves the current drive and directory,
changes to the WP directory on drive C, runs the program
:hp1.E&colon.\WP60\WP.EXE:ehp1., and, when the program terminates, returns
to the original drive and directory&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias w = `pushd c&colon.\wp &amp. e&colon.\wp60\wp.exe &amp. popd`
:exmp.:p.
This alias is enclosed in back-quotes because it contains multiple commands.
You must use the back-quotes whenever an alias contains multiple commands,
environment variables, parameters (see below), redirection, or piping. See
the :link reftype=hd refid=ALIAS.ALIAS:elink. command for full details.
:p.
Aliases can be nested, that is, one alias can invoke another. For example,
the alias above could also be written as&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias wp = e&colon.\wp60\wp.exe
    [c&colon.\] alias w = `pushd c&colon.\wp &amp. wp &amp. popd`
:exmp.:p.
If you enter W as a command, the command processor will execute the
:link reftype=hd refid=PUSHD.PUSHD:elink. command, detect that the next
command (WP) is another alias, and execute the program
:hp1.E&colon.\WP60\WP.EXE:ehp1., and - when the program exits - return to the
first alias, execute the :link reftype=hd refid=POPD.POPD:elink. command, and
return to the prompt.
:p.
You can use aliases to change the default options for both internal commands
and external commands. Suppose that you always want the
:link reftype=hd refid=DEL.DEL:elink. command to prompt before it erases a
file&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias del = *del /p
:exmp.:p.
An asterisk [:hp2.*:ehp2.] is used in front of the second "del" to show that
it is the name of an internal command, not an alias. See
:link reftype=hd refid=ALIAS.ALIAS:elink. for more information about this
use of the asterisk.
:p.
You may have a program on your system that has the same name as an internal
command. Normally, if you type the command name, you will start the internal
command rather than the program you desire, unless you explicitly add its full
path on the command line. For example, if you have a program named
:hp1.LIST.COM:ehp1. in the :hp1.C&colon.\UTIL:ehp1. directory, you could run
it with the command :hp1.C&colon.\UTIL\LIST.COM:ehp1.&per. However, if you
simply type LIST, the internal :link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink. command
will be invoked instead. Aliases give you two ways to get around this
problem.
:p.
First, you could define an alias that runs the program in question, but with a
different name&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias l = c&colon.\util\list.com
:exmp.:p.
Another approach is to rename the internal command and use the original name
for the external program. The following example renames the LIST command as
DISPLAY and then uses a second alias to run :hp1.LIST.COM:ehp1. whenever you
type LIST&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias display = *list
    [c&colon.\] alias list = c&colon.\util\list.com
:exmp.:p.
You can also assign an alias to a key, so that every time you press the key,
the command will be invoked. You do so by naming the alias with an at sign
[:hp2.@:ehp2.] followed by a key name. After you enter this next example,
you will see a 2-column directory with paging whenever you press
:hp2.Shift-F5:ehp2., then :hp2.Enter:ehp2.&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias @Shift-F5 = *dir /2/p
:exmp.:p.
This alias will put the :link reftype=hd refid=DIR.DIR:elink. command on the
command line when you press :hp2.Shift-F5:ehp2., then wait for you to enter
filenames or additional switches. You must press :hp2.Enter:ehp2. when you
are ready to execute the command. To execute the command immediately,
without displaying it on the command line or waiting for you to press
:hp2.Enter:ehp2., use two at signs at the start of the alias name&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias @@Shift-F5 = *dir /2/p
:exmp.:p.
The next example clears the screen whenever you press :hp2.Alt-F1:ehp2.&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias @@Alt-F1 = cls
:exmp.:p.
Aliases have many other capabilities as well. This example creates a simple
command-line calculator using the :link reftype=hd refid=_@EVAL.@EVAL:elink.
function. Once you have entered the example, you can type CALC 4*19, for
example, and you will see the answer&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias calc = `echo The answer is&colon. %@eval[%&amp.]`
:exmp.:p.
Our last example in this section creates an alias called IN. It will
temporarily change directories, run an internal or external command, and then
return to the current directory when the command is finished&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias in = `pushd %1 &amp. %2&amp. &amp. popd`
:exmp.:p.
Now if you type
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] in c&colon.\letters wp letter.txt
:exmp.:p.
you will change to the :hp1.C&colon.\LETTERS:ehp1. subdirectory, execute the
command WP :hp1.LETTER.TXT:ehp1. and then return to the current directory.
:p.
The above example uses two parameters&colon. %1 means the first argument on
the command line, and %2&amp. means the second and all subsequent arguments.
Parameters are explained in detail under the
:link reftype=hd refid=ALIAS.ALIAS:elink. command.
:p.
Your copy of &4OS2. includes a sample alias file called :hp1.ALIASES:ehp1.
which contains several useful aliases and demonstrates many alias techniques.
See the :link reftype=hd refid=ALIAS.ALIAS:elink. and :link reftype=hd
refid=UNALIAS.UNALIAS:elink. commands for more information and examples. Also
see :link reftype=hd refid=BATCHALIAS.Using Aliases in Batch Files:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h1 name=Batch.Batch Files
:p.
A batch file is a file that contains a list of commands to
execute. &4OS2. reads and interprets each line as if it had been
typed at the keyboard. Like :link reftype=hd refid=ALIAS.aliases:elink.,
batch files are handy for automating computing tasks. Unlike aliases,
batch files can be as long as you wish. Batch files take up separate disk
space for each file, and can't usually execute quite as quickly as
aliases, since they must be read from the disk.
:p.
The topics included in this section are&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=BatchType..BAT, .CMD, and .BTM Files:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=BatchEcho.Echoing in Batch Files:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=BatchParms.Batch File Parameters:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=BatchEnv.Using Environment Variables:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=BatchCommands.Batch File Commands:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=BatchInt.Interrupting a Batch File:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=AutoBatch.Automatic Batch Files (4START &amp. 4EXIT):elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=BatchDetect.Detecting &4OS2.:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=BatchAlias.Using Aliases in Batch Files:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=BatchDebug.Debugging Batch Files:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=BatchString.Batch File String Processing:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=BatchLineCont.Batch File Line Continuation:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=BatchComp.Batch File Compression:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=Compat.Special Character Compatibility:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=Parsing.Command Parsing:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=Quoting.Argument Quoting:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=REXX.REXX Support:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=EXTPROC.EXTPROC Support:elink.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=BatchType..BAT, .CMD, and .BTM Files
:p.
A batch file can run in two different modes. In the first,
traditional mode, each line of the batch file is read and executed
individually. In the second mode, the entire batch file is read
into memory at once. The second mode can be 5 to 10 times faster,
especially if most of the commands in the batch file are internal
commands. However, only the first mode can be used for self-modifying
batch files (which are rare), or for batch files which install memory-resident
utilities under DOS.
:p.
The batch file's extension determines its mode. Files with a
:hp1..CMD:ehp1. extension are run in the slower, traditional mode. Files
with a :hp1..BTM:ehp1. extension are run in the faster, more
efficient mode. You can change the execution mode inside a batch
file with the :link reftype=hd refid=LOADBTM.LOADBTM:elink. command.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=BatchEcho.Echoing in Batch Files
:p.
By default, each line in a batch file is displayed or "echoed" as
it is executed. You can change this behavior, if you want, in
several different ways&colon.
:lm margin=8.
:p.
Any batch file line that begins with an [:hp2.@:ehp2.] symbol will
not be displayed.
:p.
The display can be turned off and on within a batch file with
the :link reftype=hd refid=ECHO.ECHO:elink. OFF and ECHO ON commands.
:p.
The default setting can be changed with the :link reftype=hd
refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /V command, on the
:link reftype=hd refid=Options1.Options 1 page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
or the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_BatchEcho.BatchEcho:elink. directive in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:lm margin=1.
:p.
For example, the following line turns off echoing inside a batch
file. The [:hp2.@:ehp2.] symbol keeps the batch file from displaying the
ECHO OFF command&colon.
:xmp.
    @echo off
:exmp.:p.
&4OS2. also has a command line echo that is unrelated to the batch
file echo setting. See :link reftype=hd refid=ECHO.ECHO:elink. for details
about both settings.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=BatchParms.Batch File Parameters
:p.
Like aliases and application programs, batch files can examine the
command line that is used to invoke them. The command tail
(everything on the command line after the batch file name) is
separated into individual :hp2.parameters:ehp2. (also called :hp2.arguments:ehp2.
or :hp2.batch variables:ehp2.) by scanning for the spaces, tabs, and
commas that separate the parameters. A batch file can work with
the individual parameters or with the command tail as a whole.
:p.
These parameters are numbered from :hp2.%1:ehp2. to :hp2.%127:ehp2.&per. :hp2.%1:ehp2.
refers to the first parameter on the command line, :hp2.%2:ehp2. to the
second, and so on. It is up to the batch file to determine the
meaning of each parameter. You can use quotation marks to pass
spaces, tabs, commas, and other special characters in a batch file
parameter; see :link reftype=hd refid=Quoting.Argument Quoting:elink. for details.
:p.
Parameters that are referred to in a batch file, but which are
missing on the command line, appear as empty strings inside the
batch file. For example, if you start a batch file and put two
parameters on the command line, any reference in the batch file to
:hp2.%3:ehp2., or any higher-numbered parameter, will be interpreted as an
empty string.
:p.
A batch file can also work with three special parameters&colon. :hp2.%0:ehp2.
contains the name of the batch file as it was entered on the
command line, :hp2.%#:ehp2. contains the number of command line arguments,
and :hp2.%n$:ehp2. contains the complete command-line tail starting with
argument number ":hp2.n:ehp2." (for example, :hp2.%3$:ehp2. means the third
parameter and all those after it). The default value of ":hp2.n:ehp2." is
1, so :hp2.%$:ehp2. contains the entire command tail. The values of these
special parameters will change if you use the :link reftype=hd refid=SHIFT.SHIFT:elink.
command.
:p.
By default, 4DOS uses an ampersand [:hp2.&amp.:ehp2.] instead of a dollar sign
[:hp2.$:ehp2.] to indicate the remainder of the command tail. For
example, :hp2.%&amp.:ehp2. means all the parameters, and :hp2.%2&amp.:ehp2.
means the second parameter and all those after it. If you want to share
batch files or aliases between 4DOS and &4OS2., see :link reftype=hd
refid=Compat.Special Character Compatibility:elink. for
information on selecting compatible parameter characters for all products.
:p.
For example, if your batch file interprets the first argument as a
subdirectory name then the following line would move to the
specified directory&colon.
:xmp.
    cd %1
:exmp.:p.
A friendlier batch file would check to make sure the directory exists and
take some special action if it doesn't&colon.
:xmp.
    iff isdir %1 then &amp. cd %1
    else &amp. echo Subdirectory %1 does not exist! &amp. quit
    endiff
:exmp.:p.
(see the :link reftype=hd refid=IF.IF:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=IFF.IFF:elink. commands).
:p.
Batch files can also use :link reftype=hd refid=Environment.environment
variables:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=IntVars.internal variables:elink.,
and :link reftype=hd refid=VarFuncs.variable functions:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=BatchEnv.Using Environment Variables
:p.
Batch files can also use :link reftype=hd refid=Environment.environment
variables:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=IntVars.internal variables:elink.,
and :link reftype=hd refid=VarFuncs.variable functions:elink.&per.
You can use these variables and functions to determine system status
(:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., the type of CPU in the system), resource levels
(:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., the amount of free disk space), file information
(:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., the date and time a file was last modified), and other
information (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., the current date and time). You can also
perform arithmetic operations (including date and time arithmetic),
manipulate strings and substrings, extract parts of a filename, and read and
write files.
:p.
To create temporary variables for use inside a batch file, just use the
:link reftype=hd refid=SET.SET:elink. command to store the information you
want in an environment variable. Pick a variable name that isn't likely to
be in use by some other program (for example,
:link reftype=hd refid=PATH_Var.PATH:elink. would be a bad choice), and use
the :link reftype=hd refid=UNSET.UNSET:elink. command to remove these
variables from the environment at the end of your batch file. You
can use :link reftype=hd refid=SETLOCAL.SETLOCAL:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=ENDLOCAL.ENDLOCAL:elink. to create a "local"
environment so that the original environment will be restored when your
batch file is finished.
:p.
Environment variables used in a batch file may contain either numbers or
text. It is up to you to keep track of what's in each variable and use it
appropriately; if you don't (for example, if you use
%:link reftype=hd refid=_@EVAL.@EVAL:elink. to add a number to a text string),
you'll get an error message.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=BatchCommands.Batch File Commands
:p.
Several &4OS2. commands are particularly suited to batch file processing.
Here is a list of some of the commands you might find most useful&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=ACTIVATE.ACTIVATE:elink.:pd.activates another
window.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=BEEP.BEEP:elink.:pd.produces a sound of any pitch
and duration through the computer's speaker.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=CALL.CALL:elink.:pd.executes one batch file from
within another.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=CANCEL.CANCEL:elink.:pd.terminates all batch file
processing.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=CLS.CLS:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=COLOR.COLOR:elink.:pd.set the screen display colors.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=DO.DO:elink.:pd.starts a loop. The loop can be
based on a counter, or on a conditional test like those used in IF and IFF.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=DRAWBOX.DRAWBOX:elink.:pd.draws a box on the
screen.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=DRAWHLINE.DRAWHLINE:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=DRAWVLINE.DRAWVLINE:elink.:pd.draw horizontal and
vertical lines on the screen.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=ECHO.ECHO:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=ECHOS.ECHOS:elink.:pd.print text on the screen
(the text can also be redirected to a file or
device). :link reftype=hd refid=ECHO.ECHOERR:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=ECHOS.ECHOSERR:elink. print text to the standard
error device.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=GOSUB.GOSUB:elink.:pd.executes a subroutine
inside a batch file. The :link reftype=hd refid=RETURN.RETURN:elink. command
terminates the subroutine.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=GOTO.GOTO:elink.:pd.branches to a different
location in the batch file.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=FOR.FOR:elink.:pd.executes commands for each file
that matches a set of wildcards, or each entry in a list.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=IF.IF:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=IFF.IFF:elink.:pd.execute commands based on a test of
string or numeric values, program exit codes, or other conditions.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INKEY.INKEY:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=INPUT.INPUT:elink.:pd.collect keyboard input from the
user and store it in environment variables.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=KEYSTACK.KEYSTACK:elink.:pd.sends keystrokes to
applications.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=LOADBTM.LOADBTM:elink.:pd.changes the batch file
operating mode.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=ON.ON:elink.:pd.initializes error handling for
Ctrl-C / Ctrl-Break, or for program and command errors.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=PAUSE.PAUSE:elink.:pd.displays a message and waits
for the user to press a key.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=QUIT.QUIT:elink.:pd.ends the current batch file
and optionally returns an exit code.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=REM.REM:elink.:pd.places a remark in a batch file.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=SCREEN.SCREEN:elink.:pd.positions the cursor on
the screen and optionally prints a message at the new location.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=SCRPUT.SCRPUT:elink.:pd.displays a message in
color.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=SETLOCAL.SETLOCAL:elink.:pd.saves the current disk
drive, default directory, environment, alias list, and special character
settings. :link reftype=hd refid=ENDLOCAL.ENDLOCAL:elink. restores the
settings that were saved.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=SHIFT.SHIFT:elink.:pd.changes the numbering of the
batch file parameters.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=START.START:elink.:pd.starts another session or
window in certain multitasking environments.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=SWITCH.SWITCH:elink.:pd.selects a group of
statements to execute based on the value of a variable.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=TEXT.TEXT:elink.:pd.displays a block of
text. :link reftype=hd refid=TEXT.ENDTEXT:elink. ends the block.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=TIMER.TIMER:elink.:pd.starts or reads a stopwatch.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=TITLE.TITLE:elink.:pd.changes the window title.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=VSCRPUT.VSCRPUT:elink.:pd.displays a vertical
message in color.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
These commands, along with the internal variables and variable functions,
make the enhanced batch file language extremely powerful. Your copy of
&4OS2. includes a sample batch file, in the file :hp1.EXAMPLES.BTM,:ehp1. that
demonstrates some of the things you can do with batch files.
.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=BatchInt.Interrupting a Batch File
:p.
You can usually interrupt a batch file by pressing :hp2.Ctrl-C:ehp2. or
:hp2.Ctrl-Break:ehp2.&per. Whether and when these keystrokes are recognized will
depend on whether the command processor or an application program is running,
how the application (if any) was written, and whether the
:link reftype=hd refid=ON.ON:elink. BREAK command is in use.
:p.
If &4OS2. detects a Ctrl-C or Ctrl-Break (and ON BREAK is not in use), it will
display a prompt, for example&colon.
:xmp.
    Cancel batch job C&colon.\CHARGE.BTM ? (Y/N/A) &colon.
:exmp.:p.
Enter :hp2.N:ehp2. to continue, :hp2.Y:ehp2. to terminate the current batch
file and continue with any batch file which called it, or :hp2.A:ehp2. to end
all batch file processing regardless of the batch file nesting
level. Answering :hp2.Y:ehp2. is similar to the
:link reftype=hd refid=QUIT.QUIT:elink. command; answering :hp2.A:ehp2. is
similar to the :link reftype=hd refid=CANCEL.CANCEL:elink. command.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=AutoBatch.Automatic Batch Files
:p.
&4OS2. supports "automatic" batch files, files that run without your
intervention, as long as the command processor can find them.
:p.
Each time &4OS2. starts as either a primary or a secondary shell, it
looks for an automatic batch file called :hp1.4START.BTM:ehp1.
or :hp1.4START.CMD:ehp1.&per. If the :hp1.4START:ehp1. batch file is not in the
same directory as &4OS2. itself, you should use the
:link reftype=hd refid=StartupOption.Startup Configuration Page:elink.
of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.
or the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_4StartPath.4StartPath:elink. directive in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. to specify its location. :hp1.4START:ehp1. is
optional, so &4OS2. will not display an error message if it cannot find the
file.
:p.
:hp1.4START:ehp1. is a convenient place to change the color or content of
the prompt for each shell, :link reftype=hd refid=LOG.LOG:elink. the start
of a shell, or put other special startup or configuration
commands. :hp1.4START:ehp1. is also a good place to set
:link reftype=hd refid=ALIASES.aliases:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=ENVIRONMENT.environment variables:elink.&per.
:p.
The entire startup command line passed to the command processor is available to :hp1.
4START:ehp1. via
:link reftype=hd refid=BatchParms.batch file parameters:elink.
(%1, %2, etc.). This can be useful if you want to see the command line
passed to a secondary shell by an application. For example, to pause if any
parameters are passed to a secondary shell you could include this command in
:hp1.4START:ehp1. (enter this on one line)&colon.
:xmp.
    if "%1" != "" .and. "%_shell" gt 0 pause Starting shell
    %_shell with parameters [%$]
:exmp.:p.
Whenever a &4OS2. shell ends, it runs an automatic batch file called
:hp1.4EXIT.BTM:ehp1., :hp1.4EXIT.CMD:ehp1.&per. This file, if you use it,
should be in the same directory as your :hp1.4START:ehp1. batch file. Like
:hp1.4START:ehp1., :hp1.4EXIT:ehp1. is optional. It is not necessary in
most circumstances, but it is a convenient place to put commands to save
information such as a history list before a shell ends, or
:link reftype=hd refid=LOG.LOG:elink. the end of the shell.
:p.
:p.
:hp2.Pipes, Transient Sessions, and 4START:ehp2.
:p.
When you set up the 4START file, remember that it is executed
:hp2.every:ehp2. time &4OS2. starts, including when running a :link reftype=hd
refid=Piping.pipe:elink., or a transient copy of the command processor
started with the :hp2./C:ehp2. :link reftype=hd refid=Startup.startup:elink.
option.
:p.
For example, suppose you enter a command line like this, which uses a pipe:
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\data] myprog | sort > out.txt
:exmp.:p.
Normally this command would create the output file
:hp1.C&colon.\DATA\OUT.TXT:ehp1.&per. However, if you have a 4START file which
changes to a different directory, the output file will be written there -- not
in :hp1.C&colon.\DATA:ehp1.&per.
:p.
This is because the command processor starts a second copy of itself to run
the commands on the right hand side of the pipe, and that new copy runs
4START before processing the commands from the pipe. If 4START changes
directories, the command from the pipe will be executed in the new directory.
:p.
The same problem can occur if you use a transient session started with /C to
run an individual command, then exit -- the session will execute in the
directory set by 4START, not the directory in which it was originally
started. For example, suppose you set up an OS/2 desktop object with a
command line like this, which starts a transient session:
:xmp.
    Command:        d&colon.\4os2\4os2.exe /c list myfile.txt
    Working Directory:  c&colon.\data
:exmp.:p.
Normally this command would :link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink. the file
:hp1.C&colon.\DATA\MYFILE.TXT:ehp1.&per. However, if 4START changes to a different
directory, the command processor will look for :hp1.MYFILE.TXT:ehp1. there
-- not in :hp1.C&colon.\DATA:ehp1.&per.
:p.
Similarly, any changes to environment variables or other settings in 4START
will affect all copies of the command processor, including those used for
pipes and transient sessions.
:p.
You can work around these potential problems with the :link reftype=hd
refid=IF.IF:elink. or :link reftype=hd refid=IFF.IFF:elink. command and
the internal variables :link reftype=hd refid=_PIPE._PIPE:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=_TRANSIENT._TRANSIENT:elink.&per. For example, to skip
all 4START processing when running in a pipe or transient session, you could
use a command like this at the beginning of 4START:
:xmp.
    if %_pipe != 0 .or. %_transient != 0 quit
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=BatchDetect.Detecting &4OS2.
:p.
From a batch file, you can determine if &4OS2. or Take Command is loaded by
testing for the variable function :link reftype=hd refid=_@EVAL.@EVAL:elink.,
with a test like this&colon.
:xmp.
    if "%@eval[2 + 2]%" == "4" echo 4OS2 is loaded!
:exmp.:p.
This test can never succeed in :hp1.CMD.EXE.:ehp1. Other variable functions
could be used for the same purpose.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=BatchAlias.Using Aliases in Batch Files
:p.
One way to simplify batch file programming is to use aliases to hide
unnecessary detail inside a batch file. For example, suppose you want a
batch file to check for certain errors, and display a message and exit if
one is encountered. This example shows one way to do so&colon.
:xmp.
    setlocal
    unalias *
    alias error `echo. &amp. echo ERROR&colon. %$ &amp. goto dispmenu`
    alias fatalerror `echo. &amp. echo FATAL ERROR&colon. %$ &amp. quit`
    alias in `pushd %1 &amp. %2$ &amp. popd`
    if not exist setup.btm fatalerror Missing setup file!
    call setup.btm
    cls
    &colon.dispmenu
    text
          1. Word Processing
          2. Spreadsheet
          3. Communications
          4. Exit
    endtext
    echo.
    inkey Enter your choice&colon. %%userchoice
    switch %userchoice
    case 1
      input Enter the filename&colon. %%fname
      if not exist fname error File does not exist
      in d&colon.\letters c&colon.\wp60\wp.exe
    case 2
      in d&colon.\finance c&colon.\quattro\q.exe
    case 3
      in d&colon.\comm c&colon.\comsw\pcplus.exe
    case 4
      goto done
    default
      error Invalid choice, try again
    endswitch
    goto dispmenu
    &colon.done
    endlocal
:exmp.:p.
The first alias, ERROR, simply displays an error message and jumps to the label
DISPMENU to redisplay the menu. The "%$" in the second
:link reftype=hd refid=ECHO.ECHO:elink. command displays all the text passed
to ERROR as the content of the message. The similar FATALERROR alias
displays the message, then exits the batch file.
:p.
The last alias, IN, expects 2 or more command-line arguments. It uses the
first as a new working directory and changes to that directory with a
:link reftype=hd refid=PUSHD.PUSHD:elink. command. The rest of the command
line is interpreted as another command plus possible command line parameters,
which the alias executes. This alias is used here to switch to a directory,
run an application, and switch back. It could also be used from the
command line.
:p.
The following lines print a menu on the screen and then get a keystroke from
the user and store the keystroke in an environment variable called
:hp1.userchoice:ehp1.&per. Then the :link reftype=hd refid=SWITCH.SWITCH:elink.
command is used to test the user's keystroke and decide what action to take.
:p.
There's another side to aliases in batch files. If you're going to
distribute your batch files to others, you need to remember that they may
have aliases defined for the commands you're going to use. For example if
the user has aliased :link reftype=hd refid=CD.CD:elink. to
:link reftype=hd refid=CDD.CDD:elink. and you aren't expecting this, your
file may not work as you intended. There are two ways to address this
problem.
:p.
First, you can use :link reftype=hd refid=SETLOCAL.SETLOCAL:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=ENDLOCAL.ENDLOCAL:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=UNALIAS.UNALIAS:elink. to clear out aliases before
your batch file starts and restore them at the end, as we did in the previous
example. Remember that SETLOCAL and ENDLOCAL will save and restore not only
the aliases but also the environment, the current drive and directory, and
various special characters.
:p.
If this method isn't appropriate or necessary for the batch file you're
working on, you can also use an asterisk [:hp2.*:ehp2.] before the name of
any command. The asterisk means the command that follows it should not be
interpreted as an alias. For example the following command redirects a list
of filenames to the file :hp1.FILELIST:ehp1.&colon.
:xmp.
    dir /b > filelist
:exmp.:p.
However, if the user has redefined :link reftype=hd refid=DIR.DIR:elink.
with an alias this command may not do what you want. To get around this
just use&colon.
:xmp.
    *dir /b > filelist
:exmp.:p.
The same can be done for any command in your batch file. If you use the
asterisk, it will disable alias processing, and the rest of the command will
be processed normally as an internal command, external command, or batch
file. Using an asterisk before a command will work whether or not there is
actually an alias defined with the same name as the command. If there is no
alias with that name, the asterisk will be ignored and the command will be
processed as if the asterisk wasn't there.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=BatchDebug.Debugging Batch Files
:p.
&4OS2. includes a built-in batch file debugger, invoked with
the :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /Y1 command. The debugger
allows you to "single-step" through a batch file line by line, with the file
displayed in a popup window as it executes. You can execute or skip the
current line, continue execution with the debugger turned off, view the
fully-expanded version of the command line, or exit the batch file. The
batch debugger can also pop up a separate window to view current environment
variables or aliases so you can check their values during execution, and can
pop up the :link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink. command to display the
contents of any file.
:p.
To start the debugger, insert a :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink.
/Y1 command at the beginning of the portion of the batch file you want to
debug, and a SETDOS /Y0 command at the end. You can also invoke SETDOS /Y1
from the prompt, but because the debugger is automatically turned off
whenever the command processor returns to the prompt, you must enter the
SETDOS command and the batch file name on the same line, for example&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] setdos /y1 &amp. mybatch.btm
:exmp.:p.
If you use the debugger regularly you may want to define a simple alias to
invoke it, for example&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias trace `setdos /y1 &amp. %$`
:exmp.:p.
This alias simply enables the debugger, then runs whatever command is
passed to it. You can use the alias to debug a batch file with a command
like this&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] trace mybatch.btm
:exmp.:p.
When the debugger is running you can control its behavior with keystrokes.
Debugging continues after each keystroke unless otherwise noted&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=15 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.T:ehp2.(race), :hp2.Enter:ehp2., or :hp2.F8:ehp2.:pd.Execute the
current command. If it calls a subroutine with
:link reftype=hd refid=GOSUB.GOSUB:elink., or another batch file with
:link reftype=hd refid=CALL.CALL:elink., single-step into the called
subroutine or batch file.
:pt.:hp2.S:ehp2.(tep) or :hp2.F10:ehp2.:pd.Execute the current command, but
execute any subroutine or :link reftype=hd refid=CALL.CALL:elink.ed batch
file without single-stepping.
:pt.:hp2.J:ehp2.(ump):pd.Skip the current command and proceed to the next
command.
:pt.:hp2.X :ehp2.(Expand):pd.Display the next command to be executed, after
expansion of aliases and environment variables.
:pt.:hp2.L:ehp2.(ist):pd.Prompt for a filename and then view the file with
the :link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink. command.
:pt.:hp2.V:ehp2.(ariables):pd.Open a popup window to display the current
environment, in alphabetical order.
:pt.:hp2.A:ehp2.(liases):pd.Open a popup window to display the current
aliases, in alphabetical order.
:pt.:hp2.O:ehp2.(ff) or :hp2.Esc:ehp2.:pd.Turn off the debugger and continue
with the remainder of the batch file.
:pt.:hp2.Q:ehp2.(uit):pd.Quit the debugger and the current batch file,
without executing the remainder of the file.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
The debugger highlights each line of the batch file as it is executed. It
executes the commands on the line one at a time, so when a line contains more
than one command, the highlight will not move as each command is
executed. To see the individual commands, use the :hp2.X:ehp2. key to
expand each command before it is executed.
:p.
If you use a "prefix" command like
:link reftype=hd refid=EXCEPT.EXCEPT:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=FOR.FOR:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=GLOBAL.GLOBAL:elink.,
or :link reftype=hd refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink., the prefix command is
considered one command, and each command it invokes is another. For example,
this command line executes four commands -- the
:link reftype=hd refid=FOR.FOR:elink. and three
:link reftype=hd refid=ECHO.ECHO:elink. commands&colon.
:xmp.
    for %x in (a b c) do echo %x
:exmp.:p.
You cannot use the batch debugger with :link reftype=hd
refid=REXX.REXX:elink. files or :link reftype=hd
refid=EXTPROC.EXTPROC:elink. files. It can only be used with normal &4OS2.
batch files.
:p.
The debugger gives you a detailed, step-by-step view of batch file execution,
and will help solve particularly difficult batch file problems. However, in
some cases you will find it easier to diagnose these problems with techniques
that allow you to review what is happening at specific points in the batch
file without stepping through each line individually.
:p.
There are several tricks you can use for this purpose. Probably the simplest
is to turn :link reftype=hd refid=ECHO.ECHO:elink. on at the beginning of the
file while you're testing it, or use
:link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /V2 to force ECHO on even if an
ECHO OFF command is used in the batch file. This will give you a picture of
what is happening as the file is executed, without stopping at each line. It
will make your output look messy of course, so just turn it off once things
are working. You can also turn ECHO on at the beginning of a group of
commands you want to "watch", and off at the end, just by adding ECHO
commands at the appropriate spots in your file.
:p.
If an error occurs in a batch file, the error message will display the name
of the file, the number of the line that contained the error, and the error
itself. For example&colon.
:xmp.
    e&colon.\test.bat [3] Invalid parameter "/d"
:exmp.:p.
tells you that the file :hp1.E&colon.\TEST.BAT:ehp1. contains an error on
line 3. The first line of the batch file is numbered 1.
:p.
Another trick, especially useful in a fast-moving batch file or one where the
screen is cleared before you can read messages, is to insert
:link reftype=hd refid=PAUSE.PAUSE:elink. commands wherever you need them in
order to be able to watch what's happening. You can also use an
:link reftype=hd refid=ON.ON:elink. ERRORMSG command to pause if an error
occurs, then continue with the rest of the file (the first command below),
or to quit if an error occurs (the second command)&colon.
:xmp.
    on errormsg pause
    on errormsg quit
:exmp.:p.
If you can't figure out how your aliases and variables are expanded, try
turning :link reftype=hd refid=LOG.LOG:elink. on at the start of the batch
file. LOG keeps track of all commands after alias and variable expansion
are completed, and gives you a record in a file that you can examine after
the batch file is done. You must use a standard LOG command; LOG /H
(the history log) does not work in batch files.
:p.
You may also want to consider using
:link reftype=hd refid=Redirection.redirection:elink. to capture your batch
file output. Simply type the batch file name followed by the redirection
symbols, for example&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] mybatch >&amp. testout
:exmp.:p.
This records all batch file output, including error messages, in the file
:hp1.TESTOUT:ehp1., so you can go back and examine it. If you have
:link reftype=hd refid=ECHO.ECHO:elink. ON in the batch file you'll get the
batch commands intermingled with the output, which can provide a very useful
trace of what's happening. Of course, output from full-screen commands and
programs that don't write to the standard output devices can't be recorded,
but you can still gain a lot of useful information if your batch file
produces any output.
:p.
If you're using :link reftype=hd refid=Redirection.redirection:elink. to see
the output, remember that any prompts for input will probably go to the
output file and not to the screen, so you need to know in advance the
sequence of keystrokes required to get through the entire batch file, and
enter them by hand or with KEYSTACK. You can also use the
:link reftype=hd refid=TEE.TEE:elink. command to both view the output while
the batch file is running and save it in a file for later examination.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=BatchString.Batch File String Processing
:p.
As you gain experience with batch files, you're likely to find that you need
to manipulate text strings. You may need to prompt a user for a name or
password, process a list of files, or find a name in a phone list. All of
these are examples of string processing (the manipulation of lines of
readable text).
:p.
&4OS2. include several features that make string processing easier. For
example, you can use the :link reftype=hd refid=INKEY.INKEY:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=INPUT.INPUT:elink. commands for user input;
the :link reftype=hd refid=ECHO.ECHO:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=SCREEN.SCREEN:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=SCRPUT.SCRPUT:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=VSCRPUT.VSCRPUT:elink. commands for output; and the
:link reftype=hd refid=FOR.FOR:elink. command or the
:link reftype=hd refid=_@FILEREAD.@FILEREAD:elink. function to scan through
the lines of a file. In addition,
:link reftype=hd refid=VarFuncs.variable functions:elink. offer a wide range
of string handling capabilities.
:p.
For example, suppose you need a batch file that will prompt a user for a
name, break the name into a first name and a last name, and then run a
hypothetical LOGIN program. LOGIN expects the syntax
:hp2./F&colon.first /L&colon.last:ehp2. with both the first
and last names in upper case and neither name longer than 8 characters. Here
is one way to write such a program&colon.
:xmp.
    @echo off
    setlocal
    unalias *
    input Enter your name (no initials)&colon. %%name

    set first=%@word[0,%name]
    set flen=%@len[%first]
    set last=%@word[1,%name]
    set llen=%@len[%last]

    iff %flen gt 8 .or. %llen gt 8 then
      echo First or last name too long
      quit
    endiff

    login /F&colon.%@upper[%first] /L&colon.%@upper[%last]
    endlocal
:exmp.:p.
The :link reftype=hd refid=SETLOCAL.SETLOCAL:elink. command at the beginning
of this batch file saves the environment and aliases. Then the
:link reftype=hd refid=UNALIAS.UNALIAS:elink. * command removes any existing
aliases so they won't interfere with the behavior of the commands in the remainder of the batch
file. The first block of lines ends with an
:link reftype=hd refid=INPUT.INPUT:elink. command which asks the user
to enter a name. The user's input is stored in the environment variable NAME.
:p.
The second block of lines extracts the user's first and last names from the
NAME variable and calculates the length of each. It stores the first and
last name, along with the length of each, in additional environment
variables. Note that the :link reftype=hd refid=_@WORD.@WORD:elink.
function numbers the first word as 0, not as 1.
:p.
The :link reftype=hd refid=IFF.IFF:elink. command in the third block of
lines tests the length of both the first and last names. If either is
longer than 8 characters, the batch file displays an error message and
ends. Finally, in the last block, the batch file executes
the LOGIN program with the appropriate parameters, then uses the
:link reftype=hd refid=ENDLOCAL.ENDLOCAL:elink. command to restore the
original environment and alias list. At the same time, ENDLOCAL discards
the temporary variables that the batch file used (NAME, FIRST, FLEN, etc.).
:p.
When you're processing strings, you also need to avoid some common
traps. The biggest one is handling special characters.
:p.
Suppose you have a batch file with these two commands, which simply accept a
string and display it&colon.
:xmp.
    input Enter a string&colon. %%str
    echo %str
:exmp.:p.
Those lines look safe, but what happens if the user enters the string
"some > none" (without the quotes). After the string is placed in the
variable STR, the second line becomes:
:xmp.
    echo some > none
:exmp.:p.
The ">" is a :link reftype=hd refid=Redirection.redirection:elink. symbol,
so the line echoes the string "some" and redirects it to a file called
NONE - probably not what you expected. You could try using quotation marks
to avoid this kind of problem
(see :link reftype=hd refid=Quoting.Argument Quoting:elink.), but
that won't quite work. If you use back-quotes (ECHO `%STR`), the command
will echo the four-character string %STR. Environment variable names are not
expanded when they are inside back-quotes.
:p.
If you use double quotes (ECHO "%STR"), the string entered by the user will
be displayed properly, and so will the quotation marks. With double quotes,
the output would look like this&colon.
:xmp.
    "some > none"
:exmp.:p.
As you can imagine, this kind of problem becomes much more difficult if you
try to process text from a file. Special characters in the text can cause
all kinds of confusion in your batch files. Text containing back-quotes,
double quotes, or :link reftype=hd refid=Redirection.redirection:elink.
symbols can be virtually impossible to handle correctly.
:p.
One way to overcome these potential problems is to use the
:link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /X command to temporarily disable
redirection symbols and other special characters. The two-line batch file
above would be a lot more likely to produce the expected results if it were
rewritten this way&colon.
:xmp.
    setdos /x-15678
    input Enter a string&colon. %%str
    echo %str
    setdos /x0
:exmp.:p.
The first line turns off :link reftype=hd refid=Aliases.alias:elink.
processing and disables several special symbols, including the command
separator (see :link reftype=hd refid=MultCmds.Multiple Commands:elink.)
and all :link reftype=hd refid=RedirPipe.redirection:elink.
symbols. Once the string has been processed, the last line re-enables the
features that were turned off in the first line.
:p.
If you need advanced string processing capabilities beyond those provided by
&4OS2. you may want to consider using the
:link reftype=hd refid=REXX.REXX:elink. language. Our products support
external REXX programs for this purpose.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=BatchLineCont.Batch File Line Continuation
:p.
&4OS2. will combine multiple lines in the batch file into a single line for
processing when you include the
:link reftype=hd refid=Escape.escape character:elink.
as the very last character of each line to be combined (except the last).
The default escape character is the caret [:hp2.^:ehp2.]. For example&colon.
:xmp.
    echo The quick brown fox jumped over the lazy ^
    sleeping ^
    dog. > alphabet
:exmp.
:p.
Note that you will often need to prefix the escape character with a space
to get the results you want.
:p.
You cannot use this technique to extend a batch file line beyond the normal
line length limit of 1,023 characters.
:p.
This technique also works for commands entered on the command line.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=BatchComp.Batch File Compression
:p.
You can compress your batch files with a program called
:hp1.BATCOMP.EXE:ehp1., which is distributed with &4OS2.. This program
condenses batch files by about a third and makes them unreadable
with the LIST command and similar utilities. Compressed batch
files run at approximately the same speed as regular .BTM files.
:p.
You may want to consider compressing batch files if you need to
distribute them to others and keep your original code secret or
prevent your users from altering them. You may also want to
consider compressing batch files to save some disk space on the
systems where the compressed files are used.
:p.
The full syntax for the batch compression program is
:xmp.
    BATCOMP [/O] :hp1.input file:ehp1. [:hp1.output file:ehp1. ]
:exmp.:p.
You must specify the full name of the input file, including its
extension, on the BATCOMP command line. If you do not specify the
output file, BATCOMP will use the same base name as the input file
and add a :hp1..BTM:ehp1. extension. BATCOMP will also add a :hp1..BTM:ehp1.
extension if you specify a base name for the output file without an
extension. For example, to compress :hp1.MYBATCH.CMD:ehp1. and save the
result as :hp1.MYBATCH.BTM:ehp1., you can use any of these three commands&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] batcomp mybatch.cmd
    [c&colon.\] batcomp mybatch.cmd mybatch
    [c&colon.\] batcomp mybatch.cmd mybatch.btm
:exmp.:p.
If the output file (:hp1.MYBATCH.BTM:ehp1. in the examples above) already
exists, BATCOMP will prompt you before overwriting the file. You
can disable the prompt by including :hp2./O:ehp2. on the BATCOMP command
line immediately before the input filename. Even if you use the
/O option, BATCOMP will not compress a file into itself.
:p.
JP Software does not provide a decompression utility to decompress
batch files. If you use :hp1.BATCOMP.EXE:ehp1., make sure that you also
keep a copy of the original batch file for future inspection or
modification.
:p.
BATCOMP is a DOS and OS/2 character-mode application designed to run in any
environment where our command processors run. Each of our command
processors includes the same version of :hp1.BATCOMP.EXE:ehp1., and a batch
file compressed with any copy of BATCOMP can be used with any current JP
Software command processor.
:p.
You can adopt one of two strategies for keeping track of your original source
files and compressed batch files. First, you may want to create the source
files with a traditional :hp1..BAT:ehp1. or :hp1..CMD:ehp1. extension and
reserve the :hp1..BTM:ehp1. extension for compressed batch files. The
advantage of this approach is that you can modify and test the uncompressed
versions at any time, although they will run in the slower, traditional mode
unless they begin with a :link reftype=hd refid=LOADBTM.LOADBTM:elink.
command.
:p.
If you prefer, you can use a :hp1..BTM:ehp1. extension for both the source
and compressed files. In this case you will have to use a different
directory or a different base name for each file. For example, you might
use :hp1.SOURCE\MYBATCH.BTM:ehp1. for the source file and
:hp1.COMP\MYBATCH.BTM:ehp1. for the compressed version, or use
:hp1.MYBATCHS.BTM:ehp1. for the source file and :hp1.MYBATCH.BTM:ehp1. for
the compressed file (however, the latter approach may make it more difficult
to keep track of the correspondence between the source file and the
compressed file).
:p.
Each of our command processors includes its own version of
:hp1.BATCOMP.EXE:ehp1., set up to run under the corresponding operating
system. However, the output produced by each program is the same, so a
batch file compressed with any version of BATCOMP can be used with any JP
Software command processor.
:p.
If you plan to distribute batch files to users of different
platforms, see :link reftype=hd
refid=Compat.Special Character Compatibility:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=Compat.Special Character Compatibility
:p.
If you use two or more of our products, or if you want to share
aliases and batch files with users of different products, you need
to be aware of the differences in three important characters&colon. the
Command Separator (see :link reftype=hd refid=MultCmds.Multiple Commands:elink.), the Escape
Character (see :link reftype=hd refid=Escape.Escape Character:elink.), and the Parameter
Character (see :link reftype=hd refid=BatchParms.Batch File Parameters:elink.).
:p.
The default values of each of these characters in each product is
shown in the following chart&colon.
:xmp.
    Product          Separator     Escape     Parameter

    4DOS, Take Command/16    ^       &uarrow.       &amp.

    4NT, 4OS2,           &amp.      ^        $
    Take Command/32,
    Take Command for OS/2
:exmp.:p.
The up-arrow [:hp2.&uarrow.:ehp2.] represents the ASCII Ctrl-X character,
numeric value 24.)
:p.
In your batch files and aliases, and even at the command line, you
can smooth over these differences in three ways&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.*:pd.Select a consistent set of characters from the
:link reftype=hd refid=Options1.Options 1 page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
or with :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=INIConfig.configuration directives:elink. For example, to
set the &4OS2. characters to match 4DOS, use these lines in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&colon.
:xmp.
    CommandSep = ^
    EscapeChar = &uarrow.
    ParameterChar = &amp.
:exmp.:p.
:pt.*:pd.Use internal variables that contain the current special
character, rather than using the character itself (see
:link reftype=hd refid=PLUS.+:elink. and :link reftype=hd refid=EQUALS.=:elink.). For example, this command&colon.
:xmp.
    if "%1" == "" (echo Argument missing! ^ quit)
:exmp.:p.
will only work if the command separator is a caret. However, this version works regardless
of the current command separator&colon.
:xmp.
    if "%1" == "" (echo Argument missing! %+ quit)
:exmp.
:pt.*:pd.In a batch file, use the :link reftype=hd
refid=SETLOCAL.SETLOCAL:elink. command to save the command separator, escape
character, and parameter character when the batch file starts. Then use
:link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. as described above to select the
characters you want to use within the batch file. Use an
:link reftype=hd refid=ENDLOCAL.ENDLOCAL:elink. command at the end of the
batch file to restore the previous settings.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
You can also use the SETDOS command to change special characters on the
command line. However, when setting new special character values on the
command line you must take into account the possibility that one of your new
values will have a current meaning that causes problems with the setting. For
example, this command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] setdos /p&amp.
:exmp.:p.
would :hp2.not:ehp2. set the parameter character to an ampersand
[:hp2.&amp.:ehp2.] in &4OS2. if the standard &4OS2. special characters were
currently in effect. The :hp2.&amp.:ehp2. would be seen as a command
separator, and would terminate the SETDOS command before the parameter
character was set. To work around this, use the escape character variable
:hp2.%=:ehp2. before each setting to ensure that the following character is
not treated with any special meaning.
:p.
For example, the following sequence of commands in a batch file will always
set the special characters correctly to their standard &4OS2. values, no
matter what their current setting, and will restore them when the batch file
is done&colon.
:xmp.
    setlocal
    setdos /c%=^ /e%=&uarrow. /p%=&amp.
    .....
    endlocal
:exmp.:p.
A similar sequence can be used to select the standard &4OS2. and 4NT
characters, regardless of the current settings&colon.
:xmp.
    setlocal
    setdos /c%=&amp. /e%=^ /p%=$
    .....
    endlocal
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=Parsing.Command Parsing
:p.
Whenever you type something at the command line and press the
:hp2.Enter:ehp2. key, or include a command in a batch file, you have given a
command to &4OS2., which must figure out how to execute your command. If you
understand the general process that is used, you will be able to make the
best use of the commands. Understanding these steps can be especially
helpful when working with complex aliases or batch file commands.
:p.
To decide what activity to perform, the command processor goes through
several steps. Before it starts, it writes the entire command line (which
may contain multiple commands) to the history log file if history logging
has been enabled with the :link reftype=hd refid=LOG.LOG:elink. /H
command, and the command did not come from a batch file. Then, if the line
contains multiple commands, the first command is isolated for processing.
:p.
&4OS2. begins by dividing the command into a :hp2.command name:ehp2. and a
:hp2.command tail:ehp2.&per. The command name is the first word in the command;
the tail is everything that follows the command name. For example, in the
command line
:xmp.
    dir *.txt /2/p/v
:exmp.:p.
the command name is "dir", and the command tail is " *.txt /2/p/v".
:p.
Next &4OS2. tries to match the command name against its list of aliases. If it
finds a match between the command name and one of the aliases you've defined,
it replaces the command name with the contents of the alias. (This
substitution is done internally and is not normally visible to you). However,
you can view a command line with aliases expanded by pressing
:hp2.Ctrl-F:ehp2. after entering the command at the prompt.
:p.
If the alias included parameters (%1, %2, etc.), the parameter values are
filled in from the text on the command line, and any parameters used in this
process are removed from the command line. The process of replacing a
command name that refers to an alias with the contents of the alias, and
filling in the alias parameters, is called :hp2.alias expansion:ehp2.&per.
:p.
This expansion of an alias creates a new command name&colon. the first word
of the alias. This new command name is again tested against the list of
aliases, and if a match is found the contents of the new alias is expanded
just like the first alias. This process, called :hp2.nested alias
expansion:ehp2., continues until the command name no longer refers to an
alias.
:p.
Once it has finished with the aliases, &4OS2. next tries to match the command
name with its list of internal commands. If it is unsuccessful, the command
processor knows that it will have to search for a batch file or external
program to execute your command.
:p.
The next step is to locate any batch file or alias parameters, environment
variables, internal variables, or variable functions in the command, and
replace each one with its value. This process is called :hp2.variable
expansion:ehp2.&per.
:p.
The variable expansion process is modified for certain internal commands,
like :link reftype=hd refid=EXCEPT.EXCEPT:elink., :link reftype=hd
refid=IF.IF:elink., and :link reftype=hd refid=GLOBAL.GLOBAL:elink.&per. These
commands are always followed by another command, so variable expansion takes
place separately for the original command and the command that follows it.
:p.
Once all of the aliases and environment variables have been expanded, &4OS2.
will echo the complete command to the screen (if command-line echo has been
enabled) and write it to the log file (if command logging has been turned on).
:p.
Before it can actually execute your command, the command processor must scan
the command tail to see if it includes redirection or piping. If so, the
proper internal switches are set to send output to an alternate device or to
a file, instead of to the screen. A second process is started at this
point, if necessary, to receive any piped output.
:p.
Finally, it is time to execute the command. If the command name matches an
internal command, &4OS2. will perform the activities you have
requested. Otherwise, the command processor searches for an executable
(:hp1..COM:ehp1. or :hp1..EXE:ehp1.) file, a batch file, or a file with an
executable extension that matches the command name.
:p.
Once the internal command or external program has terminated, the command
processor saves the result or exit code that the command generated, cleans up
any redirection that you specified, and then returns to the original command
line to retrieve the next command. When all of the commands in a command
line are finished, the next line is read from the current batch file, or if
no batch file is active, the prompt is displayed.
:p.
You can disable and re-enable several parts of command parsing (for example
alias expansion, variable expansion, and redirection) with the :link
reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /X command.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=Quoting.Argument Quoting
:p.
As it parses the command line, &4OS2. looks for the ampersand [:hp2.&amp.:ehp2.] command
separator, conditional commands (:hp2.&splitvbar.&splitvbar.:ehp2. or
:hp2.&amp.&amp.:ehp2.), white space (spaces, tabs, and commas), percent
signs [:hp2.%:ehp2.] which indicate variables to be expanded, and
redirection and piping characters (:hp2.>:ehp2., :hp2.<:ehp2., or
:hp2.&splitvbar.:ehp2.).
:p.
Normally, these special characters cannot be passed to a command as
part of an argument. However, you can include any of the special
characters in an argument by enclosing the entire argument in single back
quotes [:hp2.`:ehp2.] or double quotes [:hp2.":ehp2.]. Although both
back quotes and double quotes will let you build arguments that include
special characters, they do not work the same way.
:p.
No alias or variable expansion is performed on an argument enclosed
in back quotes. Redirection symbols inside the back quotes are
ignored. The back quotes are removed from the command line before
the command is executed.
:p.
No alias expansion is performed on expressions enclosed in double
quotes. Redirection symbols inside double quotes are ignored.
However, variable expansion :hp2.is:ehp2. performed on expressions inside
double quotes. The double quotes themselves will be passed to the
command as part of the argument.
:p.
For example, suppose you have a batch file :hp1.CHKNAME.BTM:ehp1. which
expects a name as its first parameter (%1). Normally the name is a
single word. If you need to pass a two-word name with a space in
it to this batch file you could use the command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] chkname `MY NAME`
:exmp.:p.
Inside the batch file, %1 will have the value MY NAME, including
the space. The back quotes caused &4OS2. to pass the string to the
batch file as a single argument. The quotes keep characters together and
reduce the number of arguments in the line.
:p.
For a more complex example, suppose the batch file :hp1.QUOTES.BAT:ehp1.
contains the following commands&colon.
:xmp.
    @echo off
    echo Arg1 = %1
    echo Arg2 = %2
    echo Arg3 = %3
:exmp.:p.
and that the environment variable FORVAR has been defined with this
command&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] set FORVAR=for
:exmp.:p.
Now, if you enter the command
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] quotes `Now is the time %%forvar` all good
:exmp.:p.
the output from :hp1.QUOTES.BAT:ehp1. will look like this&colon.
:xmp.
    Arg1 = Now is the time %forvar
    Arg2 = all
    Arg3 = good
:exmp.:p.
But if you enter the command
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] quotes "Now is the time %%forvar" all good
:exmp.:p.
the output from :hp1.QUOTES.BAT:ehp1. will look like this&colon.
:xmp.
    Arg1 = "Now is the time for"
    Arg2 = all
    Arg3 = good
:exmp.:p.
Notice that in both cases, the quotes keep characters together and reduce the
number of arguments in the line.
:p.
The following example has 7 command-line arguments, while the examples above
only have 3&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] quotes Now is the time %%forvar all good
:exmp.:p.
(The double percent signs are needed in each case because the argument is
parsed twice, once when passed to the batch file and again in the ECHO
command.)
:p.
When an alias is defined in a batch file or from the command line,
its argument can be enclosed in back quotes to prevent the
expansion of replaceable parameters, variables, and multiple
commands until the alias is invoked. See :link reftype=hd
refid=ALIAS.ALIAS:elink. for details.
:p.
You can disable and re-enable back quotes and double quotes with
the :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /X command.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=REXX.REXX Support
:p.
REXX is a a powerful file and text processing language developed by
IBM, and available on many PC and other platforms. REXX is an ideal
extension to the &4OS2. batch language, especially if you need advanced
string processing capabilities.
:p.
The REXX language is not built into &4OS2.. REXX language support is provided
in OS/2 2.0 and above, and you can also purchase add-on REXX software such
as Enterprise Alternatives' Enterprise REXX, available for Windows 3.x,
Windows 95, and Windows NT; or Quercus's Personal REXX, available for DOS,
OS/2, Windows 3.x, Windows 95, and Windows NT. (If you want to learn about
or purchase one of these REXX packages, contact JP Software's sales
department for more information.)
:p.
REXX programs are stored in :hp1..CMD:ehp1. files. &4OS2. checks to see if
the first two characters on the first line of a :hp1..CMD:ehp1. file are
[:hp2./*:ehp2.], the beginning of a REXX comment. If so, it passes the
file to OS/2's built-in REXX facility for processing. If Personal
REXX for OS/2 is installed, it automatically replaces OS/2's built-in
REXX, and handles all REXX commands passed by &4OS2..
:p.
Both Personal REXX and OS/2's built-in REXX extend the interface
between REXX and &4OS2. by allowing you to invoke &4OS2. commands from within a
REXX program.
:p.
When you send a command from a REXX program back to the command processor to
be executed (for example, if you execute a :link reftype=hd
refid=DIR.DIR:elink. command within a REXX script), the REXX software must
use the correctaddre for the command processor. In most cases it is best to
use the default address of :hp2.CMD:ehp2., which is set up automatically by
&4OS2.. If you choose to use an explicit address via the REXX ADDRESS
command, you can use either :hp2.CMD:ehp2. or :hp2.&4OS2.:ehp2.&per.
:p.
For details on communication between REXX and the command processor, or for
more information on any aspect of REXX, see your REXX documentation.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=EXTPROC.EXTPROC Support
:p.
For compatibility with :hp1.CMD.EXE:ehp1., &4OS2. offers an external
processor (EXTPROC) option for batch files that lets you define an external
program to process a particular :hp1..CMD:ehp1. file. To identify a
:hp1..CMD:ehp1. file to be used with an external processor, place the
string "EXTPROC" as the first word on the first line of the file, followed
by the name of the external program that should be called. &4OS2. will start
the program and pass it the name of the :hp1..CMD:ehp1. file and any
command-line arguments that were entered.
:p.
For example, suppose :hp1.GETDATA.CMD:ehp1. contains the following lines&colon.
:xmp.
    EXTPROC D&colon.\DATAACQ\DATALOAD.EXE
    OPEN PORT1
    READ 4000
    DISKWRITE D&colon.\DATAACQ\PORT1\RAW
:exmp.:p.
Then if you entered the command&colon.
:xmp.
    [d&colon.\dataacq] getdata /p17
:exmp.:p.
&4OS2. would read the :hp1.GETDATA.CMD:ehp1. file, determine that it began
with an EXTPROC command, read the name of the processor program,
and then execute the command&colon.
:xmp.
    D&colon.\DATAACQ\DATALOAD.EXE D&colon.\DATAACQ\GETDATA.CMD /p17
:exmp.:p.
The hypothetical :hp1.DATALOAD.EXE:ehp1. program would then be responsible
for reopening the :hp1.GETDATA.CMD:ehp1. file, ignoring the EXTPROC line
at the start, and interpreting the other instructions in the file.
It would also have to respond appropriately to the command-line
parameter entered (/p17).
:p.
.* 2013-09-19 SHL #!
If :link reftype=hd refid=INI_UnixPaths.UnixPaths:elink. are enabled, you can use #! as an alias for EXTPROC.
:p.
For example&colon.
:xmp.
    #!perl
    print "hello world";
:exmp.:p.
Do not try to use &4OS2. or Take Command as the external processor named on the
EXTPROC line in the :hp1..CMD:ehp1. file. It will interpret the EXTPROC
line as a command to re-open themselves. The result will be an
infinite loop that will continue until the computer runs out of
resources and locks up.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h1 name=Environment.Environment Variables and Functions
:p.
The :hp2.environment:ehp2. is a collection of information about your
computer that every program receives. Each entry in the
environment consists of a variable name, followed by an equal sign
and a string of text. You can automatically substitute the text
for the variable name in any command. To create the substitution,
include a percent sign [:hp2.%:ehp2.] and a variable name on the command
line or in an alias or batch file.
:p.
The following environment variables have special meanings in &4OS2.&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=CDPATH.CDPATH:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=CMDLINE.CMDLINE:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=COLORDIR_Var.COLORDIR:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=COMSPEC.COMSPEC:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=FILECOMPLETION.FILECOMPLETION:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=PATH_Var.PATH:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=PATHEXT.PATHEXT:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=PROMPT_Var.PROMPT:elink.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
&4OS2. also supports two special types of
variables. :link reftype=hd refid=IntVars.Internal variables:elink.
are similar to environment variables, but are
stored internally within &4OS2., and are not visible in the
environment. They provide information about your system for use in
batch files and aliases. :link reftype=hd refid=VarFuncs.Variable
functions:elink. are referenced like environment variables, but perform
additional functions like file handling, string manipulation and arithmetic
calculations.
:p.
In &4OS2. the size of the environment is set automatically, and increased as
needed when you add variables.
:p.
The :link reftype=hd refid=SET.SET:elink. command is used to create environment variables.
For example, you can create a variable named BACKUP like this&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] set BACKUP=*.bak;*.bk!;*.bk
:exmp.:p.
If you then type
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] del %BACKUP
:exmp.:p.
it is equivalent to the following command&colon.
:xmp.
    del *.bak;*.bk!;*.bk
:exmp.:p.
Environment variable names may contain any alphabetic or numeric characters,
the underscore character [:hp2._:ehp2.], and the
dollar sign [:hp2.$:ehp2.]. You can force acceptance of other characters
by including the full variable name in square brackets, like this&colon.
:hp2.%[AB##2]:ehp2.&per. You can also "nest" environment variables using
square brackets. For example :hp2.%[%var1]:ehp2. means "the contents of
the variable whose name is stored in VAR1". A variable referenced
with this technique cannot contain more than 255 characters of
information. Nested variable expansion can be disabled with the
:link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /X command.
:p.
Environment variables may contain
:link reftype=hd refid=ALIASES.alias:elink. names. The command
processor will substitute the variable value for the name, then check for any
alias name which may have been included within the variable's value. For
example, the following commands would generate a 2-column directory of
the :hp1..TXT:ehp1. files&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias d2 dir /2
    [c&colon.\] set cmd=d2
    [c&colon.\] %cmd *.txt
:exmp.:p.
The trailing percent sign that was traditionally required for
environment variable names is not usually required in &4OS2., which
accept any character that cannot be part of a variable name (including a
space) as the terminator. However, the trailing percent can be used to
maintain compatibility.
:p.
The trailing percent sign :hp2.is:ehp2. needed if you want to join two
variable values. The following examples show the possible
interactions between variables and literal strings. First, create
two environment variables called ONE and TWO this way&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] set ONE=abcd
    [c&colon.\] set TWO=efgh
:exmp.:p.
Now the following combinations produce the output text shown&colon.
:xmp.
    %ONE%TWO        abcdTWO   ("%ONE%" + "TWO")
    %ONE%TWO%       abcdTWO   ("%ONE%" + "TWO%")
    %ONE%%TWO       abcdefgh  ("%ONE%" + "%TWO")
    %ONE%%TWO%      abcdefgh  ("%ONE%" + "%TWO%")
    %ONE%[TWO]      abcd[TWO] ("%ONE%" + "[TWO]")
    %ONE%[TWO]%     abcd[TWO] ("%ONE%" + "[TWO]%")
    %[ONE]%TWO      abcdefgh  ("%[ONE]" + "%TWO")
    %[ONE]%TWO%     abcdefgh  ("%[ONE]" + "%TWO%")
:exmp.:p.
If you want to pass a percent sign to a command, or a string which
includes a percent sign, you must use two percent signs in a row.
Otherwise, the single percent sign will be seen as the beginning of
a variable name and will not be passed on to the command. For
example, to display the string "We're with you 100%" you would use
the command&colon.
:xmp.
    echo We're with you 100%%
:exmp.:p.
You can also use back quotes around the text, rather than a double
percent sign. See :link reftype=hd refid=Quoting.Argument Quoting:elink.
for details.

