:hp2.Additional Notes:ehp2.
:p.
These internal variables are often used in batch files and aliases to examine
system resources and adjust to the current computer settings. You can
examine the contents of any internal variable (except
%:link reftype=hd refid=EQUALS.=:elink. and
%:link reftype=hd refid=PLUS.+:elink.) from the command line
with a command like this&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] echo %variablename
:exmp.:p.
On disk volumes which do not support long filenames, variables which return a
path or filename will return their result in upper or lower case depending
on the value of the :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /U switch
or the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_UpperCase.UpperCase:elink. directive in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. On volumes which do support long filenames,
these variables will return names as they are stored on the disk and no case
shifting will be performed. Returned filename values which include long
filenames are :hp2.not:ehp2. quoted automatically; you must add
quotes yourself if they are required for your use of the variable value (see
:link reftype=hd refid=Quoting.Argument Quoting:elink.).
:p.
Some variables return values based on information provided by your operating
system. These variables will only return correct information if the operating
system provides it. For example, _APMBATT will not return accurate results if
your operating system and Advanced Power Management drivers do not provide
correct information on battery status to the command processor.
:p.
:p.
:hp2.Examples:ehp2.
:p.
You can use these variables in a wide variety of ways depending upon your
needs. Here are just a few examples. For additional examples, see the
:hp1.EXAMPLES.BTM:ehp1. file which came with &4OS2..
:p.
Some of these examples rely on the :link reftype=hd refid=IF.IF:elink.
and :link reftype=hd refid=IFF.IFF:elink. commands to test the value of
a variable and perform different actions based on that value.
:p.
In a batch file, set the color based on the video card type&colon.
:xmp.
    iff "%_video"=="mono" then
      color bright white on black
    else
      color bright white on blue
    endiff
:exmp.:p.
Store the current date and time in a file, then save the output of
a DIR command in the same file&colon.
:xmp.
    echo Directory as of %_date %_time > dirsave
    dir >> dirsave
:exmp.:p.
Set up a prompt for the primary shell which displays the time and
current directory, and a different one for secondary shells which
includes the shell level rather than the time (see
:link reftype=hd refid=PROMPT.PROMPT:elink. for details about setting the prompt). Also set
different background colors for the two shells, without changing
the foreground color. You might use a sequence like this in your
:hp1.4START:ehp1. file (see :link reftype=hd refid=AutoBatch.Automatic Batch Files:elink.)&colon.
:xmp.
    iff %_shell==0 then
      prompt $t $p$g
      color %_fg on blue
    else
      prompt [$z] $p$g
      color %_fg on cyan
    endiff
:exmp.
.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_QMARK.?
:p.
:hp2.?:ehp2. contains the exit code of the last external command. Many
programs return a "0" to indicate success and a non-zero value to
signal an error. However, not all programs return an exit code. If no
explicit exit code is returned, the value of :hp2.%?:ehp2. is undefined.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=__QMARK._?
:p.
:hp2._?:ehp2. contains the exit code of the last internal command. It is
set to "0" if the command was successful, "1" if a usage error
occurred, "2" if another command processor error or an operating
system error occurred, or "3" if the command was interrupted by
:hp2.Ctrl-C:ehp2. or :hp2.Ctrl-Break:ehp2.&per. You must use or save this value
immediately, because it is set by every internal command.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=EQUALS.=
:p.
:hp2.=:ehp2. returns the current :link reftype=hd refid=Escape.escape character:elink.&per.
Use this variable,
instead of the actual escape character, if you want your batch
files and aliases to work regardless of how the escape character is
defined. For example, if the escape character is a caret [:hp2.^:ehp2.]
(the default in &4OS2.) both of the commands below will
send a form feed to the printer. However, if the escape character
has been changed, the first command will send the string "^f" to
the printer, while the second command will continue to work as
intended.
:xmp.
    echos ^f > prn
    echos %=f > prn
:exmp.
.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=PLUS.+
:p.
:hp2.+:ehp2. returns the current command separator. Use this variable,
instead of the actual command separator, if you want your batch
files and aliases to work regardless of how the command separator
is defined. For example, if the command separator is an ampersand
[:hp2.&amp.:ehp2.] (the default in &4OS2.) both of the commands
below will display "Hello" on one line and "world" on the next.
However, if the command separator has been changed the first
command will display "Hello &amp. echo world", while the second command
will continue to work as intended.
:xmp.
    echo Hello &amp. echo world
    echo Hello %+ echo world
:exmp.
.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_4VER._4VER
:p.
:hp2._4VER:ehp2. is the current &4OS2. version (for example, "&4ver.").
The current decimal character is used to separate the major and minor version
numbers (see :link reftype=hd refid=INI_DecimalChar.DecimalChar:elink.) for details.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_ANSI._ANSI
:p.
:hp2._ANSI:ehp2. is always "1" in &4OS2.. (&4OS2. enables OS/2's ANSI support,
and assumes that it remains enabled.)

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_APMAC._APMAC
:p.
:hp2._APMAC:ehp2. is the Advanced Power Management AC line status ("on-line",
"off-line", or "unknown"). An empty string is returned if APM is not
installed on your system.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_APMBATT._APMBATT
:p.
:hp2._APMBATT:ehp2. is the Advanced Power Management battery status ("high",
"low", "critical", "charging", or "unknown"). An empty string is
returned if APM is not installed.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------
:h3 name=_APMLIFE._APMLIFE
:p.
:hp2._APMLIFE:ehp2. is the Advanced Power Management remaining battery life
(0 - 100 or "unknown"). An empty string is returned if APM is not installed.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_BATCH._BATCH
:p.
:hp2._BATCH:ehp2. is the current batch nesting level. It is "0" if no
batch file is currently being processed.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_BATCHLINE._BATCHLINE
:p.
:hp2._BATCHLINE:ehp2. is the current line number in the current batch file. It is "-1"
if no batch file is currently being processed.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_BATCHNAME._BATCHNAME
:p.
:hp2._BATCHNAME:ehp2. is the full path and filename of the current batch
file. It is an empty string if no batch file is currently being processed.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_BG._BG
:p.
:hp2._BG:ehp2. is a string containing the first three characters of the
screen background color at the current cursor location (for
example, "Bla").

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_BOOT._BOOT
:p.
:hp2._BOOT:ehp2. is the boot drive letter, without a colon.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_CI._CI
:p.
:hp2._CI:ehp2. is the insert-mode cursor shape, as a percentage (see
:link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /S and the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_CursorIns.CursorIns:elink. directive).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_CMDPROC._CMDPROC
:p.
:hp2._CMDPROC:ehp2. is the name of the current command processor. Each JP
Software command processor returns a different value, as follows:
:lm margin=8.:parml tsize=32 compact break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.Product:ehp2.:pd.:hp2.Returns:ehp2.
.br
:pt.4DOS:pd."4DOS"
:pt.4OS2:pd."4OS2"
:pt.4NT:pd."4NT"
:pt.Take Command/16:pd."TCMD"
:pt.Take Command/32:pd."TCMD32"
:pt.Take Command for OS/2:pd."TCMDOS2"
:eparml.
:lm margin=1.
:p.
This variable is useful if you have batch files running in more than one
environment, and need to take different actions depending upon the underlying
command processor. If you also need to determine the operating system, see
:link reftype=hd refid=_DOS._DOS:elink.&per.
.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_CO._CO
:p.
:hp2._CO:ehp2. is the overstrike-mode cursor shape, as a percentage (see
:link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /S and the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_CursorOver.CursorOver:elink. directive).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_CODEPAGE._CODEPAGE
:p.
:hp2._CODEPAGE:ehp2. is the current code page number (see
:link reftype=hd refid=CHCP.CHCP:elink.).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_COLUMN._COLUMN
:p.
:hp2._COLUMN:ehp2. is the current cursor column (for example, "0" for the
left side of the screen).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_COLUMNS._COLUMNS
:p.
:hp2._COLUMNS:ehp2. is the current number of screen columns (for example,
"80").

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_COUNTRY._COUNTRY
:p.
:hp2._COUNTRY:ehp2. is the current country code.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_CPU._CPU
:p.
:hp2._CPU:ehp2. is the CPU type&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.86:pd.8086 and 8088
:pt.186:pd.80186 and 80188
:pt.200:pd.NEC V20 and V30
:pt.286:pd.80286
:pt.386:pd.i386
:pt.486:pd.i486
:pt.586:pd.Pentium
:pt.686:pd.Pentium Pro
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_CWD._CWD
:p.
:hp2._CWD:ehp2. is the current working directory in the format
:hp1.d&colon.\pathname:ehp1.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_CWDS._CWDS
:p.
:hp2._CWDS:ehp2. has the same value as CWD, except it ends the pathname
with a backslash [:hp2.\:ehp2.].

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_CWP._CWP
:p.
:hp2._CWP:ehp2. is the current working directory in the format
:hp1.\pathname:ehp1.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_CWPS._CWPS
:p.
:hp2._CWPS:ehp2. has the same value as CWP, except it ends the pathname
with a backslash [:hp2.\:ehp2.].

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_DATE._DATE
:p.
:hp2._DATE:ehp2. contains the current system date, in the format mm-dd-yy
(U.S.), dd-mm-yy (Europe), or yy-mm-dd (Japan) or the format set using 
DateFmt= in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. The year for any of the formats may be
changed to 4 digits using
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_Year4Digit.Year4Digit:elink.=Yes in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_DAY._DAY
:p.
:hp2._DAY:ehp2. is the current day of the month (1 to 31).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_DISK._DISK
:p.
:hp2._DISK:ehp2. is the current disk drive, without a colon (for example,
"C").

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_DNAME._DNAME
:p.
:hp2._DNAME:ehp2. is the name of the file used to store file descriptions. It
can be changed with the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_DescriptionName.DescriptionName:elink. directive
in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. or the :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /D
command.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_DOS._DOS
:p.
:hp2._DOS:ehp2. is the operating system and command processor type. Each JP
Software command processor returns a different value depending upon the
operating system, as follows:
:lm margin=4.:table rules=both frame=box cols='21 3 4 7 7 7 7'.
:row.
:c. :c.DOS :c.OS/2 :c.Windows 3.x :c.Windows 95 :c.Windows 98 :c.Windows NT
:row.
:c.4DOS :c.DOS :c.DOS :c.DOS :c.DOS :c.DOS
:row.
:c.4OS2 :c. :c.OS2
:row.
:c.4NT :c. :c. :c. :c.WIN95C :c.WIN98C :c.NT
:row.
:c.Take Command/16 :c. :c.WIN :c.WIN
:row.
:c.Take Command/32 :c. :c. :c. :c.WIN95 :c.WIN98 :c.WIN32
:row.
:c.Take Command for OS/2 :c. :c.PM
:etable.
:lm margin=1.
.br
This variable is useful if you have batch files running in more than one
environment, and need to take different actions depending upon the underlying
operating environment or command processor. If you want the current command
processor name, use :link reftype=hd refid=_CMDPROC._CMDPROC:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_DOSVER._DOSVER
:p.
:hp2._DOSVER:ehp2. is the current operating system version (for example,
"4.00"). The current decimal character is used to separate the major and
minor version numbers (see :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_DecimalChar.DecimalChar:elink.) for details.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_DOW._DOW
:p.
:hp2._DOW:ehp2. is the first three characters of the current day of the
week ("Mon", "Tue", "Wed", etc.).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_DOWI._DOWI
:p.
:hp2._DOWI:ehp2. is the current day of the week as an integer (1 = Sunday,
2 = Monday, etc.).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_DOY._DOY
:p.
:hp2._DOY:ehp2. is the day of the year (1 to 366).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_FG._FG
:p.
:hp2._FG:ehp2. is a string containing the first three letters of the
screen foreground color at the current cursor position (for
example, "Whi").

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_HLOGFILE._HLOGFILE
:p.
:hp2._HLOGFILE:ehp2. returns the name of the current history log file (or
an empty string if LOG /H is OFF). See :link reftype=hd refid=LOG.LOG:elink.
for information on logging.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_HOUR._HOUR
:p.
:hp2._HOUR:ehp2. is the current hour (0 - 23).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_KBHIT._KBHIT
:p.
:hp2._KBHIT:ehp2. returns 1 if one or more keystrokes are waiting in the keyboard
buffer, or 0 if the keyboard buffer is empty.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_LASTDISK._LASTDISK
:p.
:hp2._LASTDISK:ehp2. is the last valid drive letter, without a colon.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_LOGFILE._LOGFILE
:p.
:hp2._LOGFILE:ehp2. returns the name of the current log file (or an empty
string if LOG is OFF). See :link reftype=hd refid=LOG.LOG:elink.
for information on logging.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_MINUTE._MINUTE
:p.
:hp2._MINUTE:ehp2. is the current minute (0 - 59).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_MONITOR._MONITOR
:p.
:hp2._MONITOR:ehp2. is the monitor type ("mono" or "color").

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_MONTH._MONTH
:p.
:hp2._MONTH:ehp2. is the current month of the year (1 to 12).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_MOUSE._MOUSE
:p.
:hp2._MOUSE:ehp2. always returns "1" in &4OS2..

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_NDP._NDP
:p.
:hp2._NDP:ehp2. is the coprocessor type&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.0:pd.no coprocessor is installed
:pt.87:pd.8087
:pt.287:pd.80287
:pt.387:pd.80387, 80486DX, 80487, Pentium, or Pentium Pro
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_PID._PID
:p.
:hp2._PID:ehp2. is the current process ID number.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_PIPE._PIPE
:p.
:hp2._PIPE:ehp2. returns "1" if the current process is running inside a pipe
or "0" otherwise.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_PPID._PPID
:p.
:hp2._PPID:ehp2. is the process ID number of the parent process.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_PTYPE._PTYPE
:p.
:hp2._PTYPE:ehp2. is the current OS/2 process type&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=8 break=fit.
:pt.AVIO:pd.Character mode, windowed
:pt.DT:pd.Detached (no screen in use)
:pt.FS:pd.Character mode, full-screen
:pt.PM:pd.Presentation Manager
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_ROW._ROW
:p.
:hp2._ROW:ehp2. is the current cursor row (for example, "0" for the top of
the screen).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_ROWS._ROWS
:p.
:hp2._ROWS:ehp2. is the current number of screen rows (for example, "25").

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_SECOND._SECOND
:p.
:hp2._SECOND:ehp2. is the current second (0 - 59).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_SHELL._SHELL
:p.
:hp2._SHELL:ehp2. is the current shell nesting level. The primary shell
is level "0", and each subsequent secondary shell increments the
level by 1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_SID._SID
:p.
:hp2._SID:ehp2. is the session ID number.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_SYSERR._SYSERR
:p.
:hp2._SYSERR:ehp2. is the error code of the last operating system error.
You will need a technical or programmer's manual to understand
these error values.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_TIME._TIME
:p.
:hp2._TIME:ehp2. contains the current system time in the format
hh&colon.mm&colon.ss. The separator character may vary depending upon your
country information.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_TMSMP._TMSMP
:p.
:hp2._TMSMP:ehp2. contains the current system time and date in the format
set using TmSmpFmt= in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. or mm-dd-yy-hh-mm(-ss) (U.S.), 
dd-mm-yy-hh-mm(-ss) (Europe), or yy-mm-dd-hh-mm(-ss) (Japan) or the format 
set using :link reftype=hd refid=INI_DateFmt.DateFmt:elink.= in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. The year for any of the formats may be changed to 4
digits using
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_Year4Digit.Year4Digit:elink.=Yes in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. Time is always hh-mm(-ss) Seconds are omitted if not
included in :link reftype=hd refid=INI_TmSmpFmt.TmSmpFmt:elink.=.
The separator is always "-".

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_TRANSIENT._TRANSIENT
:p.
:hp2._TRANSIENT:ehp2. is "1" if the current shell is transient (started
with a :hp2./C:ehp2., see :link reftype=hd refid=Startup.Starting
&4OS2.:elink. for details), or "0" otherwise.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_VIDEO._VIDEO
:p.
:hp2._VIDEO:ehp2. is the video card type ("mono", "cga", "ega", "vga", "xga",
"8514", or "IA/A" (for the PS/2 Image Adapter/A).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_WINTITLE._WINTITLE
:p.
:hp2._WINTITLE:ehp2. returns the title of the current window.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_XPIXELS._XPIXELS
:p.
:hp2._XPIXELS:ehp2. returns the physical screen horizontal size in pixels.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_YEAR._YEAR
:p.
:hp2._YEAR:ehp2. is the current year (1980 to 2099).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_YPIXELS._YPIXELS
:p.
:hp2._YPIXELS:ehp2. returns the physical screen vertical size in pixels.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=VarFuncs.Variable Functions
:p.
Variable functions are like internal variables, but they take one
or more arguments (which can be environment variables or even other
variable functions) and they return a value.
:p.
The list below gives a one-line description of each function, and a
cross-reference which selects a full screen help topic on that function. A
few of the variables are simple enough that the one-line description is
sufficient, but in most cases you should check for any additional
information in the cross-reference topic if you are not already familiar
with a function. You can also obtain help on any function with a :hp2.HELP
@functionname:ehp2. command at the prompt.
:p.
See the discussion after the function list for some additional information,
and examples of how the functions can be used. For additional examples, see
the :hp1.EXAMPLES.BTM:ehp1. file which came with &4OS2..
:p.
:p.
The variable functions are&colon.
:p.
