:hp2.Additional Notes:ehp2.
:p.
Like all environment variables, these variable functions must be
preceded by a percent sign (%@EVAL, %@LEN, etc.). All variable functions
must have square brackets enclosing their argument(s). The argument(s) to a
variable function cannot exceed 255 characters in length for all arguments
taken as a group.
:p.
:p.
:hp2.Specific Functions and Arguments:ehp2.
:p.
Some variable functions, like @DISKFREE, are shown with ":hp2.b&splitvbar.k&splitvbar.m:ehp2."
as one of their arguments. Those functions return a number of
bytes, kilobytes, or megabytes based on the ":hp2.b&splitvbar.k&splitvbar.m:ehp2." argument&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.b:ehp2.:pd.return the number of bytes
:pt.:hp2.K:ehp2.:pd.return the number of kilobytes (bytes / 1,024)
:pt.:hp2.k:ehp2.:pd.return the number of thousands of bytes (bytes / 1,000)
:pt.:hp2.M:ehp2.:pd.return the number of megabytes (bytes / 1,048,576)
:pt.:hp2.m:ehp2.:pd.return the number of millions of bytes (bytes / 1,000,000)
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
You can include commas (or the "thousands separator" character for your
system) in the results from a ":hp2.b&splitvbar.k&splitvbar.m:ehp2." function
by appending a ":hp2.c:ehp2." to the argument. For example, to add commas
to a ":hp2.b:ehp2." or number of bytes result, enter ":hp2.bc:ehp2." as the
argument. To set the thousands separator see the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ThousandsChar.ThousandsChar:elink. directive.
:p.
Functions which accept a date as an argument use the date format and
separators mandated by your country code (for example dd.mm.yy in Germany, or
yy-mm-dd in Japan) or the date format you specify in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
The year may be entered as a 4-digit or 2-digit value. Two-digit years between
80 and 99 are interpreted as 1980 - 1999; values between 00 and 79 are
interpreted as 2000 - 2079.
:p.
Several functions return filenames or parts of filenames. On volumes supporting
long filenamesthe strings returned by these functions may contain whitespace
or other special characters. To avoid problems which could be caused by
these characters, quote the returned name before you pass it to other
commands, for example (either of these methods would work)&colon.
:xmp.
    set fname="%@findfirst[pro*]"
    echo First PRO file contains&colon.
    type %fname
    .....

    set fname=%@findfirst[pro*]
    echo First PRO file contains&colon.
    type "%fname"
    .....
:exmp.
:p.
If you don't use the quotes in the :link reftype=hd refid=SET.SET:elink. or
:link reftype=hd refid=TYPE.TYPE:elink. command in this example, TYPE
will not interpret any whitespace or special characters in the name properly.
:p.
In variable functions which take a drive letter as an argument,
like :link reftype=hd refid=_@DISKFREE.@DISKFREE:elink. or
:link reftype=hd refid=_@READY.@READY:elink., the argument can be a single
letter or a drive letter followed by a &colon. or a path name.
If the path name does not include a drive specification, the current drive will be checked.
The function will not work properly if you use the drive letter without the colon.
:p.
The :link reftype=hd refid=_@FILEREAD.@FILEREAD:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=_@FILEWRITE.@FILEWRITE:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=_@FILEWRITEB.@FILEWRITEB:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=_@FILESEEK.@FILESEEK:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=_@FILESEEKL.@FILESEEKL:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=_@FILECLOSE.@FILECLOSE:elink. functions
allow you to access files based on their file handle. :hp8.These
functions should only be used with file handles returned by:ehp8.
:link reftype=hd refid=_@FILEOPEN.@FILEOPEN:elink.:hp8.!:ehp8. If you use
them with any other file handle :hp8.you may damage other files:ehp8. opened
by &4OS2. (or, in a secondary shell, the program which started &4OS2.), :hp8.or
hang your system.:ehp8.
:p.
Many functions return values based on information provided by your operating
system. Such functions will only return correct information if the operating
system provides it. For example, :link reftype=hd refid=_@READY.@READY:elink.
will not return accurate results if your operating system does not provide
correct disk drive status information to the command processor.
:p.
:p.
:hp2.Examples:ehp2.
:p.
You can use variable functions in a wide variety of ways depending
on your needs. We've included a few examples below to give you an
idea of what's possible. For additional examples, see the
:hp1.EXAMPLES.BTM:ehp1. file which came with &4OS2..
:p.
To set the prompt to show the amount of free memory (see
:link reftype=hd refid=PROMPT.PROMPT:elink. for details on including variable functions in
your prompt)&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] prompt (%%@dosmem[K]K) $p$g
:exmp.:p.
Set up a simple command-line calculator. The calculator is used
with a command like CALC 3 * (4 + 5)&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] alias calc `echo The answer is&colon. %@eval[%&amp.]`
:exmp.:p.
The following batch file uses variable functions to implement "once
a day" execution of a group of commands. It works by constructing
a 6-digit number "yymmdd" from today's date, and comparing that to
a number of the same type stored in the file :hp1.C&colon.\ONCEADAY.DAT:ehp1.&per.
If today's date is numerically larger than the saved date, and the
time is after 6&colon.00 AM, then the "once a day" commands are run, and
today's date is saved in the file as the new date for comparison.
Otherwise, no action is taken. You can make this file simpler
using the %:link reftype=hd refid=_@DATE.@DATE:elink. and
%:link reftype=hd refid=_@TIME.@TIME:elink. functions instead of using
%:link reftype=hd refid=_@INSTR.@INSTR:elink. to
extract substrings of the %:link reftype=hd refid=_DATE._DATE:elink.
and %:link reftype=hd refid=_TIME._TIME:elink. variables; we used the
approach shown to demonstrate the use of %@INSTR.
:xmp.
    rem Temporary variables used to shorten example lines&colon.
    rem  DD is _date, DY is yymmdd date, TM is _time
    set dd=%_date
    set dy=%@instr[6,2,%dd]%@instr[0,2,%dd]%@instr[3,2,%dd]
    set lastdate=0
    iff exist c&colon.\onceaday.dat then
       set lastdate=%@line[onceaday.dat,0]
    endiff
    iff %dy gt %lastdate then
      set tm=%_time
      iff "%@instr[0,2,%tm]%@instr[3,2,%tm]" gt "0600" then
       rem Commands to be executed once a day go here
       echo %dy > c&colon.\onceaday.dat
      endiff
    endiff
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@ALIAS.@ALIAS
:p.
:hp2.@ALIAS[name]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the contents of the specified alias
as a string, or a null string if the alias doesn't exist. When
manipulating strings returned by @ALIAS you may need to disable
certain special characters with the
:link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /X command.
Otherwise, command separators, redirection characters, and other
similar "punctuation" in the alias may be interpreted as part of
the current command, rather than part of a simple text string.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@ASCII.@ASCII
:p.
:hp2.@ASCII[c]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the numeric value of the specified ASCII
character as a string. For example :hp2.%@ASCII[A]:ehp2. returns 65. You
can put an escape character [:hp2.^:ehp2.] before the actual
character to process. This allows quotes and other special
characters as the argument (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., :hp2.%@ASCII[^`]:ehp2.).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@ATTRIB.@ATTRIB
:p.
:hp2.@ATTRIB[filename, [-nrhsda[,p]]]:ehp2.&colon. Returns a "1" if the
specified file has the matching attribute(s); otherwise returns a "0". The
attributes are&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.N:pd.Normal (no attributes set)
:pt.R:pd.Read-only
:pt.H:pd.Hidden
:pt.S:pd.System
:pt.D:pd.Directory
:pt.A:pd.Archive
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
The attributes (other than :hp2.N:ehp2.) can be combined (for example
:hp2.%@ATTRIB[MYFILE.,HS]:ehp2.). You can prefix an attribute with
"-" to mean "everything except files with this attribute."
:p.
Without the optional :hp2.p:ehp2. as a third argument, :hp2.ATTRIB:ehp2. will
only return a 1 if all of the attributes match. With the :hp2.p:ehp2.,
:hp2.ATTRIB:ehp2. will return a 1 if there is a partial match. For example,
if :hp1.MYFILE.DAT:ehp1. has R, H, and A attributes set:
:xmp.
    %@attrib[myfile.dat,r]  returns 0 because there is not an exact match

    %@attrib[myfile.dat,r,p] returns 1 because there is a partial match
:exmp.:p.
If you do not specify any attributes, :hp2.ATTRIB:ehp2. will return the
attributes of the specified file in the format :hp2.RHSAD:ehp2., rather than
a "0" or "1". Attributes which are not set will be replaced with an
underscore. For example, if :hp1.SECURE.DAT:ehp1. has the read-only, hidden,
and archive attributes set, %:hp2.@ATTRIB[SECURE.DAT ]:ehp2.
would return :hp2.RH_A_:ehp2.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@CDROM.@CDROM
:p.
:hp2.@CDROM[d&colon.]:ehp2.&colon. Returns "1" if the drive is optical (CD,
DVD, BluRay) or "0" otherwise.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@CHAR.@CHAR
:p.
:hp2.@CHAR[n]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the character corresponding to an ASCII
numeric value. For example :hp2.%@CHAR[65]:ehp2. returns A.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@CLIP.@CLIP
:p.
:hp2.@CLIP[n]:ehp2.&colon. Returns line :hp2.n:ehp2. from the
clipboard. The first line is numbered 0. "**EOC**" is returned for all
line numbers beyond the end of the clipboard.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@COMMA.@COMMA
:p.
:hp2.@COMMA[n]:ehp2.&colon. Inserts commas, or the "thousands separator"
character for your system, into a numeric string. To set the thousands
separator see the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_ThousandsChar.ThousandsChar:elink. directive.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@CONVERT.@CONVERT
:p.
:hp2.@CONVERT[input, output, value]:ehp2.&colon. Converts a numeric string
(:hp2.value:ehp2.) from one number base (:hp2.input:ehp2.) to another
(:hp2.output:ehp2.). Valid bases range from 2 to 36. The :hp2.value:ehp2.
must be a positive number between 0 and 2**32-1 (2,147,483,647). No error
is returned if :hp2.value:ehp2. is outside that range. For example, to
convert "1010101" from binary to decimal, use this syntax&colon.
:xmp.
    %@convert[2,10,1010101]
:exmp.:p.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@DATE.@DATE
:p.
:hp2.@DATE[mm-dd-yy]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the number of days since January 1,
1980 for the specified date. DATE uses the date format and
separators mandated by your country code (for example dd.mm.yy in
Germany, or yy-mm-dd in Japan) or the date format you specify in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. using DateFmt=. The year may be entered as a 4-digit or
2-digit value. Two-digit years between 80 and 99 are interpreted as 1980 - 1999; 
values between 00 and 79 are interpreted as 2000 - 2079.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@DAY.@DAY
:p.
:hp2.@DAY[mm-dd-yy]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the numeric day of the month for the
specified date. DATE uses the date format and separators mandated by your
country code (for example dd.mm.yy in Germany, or yy-mm-dd in Japan) the date 
format you specify in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. The year may be entered as a
4-digit or 2-digit value. Two-digit years between 80 and 99 are interpreted as
1980 - 1999; values between 00 and 79 are interpreted as 2000 - 2079.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@DEC.@DEC
:p.
:hp2.@DEC[%var]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the same value as @EVAL[%var - 1]. That
is, it retrieves and decrements the value of a variable. The
variable itself is not changed; to do so, use a command like this&colon.
:xmp.
    set var=%@dec[%var]
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@DESCRIPT.@DESCRIPT
:p.
:hp2.@DESCRIPT[filename]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the file description for the
specified filename (see :link reftype=hd refid=DESCRIBE.DESCRIBE:elink.).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@DEVICE.@DEVICE
:p.
:hp2.@DEVICE[name]:ehp2.&colon. Returns "1" if the specified name is a
character device (such as a printer or serial port), or "0" if not.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@DISKFREE.@DISKFREE
:p.
:hp2.@DISKFREE[d&colon.,b&splitvbar.k&splitvbar.m]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the
amount of free disk space on the specified drive.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@DISKTOTAL.@DISKTOTAL
:p.
:hp2.@DISKTOTAL[d&colon.,b&splitvbar.k&splitvbar.m]:ehp2.&colon. Returns
the total disk space on the specified drive.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@DISKUSED.@DISKUSED
:p.
:hp2.@DISKUSED[d&colon.,b&splitvbar.k&splitvbar.m]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the amount of disk space in use
by files and directories on the specified drive.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@DOSMEM.@DOSMEM
:p.
:hp2.@DOSMEM[b&splitvbar.k&splitvbar.m]:ehp2.&colon. Returns
the size of the largest free memory block (either in physical or virtual
memory).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@DOW.@DOW
:p.
:hp2.@DOW[mm-dd-yy]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the first three characters of the
day of the week for the specified date ("Mon", "Tue", "Wed", etc.).
DATE uses the date format and separators mandated by your
country code (for example dd.mm.yy in Germany, or yy-mm-dd in Japan). The
year can be entered as a 4-digit or 2-digit value. Two-digit years between
80 and 99 are interpreted as 1980 - 1999; values between 00 and 79 are
interpreted as 2000 - 2079.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@DOWI.@DOWI
:p.
:hp2.@DOWI[mm-dd-yy]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the day of the week for the
specified date as an integer (1 = Sunday, 2 = Monday, etc.). DATE uses the
date format and separators mandated by your country code (for example
dd.mm.yy in Germany, or yy-mm-dd in Japan). The year can be entered as a
4-digit or 2-digit value. Two-digit years between 80 and 99 are interpreted
as 1980 - 1999; values between 00 and 79 are interpreted as 2000 - 2079.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@DOY.@DOY
:p.
:hp2.@DOY[mm-dd-yy]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the day of year for the specified
date (1-366). DATE uses the date format and separators mandated by your
country code (for example dd.mm.yy in Germany, or yy-mm-dd in Japan). The
year can be entered as a 4-digit or 2-digit value. Two-digit years between
80 and 99 are interpreted as 1980 - 1999; values between 00 and 79 are
interpreted as 2000 - 2079.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@EAREAD.@EAREAD
:p.
:hp2.@EAREAD[filename, EAname]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the specified extended
attribute (:hp2. EAname:ehp2.) for a file or an empty string if the extended
attribute does not exist. This function can only read EAs stored as text;
it cannot read binary EAs. Wildcards cannot be used in the filename. For
example, to read the .SUBJECT extended attribute for
:hp1.README.TXT:ehp1.&colon.
:xmp.
    set subject=%@earead[readme.txt,.subject]
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@EAWRITE.@EAWRITE
:p.
:hp2.@EAWRITE[filename, EAname, [value]]:ehp2.&colon. Creates or updates the
extended attribute named :hp2.EAname:ehp2. for the specified file. If the
:hp2.value:ehp2. is not included, the extended attribute is deleted. Returns
"0" for success or "-1" for failure. This function can only write EAs stored
as text; it cannot write binary EAs.
:p.
Wildcards cannot be used in the filename and the :hp2.filename:ehp2. must
be in quotes if it contains whitespace or special characters.
:p.
For example, to set the .SUBJECT extended attribute for
:hp1.README.TXT:ehp1. (enter this on one line)&colon.
:xmp.
    if %@eawrite[readme.txt,.subject,Installation notes for
    latest version] != 0 echo EAWRITE failed!
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@EVAL.@EVAL
:p.
:hp2.@EVAL[expression]:ehp2.&colon. Evaluates an arithmetic
expression. @EVAL supports addition (:hp2.+:ehp2.), subtraction
(:hp2.-:ehp2.), multiplication (:hp2.*:ehp2.), division
(:hp2./:ehp2.), integer division (:hp2.\:ehp2., returns the integer
part of the quotient), modulo (:hp2.%%:ehp2.), and integer
exponentiation (:hp2.**:ehp2.). The expression can contain
environment variables and other variable functions. @EVAL also
supports parentheses, commas, and decimals. Parentheses can be
nested. @EVAL will strip leading and trailing zeros from the result.
When evaluating expressions, :hp2.**:ehp2., :hp2.*:ehp2.,
:hp2./:ehp2., and :hp2.%%:ehp2. take precedence over :hp2.+:ehp2. and
:hp2.-:ehp2.&per. For example, 3 + 4 * 2 will be interpreted as 3 + 8,
not as 7 * 2. To change this order of evaluation, use parentheses to
specify the order you want. Also see
:link reftype=hd refid=_@DEC.@DEC:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=_@INC.@INC:elink.
:p.
To ensure that your @EVAL expressions are interpreted correctly, spaces
should be placed on both sides of each operator, for example&colon.
:xmp.
    %@eval[(20 %% 3) + 4]
:exmp.:p.
The maximum precision is 16 digits to the left of the decimal point
and 8 digits to the right of the decimal point. You can alter
the default precision to the right of the decimal point on the
:link reftype=hd refid=Options2.Options 2 page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
or with the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_EvalMax.EvalMax:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_EvalMin.EvalMin:elink. directives in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink., or with the
:link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /F command. You can alter the
decimal character from the
:link reftype=hd refid=Options1.Options 1 page:elink. of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.,
with the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_DecimalChar.DecimalChar:elink. directive, or
the :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /G command.
:p.
You can alter the precision for a single evaluation with the construct
@EVAL[expression=x.y]. The :hp2.x:ehp2. value specifies the minimum decimal
precision (:hp1.i.e.:ehp1., the minimum number of decimal places displayed);
the :hp2.y:ehp2. value sets the maximum decimal precision. You can use
:hp2.=x,y:ehp2. instead of :hp2.=x.y:ehp2. if the comma is your decimal
separator. If :hp2.x:ehp2. is greater than :hp2.y:ehp2., it is
ignored. You can specify either or both arguments, for example&colon.
:xmp.
    @eval[3 / 7=2]      returns 0.42857143
    @eval[3 / 7=.4]     returns 0.4286
    @eval[3 / 6=2.4]    returns 0.50
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@EXEC.@EXEC
:p.
:hp2.@EXEC[[@]command]:ehp2.&colon. Execute the command and return the
numeric exit code. The command can be an alias, internal command, external
command, or :hp1..BTM:ehp1. file, :hp1..BAT:ehp1., or :hp1..CMD:ehp1. file.
:p.
@EXEC is primarily intended for running a program from within the PROMPT. It
is a "back door" entry into command processing and :hp8.should be used with
extreme caution:ehp8.&per. Incorrect or recursive use of @EXEC may hang your
system.
:p.
By default, @EXEC returns the result code from the command; if you
preface the command name with an '@' then @EXEC will return an empty
string.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@EXECSTR.@EXECSTR
:p.
:hp2.@EXECSTR[command]:ehp2.&colon. Runs the specified :hp2.command:ehp2.
and returns the first line written to STDOUT by that :hp2.command:ehp2.&per.
:p.
@EXEC is primarily intended for running a program from within the PROMPT. It
is a "back door" entry into command processing and :hp8.should be used with
extreme caution:ehp8.&per. Incorrect or recursive use of @EXEC may hang your
system.
:p.
@EXECSTR is useful for retrieving a result from an external utility -- for
example, if you have an external utility called :hp1.NETTIME.EXE:ehp1. which
retrieves the time of day from your network server and writes it to standard
output, you could save it in an environment variable using a command like
this&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] set server_time=%@execstr[d&colon.\path\nettime.exe]
:exmp.:p.
If the same utility returned a result properly formatted for the :link
reftype=hd refid=TIME.TIME:elink. command
you could also use it to set the time on your system&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\] time %@execstr[d&colon.\path\nettime.exe]
:exmp.:p.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@EXETYPE.@EXETYPE
:p.
:hp2.@EXETYPE[filename]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the application type as a string&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=14 break=fit.
:pt.DOS:pd.DOS :hp1..COM:ehp1., :hp1..EXE:ehp1., or :hp1..BAT:ehp1.
:pt.AVIO:pd.OS/2 Character mode, windowed
:pt.FS:pd.OS/2 Character mode, full-screen
:pt.PM:pd.OS/2 Presentation Manager
:pt.WIN:pd.Windows 3
:pt.UNKNOWN:pd.Any other file
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@EXPAND.@EXPAND
:p.
:hp2.@EXPAND[filename [,-nrhsda]]&colon.:ehp2. Returns, on a single line,
the names of all files and directories that match the :hp2.filename:ehp2.
specification, which may contain wildcards and include lists. Returns an
empty string if no files match. If the file list is longer than the allowed
command line length, it will be truncated without an error message.
:p.
The second argument, if included, defines the attributes of the files that
will be included in the search. The attributes are&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.N:pd.Normal (no attributes set)
:pt.R:pd.Read-only
:pt.H:pd.Hidden
:pt.S:pd.System
:pt.D:pd.Directory
:pt.A:pd.Archive
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
The attributes (other than :hp2.N:ehp2.) can be combined (for example
:hp2.%@EXPAND[MYFILE,HS]:ehp2.). You can prefix an
attribute with "-" to mean "everything except files with this attribute."

If the attribute argument is not used, hidden files, system files, and
directories will be excluded from the returned list; all other files
which match the :hp2.filename:ehp2. will be included.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@EXT.@EXT
:p.
:hp2.@EXT[filename]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the extension from a
:hp2.filename:ehp2., without a leading period. On HPFS volumes, the extension
may be up to 64 characters in length. On JFS and FAT32 volumes, the extension
may be of any length, though the filename, separator, and extension together may
not exceed 255 bytes (255 UCS-2 characters for FAT32). On FAT16 volumes, the
extension may be up to 3 UCS-2 characters in length.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@FILEAGE.@FILEAGE
:p.
:hp2.@FILEAGE[filename[,acw]]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the date and time of the
file as a single numeric value. The number can be used to compare the
relative ages of two or more files, but can not be used for date and time
calculations as it is not returned in identifiable units.

The optional second argument selects which date field is returned for files
on a volume supporting multiple timestamps: :hp2.a:ehp2. means the last access date, :hp2.c:ehp2.
means the creation date, and :hp2.w:ehp2. means the last modification
(write) date, which is the default.

Also see :link reftype=hd refid=_@MAKEAGE.@MAKEAGE:elink.&per.
.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@FILECLOSE.@FILECLOSE
:p.
:hp2.@FILECLOSE[n]:ehp2.&colon. Closes the file whose handle is
:hp2.n:ehp2.&per. You cannot close handles 0, 1 or 2. Returns "0" if the file
closed OK or "-1" if an error occurred. :hp8.Be sure to read the cautionary
note:ehp8. about file functions under
:link reftype=hd refid=VarFuncs.Variable Functions:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@FILEDATE.@FILEDATE
:p.
:hp2.@FILEDATE[filename[,acw]]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the date a file was last
modified, in the default country format (mm-dd-yy for the US). The optional
second argument selects which date field is returned for files on volumes
supporting multiple timestamps: :hp2.a:ehp2. means the last access date,
:hp2.c:ehp2. means the creation date, and :hp2.w:ehp2. means the last
modification (write) date, which is the default.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@FILENAME.@FILENAME
:p.
:hp2.@FILENAME[filename]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the name and extension of a
file, without a path.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@FILEOPEN.@FILEOPEN
:p.
:hp2.@FILEOPEN[filename, read &splitvbar. write &splitvbar. append, [b &splitvbar. t]]:ehp2.&colon. Opens the file in
the specified mode and returns the file handle as an integer. Returns "-1" if the
file cannot be opened.
:p.
The optional third parameter controls whether the file is opened in binary mode
("b") or text mode ("t"). Text mode (the default) should be used to read text
using :link reftype=hd refid=_@FILEREAD.@FILEREAD:elink. :hp2.without:ehp2. a
"length" parameter, and to write text using :link reftype=hd refid=_@FILEWRITE.@FILEWRITE:elink.&per. Binary
mode should be used to read binary data with @FILEREAD :hp2.with:ehp2. a "length"
parameter, and to write binary data with :link reftype=hd refid=_@FILEWRITEB.@FILEWRITEB:elink.&per.
:p.
:hp8.Be sure to read the cautionary note:ehp8. about file functions under
:link reftype=hd refid=VarFuncs.Variable Functions:elink.&per.
:p.
@FILEOPEN can also open named pipes. The pipe name must begin with
:hp2.\pipe\:ehp2.&per. @FILEOPEN first tries to open an existing pipe; if that
fails it tries to create a new pipe. Pipes are opened in blocking mode,
duplex access, byte-read mode, and inheritable. For more information
on named pipes see your OS/2 documentation.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@FILEREAD.@FILEREAD
:p.
:hp2.@FILEREAD[n [,length]]:ehp2.&colon.
Reads data from the file whose handle is :hp2.n:ehp2.&per. Returns "**EOF**" if
you attempt to read past the end of the file. If :hp2.length:ehp2. is not
specified @FILEREAD will read until the next CR or LF (end of line)
character. If :hp2.length:ehp2. is specified, @FILEREAD will read
:hp2.length:ehp2. bytes regardless of any end of line characters.
:p.
If you plan to read text a line at a time, without using :hp2.length:ehp2.,
you should open the file in text mode. If you plan to read binary data using
:hp2.length:ehp2., you should open the file in binary mode. See :link
reftype=hd refid=_@FILEOPEN.@FILEOPEN:elink.
for details on opening the file in the proper mode.
:p.
Be sure to read the cautionary note about file functions under :link
reftype=hd refid=VarFuncs.Variable Functions:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@FILES.@FILES
:p.
:hp2.@FILES[filename [,-nrhsda]]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the number of files
that match the filename, which may contain wildcards and include
lists. Returns "0" if no files match. The filename must refer to
a single directory; to check several directories, use @FILES once for each
directory, and add the results together with
:link reftype=hd refid=_@EVAL.@EVAL:elink.&per.
:p.
The second argument is a list of file attributes. If it is included, only
those files matching all the specified attributes are counted. The
attributes are&colon.

:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.N:pd.Normal (no attributes set)
:pt.R:pd.Read-only
:pt.H:pd.Hidden
:pt.S:pd.System
:pt.D:pd.Directory
:pt.A:pd.Archive
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br

The attributes (other than :hp2.N:ehp2.) can be combined (for example
:hp2.%@FILES[MYFILE,HS]:ehp2.). You can prefix an attribute with
:hp2.-:ehp2. to mean "everything except files with this attribute."

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@FILESEEK.@FILESEEK
:p.
:hp2.@FILESEEK[n,offset,start]:ehp2.&colon. Moves the file pointer :hp2.offset:ehp2.
bytes in the file whose handle is :hp2.n:ehp2.&per. Returns the new position of
the pointer, in bytes from the start of the file. Set :hp2.start:ehp2. to 0
to seek relative to the beginning of the file, 1 to seek relative
to the current file pointer, or 2 to seek relative to the end of
the file. The offset value may be negative (seek backward),
positive (seek forward), or zero (return current position, but do
not change it). :hp8.Be sure to read the cautionary note:ehp8. about file
functions under :link reftype=hd refid=VarFuncs.Variable Functions:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@FILESEEKL.@FILESEEKL
:p.
:hp2.@FILESEEKL[n,line]:ehp2.&colon. Moves the file pointer to the
specified :hp2.line:ehp2. in the
file whose handle is :hp2.n:ehp2.&per. The first line in the file is numbered
0. Returns the new position of the pointer, in bytes
from the start of the file.:hp8. Be sure to read the cautionary note:ehp8. about file
functions under :link reftype=hd refid=VarFuncs.Variable Functions:elink.&per.
:p.
@FILESEEKL must read each line of the file up to the target line in order to
position the pointer, and will therefore cause significant delays if used in
a long loop or on a large file.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@FILESIZE.@FILESIZE
:p.
:hp2.@FILESIZE[filename,b&splitvbar.k&splitvbar.m[,a]]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the size of a file, or "-1"
if the file does not exist. If the filename includes wildcards or
an include list, returns the combined size of all matching files.
:p.
The optional third argument :hp2.a:ehp2. (allocated), if used, instructs
@FILESIZE to return the amount of space allocated for the file(s) on the
disk, rather than the amount of data in the file. Network drives and
compressed drives may not always report allocated sizes accurately,
depending upon the way the network or disk compression software
is implemented.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@FILETIME.@FILETIME
:p.
:hp2.@FILETIME[filename[,acw]]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the time a file was last
modified, in hh&colon.mm format. The optional second argument selects which
time field is returned for files on a volume supporting multiple timestamps&colon. :hp2.a:ehp2. means
the last access time, :hp2.c:ehp2. means the creation time, and :hp2.w:ehp2.
means the last modification (write) time, which is the default.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@FILEWRITE.@FILEWRITE
:p.
:hp2.@FILEWRITE[n,text]:ehp2.&colon. Writes a line to the file whose handle is
:hp2.n:ehp2.&per. Returns the number of bytes written, or "-1" if an error
occurred. :hp2.n:ehp2. must be a handle returned by :link reftype=hd
refid=_@FILEOPEN.@FILEOPEN:elink.; or 1 (for standard output) or 2 (for
standard error).
:p.
:hp8.Be sure to read the cautionary note:ehp8. about file functions
under :link reftype=hd refid=VarFuncs.Variable Functions:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@FILEWRITEB.@FILEWRITEB
:p.
:hp2.@FILEWRITEB[n,length,string]:ehp2.&colon. Writes the specified number
of bytes from :hp2.string:ehp2. to the file whose handle is :hp2.n:ehp2.&per. Returns the number of
bytes written, or "-1" if an error occurred.
:p.
If you plan to write binary data with @FILEWRITEB, you should open the file in binary
mode (see :link reftype=hd refid=_@FILEOPEN.@FILEOPEN:elink.). If you want to write
text a line at a time you should use :link reftype=hd refid=_@FILEWRITE.@FILEWRITE:elink. instead,
and open the file in text mode.
:p.
:hp8.Be sure to read the cautionary note:ehp8. about file functions under
:link reftype=hd refid=VarFuncs.Variable Functions:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@FINDCLOSE.@FINDCLOSE
:p.
:hp2.@FINDCLOSE[filename]:ehp2.&colon. Signals the end of a :link
reftype=hd refid=_@FINDFIRST.@FINDFIRST:elink. /
:link reftype=hd refid=_@FINDNEXT.@FINDNEXT:elink. sequence. You
:hp2.must:ehp2. use this function to release the directory search handle
used for @FINDFIRST / @FINDNEXT.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@FINDFIRST.@FINDFIRST
:p.
:hp2.@FINDFIRST[filename [,-nrhsda]]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the name of the first
file that matches the filename, which may contain wildcards and "include lists." The
second argument, if included, defines the attributes of the files
that will be included in the search. Returns an empty string if no
files match. The attributes are&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.N:pd.Normal (no attributes set)
:pt.R:pd.Read-only
:pt.H:pd.Hidden
:pt.S:pd.System
:pt.D:pd.Directory
:pt.A:pd.Archive
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
The attributes (other than :hp2.N:ehp2.) can be combined (for example
:hp2.%@FINDFIRST[MYFILE,HS]:ehp2.). You can prefix an attribute
with :hp2.-:ehp2. to mean "everything except files with this attribute."
:p.
@FINDFIRST always skips the "." and ".." entries when processing directory names.
:p.
After @FINDFIRST or the last
:link reftype=hd refid=_@FINDNEXT.@FINDNEXT:elink., you :hp2.must:ehp2. use
:link reftype=hd refid=_@FINDCLOSE.@FINDCLOSE:elink. to avoid running out of
directory search handles.
:p.
See the notes under :link reftype=hd refid=VarFuncs.Variable Functions:elink.
about quoting returned long filenames.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@FINDNEXT.@FINDNEXT
:p.
:hp2.@FINDNEXT[filename [,-nrhsda]]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the name of the
next file that matches the filename passed to :link reftype=hd refid=_@FINDFIRST.@FINDFIRST:elink.&per.
@FINDNEXT should only be used after a successful call to
:link reftype=hd refid=_@FINDFIRST.@FINDFIRST:elink.&per. The first argument is included for compatibility with
previous versions, but is ignored; it can be omitted if the second
argument is not used (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1. %@FINDNEXT[]). The second argument,
if included, defines the attributes of the files that will be included in
the search. Returns an empty string when no more files match. The
attributes are&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.N:pd.Normal (no attributes set)
:pt.R:pd.Read-only
:pt.H:pd.Hidden
:pt.S:pd.System
:pt.D:pd.Directory
:pt.A:pd.Archive
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
The attributes (other than :hp2.N:ehp2.) can be combined (for example
:hp2.%@FINDNEXT[MYFILE,HS]:ehp2.). You can prefix an attribute
with :hp2.-:ehp2. to mean "everything except files with this attribute."
:p.
@FINDNEXT always skips the "." and ".." entries when processing directory
names.
:p.
After :link reftype=hd refid=_@FINDFIRST.@FINDFIRST:elink. or the last
@FINDNEXT, you :hp2.must:ehp2. use
:link reftype=hd refid=_@FINDCLOSE.@FINDCLOSE:elink. to avoid running out of
directory search handles.
:p.
See the notes under :link reftype=hd refid=VarFuncs.Variable Functions:elink.
about quoting returned long filenames.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@FORMAT.@FORMAT
:p.
:hp2.@FORMAT[[-][x][.y],string]:ehp2.&colon. Reformats a string, truncating
it or padding it with spaces as necessary. If you use the minus [-], the
string is left-justified; otherwise, it is right-justified. The
:hp2.x:ehp2. value is the minimum number of characters in the result. The
:hp2.y:ehp2. value is the maximum number of characters in the result. You
can combine the options as necessary. For example&colon.
:xmp.
    %@format[12,JPSoftware]     returns "JPSoftware"
    %@format[.3,JPSoftware]     returns "JPS"
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@FSTYPE.@FSTYPE
:p.
:hp2.@FSTYPE[d&colon.]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the filesystem type for the
specified volume. Examples which @FSTYPE may return are&colon. :hp1.FAT:ehp1.
for a DOS-compatible FAT12 or FAT16 volume, :hp1.FAT32:ehp1. for a 32-bit FAT
volume, :hp1.HPFS:ehp1., :hp1.JFS:ehp1., :hp1.CDFS:ehp1. for a CD filesystem,
or :hp1.UDF:ehp1. for a DVD filesystem. This is not an exhaustive list;
@FSTYPE may return other values for additional filesystems installed with the
IFS= directive in :hp1.CONFIG.SYS:ehp1.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@FULL.@FULL
:p.
:hp2.@FULL[filename]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the fully qualified path and file
name of a file.
:p.
See the notes under :link reftype=hd refid=VarFuncs.Variable Functions:elink.
about quoting returned long filenames.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@IF.@IF
:p.
:hp2.@IF[condition,true,false]:ehp2.&colon. Evaluates the condition and returns a string
based on the result. The condition can include any of the tests allowed in
the :link reftype=hd refid=IF.IF:elink. command. If the condition is true, @IF returns the first result
string; if it is false, @IF returns the second string. For example,
"echo %@IF[2 == 2,Correct!,Oops!]" displays "Correct!"

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@INC.@INC
:p.
:hp2.@INC[%var]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the same value as
%:link reftype=hd refid=_@EVAL.@EVAL:elink.[%var + 1]. That is, it
retrieves and increments the value of a variable. The variable itself is
not changed; to do so, use a command like this&colon.
:xmp.
    set var=%@inc[%var]
:exmp.
.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@INDEX.@INDEX
:p.
:hp2.@INDEX[string1,string2]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the position of string2
within :hp2.string1:ehp2., or "-1" if :hp2.string2:ehp2. is not found. The
first position in :hp2.string1:ehp2. is numbered 0. The comparison is
case-insensitive.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@INSERT.@INSERT
:p.
:hp2.@INSERT[n, string1, string2]:ehp2.&colon. Inserts :hp2.string1:ehp2.
into :hp2.string2:ehp2. starting at position :hp2.n:ehp2.&per. The first
position in the string is postion 0. For example,
:hp2.%@insert[1,arm,wing]:ehp2. returns the string "warming".

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@INSTR.@INSTR
:p.
:hp2.@INSTR[start, length, string]:ehp2.&colon. Returns a substring,
starting at the position :hp2.start:ehp2. and continuing for
:hp2.length:ehp2. characters. If the :hp2.length:ehp2. is omitted, it will
default to the remainder of the :hp2.string:ehp2.&per. If the :hp2.length:ehp2.
is negative, the start is relative to the right side of the
:hp2.string:ehp2.&per. The first character in the :hp2.string:ehp2. is numbered
0; if the :hp2.length:ehp2. is negative, the last character is numbered 0.
:p.
For example, %@INSTR[0,2,%_TIME] gets the current time and extracts the hour;
%@INSTR[1,-2,%_TIME] extracts the seconds. If the :hp2.string:ehp2. includes
commas, it must be quoted with double quotes [:hp2.":ehp2.] or back-quotes
[:hp2.`:ehp2.]. The quotes :hp2.do:ehp2. count in calculating the position
of the substring. :link reftype=hd refid=_@SUBSTR.@SUBSTR:elink. is an older
version of the same function.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@INT.@INT
:p.
:hp2.@INT[n]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the integer part of the number
:hp2.n:ehp2.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@LABEL.@LABEL
:p.
:hp2.@LABEL[d&colon.]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the volume label of the
specified disk drive.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@LEFT.@LEFT
:p.
:hp2.@LEFT[n, string]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the leftmost :hp2.n:ehp2.
characters from the :hp2.string:ehp2.&per. If :hp2.n:ehp2. is greater than the
length of the :hp2.string:ehp2., returns the entire :hp2.string:ehp2.&per. For
example, :hp2.%@left[2,jpsoft]:ehp2. returns the string "jp".

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@LEN.@LEN
:p.
:hp2.@LEN[string]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the length of a :hp2.string:ehp2.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------
:h3 name=_@LINE.@LINE
:p.
:hp2.@LINE[filename,n]:ehp2.&colon. Returns line :hp2.n:ehp2. from the
specified file. The first line in the file is numbered 0. "**EOF**" is
returned for all line numbers beyond the end of the file.
:p.
@LINE works with files having lines of no more than 1023 characters; longer
lines will not be counted accurately.
:p.
The @LINE function must read each line of the file to find the line you
request, and will therefore cause significant delays if used in a long loop
or on a large file. For a more effective method of processing each line of
a file in sequence use the :link reftype=hd refid=FOR.FOR:elink. command, or
:link reftype=hd refid=_@FILEOPEN.@FILEOPEN:elink. and a sequence of
:link reftype=hd refid=_@FILEREAD.@FILEREAD:elink.s.
:p.
You can retrieve input from standard input if you specify CON as the
filename. If you are :link reftype=hd refid=Redirection.redirecting:elink.
input to @LINE using this feature, you must use
:link reftype=hd refid=Grouping.command grouping:elink. or the redirection
will not work properly (you can :link reftype=hd refid=Piping.pipe:elink. to
@LINE without a command group; this restriction applies only to input
redirection). For example&colon.
:xmp.
    (echo %@line[con,0]) < myfile.dat
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@LINES.@LINES
:p.
:hp2.@LINES[filename]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the line number of the last line
in the file, or "-1" if the file is empty. The first line in the file
is numbered 0, so (for example) @LINES will return 0 for a file
containing one line. To get the actual number of lines, use
%@INC[%@LINES[filename]].
:p.
@LINES works with files having lines of no more than 1023 characters; longer
lines will not be counted accurately.
:p.
@LINES must read each line of the file in order to count it, and will
therefore cause significant delays if used in a long loop or on a large file.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@LOWER.@LOWER
:p.
:hp2.@LOWER[string]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the :hp2.string:ehp2. converted to
lower case.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@MAKEAGE.@MAKEAGE
:p.
:hp2.@MAKEAGE[date[,time]]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the date and time (if
included) as a single value in the same format as :link reftype=hd
refid=_@FILEAGE.@FILEAGE:elink.&per. @MAKEAGE can be used to compare the time
stamp of a file with a specific date and time, for example&colon.
:xmp.
    if %@fileage[myfile] lt %@makeage[1/1/85] echo OLD!
:exmp.:p.
The value returned by @MAKEAGE can be used for comparisons, but can not be
used for date and time calculations because it is not in identifiable units.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@MAKEDATE.@MAKEDATE
:p.
:hp2.@MAKEDATE[n]:ehp2.&colon. Returns a date (formatted according to the
current country settings). :hp2.n:ehp2. is the number of days since 1/1/80.
This is the inverse of :link reftype=hd refid=_@DATE.@DATE:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@MAKETIME.@MAKETIME
:p.
:hp2.@MAKETIME[n]:ehp2.&colon. Returns a time (formatted according to the
current country settings). :hp2.n:ehp2. is the number of seconds since
midnight. This is the inverse of :link reftype=hd refid=_@TIME.@TIME:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@MONTH.@MONTH
:p.
:hp2.@MONTH[mm-dd-yy]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the month number for the
specified date (1-12). MONTH uses the date format and separators mandated
by your country code (for example dd.mm.yy in Germany, or yy-mm-dd in Japan).
The year can be entered as a 4-digit or 2-digit value. Two-digit years
between 80 and 99 are interpreted as 1980 - 1999; values between 00 and 79
are interpreted as 2000 - 2079.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@NAME.@NAME
:p.
:hp2.@NAME[filename]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the base name of a file, without
the path or extension.
:p.
See the notes under :link reftype=hd refid=VarFuncs.Variable Functions:elink.
about quoting returned long filenames.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@NUMERIC.@NUMERIC
:p.
:hp2.@NUMERIC[string]:ehp2.&colon. Returns "1" if the argument is composed
entirely of digits (0 to 9), signs (:hp2.+:ehp2. or :hp2.-:ehp2.), and the
thousands and decimal separators. Otherwise, returns "0". If the
:hp2.string:ehp2. begins with a decimal separator it is not considered
numeric unless the next character is a digit, and there are no more decimal
separators within the string. For example, ".07" is numeric, but ".a" and
".07.01" are not.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@PATH.@PATH
:p.
:hp2.@PATH[filename]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the path from a filename, including
the drive letter and a trailing backslash but not including the
base name or extension.
:p.
See the notes under :link reftype=hd refid=VarFuncs.Variable Functions:elink.
about quoting returned long filenames.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@RANDOM.@RANDOM
:p.
:hp2.@RANDOM[min, max]:ehp2.&colon. Returns a "pseudo-random" value between
:hp2.min:ehp2. and :hp2.max:ehp2., inclusive. :hp2.Min:ehp2.,
:hp2.max:ehp2., and the returned value are all integers.
:p.
The random number generator is initialized from the system clock the first
time it is used after the command processor starts, so it will produce a
different sequence of random numbers each time you use it.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@READSCR.@READSCR
:p.
:hp2.@READSCR[row,col,length]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the text displayed on the
screen at the specified location. The upper left corner of the
screen is location 0,0.
:p.
The :hp2.row:ehp2. and :hp2.column:ehp2. can be specified as an offset from
the current cursor location by preceding either value with a [:hp2.+:ehp2.] or
[:hp2.-:ehp2.]. For example,
:xmp.
    %@readscr[-2,+2,10]
:exmp.:p.
returns 10 characters from the screen, starting 2 rows above and 2 columns to
the right of the current cursor position.
:p.
You can also specify the row and column as offsets from the current cursor
position. Begin the value with a plus sign [:hp2.+:ehp2.] to read the
screen the specified number of rows below (or columns to the right of) the
current position, or with a minus sign [:hp2.-:ehp2.] to read the screen
above (or to the left of) the current position.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@READY.@READY
:p.
:hp2.@READY[d&colon.]:ehp2.&colon. Returns "1" if the specified drive is
ready; otherwise returns "0".
:p.
The drive specification can be a single letter or a drive letter followed by
a &colon. or a path name. If the path name does not include a drive specification,
the current drive will be checked.


.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@REMOTE.@REMOTE
:p.
:hp2.@REMOTE[d&colon.]:ehp2.&colon. Returns "1" if the specified drive is a remote
(network) drive; otherwise returns "0".

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@REMOVABLE.@REMOVABLE
:p.
:hp2.@REMOVABLE[d&colon.]:ehp2.&colon. Returns "1" if the specified drive is
removable (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., a floppy disk or removable hard disk);
otherwise returns "0".

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@REPEAT.@REPEAT
:p.
:hp2.@REPEAT[c,n]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the character :hp2.c:ehp2. repeated
:hp2.n:ehp2. times.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@REPLACE.@REPLACE
:p.
:hp2.@REPLACE[string1, string2, text]:ehp2.&colon. Replaces all occurrences
of :hp2.string1:ehp2. in the :hp2.text:ehp2. string with
:hp2.string2:ehp2.&per. For example, :hp2.%@replace[w,ch,warming]:ehp2. returns
the string "charming". The search :hp2.is:ehp2. case-sensitive.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@REXX.@REXX
:p.
:hp2.@REXX[expr]:ehp2.&colon. Calls the REXX interpreter to execute the
:hp2.expr:ehp2.ession. Returns the result string from REXX; if the REXX
expression does not return a string, @REXX returns the REXX numeric result
code. See :link reftype=hd refid=REXX.REXX Support:elink. for more
information.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@RIGHT.@RIGHT
:p.
:hp2.@RIGHT[n,string]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the rightmost :hp2.n:ehp2.
characters from the :hp2.string:ehp2.&per. If :hp2.n:ehp2. is greater than the
length of the :hp2.string:ehp2., returns the entire string. For example,
:hp2.%@right[4,jpsoft]:ehp2. returns the string "soft."

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@SEARCH.@SEARCH
:p.
:hp2.@SEARCH[filename[,path]]:ehp2.&colon. Searches for the
:hp2.filename:ehp2. using the :link reftype=hd refid=PATH_Var.PATH:elink.
environment variable or the specified :hp2.path:ehp2., appending an extension
if one isn't specified.
:p.
@SEARCH returns the fully-expanded name of the file including
drive, path, base name, and extension, or an empty string if a
matching file is not found. If wildcards are used in the filename,
:hp2.@SEARCH:ehp2. will search for the first file that matches the
wildcard specification, and return the drive and path for that file
plus the wildcard filename (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., :hp1.E&colon.\UTIL\*.COM:ehp1.).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@SELECT.@SELECT
:p.
:hp2.@SELECT[filename,top,left,bottom,right,title[,1]]:ehp2.&colon. Pops up
a selection window with the lines from the specified file, allowing you to
display menus or other selection lists from within a batch file. You can
move through the selection window with standard :link reftype=hd
refid=Popup.popup window:elink. navigation keystrokes, including character
matching. @SELECT returns the text of the line the scrollbar is on if you
press :hp2.Enter:ehp2., or an empty string if you press :hp2.Esc:ehp2.&per. The
filename must be in quotes if it contains whitespace or special
characters. The file size is limited only by available memory. To select
from lines passed through input redirection or a pipe, use :hp2.CON:ehp2. as
the filename. If you use the optional :hp2.1:ehp2. argument after the
window title, the list will be sorted alphabetically.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@STRIP.@STRIP
:p.
:hp2.@STRIP[chars,string]:ehp2.&colon. Removes the characters in
:hp2.chars:ehp2. from the :hp2.string:ehp2. and returns the result. For
example, %@STRIP[AaEe,All Good Men] returns "ll Good Mn". The test is case
sensitive. To include a comma in the :hp2.chars:ehp2. string,
enclose the entire first argument in double quotes. @STRIP will remove the
quotes before processing the :hp2.string:ehp2.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@SUBSTR.@SUBSTR
:p.
:hp2.@SUBSTR[string,start,length]:ehp2.&colon. This is an older version of
:link reftype=hd refid=_@INSTR.@INSTR:elink. The :hp2.string:ehp2. parameter
is at the start of the @SUBSTR argument list, and therefore cannot contain
commas (because any commas in the string would be taken as argument
separators). @INSTR, which has the :hp2.string:ehp2. argument last, does not
have this restriction.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@TIME.@TIME
:p.
:hp2.@TIME[hh&colon.mm&colon.ss]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the number of seconds since midnight
for the specified time. The time must be in 24-hour format; "am"
and "pm" cannot be used.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@TIMER.@TIMER
:p.
:hp2.@TIMER[n]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the current split time for a stopwatch started with
the :link reftype=hd refid=TIMER.TIMER:elink. command. The value of
:hp2.n:ehp2. specifies the timer to read and can be 1, 2, or 3.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@TRIM.@TRIM
:p.
:hp2.@TRIM[string]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the :hp2.string:ehp2. with the
leading and trailing white space (space and tab characters) removed.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@UNIQUE.@UNIQUE
:p.
:hp2.@UNIQUE[d&colon.\path]:ehp2.&colon. Creates a zero-length file with
a unique name in the specified directory, and returns the full name and
path. If no path is specified, the file will be created in the
current directory. the filename will be FAT-compatible (8
character name and 3-character extension) regardless of whether the
file is created on a volume supporting long filenames. This function
allows you to create a temporary file without overwriting an existing file.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@UPPER.@UPPER
:p.
:hp2.@UPPER[string]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the :hp2.string:ehp2. converted to
upper case.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@WILD.@WILD
:p.
:hp2.@WILD[string1,string2]:ehp2.&colon. Performs a comparison of the two
strings, and returns "1" if they match or "0" if they don't match. The
second argument, :hp2.string2:ehp2., may contain wildcards or extended
wildcards; the first argument, :hp2.string1:ehp2., may not. The test is not
case-sensitive. The following example tests whether the \UTIL directory
(or any directory that begins with the characters UTIL) is included in the
:link reftype=hd refid=PATH_Var.PATH:elink.&colon.
:xmp.
    if %@wild[%path,*\UTIL*] == 1 :hp1.command:ehp1.
:exmp.:p.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@WORD.@WORD
:p.
:hp2.@WORD[["xxx",]n,string]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the :hp2.n:ehp2.th word
in a string. The first word is numbered 0. If :hp2.n:ehp2. is negative,
words are returned from the end of the string. The first argument is a list
of word separators you want to use; if you don't specify it, only spaces,
tabs, and commas are considered to be word separators. For example&colon.
:xmp.
    %@WORD[2,NOW IS THE TIME]     returns "THE"
    %@WORD[-0,NOW IS THE TIME]    returns "TIME"
    %@WORD[-2,NOW IS THE TIME]    returns "IS"
    %@WORD["=",1,2 + 2=4]     returns "4"
:exmp.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@WORDS.@WORDS
:p.
:hp2.@WORDS[["xxx",]string]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the number of words in the
:hp2.string:ehp2.&per. The optional list of separators follows the same format as
:link reftype=hd refid=_@WORD.@WORD:elink.&per. If the :hp2.string:ehp2.
argument is enclosed in quotation marks, you must enter a list of separators
as well.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=_@YEAR.@YEAR
:p.
:hp2.@YEAR[mm-dd-yy]:ehp2.&colon. Returns the year for the specified
date. YEAR uses the date format and separators mandated by your country code
(for example dd.mm.yy in Germany, or yy-mm-dd in Japan). The year can be
specified as two digits or four digits; @YEAR returns the same number of
digits included in its argument. Two-digit years between 80 and 99
are interpreted as 1980 - 1999; values between 00 and 79 are interpreted as
2000 - 2079.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h1 name=INIFile.&4OS2INI.
:p.
Most of the configuration of &4OS2. is controlled through a file of
initialization information called :hp1.&4OS2INI.:ehp1., which is discussed in
the following sections:
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=INIModify.Modifying the .INI File:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=INIUsing.Using the .INI File:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=INISections..INI File Sections:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=INIDirectives..INI File Directives:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=INIExamples..INI File Examples:elink.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
We also discuss many ways of configuring &4OS2. in other sections of the help,
for example&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.*:pd.With :link reftype=hd refid=Aliases.aliases:elink. you can set
default options for internal commands and create new commands.
:pt.*:pd.With :link reftype=hd refid=ExeExt.executable extensions:elink.
you can associate data files with the applications you use to open them.
:pt.*:pd.With the :link reftype=hd
refid=FILECOMPLETION.FILECOMPLETION:elink. environment variable and the
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_FileCompletion.FileCompletion:elink. .INI
directive you can customize :link reftype=hd refid=FileComp.filename completion:elink.
to match the command you are working with.
:pt.*:pd.With the :link reftype=hd refid=COLORDIR_Var.COLORDIR:elink.
environment variable and the :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_ColorDir.ColorDir:elink. :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. directive you can set the
colors used by the :link reftype=hd refid=DIR.DIR:elink. and :link reftype=hd
refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink. commands.
:pt.*:pd.With the :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. command, you
can change some aspects of the command processor's operation "on the fly."
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=INIModify.Modifying the .INI File
:p.
You can create, add to, and modify :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.
in two ways&colon.
:p.
with the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.
and/or by editing the file with any ASCII editor. Start the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.
by using the :link reftype=hd refid=OPTION.OPTION:elink. command without
parameters. This presents a standard WPS settings notebook which allows you to
modify the most common options.
:p.
See
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.
for additional details.
:p.
Changes you make on the :link reftype=hd refid=StartupOption.Startup page:elink.
of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.
will only take effect when you restart the session or window in which &4OS2. is
running.
:p.
The
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.
handles most standard :hp1..INI :ehp1.file settings. A few more advanced
settings, as well as all settings that affect the interpretation of keystrokes,
cannot be modified with the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.
and must be inserted or modified manually. For more details see the
:link reftype=hd refid=TOC_ConfigurationNotebook.Configuration Notebook:elink.&per.
:p.
You can also create, add to, and edit :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.
manually with any ASCII text editor. Each command processor reads
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. when it starts, and configures itself accordingly.
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. is not re-read when you change it manually. For
manual changes to take effect, you must restart the session or window in
which &4OS2. is running. If you edit :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. manually, make
sure you save the file in ASCII format.
:p.
Each item that you can include in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. has a default
value. You only need to include entries in the file for settings that you
want to change from their default values.
:p.
:p.
:hp2.Format&colon.:ehp2.
:p.
Most lines in the :hp1..INI :ehp1.file consist of a one-word
:hp2.directive:ehp2., an equal sign [:hp2.=:ehp2.], and a
:hp2.value:ehp2.&per. For example, in the following line, the word
"Environment" is the directive and "2048" is the value&colon.
:xmp.
    Environment = 2048
:exmp.:p.
Any spaces before or after the equal sign are ignored.
:p.
If you have a long string to enter in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. (for
example, for the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_ColorDir.ColorDir:elink.
directive), you must enter it all on one line. Strings cannot be
"continued" to a second line. Each line may be up to 1023 characters long.
:p.
The format of the value part of a directive line depends upon the individual
directive. It may be a numeric value, a single character, a choice (like
"Yes" or "No"), a color setting, a key name, a path, a filename, or a text
string. The value begins with the first non-blank character after the
equal sign and ends at the end of the line or the beginning of a comment.
:p.
Blank lines are ignored in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. and can be used to
separate groups of directives. You can place comments in the file by
beginning a line with a semicolon [:hp2.;:ehp2.]. You can also place
comments at the end of any line except one containing a text string
value. To do so, enter at least one space or tab after the value, a
semicolon, and your comment, like this&colon.
:xmp.
    Environment = 2048   ;set standard environment size
:exmp.:p.
If you try to place a comment at the end of a string value, the comment will
become part of the string and will probably cause an error.
:p.
If you use the :link reftype=hd refid=OPTION.OPTION:elink. dialogs to
modify :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink., comments on lines modified from within
the dialogs will not be preserved when the new lines are saved. To be
sure :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. comments are preserved, put them on separate lines in the
file
:p.
If you want to include the text of one .INI file within another
(for example, if you have a set of common directives used by several JP
Software products), see the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_Include.Include:elink.
directive.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=INIUsing.Using the .INI File
:p.
Some settings in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. are initialized when you install
&4OS2., so you will probably have a :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. even if you didn't
create one yourself.
:p.
&4OS2. primary shells search for :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. in three places&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.*:pd.If there is an "@d&colon.\path\inifile" option on the startup
command line, the command processor will use the path and filename
specified there, and will not look elsewhere. See :link reftype=hd
refid=Startup.Starting 4OS2:elink. for details.
:pt.*:pd.If there is no :hp1..INI :ehp1. filename on the startup command
line, the search proceeds to the same directory where the command processor
program file (:hp1.4OS2.EXE:ehp1.) is stored. This is the "normal" location
for :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. &4OS2. determines this directory automatically.
:pt.*:pd.If :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. is not found in the directory where the
program file is stored, a final check is made in the root directory of the
boot drive.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
When &4OS2. is loaded as a secondary shell, it does not search for
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. Instead, it retrieves the primary shell's
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. data, processes the :hp2.[Secondary]:ehp2. section of
the original :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. if necessary (see :link reftype=hd
refid=INISections..INI File Sections:elink.), and then processes any
"@d&colon.\path\inifile" option on the secondary shell command line (see
:link reftype=hd refid=Startup.Starting 4OS2:elink.). You can override this
behavior with the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_NextINIFile.NextINIFile:elink.
directive.
:p.
Secondary shells automatically inherit the configuration settings currently
in effect in the previous shell. If values have been changed by :link
reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. since the primary shell started, the
current values will be passed to the secondary shell. If the previous
shell's :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. had a :hp2.[Secondary]:ehp2. section, it will
then be read and processed (see :link reftype=hd refid=INISections..INI
File Sections:elink.&per. If not, the previous shell's settings will remain in
effect.
:p.
For example, you might set :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_BatchEcho.BatchEcho:elink. to Yes in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink., to
enable batch file echo. If you then use SETDOS /V0 to turn off batch file echoing in the
primary shell, then any secondary shells will inherit the SETDOS setting,
rather than the original value from :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.;
:hp1.i.e.:ehp1., batch files in the secondary shell will default to no echo.
:p.
If you want to force secondary shells to start with a specific value for a
particular directive, regardless of any changes made with SETDOS in a
previous shell, repeat the directive in the :hp2.[Secondary]:ehp2. section
of :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:p.
The :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. command can override
several of :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. directives. For example, the cursor
shape used by &4OS2. can be adjusted either with the :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_CursorIns.CursorIns:elink. and :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_CursorOver.CursorOver:elink. directives or the SETDOS /S
command. The correspondence between SETDOS options and .:hp1.INI:ehp1.
directives is noted with each directive, and under each option of the
SETDOS command.
:p.
When the command processor detects an error while processing
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink., it displays an error message and prompts you to press
a key to continue processing the file. This allows you to note any errors
before the startup process continues. The directive in error will retain
its previous or default value. Only the most catastrophic errors (like a
disk read failure) will terminate processing of the remainder of
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. If you don't want a pause after each error, use a
":link reftype=hd refid=INI_PauseOnError.PauseOnError:elink. = No"
directive at the beginning of :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:p.
If you need to test different values for an :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. directive
without repeatedly editing :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink., use the :link
reftype=hd refid=OPTION.OPTION:elink. command or see the :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_INIQuery.INIQuery:elink. directive.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=INISections..INI File Sections
:p.
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. has three possible sections&colon. the first or
:hp2.global:ehp2. section, named :hp2.[4OS2]:ehp2.; the
:hp2.[Primary]:ehp2. section; and the :hp2.[Secondary]:ehp2. section. Each
section is identified by the section name in square brackets on a line by
itself.
:p.
Directives in the global section are effective in all shells. In most cases,
this is the only section you will need. Any changes you make to
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. with the :link reftype=hd refid=OPTION.OPTION:elink.
command are stored in the global section.
:p.
The :hp2.[Primary]:ehp2. and :hp2.[Secondary]:ehp2. sections include
directives that are used only in primary and secondary shells,
respectively. You don't need to set up these sections unless you want
different directives for primary and secondary shells.
:p.
Directives in the :hp2.[Primary]:ehp2. section are used for the first or
primary shell. The values are passed automatically to all secondary
shells, unless overridden by a directive with the same name in the
:hp2.[Secondary]:ehp2. section.
:p.
Directives in the :hp2.[Secondary]:ehp2. section are used in secondary
shells only, and override any corresponding primary shell settings. For
example, these lines in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&colon.
:xmp.
    [Primary]
    ScreenRows = 25

    [Secondary]
    ScreenRows = 50
:exmp.:p.
mean to assume that you have 25 rows on the screen in the primary shell and
50 lines in all secondary shells.
:p.
Sections that begin with any name other than :hp2.[4OS2]:ehp2.,
:hp2.[Primary]:ehp2., or :hp2.[Secondary]:ehp2. are ignored.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=INIDirectives..INI File Directives
:p.
For information on specific directives see the separate topic for each type
of directive&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=INIInit.Initialization Directives:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=INIConfig.Configuration Directives:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=INIColor.Color Directives:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=INIKeyMap.Key Mapping Directives:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=INIAdv.Advanced Directives:elink.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
These topics list the directives, with a one-line description of each, and
a cross-reference which selects a full screen help topic on that directive.
A few of the directives are simple enough that the one-line description is
sufficient, but in most cases you should check for any additional
information in the cross-reference topic if you are not already familiar
with the directive.
:p.
You can also obtain help on most directives with a :hp2.HELP directive:ehp2.
command at the prompt.
:p.
There are 8 types of directives in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. The different
types of directives are shown in the descriptions as follows&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.*:pd.:hp2.Name = nnnn (1234):ehp2.&colon. This directive takes a
numeric value which replaces the "nnnn." The default value is shown in
parentheses.
:pt.*:pd.:hp2.Name = c (X):ehp2.&colon. This directive accepts a single
character as its value. The default character is shown in parentheses. You
must type in the actual character; you cannot use a key name.
:pt.*:pd.:hp2.Name = CHOICE1 | Choice2 | ...:ehp2. &colon. This directive
takes a choice value. The possible choices are listed, separated by
vertical bars. The default value is shown in all upper case letters in the
directive description, but in your file any of the choices can be entered in
upper case or lower case. For example, if the choices were shown as "YES |
No" then "YES" is the default.
:pt.*:pd.:hp2.Name = Color:ehp2.&colon. This directive takes a color
specification. See :link reftype=hd refid=Colors.Colors and Color
Names:elink.&per.
:pt.*:pd.:hp2.Name = Key (Default):ehp2.&colon. This directive takes a key
specification. See :link reftype=hd refid=KeyNames.Key Names:elink.&per.
:pt.*:pd.:hp2.Name = Path:ehp2.&colon. This directive takes a path
specification, but not a filename. The value should include both a drive
and path (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., :hp1.C&colon.\4OS2:ehp1.) to avoid any possible
ambiguities. A trailing backslash [:hp2.\:ehp2.] at the end of the path
name is acceptable but not required. Any default path is described in the
text.
:pt.*:pd.:hp2.Name = File:ehp2.&colon. This directive takes a filename. We
recommend that you use a full filename including the drive letter and path
to avoid any possible ambiguities. Any default filename is described in the
text.
:pt.*:pd.:hp2.Name = String:ehp2.&colon. This directive takes a string in
the format shown. The text describes the default value and any additional
requirements for formatting the string correctly. :hp2.No comments are
allowed:ehp2.&per.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
&4OS2. contains a fixed-length area for storing strings entered in
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink., including filenames, paths, and other strings. This
area is large and is unlikely to overflow; if it does, you will receive an
error message. If this occurs, reduce the complexity of
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. or contact support for assistance.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=INIInit.Initialization Directives
:p.
The directives in this section control how &4OS2. starts and where it
looks for its files. The initialization directives are&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=20 break=fit.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_4StartPath.4StartPath:elink.:pd.Path for 4START and 4EXIT
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_DirHistory.DirHistory:elink.:pd.Size of directory history list
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_DuplicateBugs.DuplicateBugs:elink.:pd.Duplicate bugs in CMD.EXE
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_HelpBook.HelpBook:elink.:pd.Books to load in help system
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_History.History:elink.:pd.Size of history list
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_INIQuery.INIQuery:elink.:pd.Query for each line in &4OS2INI.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_LocalAliases.LocalAliases:elink.:pd.Local vs. global aliases
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_LocalDirHistory.LocalHistory:elink.:pd.Local vs. global directory history
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_LocalHistory.LocalHistory:elink.:pd.Local vs. global history
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_PauseOnError.PauseOnError:elink.:pd.Pause on errors in &4OS2INI.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_SwapFilePath.SwapFilePath:elink.:pd.Path to OS/2 swap file
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_TreePath.TreePath:elink.:pd.Path for directory database
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_WindowState.WindowState:elink.:pd.Initial state for the 4OS2 window
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_WindowX.WindowX, WindowY, WindowWidth, WindowHeight:elink.:pd.Initial size and position of the 4OS2 window
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_4StartPath.4StartPath
:p.
:hp2.4StartPath:ehp2. = Path&colon. Sets the drive and directory where the
:hp1.4START:ehp1. and :hp1.4EXIT:ehp1. batch files (if any) are located.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_DirHistory.DirHistory (directive)
:p.
.* 2013-04-25 SHL change 256 -> 4092
:hp2.DirHistory:ehp2. = nnnn (4092)&colon. Sets the amount of memory
allocated to the directory history in bytes. The allowable range of values
is 256 to 32767 bytes. If you use a :link reftype=hd
refid=GlobalDirHistory.global directory history list:elink. the DirHistory
value will be ignored in all shells except the shell which first establishes
the global list.
:p.
The directory history buffer is allocated from shared memory
which is allocated in multiples of 4096 byte pages.
The history buffer includes a 4 byte header, so memory usage is better if
DirHistory is set to (pages * 4096) - 4 where pages is between 1 and 16.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_DuplicateBugs.DuplicateBugs
:p.
:hp2.DuplicateBugs:ehp2. = YES | No&colon. Tells the &4OS2. parser to
duplicate certain well-known bugs in :hp1.CMD.EXE:ehp1.&per. The only bug
currently replicated is in the :link reftype=hd refid=IF.IF:elink. command.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_HelpBook.HelpBook
:p.
:hp2.HelpBook:ehp2. = String&colon. Sets the names of the "books" to be loaded
when &4OS2. help is invoked with the :link reftype=hd refid=HELP.HELP:elink. command or the
:hp2.F1:ehp2. key. The default is :hp2.4OS2+CMDREF:ehp2. which loads the &4OS2.
help and the OS/2 command reference.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_History.History (directive)
:p.
.* 2013-04-25 SHL change 1024 -> 4092. Doc optimal usage
:hp2.History:ehp2. = nnnn (4092)&colon. Sets the amount of memory allocated to
the command history list in bytes. The allowable range of values
is 256 to 32767 bytes. If you use a global history list (see
:link reftype=hd refid=CmdHist.Command History and Recall:elink.), the History value is
ignored in all shells except the shell which first establishes the
global list.
:p.
The command history buffer is allocated from shared memory
which is allocated in multiples of 4096 byte pages.
The history buffer includes a 4 byte header, so memory usage is better if
History is set to (pages * 4096) - 4 where pages is between 1 and 16.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_INIQuery.INIQuery
:p.
:hp2.INIQuery:ehp2. = Yes &splitvbar. NO&colon. If set to :hp2.Yes:ehp2., a prompt will be
displayed before execution of each subsequent line in the current
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. file. This allows you to modify certain directives when
you start &4OS2. in order to test different configurations. INIQuery
can be reset to :hp2.No:ehp2. at any point in the file. Normally INIQuery
= Yes is only used during testing of other :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. file
directives.
:p.
The prompt generated by INIQuery = Yes is&colon.
:xmp.
    [contents of the line] (Y/N/Q/R/E) ?
:exmp.:p.
At this prompt, you may enter&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.Y = Yes&colon.:pd.Process this line and go on to the next.
:pt.N = No&colon.:pd.Skip this line and go on to the next.
:pt.Q = Quit&colon.:pd.Skip this line and all subsequent lines.
:pt.R = Rest&colon.:pd.Execute this and all subsequent lines.
:pt.E = Edit&colon.:pd.Edit the value for this entry.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
If you choose E for Edit, you can enter a new value for the
directive, but not a new directive name.
:p.
For example, if you have found a compatibility problem you think
may be related to &4OS2.'s character (as opposed to line) input mode,
you might change :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. so a part of it read as
follows&colon.
:xmp.
    INIQuery = Yes
    LineInput = Yes
    INIQuery = No
:exmp.:p.
You could then choose to process, ignore, or edit the LineInput
directive each time &4OS2. started. This would allow you to check whether
changing the line input mode would resolve the compatibility problem.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_LocalAliases.LocalAliases
:p.
:hp2.LocalAliases:ehp2. = Yes &splitvbar. NO&colon. :hp2.No:ehp2. forces all copies
of &4OS2. to share the same alias list. :hp2.Yes:ehp2. keeps the lists for each
shell separate. See :link reftype=hd refid=ALIAS.ALIAS:elink. for more details on local and
global alias lists.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_LocalDirHistory.LocalDirHistory
:p.
:hp2.LocalDirHistory:ehp2. = Yes &splitvbar. NO&colon. :hp2.No:ehp2. forces
all copies of command processor to share the same directory history. :hp2.Yes:ehp2.
keeps the directory histories for each shell separate. See
:link reftype=hd refid=GlobalDirHistory.Local and Global Directory History:elink. for
more details.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_LocalHistory.LocalHistory
:p.
:hp2.LocalHistory:ehp2. = Yes &splitvbar. NO&colon. :hp2.No:ehp2. forces all copies of &4OS2.
to share the same history list. :hp2.Yes:ehp2. keeps the lists for each
shell separate. See :link reftype=hd refid=CmdHist.Command History and Recall:elink. for
more details on local and global history lists.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_PauseOnError.PauseOnError
:p.
:hp2.PauseOnError:ehp2. = YES &splitvbar. No&colon. :hp2.Yes:ehp2. forces a
pause with the message "Error in :hp1.filename:ehp1., press any key to
continue processing" after displaying any error message related to a
specific line in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per. :hp2.No:ehp2. continues processing
with no pause after an error message is displayed.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_SwapFilePath.SwapFilePath
:p.
:hp2.SwapFilePath:ehp2. = Path | File&colon. Specifies the path to the OS/2
swap file so that the :link reftype=hd refid=MEMORY.MEMORY:elink. command
can find it. You can either specify a full path and filename for the swap
file or just the path. If you specify a path only, &4OS2. assumes that the
file is called :hp1.SWAPPER.DAT:ehp1.&per. If SwapFilePath is not used, &4OS2.
assumes that the file is named :hp1.SWAPPER.DAT:ehp1. and stored in the
:hp1.\OS2\SYSTEM:ehp1. directory of the boot drive.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_TreePath.TreePath
:p.
:hp2.TreePath:ehp2. = Path&colon. Sets the location of
:hp1.JPSTREE.IDX:ehp1., the file used for :link reftype=hd
refid=ExtDirSearch.extended directory searches:elink. By default, the file is
placed in the &4OS2. installation directory (if writable) or in the root of the
boot volume.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_WindowState.WindowState
:p.
:hp2.WindowState:ehp2. = STANDARD &splitvbar. Maximize &splitvbar. Minimize &splitvbar. Custom&colon.
Sets the initialstate of the &4OS2. window.
:hp2.Standard:ehp2. puts the window in the
default position on the OS/2 desktop, and is the default setting.
:hp2.Maximize:ehp2. maximizes the window;
:hp2.Minimize:ehp2. minimizes it;
:hp2.Custom:ehp2. enables the custom size and postion settings.
If you use Maximize or Minimize, you may see the &4OS2. window appear
briefly in the Standard position as it is created by OS/2, then
switch to the new state.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_WindowX.WindowX, WindowY, WindowWidth, WindowHeight
:p.
:hp2.WindowX:ehp2. = nnnn, :hp2.WindowY:ehp2. = nnnn, :hp2.WindowWidth:ehp2.
= nnnn, :hp2.WindowHeight:ehp2. = nnnn&colon. These 4 directives set the
initial size and position of the &4OS2. window. The measurements are in
pixels or pels. :hp2.WindowX:ehp2. and :hp2.WindowY:ehp2. refer to the
position of the bottom left corner of the window relative to the bottom left
corner of the screen.
:p.
These settings are active only if :hp2.WindowState:ehp2. Custom is also set.
:p.
The :link reftype=hd refid=OPTION.OPTION:elink. command can be used to dynamically position and
resize the window:
:xmp.
     option //WindowState = Standard
     option //WindowX=20 //WindowY=20 //WindowHeight = 100 //WindowWidth = 50 //WindowState = Custom
:exmp.:p.


.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=INIConfig.Configuration Directives
:p.
These directives control the way that &4OS2. operate. Some can be
changed with the :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. command while &4OS2. is running.
Any corresponding SETDOS command is listed in the description of
each directive. The configuration directives are&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=20 break=fit.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_AmPm.AmPm:elink.:pd.Time display format
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_AppendToDir.AppendToDir:elink.:pd."\" on directory names in filename completion
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_BatchEcho.BatchEcho:elink.:pd.Default batch file echo state
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_BeepFreq.BeepFreq:elink.:pd.Default beep frequency
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_BeepLength.BeepLength:elink.:pd.Default beep length
