:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_HistMove.HistMove:elink.:pd.History move mode
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_HistNoDups.HistNoDups:elink.:pd.History no duplicates mode
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_HistWrap.HistWrap:elink.:pd.History wrap mode
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_LineInput.LineInput:elink.:pd.Enable / disable line input mode
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ListRowStart.ListRowStart:elink.:pd.Starting row number for LIST and FFIND
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_LogName.LogName:elink.:pd.Log filename
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_NewByteDisp.NewByteDisp:elink.:pd.Tuning of bytes used/allocated/free display with dir command
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_NoClobber.NoClobber:elink.:pd.Overwrite protection for output redirection
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ParameterChar.ParameterChar:elink.:pd.Alias / batch file parameter character
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_PathExt.PathExt:elink.:pd.Enable or disable the PATHEXT variable
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_PopupWinLeft.PopupWinLeft, PopupWinTop, PopupWinWidth, PopupWinHeight:elink.:pd.Initial position and size of popup windows
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_PopupWinPosRelative.PopupWinPosRelative:elink.:pd. Popup window relative to cursor position
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_Printer.Printer:elink.:pd.LIST print device
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ScreenRows.ScreenRows:elink.:pd.Screen height
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_TabStops.TabStops:elink.:pd.Tab width in LIST
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ThousandsChar.ThousandsChar:elink.:pd.Thousands separator
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_TmSmpFmt.TmSmpFmt:elink.:pd.Format used for time stamp (_TMSMP).
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_UnixPaths.UnixPaths:elink.:pd.Enable or disable slash in command paths
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_UpperCase.UpperCase:elink.:pd.Force filenames to upper case
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_Year4Digit.Year4Digit:elink.:pd.Displays years as 4 digits.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_AmPm.AmPm
:p.
:hp2.AmPm:ehp2. = Yes &splitvbar. NO &splitvbar. Auto&colon. :hp2.Yes:ehp2. displays times in 12-hour
format with a trailing "a" for AM or "p" for PM. The default of
:hp2.No:ehp2. forces a display in 24-hour time format. :hp2.Auto:ehp2. formats
the time according to the country code set for your system. AmPm
controls the time displays used by :link reftype=hd refid=DIR.DIR:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink., in :link reftype=hd refid=LOG.LOG:elink. files, and the output of the
:link reftype=hd refid=TIMER.TIMER:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=DATE.DATE:elink., and :link reftype=hd refid=TIME .TIME :elink.commands. It
has no effect on :link reftype=hd refid=_TIME.%_TIME:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=_@MAKETIME.%@MAKETIME:elink., the
$t and $T options of :link reftype=hd refid=PROMPT.PROMPT:elink., or date and time
:link reftype=hd refid=ranges.ranges:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_AppendToDir.AppendToDir
:p.
:hp2.AppendToDir:ehp2. = Yes &splitvbar. NO&colon. :hp2.Yes:ehp2. appends a
trailing "\" to directory names when doing :link reftype=hd refid=FileComp.filename completion:elink.&per.
The default
is :hp2.No:ehp2.&per. (Regardless of the setting of this directive, a trailing
backslash is always appended to a directory name at the beginning of the
command line to enable automatic directory changes.)

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_BatchEcho.BatchEcho
:p.
:hp2.BatchEcho:ehp2. = YES &splitvbar. No&colon. Sets the default batch echo mode.
:hp2.Yes:ehp2. enables echoing of all batch file commands unless
:link reftype=hd refid=ECHO.ECHO:elink. is explicitly set off in the batch file. :hp2.No:ehp2.
disables batch file echoing unless ECHO is explicitly set on. Also
see :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /V.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_BeepFreq.BeepFreq
:p.
:hp2.BeepFreq:ehp2. = nnnn (440)&colon. Sets the default :link reftype=hd refid=BEEP.BEEP:elink.
command frequency in Hz. This is also the frequency for "error"
beeps (for example, if you press an illegal key). To disable all
error beeps set this or BeepLength to 0. If you do, the BEEP
command will still be operable, but will not produce sound unless
you explicitly specify the frequency and duration.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_BeepLength.BeepLength
:p.
:hp2.BeepLength:ehp2. = nnnn (2)&colon. Sets the default :link reftype=hd refid=BEEP.BEEP:elink. length
in system clock ticks (approximately 1/18 of a second per tick).
BeepLength is also the default length for "error" beeps (for
example, if you press an illegal key).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_CDDWinLeft.CDDWinLeft, CDDWinTop, CDDWinWidth, CDDWinHeight
:p.
:hp2.CDDWinLeft:ehp2. = nnnn, :hp2.CDDWinTop:ehp2. = nnnn,
:hp2.CDDWinWidth:ehp2. = nnnn, :hp2.CDDWinHeight:ehp2. = nnnn&colon. These
values set the position and size of the popup window used by :link
reftype=hd refid=ExtDirSearch.extended directory searches:elink., in
characters, including the border. The defaults are 3, 3, 72, and 16,
respectively (:hp1.i.e.:ehp1., a window beginning in column 3, row 3, 72
columns wide and 16 rows high). The position is relative to the top left
corner of the screen. The width and height values include the space
required for the window border.
:p.
The window cannot be smaller than than 10 columns wide by 5 rows high
(including the border). The values you enter will be adjusted if necessary
to keep a minimum-size window visible on the screen.
:p.
The window is normally displayed with a shadow, but if you specify a window
starting at column 0 and extending to the right margin, the shadow is
eliminated; this may be useful to prevent speech software from reading text
in the shadow area while viewing the window.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_ChangeTitle.ChangeTitle
:p.
:hp2.ChangeTitle:ehp2. = YES &splitvbar. No&colon. Determines whether &4OS2.
changes the OS/2 session title when running an external program.
:p.
Also see :link reftype=hd refid=_WINTITLE._WINTITLE:elink. internal variable.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_CDWithoutBackslash.CDWithoutBackslash
:p.
:hp2.CDWithoutBackslash:ehp2. = 0 &splitvbar. 1 &splitvbar. 2&colon.
Determines if &4OS2. should change into subdirectory when entering its name
even without leading cd and trailing backslash (\).
:p.
Directory change by typing in the directory name without cd is now possible
even without leading backslash (\). Backslash on some keyboard layouts (like
the German one) is not that easy to type.
:p.
If you want the old behavior, disable it with the :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. entry
CDWithoutBackslash=0
:p.
With CDWithoutBackslash=1 (default), directory change takes place only if
no executable with the same name exist (4nt8 behavior)
:p.
With CDWithoutBackslash=2 a directory change is made before checking for an
external executable with the same name (cmdshl behavior). Of course you
can start such an executable by typing the name with extension f.i.
name.exe or name.cmd.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_CMDDirMvCpy.CMDDirMvCpy
:p.

:hp2.CMDDirMvCpy:ehp2. = YES | No&colon. CMD copies or moves the directory to 
the target when the command line aurgument is a directory. By default &4OS2. 
copies or moves the files in the directory to the target. Setting this to yes 
makes &4OS2. provide the CMD behavior. Using :link reftype=hd
refid=COPY.COPY:elink. /J or :link reftype=hd refid=MOVE.MOVE:elink. /J has 
the same effect.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_CommandSep.CommandSep
:p.
:hp2.CommandSep:ehp2. = c&colon. This is the character used to separate
multiple commands on the same line. The default is the ampersand [:hp2.&amp.:ehp2.].
You cannot use any of the redirection characters (:hp2.&splitvbar.:ehp2. :hp2.>:ehp2. :hp2.<:ehp2.
) or any of the whitespace characters (space, tab, comma, or equal
sign). The command separator is saved by :link reftype=hd
refid=SETLOCAL.SETLOCAL:elink. and restored by :link reftype=hd
refid=ENDLOCAL.ENDLOCAL:elink.&per.
:p.
Also see :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /C, the :link
reftype=hd refid=PLUS.%+:elink. internal variable, and :link reftype=hd
refid=Compat.Special Character Compatibility:elink. for
information on using compatible command separators for two or more products.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_CursorIns.CursorIns
:p.
:hp2.CursorIns:ehp2. = nnnn (100)&colon. This is the shape of the cursor for
insert mode during command-line editing and all commands which
accept line input (DESCRIBE, ESET, etc.). The size is a percentage
of the total character cell size, between 0% and 100%. Because of
the way video drivers map the cursor shape, you may not
get a smooth progression in cursor shapes as :hp2.CursorIns:ehp2. and
:hp2.CursorOver:ehp2. change. If :hp2.CursorIns:ehp2. or :hp2.CursorOver:ehp2. is set to
-1, &4OS2. will not attempt to modify the cursor shape at all; you can use this
feature to give another program full control of the cursor shape.
:p.
Also see :link reftype=hd refid=INI_CursorOver.CursorOver:elink.
and :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /S.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_CursorOver.CursorOver
:p.
:hp2.CursorOver:ehp2. = nnnn (15)&colon. This is the shape of the cursor for
overtype mode during command-line editing and all commands which
accept line input. The size is a percentage of the total character
cell size, between 0% and 100%. For details see :link reftype=hd refid=INI_CursorIns.CursorIns:elink.;
also see :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /S.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_DateFmt.DateFmt
:p.

:hp2.DateFmt:ehp2. = YYYY-MM-DD&colon.

Sets the format for 
the date strings returned by :link reftype=hd refid=_DATE._DATE:elink. and elsewhere.
This, if set, format is used everywhere dates are formatted.  If not set, the locale
specfic date format is used.

:p.
The supported formats include DD-MM-YYYY, MM-DD-YYYY,
YYYY-MM-DD and YYYY-DD-MM.
The separator can be "-" or "/".
The year can be output as 2 or 4 digits.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_DecimalChar.DecimalChar
:p.
:hp2. DecimalChar:ehp2. = . &splitvbar. , &splitvbar. AUTO&colon. Sets the
character used as the decimal separator for :link reftype=hd
refid=_@EVAL.@EVAL:elink., numeric :link reftype=hd refid=IF.IF:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=IFF.IFF:elink. tests, version numbers, and other
similar uses. The only valid settings are period [:hp2..:ehp2.], comma
[:hp2.,:ehp2.], and :hp2.Auto:ehp2. (the default). A setting of Auto tells
the command processor to use the decimal separator associated with your
current country code. If you change the decimal character you must also
adjust the thousands character (with :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_ThousandsChar.ThousandsChar:elink.) so that the two characters are
different.
:p.
Also see :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /G.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_DescriptionMax.DescriptionMax
:p.
:hp2.DescriptionMax:ehp2. = nnnn (40)&colon. Controls the description length
limit for :link reftype=hd refid=DESCRIBE.DESCRIBE:elink.&per. The allowable range is 20 to 511
characters.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_DescriptionName.DescriptionName
:p.
:hp2.DescriptionName:ehp2. = [File &splitvbar. EA]&colon. Sets the file
name in which to store file descriptions. The default filename is
:hp1.DESCRIPT.ION:ehp1.&per. :hp8.Use this directive with caution:ehp8. because
changing the name from the default will make it difficult to transfer file
descriptions to another system.
:p.
If you set :hp2.DescriptionName = EA:ehp2., &4OS2. will use the ".SUBJECT"
extended attribute (EA) for file descriptions instead of a separate
file. Note that using EAs will slow the :link reftype=hd
refid=DIR.DIR:elink. and :link reftype=hd refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink.
commands noticeably. On a FAT16 volume, performance may be substantially
slower, depending upon whether the system has cached the extended attributes.
:p.
Also see :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /D.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_Descriptions.Descriptions
:p.
:hp2.Descriptions:ehp2. = YES &splitvbar. No&colon. Turns description
handling on or off during the file processing commands :link reftype=hd
refid=COPY.COPY:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=DEL.DEL:elink., :link
reftype=hd refid=MOVE.MOVE:elink., and :link reftype=hd
refid=REN.REN:elink.&per. If set to :hp2.No:ehp2., &4OS2. will not update the
description file when files are moved, copied, deleted or renamed.
:p.
Also see :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /D.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_EditMode.EditMode
:p.
:hp2.EditMode:ehp2. = Insert &splitvbar. OVERSTRIKE&colon. This directive
lets you start the command-line editor in either insert or overstrike
mode. Also see :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /M.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_EscapeChar.EscapeChar
:p.
:hp2.EscapeChar:ehp2. = c &colon. Sets the character used to suppress the
normal meaning of the following character. The default is a caret [:hp2.^:ehp2.].
See :link reftype=hd refid=Escape.Escape Character:elink. for a description of special
escape sequences. You cannot use any of the
:link reftype=hd refid=RedirPipe.redirection:elink. characters
(:hp2.&splitvbar.:ehp2., :hp2.>:ehp2., or :hp2.<:ehp2. ) or
the whitespace characters (space, tab, comma, or equal sign) as the
escape character. The escape character is saved by :link reftype=hd
refid=SETLOCAL.SETLOCAL:elink. and restored by :link reftype=hd
refid=ENDLOCAL.ENDLOCAL:elink.&per.
:p.
Also see :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /E, the
:link reftype=hd refid=EQUALS.%=:elink. internal variable, and :link
reftype=hd refid=Compat.Special Character Compatibility:elink. for
information on using compatible escape characters for two or more products.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_EvalMax.EvalMax
:p.
:hp2.EvalMax:ehp2. = nnnn (8)&colon. Controls the maximum number of digits
after the decimal point in values returned by :link reftype=hd
refid=_@EVAL.@EVAL:elink.&per. This setting can be overridden with the construct
:hp2.@EVAL[expression=n.n]:ehp2.&per. The allowable range is 0 to 8. Also see
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_EvalMin.EvalMin:elink. and :link reftype=hd
refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /F.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_EvalMin.EvalMin
:p.
:hp2.EvalMin:ehp2. = nnnn (8)&colon. Controls the minimum number of digits after the
decimal point in values returned by :link reftype=hd refid=_@EVAL.@EVAL:elink.&per. This
setting can be overridden with the construct :hp2.@EVAL[expression=n.n]:ehp2.&per. The
allowable range is 0 to 8. The :hp2.EvalMin:ehp2. value will be ignored if it is
larger than :link reftype=hd refid=INI_EvalMax.EvalMax:elink.&per. Also
see :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /F.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_ExecWait.ExecWait
:p.
:hp2.ExecWait:ehp2. = Yes &splitvbar. NO&colon. Controls whether &4OS2.
waits for an external program to complete before redisplaying the prompt. See
:link reftype=hd refid=WaitForApps.Waiting for Applications to Finish:elink.
for details on the effects of this directive.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_FileCompletion.FileCompletion
:p.
:hp2.FileCompletion:ehp2. = cmd1&colon. ext1 ext2 ...; cmd2&colon. ext3
ext4 ..&per. Sets the files made available during filename completion for selected
commands. The format is the same as that used for the :link reftype=hd
refid=FILECOMPLETION.FILECOMPLETION:elink. environment variable. See :link
reftype=hd refid=FileComp.Filename Completion:elink. for a detailed
explanation of selective filename completion.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_FuzzyCD.FuzzyCD
:p.
:hp2.FuzzyCD:ehp2. = 0 | 1 | 2 | 3;  Enables or disables extended directory
searches, and controls their behavior. A setting of 0 (the default)
disables extended searches. For complete details on the meaning of the
other settings see :link reftype=hd refid=ExtDirSearch.Extended Directory
Searches:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_HistCopy.HistCopy
:p.
:hp2.HistCopy:ehp2. = Yes &splitvbar. NO&colon. Controls what happens when you re-execute
a line from the command history. If this option is set to :hp2.Yes:ehp2.,
the line is appended to the end of the history list. By default, or if
this option is set to :hp2.No:ehp2., the command is not copied. The
original copy of the command is retained at its original position in the
list, regardless of the setting of HistCopy.
:p.
Set this option to No if you want to use :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_HistMove.HistMove:elink. = Yes; otherwise, the HistCopy setting
will override HistMove.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_HistLogName.HistLogName
:p.
:hp2.HistLogName:ehp2. = File&colon. Sets the history log filename and
path. Using HistLogName does not turn history logging on; you must use
a :link reftype=hd refid=LOG.LOG:elink. /H ON command to do so.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_HistMin.HistMin
:p.
:hp2.HistMin:ehp2. = nnnn (0)&colon. Sets the minimum command-line size to
save in the command history list. Any command line whose length is
less than this value will not be saved. Legal values range from 0,
which saves everything, to 1024, which disables all command history saves.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_HistMove.HistMove
:p.
:hp2.HistMove:ehp2. = Yes &splitvbar. NO&colon. If set to Yes, a recalled
line is moved to the end of the command history. The difference between
this directive and :link reftype=hd refid=INI_HistCopy.HistCopy:elink., is
that HistCopy = Yes copies each recalled line to the end of the history but
leaves the original in place. HistMove = Yes places the line at the end of
history and removes the original line.
:p.
This directive has no effect if HistCopy = Yes.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_HistNoDups.HistNoDups
:p.
:hp2.HistNoDups:ehp2. = Yes &splitvbar. NO&colon. If set to Yes, when you type a 
command that is already in the history the duplicate command will not be added to 
the history list. 
.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_HistWrap.HistWrap
:p.
:hp2.HistWrap = :ehp2.YES &splitvbar. No&colon. Controls whether the
command history recall "wraps" when you reach the top or bottom of the list. The default
setting enables wrapping, so the list appears "circular". If HistWrap is set
to No, history recall will stop at the beginning and end of the list rather
than wrapping. This setting affects history recall at the prompt only; the
command history window never wraps.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_LineInput.LineInput
:p.
:hp2.LineInput:ehp2. = Yes &splitvbar. NO&colon. This directive controls
how &4OS2. gets its input from the command line. :hp2.Yes:ehp2. forces &4OS2.
to perform line-by-line input, just as :hp1.CMD.EXE:ehp1. does, instead of
character-by-character input. This will disable command-line editing,
history recall, the directory history window, and filename completion, and
will reduce the &4OS2. input length limit from 1023 characters to 299
characters. It is normally used only for applications which do not work
properly unless &4OS2. uses line input.
:p.
If you have a particular program that requires line input, you can use :link
reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /L to temporarily change modes.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_ListRowStart.ListRowStart
:p.
:hp2.ListRowStart:ehp2. = 1 &splitvbar. 0&colon. Specifies whether
:link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink. and :link reftype=hd
refid=FFIND.FFIND:elink. consider the first line in the file to be line
"1" or line "0". The default is "1".

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------


:h4 name=INI_LogName.LogName
:p.
:hp2.LogName:ehp2. = File&colon. Sets the log filename and path. Using
LogName does not turn logging on; you must use a
:link reftype=hd refid=LOG.LOG:elink. ON command to do so.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_NoClobber.NoClobber
:p.
:hp2.NoClobber:ehp2. = Yes &splitvbar. NO&colon. If set to :hp2.Yes:ehp2.,
will prevent standard output :link reftype=hd
refid=Redirection.redirection:elink. from overwriting an existing file, and
will require that the output file already exist for append
redirection. Also see :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /N.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_NewByteDisp.NewByteDisp
:p.
:hp2.NewByteDisp:ehp2. = 0 &splitvbar. 1 &splitvbar. 2&colon.
Tuning of the byte summary displayed at the bottom of a directory listing can
be made with NewByteDisp setting in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.&per.
:p.
NewByteDisp=0: Standard (old) 4os2 display, used and allocated bytes in the same line
:p.
NewByteDisp=1 (default): Adds (xxxGB) info for better readability of large values.
The allocated space is not shown any more.
:p.
NewByteDisp=2: In addition to level 1, 2 reenables the allocated size summary but
on a new line instead as the same as the bytes/files/dirs (it does not fit there
any more with 80 character displays and large values)

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_ParameterChar.ParameterChar
:p.
:hp2.ParameterChar:ehp2. = c&colon. Sets the character used after a percent
sign to specify all or all remaining command-line arguments in a
batch file or alias (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., :hp2.%$:ehp2. or
:hp2.%n$:ehp2.; see :link reftype=hd refid=Batch.Batch Files:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=ALIAS.ALIAS:elink.). The default is the dollar sign
[:hp2.$:ehp2.]. The parameter character is saved by :link reftype=hd
refid=SETLOCAL.SETLOCAL:elink. and restored by :link reftype=hd
refid=ENDLOCAL.ENDLOCAL:elink.&per.
:p.
Also see :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /P. See :link
reftype=hd refid=Compat.Special Character Compatibility:elink. for
information on using compatible parameter characters for two or more
products.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_PathExt.PathExt
:p.
:hp2.PathExt:ehp2. = Yes &splitvbar. NO&colon. Determines whether
&4OS2. will use the PATHEXT environment variable. If set to No (the
default), the PATHEXT variable is ignored. If set to Yes, the PATHEXT
variable will be used to determine extensions to look for when searching
the PATH for an executable file. For details, see the :link reftype=hd
refid=PATHEXT.PATHEXT:elink. variable and the :link reftype=hd
refid=PATH.PATH:elink. command.
:p.
:hp8.CAUTION&colon. If you set PathExt = Yes in :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. and then fail
to set the PATHEXT variable, path searches will fail as there will be no
extensions for which to search!:ehp8.
:p.
PATHEXT is supported for compatibility reasons but should not generally
be used as a substitute for the more flexible :link reftype=hd
refid=ExeExt.executable extensions:elink. feature.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_PopupWinLeft.PopupWinLeft, PopupWinTop, PopupWinWidth, PopupWinHeight
:p.
:hp2.PopupWinLeft:ehp2. = nnnn, :hp2.PopupWinTop:ehp2. = nnnn,
:hp2.PopupWinWidth:ehp2. = nnnn, :hp2.PopupWinHeight:ehp2. = nnnn&colon. These
values set the position and size of the command-line,
directory history, and filename completion windows, and most other popup
windows (see :link reftype=hd refid=INI_CDDWinLeft.CDDWinLeft:elink. etc.
for the extended directory search window). The values are in characters,
and include the border. The defaults are 40, 1, 36, and 12, respectively
(i.e., a window beginning in column 40, row 1, 36 columns wide and 12 rows
high). The position is relative to the top left corner of the screen. The
width and height values include the space required for the window border.
:p.
The window cannot be smaller than than 10 columns wide by 5 rows high
(including the border). The values you enter will be adjusted if necessary
to keep a minimum-size window visible on the screen.
:p.
The window is normally displayed with a shadow, but if you specify a window
starting at column 0 and extending to the right margin, the shadow is
eliminated; this may be useful to prevent speech software from reading text
in the shadow area while viewing the window.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_PopupWinPosRelative.PopupWinPosRelative
:p.
:hp2.PopupWinPosRelative:ehp2. = YES &splitvbar. No&colon. Determines whether &4OS2.
should place the popup window relative to the current cursor position.
:p.
The position of popup windows is defined in the options dialog. If PopupWinPosRelative=YES (default),
popup windows are positioned relative to the current cursor line. Otherwise the position is defined
by the top of the window.
:p.
If PopupWinPosRelative=YES you can use negative values to place popup windows below the current cursor line.
Of course popup windows can not be placed outside the current window. The position is dynamically adopted to fit
into the window if the specified value would go beyond boundaries.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_Printer.Printer
:p.
:hp2.Printer:ehp2. = devicename&colon. Sets the output device that the
:link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink. command will print to. By default, LPT1 is used.
The device can be PRN, LPT1 to 3, COM1 to 4, NUL (which will
disable printed output) or any other installed character device.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_ScreenRows.ScreenRows
:p.
:hp2.ScreenRows:ehp2. = nnnn&colon. Sets the number of screen rows used by
the video display. Normally the screen size is determined
automatically, but if you have a non-standard display you may need
to set it explicitly. This value does not affect screen scrolling,
which is controlled by OS/2 and your video driver.
:p.
ScreenRows is used only by the :link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink. commands, the paged output
options of other commands (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., TYPE /P), and error checking
in the screen output commands.
:p.
Also see :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /R.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_TabStops.TabStops
:p.
:hp2.TabStops:ehp2. = nnnn (8)&colon. Sets the tab stops for files
displayed with the :link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink. command. Setting
TabStops=3, for example, will place a tab stop in every third column. The
allowable range is 1 to 32.
.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_ThousandsChar.ThousandsChar
:p.
:hp2.ThousandsChar:ehp2. = . &splitvbar. , &splitvbar. AUTO&colon. Sets the
character used as the thousands separator for numeric output. The only
valid settings are period [:hp2..:ehp2.], comma [:hp2.,:ehp2.], and
:hp2.Auto:ehp2. (the default). A setting of Auto tells the command
processor to use the thousands separator associated with your current country
code. If you change the thousands character you must also adjust the decimal
character (with :link reftype=hd refid=INI_DecimalChar.DecimalChar:elink.)
so that the two characters are different.
:p.
Also see :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /G.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_TitleIsCurDir.TitleIsCurDir
:p.
:hp2.TitleIsCurDir:ehp2. = YES &splitvbar. No&colon. Determines whether
the OS/2 session title should reflect the the current path.
:p.
Window title is current path by default. Of course, if title is set
with title or window command, this will be used instead. To set back default
title (current path), use title /d. If you ever want a window title of "/d"
(without quotes), use window "/d" (with quotes). Use TitleIsCurDir=No or title /c
if you like the old 4os2 standard titles ('4os2 Window' / '4os2 Full Screen')
:p.
Also see :link reftype=hd refid=_WINTITLE._WINTITLE:elink. and :link
reftype=hd refid=TITLE.TITLE:elink. internal variable.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_TmSmpFmt.TmSmpFmt
:p.
:hp2.TmSmpFmt:ehp2. = YY-MM-DD-HH-MM(-SS)&colon. Sets the format for 
the time stamp string returned by :link reftype=hd refid=_TMSMP._TMSMP:elink..
If the format is not set the default date and time formats are used.
:p.
The separator may be "-" or omitted.  The "/" separator is not supported.
:p.
The date field order may be controlled in the same way as
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_DateFmt.DateFmt:elink..
The time field order is fixed at HH-MM-SS,
although seconds may be omitted from the output string.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_UnixPaths.UnixPaths
:p.
:hp2.UnixPaths:ehp2. = Yes &splitvbar. NO&colon. Enables the forward
slash as a path separator in the command name (the first item on the
command line) and for :link reftype=hd refid=FileComp.filename completion:elink.&per.
This allows you to enter a command like&colon.
:xmp.
     [c&colon.\] /bin/programs/foo.exe
:exmp.:p.
without having the forward slashes (:hp2./:ehp2.) interpreted as switch characters.
It also also the forward slash to be used as the path element separator
for filename completion.
:p.
Note that setting UnixPaths to Yes does :hp2.not:ehp2. change the command
processor or operating system switch character. It's still ':hp2./:ehp2.'. It
simply allows you to put forward slashes in the command name, and in some case
command arguments, without problems.
:p.
When UnixPaths is set to Yes command switches beginning with a forward
slash must be preceded by a space to avoid confusion (this is a good
general practice regardless of the setting of UnixPaths). For example&colon.
:xmp.
     [c&colon.\] \bin\foo.exe /c           OK
     [c&colon.\] /bin/foo.exe /c           OK
     [c&colon.\] /bin/foo.exe c&colon./path/to/file  OK for some foo
     [c&colon.\] \bin\foo.exe/c        Error
     [c&colon.\] /bin/foo.exe/c        Error
:exmp.:p.
:hp2.Warning&colon.:ehp2. UNIX compatibility is not yet fully implemented.
Internal commands will continue to interpret forward slashes in command arguments
as the switch character.
The workaround is to quote the path arguments that contain the forward slashes.
:p.


.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_UpperCase.UpperCase
:p.
:hp2.UpperCase:ehp2. = Yes &splitvbar. NO&colon. :hp2.Yes:ehp2. specifies
that file and directory names should be displayed in the traditional
upper-case by internal commands like COPY and DIR. :hp2.No:ehp2. allows the
normal &4OS2. lower-case style. This directive does not affect the display of
filenames on case-retentive filesystem volumes (HPFS, JFS, FAT32, etc.).
:p.
Also see :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /U.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_Year4Digit.Year4Digit
:p.
:hp2.Year4Digit:ehp2. = Yes &splitvbar. NO&colon. :hp2.Yes:ehp2. specifies
that dates will display 4 digit years. Otherwise they will be 2 digit unless
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_DateFmt.DateFmt:elink. is set with 4 digit years.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=INIColor.Color Directives
:p.
These directives control the colors that &4OS2. use for its displays.
Screen border colors can only be set in StdColors. "BORder" color
specifications included in other directives will be ignored. For
complete details on color names see
:link reftype=hd refid=Colors.Colors and Color Names:elink.&per. The color directives are&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=24 break=fit.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_BrightBG.BrightBG:elink.:pd.Bright background colors
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_CDDWinColors.CDDWinColors:elink.:pd.Directory change window colors
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ColorDir.ColorDir:elink.:pd.Directory colors
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_InputColors.InputColors:elink.:pd.Input colors
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ListboxBarColors.ListboxBarColors:elink.:pd.Light bar color in list boxes
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ListColors.ListColors:elink.:pd.LIST display colors
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ListStatBarColors.ListStatBarColors:elink.:pd.LIST status bar colors
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_PopupWinColors.PopupWinColors:elink.:pd.Popup window colors
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_SelectColors.SelectColors:elink.:pd.SELECT display colors
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_SelectStatBarColors.SelectStatBarColors:elink.:pd.SELECT status bar colors
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_StdColors.StdColors:elink.:pd.Standard display colors
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_BrightBG.BrightBG
:p.
:hp2.BrightBG:ehp2. = Yes &splitvbar. No. If set to :hp2.Yes:ehp2., &4OS2. will
enable bright background colors in full-screen sessions. If set to :hp2.No:ehp2., bright
backgrounds will be disabled, but blinking foreground characters
will be enabled. If BrightBG is not used, &4OS2. will not
adjust the bright background / blinking foreground switch at all. Most
color video boards default to a blinking foreground with
bright background colors disabled.
:p.
See also :link reftype=hd refid=SETDOS.SETDOS:elink. /B.
:p.
Using BrightBG requires careful attention to interactions of
display type, mode, and color. For a detailed explanation, see
:link reftype=hd refid=Colors.Colors and Color Names:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_CDDWinColors.CDDWinColors
:p.
:hp2.CDDWinColors:ehp2. = Color&colon. Sets the default colors for the
popup window used by :link reftype=hd refid=ExtDirSearch.extended directory
searches:elink.&per. If this directive is not used, the colors will be reversed
from the current colors on the screen.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_ColorDir.ColorDir
:p.
:hp2.ColorDir:ehp2. = ext1 ext2 ...&colon.colora;ext3 ext4 ...
&colon.colorb; ...&colon. Sets the directory colors used by DIR and
SELECT. The format is the same as that used for the COLORDIR environment
variable. See the Color-Coded Directories topic under the :link reftype=hd
refid=DIR.DIR:elink. command for a complete description of the format of
this variable.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_InputColors.InputColors
:p.
:hp2.InputColors:ehp2. = Color&colon. Sets the colors used for command-line
input. This setting is useful for making your input stand out from
the normal output.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_ListboxBarColors.ListboxBarColors
:p.
:hp2.ListboxBarColors:ehp2. = Color&colon. Sets the color for the highlight
bar in the popup list boxes (:hp1.i.e.:ehp1., :link reftype=hd
refid=HistWin.command history window:elink., :link reftype=hd
refid=FileComp.filename completion:elink. window, :link reftype=hd
refid=_@SELECT.@SELECT:elink. window, etc.).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_ListColors.ListColors
:p.
:hp2.ListColors:ehp2. = Color&colon. Sets the colors used by the :link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink.
command. If this directive is not used, LIST will use the current
default colors set by the :link reftype=hd refid=CLS.CLS:elink. or :link reftype=hd refid=COLOR.COLOR:elink. command
or by the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_StdColors.StdColors:elink. directive.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_ListStatBarColors.ListStatBarColors
:p.
:hp2.ListStatBarColors:ehp2. = Color&colon. Sets the colors used on the
:link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink. status bar. If this directive is
not used, LIST will set the status bar to the reverse of the screen color (the
screen color is controlled by :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_ListColors.ListColors:elink.).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_PopupWinColors.PopupWinColors
:p.
:hp2.PopupWinColors:ehp2. = Color&colon. Sets the default colors for the
command-line, directory history, and filename completion windows, and most
other popup windows (see :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_CDDWinColors.CDDWinColors:elink. for the extended directory search
window). If this directive is not used, the colors will be reversed from
the current colors on the screen.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_SelectColors.SelectColors
:p.
:hp2.SelectColors:ehp2. = Color&colon. Sets the color used by the
:link reftype=hd refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink. command. If this directive is
not used, SELECT will use the current default colors set by the :link
reftype=hd refid=CLS.CLS:elink. or :link reftype=hd refid=COLOR.COLOR:elink.
command or by the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_StdColors.StdColors:elink.
directive.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_SelectStatBarColors.SelectStatBarColors
:p.
:hp2.SelectStatBarColors:ehp2. = Color&colon. Sets the color used on the
:link reftype=hd refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink. status bar. If this directive
is not used, SELECT will set the status bar to the reverse of the screen color
(the screen color is controlled by
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_SelectColors.SelectColors:elink.).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_StdColors.StdColors
:p.
:hp2.StdColors:ehp2. = Color&colon. Sets the standard colors to be used when
:link reftype=hd refid=CLS.CLS:elink. is used without a color specification, and for
:link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink. and :link reftype=hd refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink. if
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ListColors.ListColors:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_SelectColors.SelectColors:elink. are not
used. Using this directive is similar to placing a :link reftype=hd
refid=COLOR.COLOR:elink. command in 4START.
:p.
StdColors takes effect the first time :link reftype=hd refid=CLS.CLS:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink., or :link reftype=hd
refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink. is used after &4OS2. starts, but will not affect
the color of error or other messages displayed during the loading and
initialization process.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=INIKeyMap.Key Mapping Directives
:p.
These directives allow you to change the keys used for command-line
editing and other internal functions. They are divided into four types,
depending upon the context in which the keys are used. For a discussion
and list of directives for each type see&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=INIGenKeys.General Input Keys:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=INIEditKeys.Command-Line Editing Keys:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=INIHWinKeys.Popup Window Keys:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=INIListKeys.LIST Keys:elink.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
Using a key mapping directive allows you to assign a different or
additional key to perform the function described. For example, to
use function key :hp2.F3:ehp2. to invoke the HELP facility (normally
invoked with :hp2.F1:ehp2.)&colon.
:xmp.
    Help = F3
:exmp.:p.
Any directive can be used multiple times to assign multiple keys to
the same function. For example&colon.
:xmp.
    ListFind = F        ;F does a find in LIST
    ListFind = F5       ;F5 also does a find in LIST
:exmp.:p.
Use some care when you reassign keystrokes. If you assign a
default key to a different function, it will no longer be available
for its original use. For example, if you assign :hp2.F1:ehp2. to the
AddFile directive (a part of filename completion), the :hp2.F1:ehp2. key
will no longer invoke the help system, so you will probably want to
assign a different key to Help.
:p.
See :link reftype=hd refid=KeyNames.Keys and Key Names:elink. before using the key mapping
directives.
:p.
Key assignments are processed before looking for keystroke aliases. For
example, if you assign :hp2.Shift-F1:ehp2. to HELP and also assign
:hp2.Shift-F1:ehp2. to a key alias, the key alias will be ignored.
:p.
Assigning a new keystroke for a function does not deassign the
default keystroke for the same function. If you want to deassign
one of the default keys, use the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_NormalKey.NormalKey:elink.
directive described below or the corresponding directive for keys
in the other key groups (:link reftype=hd refid=INI_NormalEditKey.NormalEditKey:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_NormalPopupKey.NormalPopupKey:elink., or
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_NormalListKey.NormalListKey:elink.).

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INIGenKeys.General Input Keys
:p.
These directives apply to all input. They are in effect whenever
&4OS2. requests input from the keyboard, including during
:link reftype=hd refid=Editing.command-line editing:elink. and the :link reftype=hd refid=DESCRIBE.DESCRIBE:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=ESET.ESET:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=INPUT.INPUT:elink., :link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink. commands. The general input keys are&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=20 break=fit.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_Backspace.Backspace:elink.:pd.Deletes the character to the left of the cursor
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_BeginLine.BeginLine:elink.:pd.Moves the cursor to the start of the line
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_Del.Del:elink.:pd.Deletes the character at the cursor
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_DelToBeginning.DelToBeginning:elink.:pd.Deletes from the cursor to the start of the line
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_DelToEnd.DelToEnd:elink.:pd.Deletes from the cursor to the end of the line
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_DelWordLeft.DelWordLeft:elink.:pd.Deletes the word to the left of the cursor
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_DelWordRight.DelWordRight:elink.:pd.Deletes the word to the right of the cursor
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_Down.Down:elink.:pd.* Moves the cursor or scrolls the display down
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_EndLine.EndLine:elink.:pd.Moves the cursor to the end of the line
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_EraseLine.EraseLine:elink.:pd.Deletes the entire line
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ExecLine.ExecLine:elink.:pd.Executes or accepts a line
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_Ins.Ins:elink.:pd.Toggles insert / overstrike mode
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_Left.Left:elink.:pd.* Moves the cursor or scrolls the display left
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_NormalKey.NormalKey:elink.:pd.* Deassigns a key
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_Right.Right:elink.:pd.* Moves the cursor or scrolls the display right
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_Up.Up:elink.:pd.* Moves the cursor or scrolls the display up
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_WordLeft.WordLeft:elink.:pd.Moves the cursor left one word
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_WordRight.WordRight:elink.:pd.Moves the cursor right one word
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_Backspace.Backspace
:p.
:hp2.Backspace:ehp2. = Key (Bksp)&colon. Deletes the character to the left of
the cursor.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_BeginLine.BeginLine
:p.
:hp2.BeginLine:ehp2. = Key (Home)&colon. Moves the cursor to the beginning of
the line.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_Del.Del
:p.
:hp2.Del:ehp2. = Key (Del)&colon. Deletes the character at the cursor.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_DelToBeginning.DelToBeginning
:p.
:hp2.DelToBeginning:ehp2. = Key (Ctrl-Home)&colon. Deletes from the cursor to
the start of the line.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_DelToEnd.DelToEnd
:p.
:hp2.DelToEnd:ehp2. = Key (Ctrl-End)&colon. Deletes from the cursor to the end
of the line.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_DelWordLeft.DelWordLeft
:p.
:hp2.DelWordLeft:ehp2. = Key (Ctrl-L)&colon. Deletes the word to the left of
the cursor.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_DelWordRight.DelWordRight
:p.
:hp2.DelWordRight:ehp2. = Key (Ctrl-R, Ctrl-Bksp)&colon. Deletes the word to
the right of the cursor. See :link reftype=hd refid=INI_ClearKeyMap.ClearKeyMap:elink. if
you need to remove the default mapping of :hp2.Ctrl-Bksp:ehp2. to this
function.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_Down.Down
:p.
:hp2.Down:ehp2. = Key (Down)&colon. Scrolls the display down one line in LIST;
moves the cursor down one line in :link reftype=hd refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink. and in the
command-line history, directory history, or :link reftype=hd refid=_@SELECT.%@SELECT:elink.
window. (Scrolling down through the command history at the prompt
is controlled by :link reftype=hd refid=INI_NextHistory.NextHistory:elink., not by this
directive.)

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_EndLine.EndLine
:p.
:hp2.EndLine:ehp2. = Key (End)&colon. Moves the cursor to the end of the line.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_EraseLine.EraseLine
:p.
:hp2.EraseLine:ehp2. = Key (Esc)&colon. Deletes the entire line.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_ExecLine.ExecLine
:p.
:hp2.ExecLine:ehp2. = Key (Enter)&colon. Executes or accepts a line.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_Ins.Ins
:p.
:hp2.Ins:ehp2. = Key (Ins)&colon. Toggles insert / overstrike mode during line
editing.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_Left.Left
:p.
:hp2.Left:ehp2. = Key (Left)&colon. Moves the cursor left one character on
the input line; scrolls the display left 8 columns in LIST; scrolls the
display left 4 columns in the command-line, directory history, or
:link reftype=hd refid=_@SELECT.%@SELECT:elink. window.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_NormalKey.NormalKey
:p.
:hp2.NormalKey:ehp2. = Key&colon. Deassigns a general input key in order to
disable the usual meaning of the key within &4OS2. and/or make it
available for keystroke aliases. This will make the keystroke
operate as a "normal" key with no special function. For example&colon.
:xmp.
    NormalKey = Ctrl-End
:exmp.:p.
will disable Ctrl-End, which is the standard "delete to end of
line" key. Ctrl-End could then be assigned to a keystroke alias.
Another key could be assigned the "delete to end of line" function
with the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_DelToEnd.DelToEnd:elink. directive.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_Right.Right
:p.
:hp2.Right:ehp2. = Key (Right)&colon. Moves the cursor right one character
on the input line; scrolls the display right 8 columns in :link reftype=hd
refid=LIST.LIST:elink.; scrolls the display right 4 columns in the
command-line history, directory history, or :link reftype=hd
refid=_@SELECT.%@SELECT:elink. window.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_Up.Up
:p.
:hp2.Up:ehp2. = Key (Up)&colon. Scrolls the display up one line in
:link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink.; moves the cursor up one line in :link reftype=hd refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink.
and in the command-line history, directory history, or
:link reftype=hd refid=_@SELECT.%@SELECT:elink. window. (Scrolling up through the command
history at the prompt is controlled by
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_PrevHistory.PrevHistory:elink., not by this directive.)

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_WordLeft.WordLeft
:p.
:hp2.WordLeft:ehp2. = Key (Ctrl-Left)&colon. Moves the cursor left one word;
scrolls the display left 40 columns in :link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_WordRight.WordRight
:p.
:hp2.WordRight:ehp2. = Key (Ctrl-Right)&colon. Moves the cursor right one
word; scrolls the display right 40 columns in :link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INIEditKeys.Command-Line Editing Keys
:p.
These directives apply only to command-line editing. They are only
effective at the &4OS2. prompt. The command-line editing keys are&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=20 break=fit.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_AddFile.AddFile:elink.:pd.Keeps filename completion entry and adds another
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_AliasExpand.AliasExpand:elink.:pd.Expands aliases without executing them
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_CommandEscape.CommandEscape:elink.:pd.Allows direct entry of a keystroke
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_DelHistory.DelHistory:elink.:pd.Deletes a history list entry
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_EndHistory.EndHistory:elink.:pd.Displays the last entry in the history list
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_Help.Help:elink.:pd.Invokes this help system
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_LineToEnd.LineToEnd:elink.:pd.Copies the current line to the end of the history
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_NextFile.NextFile:elink.:pd.Gets the next matching filename
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_NextHistory.NextHistory:elink.:pd.Recalls the next command from the history
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_NormalEditKey.NormalEditKey:elink.:pd.Deassigns a command-line editing key
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_PopFile.PopFile:elink.:pd.Opens the filename completion window
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_PrevFile.PrevFile:elink.:pd.Gets the previous matching filename
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_PrevHistory.PrevHistory:elink.:pd.Recalls the previous command from the history
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_SaveHistory.SaveHistory:elink.:pd.Saves the command line without executing it
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_AddFile.AddFile
:p.
:hp2.AddFile:ehp2. = Key (F10)&colon. Keeps the current filename completion
entry and inserts the next matching name.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_AliasExpand.AliasExpand
:p.
:hp2.AliasExpand:ehp2. = Key (Ctrl-F)&colon. Expands all aliases in the
current command line without executing them.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_CommandEscape.CommandEscape
:p.
:hp2.CommandEscape:ehp2. = Key (Alt-255)&colon. Allows direct entry of a
keystroke that would normally be handled by the command line editor
(:hp1.e.g.:ehp1. :hp2.Tab:ehp2. or :hp2.Ctrl-D):ehp2.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_DelHistory.DelHistory
:p.
:hp2.DelHistory:ehp2. = Key (Ctrl-D)&colon. Deletes the displayed history list
entry and displays the previous entry.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_EndHistory.EndHistory
:p.
:hp2.EndHistory:ehp2. = Key (Ctrl-E)&colon. Displays the last entry in the
history list.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_Help.Help
:p.
:hp2.Help:ehp2. = Key (F1)&colon. Invokes the HELP facility.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_LineToEnd.LineToEnd
:p.
:hp2.LineToEnd:ehp2. = Key (Ctrl-Enter)&colon. Copies the current command
line to the end of the history list, then executes it.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_NextFile.NextFile
:p.
:hp2.NextFile:ehp2. = Key (F9, Tab)&colon. Gets the next matching filename.
See :link reftype=hd refid=INI_ClearKeyMap.ClearKeyMap:elink. if you need to
remove the default mapping of :hp2.Tab:ehp2. to this function.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_NextHistory.NextHistory
:p.
:hp2.NextHistory:ehp2. = Key (Down)&colon. Recalls the next command from the
command history.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_NormalEditKey.NormalEditKey
:p.
:hp2.NormalEditKey:ehp2. = Key&colon. Deassigns a command-line editing key in
order to disable the usual meaning of the key while editing a
command line, and/or make it available for keystroke aliases. For
additional details see :link reftype=hd refid=INI_NormalKey.NormalKey:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_PopFile.PopFile
:p.
:hp2.PopFile:ehp2. = Key (F7, Ctrl-Tab)&colon. Opens the filename completion
window. You may not be able to use :hp2.Ctrl-Tab:ehp2., because not all
systems recognize it as a keystroke. See
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ClearKeyMap.ClearKeyMap:elink. if you need to
remove the default mapping of :hp2.Ctrl-Tab:ehp2. to this function.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_PrevFile.PrevFile
:p.
:hp2.PrevFile:ehp2. = Key (F8, Shift-Tab)&colon. Gets the previous matching
filename. See :link reftype=hd refid=INI_ClearKeyMap.ClearKeyMap:elink. if
you need to remove the default mapping of :hp2.Shift-Tab:ehp2. to this
function.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_PrevHistory.PrevHistory
:p.
:hp2.PrevHistory:ehp2. = Key (Up)&colon. Recalls the previous command from
the command history.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_SaveHistory.SaveHistory
:p.
:hp2.SaveHistory:ehp2. = Key (Ctrl-K)&colon. Saves the command line in the
command history list without executing it.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INIHWinKeys.Popup Window Keys
:p.
These directives apply to popup windows, including the command history
window, the directory history window, the filename completion window, the
extended directory search window, and the :link reftype=hd
refid=_@SELECT.%@SELECT:elink. window. The popup window keys are&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=20 break=fit.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_DirWinOpen.DirWinOpen:elink.:pd.Opens the directory history window
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_HistWinOpen.HistWinOpen:elink.:pd.Opens the command history window
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_NormalPopupKey.NormalPopupKey:elink.:pd.Deassigns a popup window key
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_PopupWinBegin.PopupWinBegin:elink.:pd.Moves to the first line of the popup window
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_PopupWinDel.PopupWinDel:elink.:pd.Deletes a line from within the popup window
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_PopupWinEdit.PopupWinEdit:elink.:pd.Moves a line from the popup window to the prompt
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_PopupWinEnd.PopupWinEnd:elink.:pd.Moves to the last line of the popup window
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_PopupWinExec.PopupWinExec:elink.:pd.Executes the selected line in the popup window
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_DirWinOpen. DirWinOpen
:p.
:hp2.DirWinOpen:ehp2. = Key (Ctrl-PgUp)&colon. Opens the directory history
window while at the command line.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_HistWinOpen.HistWinOpen
:p.
:hp2.HistWinOpen:ehp2. = Key (PgUp)&colon. Brings up the history window while
at the command line.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_NormalPopupKey.NormalPopupKey
:p.
:hp2.NormalPopupKey:ehp2. = Key&colon. Deassigns a popup window key in
order to disable the usual meaning of the key within the popup window.
:p.
For additional details see :link reftype=hd
refid=INI_NormalKey.NormalKey:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_PopupWinBegin.PopupWinBegin
:p.
:hp2.PopupWinBegin:ehp2. = Key (Ctrl-PgUp)&colon. Moves to the first item in
the list when in the popup window

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_PopupWinDel.PopupWinDel
:p.
:hp2.PopupWinDel:ehp2. = Key (Ctrl-D)&colon. Deletes a line from within the
command history or directory history window.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_PopupWinEdit.PopupWinEdit
:p.
:hp2.PopupWinEdit:ehp2. = Key (Ctrl-Enter)&colon. Moves a line from the
command history or directory history window to the prompt for editing.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_PopupWinEnd.PopupWinEnd
:p.
:hp2.PopupWinEnd:ehp2. = Key (Ctrl-PgDn)&colon. Moves to the last item
when in the popup window.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_PopupWinExec.PopupWinExec
:p.
:hp2.PopupWinExec:ehp2. = Key (Enter)&colon. Selects the current item and
closes the window.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INIListKeys.LIST Keys
:p.
These directives are effective only inside the :link reftype=hd refid=LIST.LIST:elink.
command. The LIST keys are&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=20 break=fit.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ListExit.ListExit:elink.:pd.Exits the current file.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ListFind.ListFind:elink.:pd.Prompts and searches for a string
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ListFindReverse.ListFindReverse:elink.:pd.Prompts and searches backward for a string
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ListHex.ListHex:elink.:pd.Toggles hexadecimal display mode
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ListHighBit.ListHighBit:elink.:pd.Toggles LIST's "strip high bit" option
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ListInfo.ListInfo:elink.:pd.Displays information about the current file
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ListNext.ListNext:elink.:pd.Finds the next matching string
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ListPrevious.ListPrevious:elink.:pd.Finds the previous matching string
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ListPrint.ListPrint:elink.:pd.Prints the file on LPT1
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ListWrap.ListWrap:elink.:pd.Toggles LIST's wrap option
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_NormalListKey.NormalListKey:elink.:pd.Deassigns a LIST key
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_ListExit.ListExit
:p.
:hp2.ListExit:ehp2. = Key (Esc)&colon. Exits from the LIST command.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_ListFind.ListFind
:p.
:hp2.ListFind:ehp2. = Key (F)&colon. Prompts and searches for a string.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_ListFindReverse.ListFindReverse
:p.
:hp2.ListFindReverse:ehp2. = Key (Ctrl-F)&colon. Prompts and searches
backward for a string.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_ListHex.ListHex
:p.
:hp2.ListHex:ehp2. = Key (X)&colon. Toggles hexadecimal display mode.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_ListHighBit.ListHighBit
:p.
:hp2.ListHighBit:ehp2. = Key (H)&colon. Toggles LIST's "strip high bit"
option, which can aid in displaying files from certain word processors.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_ListInfo.ListInfo
:p.
:hp2.ListInfo:ehp2. = Key (I)&colon. Displays information about the current
file.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_ListNext.ListNext
:p.
:hp2.ListNext:ehp2. = Key (N)&colon. Finds the next matching string.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_ListPrevious.ListPrevious
:p.
:hp2.ListPrevious:ehp2. = Key (Ctrl-N)&colon. Finds the previous matching
string.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_ListPrint.ListPrint
:p.
:hp2.ListPrint:ehp2. = Key (P)&colon. Prints the file on LPT1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_ListWrap.ListWrap
:p.
:hp2.ListWrap:ehp2. = Key (W)&colon. Toggles LIST's wrap option on and off.
The wrap option wraps text at the right margin.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h5 name=INI_NormalListKey.NormalListKey
:p.
:hp2.NormalListKey:ehp2. = Key&colon. Deassigns a LIST key in order to disable
the usual meaning of the key within LIST. For additional details
see :link reftype=hd refid=INI_NormalKey.NormalKey:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=INIAdv.Advanced Directives
:p.
These directives are generally used for unusual circumstances, or
for diagnosing problems. Most often they are not needed in normal
use. The advanced directives are&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=20 break=fit.
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ClearKeyMap.ClearKeyMap:elink.:pd.Clear default key mappings
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_Debug.Debug:elink.:pd.Set debugging options
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_Include.Include:elink.:pd.Include a file containing :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. directives
:pt.:link reftype=hd refid=INI_NextINIFile.NextINIFile:elink.:pd.Set secondary shell :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. filename
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_ClearKeyMap.ClearKeyMap
:p.
:hp2.ClearKeyMap:ehp2.&colon. Clears all current
:link reftype=hd refid=INIKeyMap.key mappings:elink.&per. ClearKeyMap is a
special directive which has no value or "=" after it. Use ClearKeyMap to make
one of the keys in the default map (:hp2.Tab:ehp2., :hp2.Shift-Tab:ehp2.,
:hp2.Ctrl-Tab:ehp2., or :hp2.Ctrl-Bksp:ehp2.) available for a keystroke alias,
or in the :hp2.[Secondary]:ehp2. section of the
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. file to clear key mappings
inherited from the primary shell. ClearKeyMap should appear before any key
mapping directives. If you want to clear some but not all of the default
mappings, use ClearKeyMap, then recreate the mappings you want to
retain (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1., with "NextFile=Tab", etc.).
:p.
If you set :hp2.DescriptionName = EA, :ehp2.&4OS2. will use the ".SUBJECT"
extended attribute (EA) for file descriptions instead of a separate
file. Note that using EAs will slow the :link reftype=hd
refid=DIR.DIR:elink. and :link reftype=hd refid=SELECT.SELECT:elink.
commands noticeably. On a FAT16 volume, performance may be 10% to 200%
slower, depending upon whether the system has cached the extended attributes.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_Debug.Debug
:p.
:hp2.Debug:ehp2. = nnnn (0)&colon. Controls certain debugging options which
can assist you in tracking down unusual problems. Use the following values
for Debug; to select more than one option, add the values together:
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.1:ehp2.:pd.During the startup process, display the complete command
tail passed to &4OS2., then wait for a keystroke.
:pt.:hp2.2:ehp2.:pd.Include the product name with each error message
displayed by &4OS2.. This may be useful if you are unsure of the origin of a
particular error message.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
:p.
Also see the :link reftype=hd refid=BatchDebug.batch file debugger:elink., a
separate and unrelated facility for stepping through batch files.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_Include.Include
:p.
:hp2.Include:ehp2. = File&colon. Include the text from the named file at
this point in the processing of the current :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. file. Use this
option to share a file of directives between several products. The text in
the named file is processed just as if it were part of the original
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. file. When the include file is finished, processing resumes
at the point where it left off in the original file. The included file may contain any valid directive for the
current section, but may not contain a section name. Includes may be nested up
to three levels deep (counting the original file as level 1).
:p.
You must maintain include files manually -- the :link reftype=hd
refid=OPTION.OPTION:elink. command modifies the original :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.
file only, and does not update included files.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h4 name=INI_NextINIFile.NextINIFile
:p.
:hp2.NextINIFile:ehp2. = File. The full path and name of the file must be
specified. All subsequent shells will read the specified :link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink.
file, and ignore any :hp2.[Secondary]:ehp2. section in the original
:link reftype=hd refid=INIFile.&4OS2INI.:elink. file.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=INIExamples..INI File Examples
:p.
This example configures certain special characters to match &4OS2., and
changes other default settings to suit the user's preferences. Note that
the comments for the :link reftype=hd refid=INI_HelpBook.HelpBook:elink. and
:link reftype=hd refid=INI_ColorDir.ColorDir:elink. directives are on
separate lines before the directives themselves, as no comments are allowed
in string directives&colon.
:xmp.
    [4OS2]
    InstallPath = c&colon.\4OS2300      ;installation directory
    PauseOnError = No         ;don't stop on INI errors
    CommandSep = ^        ;4OS2 command separator
    ParameterChar = &amp.    ;4OS2 parameter character
    BatchEcho = No        ;default to ECHO OFF
                      ;show only 4OS2 help for F1 / HELP
    HelpBook = 4OS2
    History = 2048        ;expand history to 2K bytes
    BeepFreq = 880        ;make beep higher pitch
    EditMode = Insert         ;insert mode for cmd edit
    CursorOver = 100          ;overstrike cursor 100%
    CursorIns = 10        ;insert cursor 10%
    ListFind = F5         ;F5 does a find in LIST
    ListNext = F6         ;and F6 does a find next
    StdColors = bri cya on blu    ;default colors
    ListColors = bri whi on blu   ;colors for LIST
    SelectColors = bri whi on blu ;same colors for SELECT
                      ;set directory display colors
    colordir = DIRS&colon.bri yel;com exe bat btm cmd&colon.bri whi
:exmp.
:p.

