.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h2 name=FilesysRef.Filesystems and Filename Conventions
:p.
You may have dozens, hundreds, or thousands of files stored on your
computer's disks. Your operating system is responsible for managing all of
these files. In order to do so, it uses a unique name to locate each file in
much the same way that the post office assigns a unique address to every
residence.
:p.
The unique name of any file is composed of a :hp2.drive letter:ehp2., a
directory :hp2.path:ehp2., and a :hp2.filename:ehp2.&per. Each of these parts
of the file's name is case-insensitive; you can mix upper and lower case
letters in any way you wish.
:p.
The topics below are roughly divided according to the different parts of a
filename, and cover the filesystem structure and naming
conventions&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=DriveVol.Drives and Volumes:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=Filesys.Filesystems:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=Directories.Directories and Subdirectories:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=Filenames.Filenames:elink.
:pt.:pd.:link reftype=hd refid=FileAttr.File Attributes and Time Stamps:elink.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=DriveVol.Drives and Volumes
:p.
A :hp2.drive letter:ehp2. designates which drive contains the file. In a
file's full name, the drive letter is followed by a colon. Drive letters
:hp2.A&colon.:ehp2. and :hp2.B&colon.:ehp2. are normally reserved for the
floppy disk drives.
:p.
Normally, drive :hp2.C&colon.:ehp2. is the first (or only) hard disk
drive. Most current operating systems can divide a large hard disk into
multiple logical drives or :hp2.volumes:ehp2. that are usually called
:hp2.C&colon.:ehp2., :hp2.D&colon.:ehp2., :hp2.E&colon.:ehp2., etc. Network
systems (LANs) give additional drive letters to sections of the network file
server drives.
:p.
Most modern systems also include one or more optical (CD, DVD, BluRay) drives.
These drives are also assigned drive letter (or several letters, for disc
changers), typically using letters beyond that used by the last hard disk in the
system, but before any network drives. Some systems may have "RAM disks"
(sometimes called "virtual disks"), which are areas of memory set aside by
software (a "RAM disk driver") for use as fast but temporary storage. Like
optical drives, RAM disks are usually assigned drive letters beyond the last
hard disk in the system, but before network drives.
:p.
For example, on a system with a large hard disk you might have
:hp2.A&colon.:ehp2. and :hp2.B&colon.:ehp2. as floppy drives,
:hp2.C&colon.:ehp2., :hp2.D&colon.:ehp2., and :hp2.E&colon.:ehp2. as parts
of the hard disk, :hp2.F&colon.:ehp2. as a DVD-ROM drive, :hp2.G&colon.:ehp2.
as a RAM disk, and :hp2.H&colon.:ehp2. and :hp2.I&colon.:ehp2. as network
drives.
:p.
Each volume is formatted under a particular filesystem; see
:link reftype=hd refid=Filesys.Filesystems:elink. for details. Additional
information about disk files and directories is available under
:link reftype=hd refid=Directories.Directories and Subdirectories:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=Filenames.Filenames:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=FileAttr.File Attributes and Time Stamps:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=Filesys.Filesystems
:p.
Each disk volume is organized according to a :hp2.filesystem:ehp2.&per. The
filesystem determines how files are named and how they are organized on the
disk.
:p.
As hard disk technology and operating systems have evolved, new filesystems
have been invented to support longer filenames, larger volumes, and higher
disk performance. Several different and incompatible schemes have
evolved. Which filesystems you can use depend on which operating system
you are using, and how the operating system and your hard disk are configured.
:p.
The operating systems under which &4OS2. runs can support standard OS/2 file
systems&colon. JFS, HPFS, FAT16, and FAT32. See
:link reftype=hd refid=Filenames.Filenames:elink. for details on the rules
for naming files under each filesystem.
:p.
:lm margin=4.:parml tsize=4 break=fit.
:pt.*:pd.The :hp2.FAT16 filesystem:ehp2. is the traditional filesystem used
by all modern versions of DOS. Its name comes from the 16-bit :hp2.F:ehp2.ile
:hp2.A:ehp2.llocation :hp2.T:ehp2.able DOS uses to keep track of the space
allocated to each file. Windows 95, Windows NT, and OS/2 also support the
FAT16 filesystem, as do all Linux distributions.
:pt.*:pd.The :hp2.FAT12 filesystem:ehp2. is the traditional filesystem used
by earlier versions of DOS, and commonly found on floppy disk media. FAT12
follows the same naming conventions as FAT16, though it supports smaller
volumes with its more limited 12-bit FAT.
:pt.*:pd.The :hp2.High Performance File System:ehp2. or :hp2.HPFS:ehp2. is a
filesystem provided with all versions of OS/2, and is also supported in
Windows NT version 3.51 and below. It supports long filenames, and offers
higher performance and better support for large volumes (up to 64GB) than the
FAT16 filesystem. It also supports "extended attributes" to retain additional
information about your files. The maximum write cache for HPFS is 2MB.
:p.
DOS sessions running under OS/2 can access files on HPFS volumes if the
files have short, FAT-compatible names. Other operating systems (DOS,
Windows 95, and Windows NT 4.0 and above) can not access files on HPFS
volumes.
:pt.*:pd.The :hp2.Journaled File System:ehp2. or :hp2.JFS:ehp2. is a
filesystem ported from IBM's AIX to OS/2 (and subsequently available for Linux)
which supports volumes up to 2TB in size, and individual files up to 2TB. The
filesystem includes a "journal" of changes to be written to the volume and as
a result, crash recovery can be much faster than for non-journaled filesystems
(such as HPFS). JFS also supports large cache sizes (by default, 12.5% of
physical RAM).
:p.
As with HPFS, DOS sessions running under OS/2 can access files on HPFS volumes
if the files have short, FAT-compatible names. Also, as with HPFS, native DOS
and Windows systems can not access files on JFS volumes, although many Linux
distributions can (assuming the distribution includes a JFS driver).
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
:p.
Additional filesystems may be installed under some operating systems to
support optical (CD, DVD, BluRay) or network shares. The filesystem type
(e.g., JFS, HPFS, etc.) is determined when a hard disk volume is formatted and
applies to the entire volume. For example, under OS/2 you might have a 2TB hard
disk divided into four volumes, with the first three volumes (C&colon.,
D&colon., and E&colon.) formatted for the JFS filesystem, and the fourth
formatted for HPFS.
:p.
&4OS2. supports any standard filesystem installed under your operating
system. If your operating system can access files on a particular volume,
then &4OS2. will be able to access those files as well.
:p.
Additional information about disk files and directories is available under
:link reftype=hd refid=DriveVol.Drives and Volumes:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=Directories.Directories and Subdirectories:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=Filenames.Filenames:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=FileAttr.File Attributes and Time Stamps:elink.&per.
:p.
:p.
:hp2.Network Filesystems:ehp2.
:p.
A network filesystem allows you to access files stored on another computer
on a network, rather than on your own system. &4OS2. supports all network
filesystems which are recognized by the operating system.
:p.
File and directory names for network filesystems depend on both the "server"
software running on the system that has the files on it, and the "client"
software running on your computer to connect it to the network. However,
they usually follow the rules described under
:link reftype=hd refid=Filenames.Filenames:elink.&per.
:p.
Most network software "maps" unused drive letters on your system to specific
locations on the network, and you can then treat the drive as if it were
physically part of your local computer.
:p.
Some networks also support the :hp2.Universal Naming Convention:ehp2., which
provides a common method for accessing files on a network drive without
using a "mapped" drive letter. Names specified this way are called UNC
names. They typically appear as :hp2.\\server\volume\path\filename:ehp2.,
where :hp2.server:ehp2. is the name of the network server where the files
reside, :hp2.volume :ehp2.is the name of a disk volume on that server, and
the :hp2.path\filename:ehp2. portion is a directory name and filename
which follow the conventions described in :link reftype=hd
refid=Directories.Directories and Subdirectories:elink.&per. &4OS2. supports UNC
filenames, and also allows you to use UNC directory names when changing
directories (see :link reftype=hd refid=DirNav.Directory Navigation:elink.
for more details).
:p.
When you use a network filesystem, remember that the naming conventions for
files on the network may not match those on your local system. For example,
your local system may support long filenames while the network server or
client software does not, or vice versa. &4OS2. will usually handle whatever
naming conventions are supported by your network software, as long as the
network software accurately reports the types of names it can handle.
:p.
In rare cases, &4OS2. may not be able to report correct statistics on network
drives (such as the number of bytes free on a drive). This is usually
because the network filesystem does not provide complete or accurate
information.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=Directories. Directories and Subdirectories
:p.
:hp2.Directories:ehp2. are used to divide the files in a filesystem into
logical groups that are easy to work with. Their purpose is
similar to the use of file drawers to contain groups of hanging folders,
hanging folders to contain smaller manilla folders, and so
on. :hp2.Directories :ehp2.are also sometimes referred to as
:hp2.folders:ehp2., although generally, folders are "desktop constructs" simply
providing graphical representations of the directories in the filesystem.
:p.
Every volume has a :hp2.root:ehp2. or base directory, and many have one or
more :hp2. subdirectories:ehp2.&per. Subdirectories can also have
subdirectories, extending in a branching :hp2.tree:ehp2. structure from the
root directory. The collection of all directories on a drive is often
called the :hp2.directory tree:ehp2., and a portion of the tree is sometimes
called a :hp2.subtree:ehp2.&per. The terms :hp2.directory:ehp2. and
:hp2.subdirectory:ehp2. are typically used interchangeably to mean a single
subdirectory within this tree structure.
:p.
Subdirectory names follow the same rules as filenames (see
:link reftype=hd refid=Filenames.Filenames:elink.).
:p.
The drive letter and subdirectory portion of a file's name are collectively
called the file's :hp2.path:ehp2.&per. For example, the filename
:hp1.C&colon.\DIR1\DIR2\MYFILE.DAT:ehp1. says to look for the file
:hp1.MYFILE.DAT:ehp1. in the subdirectory :hp1.DIR2:ehp1. which is part of
the subdirectory :hp1.DIR1:ehp1. which is on drive C. The path for
:hp1.MYFILE.DAT:ehp1. is :hp1.C&colon.\DIR1\DIR2:ehp1.&per. The backslashes
between subdirectory names are required. On JFS and HPFS volumes the path
and filename must each be 255 bytes or less in length (255 UCS-2 characters
for FAT16, and FAT32), and in addition the total length of the path and
filename together cannot exceed 260 characters.
:p.
The operating system and command processor remember both a
:hp2.current:ehp2. or :hp2.default drive:ehp2. for your system as a whole,
and a :hp2.current:ehp2. or :hp2.default directory:ehp2. for every drive in
your system. Whenever a program tries to create or access a file without
specifying the file's path, the operating system uses the current drive (if
no other drive is specified) and the current directory (if no other
directory path is specified).
:p.
The root directory is named using the drive letter and a single
backslash. For example, D&colon.\ refers to the root directory
of drive D&colon.&per. Using a drive letter with no directory name
at all refers to the current directory on the specified drive. For example,
:hp1.E&colon.README.DOC:ehp1. refers to the file :hp1.README.DOC:ehp1. in
the current directory on drive E&colon., whereas
:hp1.E&colon.\README.DOC:ehp1. refers to the file :hp1.README.DOC:ehp1. in
the root directory on drive E&colon..
:p.
There are also two special subdirectory names that are useful in many
situations&colon. a single dot by itself [:hp2..:ehp2.] means "the
current default directory." Two dots together [:hp2...:ehp2.] means "the
directory which contains the current default directory" (often referred to
as the :hp2.parent directory:ehp2.). These special names can be used
wherever a full directory name can be used. &4OS2. allows you to use
additional dots to specify directories further "up" the tree (see :link
reftype=hd refid=ParDir.Extended Parent Directory Names:elink.).
:p.
Additional information about disk files and filesystems is available under
:link reftype=hd refid=DriveVol.Drives and Volumes:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=Filesys.Filesystems:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=Filenames.Filenames:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=FileAttr.File Attributes and Time Stamps:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=Filenames.Filenames
:p.
Under the FAT16 filesystem, the filename consists of a :hp2.base name:ehp2.
of 1 to 8 characters plus an optional :hp2.extension:ehp2. composed of a
dot plus 1 to 3 more characters.
:p.
You can use alphabetic and numeric characters plus the punctuation marks
:hp2.! # $ % &amp. ' ( ) - @ ^ _ ` { }:ehp2. and :hp2.~:ehp2. in both the
base name and the extension of a FAT filename. Because the exclamation
point [:hp2.!:ehp2.], percent sign [:hp2.%:ehp2.], caret [:hp2.^:ehp2.], at
sign [:hp2.@:ehp2.], parentheses [:hp2.():ehp2.], and back-quote
[:hp2.`:ehp2.] also have other meanings to &4OS2., it is best to avoid using
them in filenames.
:p.
The HPFS and JFS filesystems allow filenames up to 255 bytes in length (255
UNC-2 characters for FAT32), including spaces and other characters that are not
allowed in a FAT system filename, but excluding some punctuation characters
which are allowed in FAT16 filenames. See your operating system documentation
for details on the characters allowed. If you use filenames which contain
semicolons [:hp2.;:ehp2.], see :link reftype=hd refid=Wildcards.Wildcards:elink.
for details on avoiding problems with interpretation of those filenames under
&4OS2..
:p.
HPFS, JFS, and FAT32 filenames are stored and displayed exactly as entered, and
are not automatically shifted to upper or lower case. For example, you
could create a file called :hp1.MYFILE:ehp1., :hp1.myfile:ehp1., or
:hp1.MyFile:ehp1., and each name would be stored in the directory just as
you entered it. However, case is ignored when looking for filenames, so you
cannot have two files whose names differ only in case (:hp1.i.e.:ehp1., the
three names given above would all refer to the same file). This behavior is
sometimes described as "case-retentive but not case-sensitive" because the
case information is retained, but does not affect access to the files.
:p.
Files stored on volumes suporting long filenames often have "FAT-compatible"
names&colon. names which contain only those characters legal on a FAT16 volume,
and which meet the 8-character name / 3-character extension limits. Programs
which cannot handle long names generally can access files by using
FAT-compatible names.
:p.
If a filename includes spaces or other characters that
would not be allowed in a FAT16 name, you :hp2.must:ehp2. place double
quotes around the name. For example, suppose you have a file named
:hp1.LET3:ehp1. on a FAT16 volume, and you want to copy it to the
:hp1.LETTERS:ehp1. directory on drive F&colon., an HPFS partition, and give
it the name :hp1.Letter To Sara:ehp1.&per. To do so, use either of these
commands&colon.
:xmp.
    [c&colon.\wp] copy let3 f&colon.\LETTERS\"Letter To Sara"

    [c&colon.\wp] copy let3 "f&colon.\LETTERS\Letter To Sara"
:exmp.:p.
The HPFS, JFS, and FAT32 filesystems do not explicitly define an "extension" for
filenames which are not FAT-compatible. However, by convention, all characters
after the last period in the filename are treated as the extension. For
example, the filename :hp1."Letter to Sara":ehp1. has no extension, whereas the
name :hp1."Letter.to.Sara":ehp1. has the extension :hp1.Sara:ehp1.&per.
:p.
Additional information about disk files and filesystems is available under
:link reftype=hd refid=DriveVol.Drives and Volumes:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=Filesys.Filesystems:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=Directories.Directories and Subdirectories:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=FileAttr.File Attributes and Time Stamps:elink.&per.

.* --------------------------------------------------------------------------

:h3 name=FileAttr.File Attributes and Time Stamps
:p.
Each file also has :hp2.attributes:ehp2., and one or more :hp2.time
stamps:ehp2.&per. Attributes define characteristics of the file which may be
useful to the operating system, to you, or to an application program. Time
stamps can record when the file was created, last modified, or last
accessed. Most &4OS2. file processing commands allow you to select files for
processing based on their attributes and/or time stamp(s).
:p.
Each file on your system has four standard attributes. Every time a program
modifies a file, the operating system sets the :hp2.Archive:ehp2. attribute,
which signals that the file has been modified since it was last backed
up. This attribute can be used by &4OS2. to determine which files to :link
reftype=hd refid=COPY.COPY:elink., and by backup programs to determine which
files to back up. When the :hp2.Read-only:ehp2. attribute is set, the
file can't be changed or erased accidentally; this can be used to help
protect important files from damage. The :hp2.Hidden:ehp2. and
:hp2.System:ehp2. attributes prevent the file from appearing in normal
directory listings. (Two additional attributes, :hp2.Directory:ehp2. and
:hp2.Volume label:ehp2., are also available. These attributes are
controlled by the operating system, and are not modified directly by &4OS2..)
:p.
Attributes can be set and viewed with the :link reftype=hd
refid=ATTRIB.ATTRIB:elink. command. The :link reftype=hd
refid=DIR.DIR:elink. command also has options to select filenames to view
based on their attributes, to view the attributes themselves, and to view
information about normally "invisible" hidden and system files.
:p.
When a file is created, and every time it is modified, the operating system
records the system time and date in a :hp2.time stamp:ehp2. in the file's
directory entry. Several &4OS2. commands and variable functions, and many
backup and utility programs, use this time stamp to determine the relative
ages of files.
:p.
On FAT16 volumes, only the single time stamp described above is
available. Files on HPFS, JFS, and FAT32 volumes have three sets of time and
date stamps. The operating system records when each file was created, when it
was last written or modified, and when it was last accessed. The "last
write" time stamp matches the single time stamp used on traditional FAT16
volumes.
:p.
Several &4OS2. commands and variable functions let you specify which set of
time and date stamps you want to view or manipulate on volumes supporting
multiple timestamps. These commands and functions use the letter :hp2.c:ehp2.
to refer to the creation time stamp, :hp2.w:ehp2. for the last write time stamp,
and :hp2.a:ehp2. for the last access time stamp.
:p.
Additional information about disk files and filesystems is available under
:link reftype=hd refid=DriveVol.Drives and Volumes:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=Filesys.Filesystems:elink.,
:link reftype=hd refid=Directories.Directories and Subdirectories:elink., and
:link reftype=hd refid=Filenames.Filenames:elink.&per.

