:h3 name=KeyScan.Key Codes and Scan Codes Table
:p.
(For more details on key codes and scan codes, see the
:link reftype=hd refid=KeyScanExpl.Key Codes and Scan Codes Explanation:elink.&per.)
:p.
The following table lists all of the keys on the 101-key "enhanced" U.S.
keyboard. Many non-U.S. keyboards are similar, but will not be exactly the
same. The keys are arranged roughly in scan code order, which is generally
left to right, moving from the top of the keyboard to the bottom.
:p.
Column 1 shows the key's keycap symbol or name. Columns 2 and 3 show the
scan code, and the ASCII code if the key is unshifted. Columns 4 and 5
contain the codes for the shifted key. Columns 6 and 7 show the codes for
Ctrl plus the key. The last column contains the scan code for Alt plus the
key (Alt keystrokes have no ASCII code and always generate an ASCII code of
0, which is not shown).
:p.
Key names prefaced by :hp2.np:ehp2. are on the numeric keypad. Those
prefaced by :hp2.cp:ehp2. are on the cursor keypad between the main typing
keys and the number keypad. The numeric keypad values are valid if
Num Lock is turned off. If you need to specify a number key from
the numeric keypad when Num Lock is on, use the scan code shown for the
keypad and the ASCII code shown for the corresponding typewriter key. For
example, the keypad "7" has a scan code of 71 (the np Home scan code) and an
ASCII code of 54 (the ASCII code for "7").
:p.
The chart is blank for key combinations that do not have scan codes
or ASCII codes, like :hp2.Ctrl-1:ehp2. or :hp2.Alt-PgUp:ehp2.&per.
:xmp.

