:h3 name=ANSI.ANSI
:p.
This section is a quick-reference to commonly-used ANSI commands.
:p.
An ANSI command string consists of three parts&colon.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=20 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.ESC[:ehp2.:pd.The ASCII character ESC, followed by a left
bracket. These two characters must be present
in all ANSI strings.
:pt.:hp2.parameters:ehp2.:pd.Optional parameters for the command. If there
are multiple parameters they are separated by semicolons.
:pt.:hp2.cmd:ehp2.:pd.A single-letter command. The case of the
letter IS meaningful.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
For example, to position the cursor to row 7, column 12 the ANSI
command is&colon.
:xmp.
    ESC[7;12H
:exmp.:p.
To transmit ANSI commands to the screen with &4OS2., you should use
the :link reftype=hd refid=ECHO.ECHO:elink. command. The ESC character can be generated by
inserting it into the string directly (if you are putting the string in a
batch file and your editor will insert such a character), or by using
&4OS2.'s internal "escape" character (caret, [:hp2.^:ehp2.])
followed by a lower-case "e". For example, the sequence shown
above could be transmitted from a batch file with either of these
commands (the first uses an ESC character directly; the second uses
^e)&colon.
:xmp.
    echo [7;12H
    echo ^e[7;12H
:exmp.:p.
You can also include ANSI commands in your prompt, using $e to
transmit the ESC character. You can NOT use PROMPT to transmit
ANSI commands to the screen from a batch file (see
:link reftype=hd refid=PROMPT.PROMPT:elink.).
:p.
:p.
:hp2.Commands:ehp2.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=24 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.ESC[rowsA:ehp2.:pd.Cursor up
:pt.:hp2.ESC[rowsB:ehp2.:pd.Cursor down
:pt.:hp2.ESC[colsC:ehp2.:pd.Cursor right
:pt.:hp2.ESC[colsD:ehp2.:pd.Cursor left
:pt.:hp2.ESC[row;colH:ehp2.:pd.Set cursor position (top left is row 1, column 1)
:pt.:hp2.ESC[2J:ehp2.:pd.Clear screen
:pt.:hp2.ESC[K:ehp2.:pd.Clear from cursor to end of line
:pt.:hp2.ESC[row;colf:ehp2.:pd.Set cursor position, same as "H" command
:pt.:hp2.ESC[attr;attr;...m:ehp2.:pd.Set display attributes; see table of attribute values below
:pt.:hp2.ESC[s:ehp2.:pd.Save cursor position (may not be nested)
:pt.:hp2.ESC[u:ehp2.:pd.Restore cursor position after a save
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
:hp2.Display Attributes:ehp2.
:lm margin=8.:parml compact tsize=12 break=fit.
:pt.:hp2.0:ehp2.:pd.All attributes off (normal white on black)
:pt.:hp2.1:ehp2.:pd.High intensity (bold)
:pt.:hp2.2:ehp2.:pd.Normal intensity
:pt.:hp2.4:ehp2.:pd.Underline (usually effective only on monochrome displays)
:pt.:hp2.5:ehp2.:pd.Blinking
:pt.:hp2.7:ehp2.:pd.Reverse Video
:pt.:hp2.8:ehp2.:pd.Invisible
:pt.:hp2.30-37:ehp2.:pd.Set the foreground color&colon.
:pt.:pd.   30=Black   31=Red       32=Green   33=Yellow
:pt.:pd.   34=Blue    35=Magenta   36=Cyan    37=White
:pt.:hp2.40-47:ehp2.:pd.Set the background color, same values as above but substitute 40 for 30 etc.
:eparml.:lm margin=1.
.br
Settings are cumulative, so (for example) to set bright red
foreground set all attributes off, then set red, then bold, use&colon.
:xmp.
    echo ^e[0;31;1m
:exmp.:p.
:p.
:hp2.Examples:ehp2.
:p.
Clear the display attributes, then set the display to bright cyan
on blue, and clear the screen&colon.
:xmp.
    echo ^e[0;44;36;1m^e[2J
:exmp.:p.
Set up a prompt which saves the cursor position, displays the &4OS2.
shell level, date, and time on the top line in bright white on
magenta, and then restores the cursor position and sets the color
to bright cyan on blue, and displays the standard prompt&colon.
:xmp.
    prompt $e[s$e[1;1f$e[0;45;37;1m$e[K($z) $d $t$e[u$e[0;44;36;1m$p$g
:exmp.

