:link reftype=hd refid=Glossary_G.G:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=Glossary_H.H:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=Glossary_I.I:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=Glossary_J.J:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=Glossary_K.K:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=Glossary_L.L:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=Glossary_M.M:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=Glossary_N.N:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=Glossary_O.O:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=Glossary_P.P:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=Glossary_R.R:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=Glossary_S.S:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=Glossary_T.T:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=Glossary_U.U:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=Glossary_V.V:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=Glossary_W.W:elink.
:link reftype=hd refid=Glossary_X.X:elink.
:p.
:p.
:hp2.Base Name:ehp2.&colon. the filename without a drive, path, or
extension. For example, in the filename
:hp1.C&colon.\DIR1\LETTER.DAT:ehp1. the base name is :hp1.LETTER:ehp1.&per.
:p.
:hp2.BAT File:ehp2.&colon. See :hp2.Batch File:ehp2.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Batch File:ehp2.&colon. A text file containing a sequence of commands
for the command processor to execute. Batch files are used to save command
sequences so that they can be re-executed at any time, transferred to
another system, etc. The extension of a batch file may be :hp1..BAT:ehp1.,
:hp1..CMD:ehp1., or :hp1..BTM:ehp1., depending upon the operating system and
command processor you are using.
:p.
:hp2.Batch File Parameter:ehp2.&colon. A numbered variable (:hp1.e.g.:ehp1.
%2) used within a batch file, allowing a different value to be used at that
spot in the file each time it is executed.
:p.
:hp2.Binary File:ehp2.&colon. A file containing information which does not
represent or cannot sensibly be interpreted as text. See also :hp2.ASCII
File:ehp2.&per.
:p.
:hp2.BIOS:ehp2. or :hp2.Basic Input Output System:ehp2.&colon. The software
(or "firmware") stored on chips inside PC systems. The BIOS provides basic
low-level control of devices required to operate the system, such as the
keyboard, floppy disk, and screen; it also handles system self-tests at
startup, and initiates loading of the operating system.
:p.
:hp2.Block Device:ehp2.&colon. A physical device for input or output which
can transmit or receive large blocks of data while the computer is engaged
in other activities. Examples include disk and optical drives. See
also :hp2.Character Device:ehp2.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Boot Directory:ehp2.&colon. The current directory at the time the
system is booted, usually the root directory of the boot drive.
:p.
:hp2.Boot Drive:ehp2.&colon. The disk drive that the system is booted from,
usually A&colon. (the floppy disk) or C&colon. (the hard disk).
:p.
:hp2.Boot:ehp2.&colon. The process of starting the computer and loading the
operating system into memory. See also :hp2.Reboot:ehp2., :hp2.Cold
Reboot:ehp2., and :hp2.Warm Reboot:ehp2.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Break:ehp2.&colon. A signal sent to a program to tell it to halt what
it is doing. The :hp2. Ctrl-C:ehp2. key  or :hp2.Ctrl-Break:ehp2. key is
used to send this signal. Some external commands abort when they receive a
break signal; others return to a previous screen or menu, or abort the
current operation.
:p.
:hp2.BTM File:ehp2.&colon. A special type of &4OS2. batch file which is loaded
into memory to speed up execution.
:p.
:hp2.Buffer:ehp2.&colon. An area of memory set aside for storage. For
example, disk buffers are used to save information as it is transferred
between your program and the disk, and the keyboard buffer holds keystrokes
until a program can use them.

