:p.
:p.
:hp2.FAT File System:ehp2.&colon. The traditional filesystem used by DOS
to store files on diskettes (FAT12) and hard disks (FAT16); also supported by
OS/2, Windows, and Linux. Uses a :hp2.F:ehp2.ile :hp2.A:ehp2.llocation
:hp2.T:ehp2.able to keep track of allocated and unallocated space on the disk.
FAT32 is a FAT filesystem variant utilizing a 32-bit FAT, capable of storing
long filenames with case-retention on larger volumes.
:p.
:hp2.FAT-Compatible Filename:ehp2.&colon. See :hp2.SFN:ehp2.&per.
:p.
:hp2.FF:ehp2. or :hp2.Form Feed:ehp2.&colon. The ASCII character "form
feed" (decimal value 12), which typically causes a printer to skip to a new
page. The FF character is not normally entered from the keyboard, but in
many cases it can be generated, if necessary, by holding the Alt key,
pressing 0-1-2, and releasing the Alt key.
:p.
:hp2.File Attribute:ehp2.&colon. See :hp2.Attribute:ehp2.&per.
:p.
:hp2.File Description:ehp2.&colon. See :hp2.Description:ehp2.&per.
:p.
:hp2.File Exclusion Range:ehp2.&colon. A &4OS2. feature which allows you to
exclude files from processing by internal commands based on their names.
:p.
:hp2.Filename Completion:ehp2.&colon. A &4OS2. feature which allows you to
type part of a filename on the command line, and have the command processor
fill in the rest for you.
:p.
:hp2.Free Memory:ehp2.&colon. Usually, the amount of total memory which is
unoccupied and available for applications.

