:p.
:p.
:hp2.RAM:ehp2. or :hp2.Random Access Memory:ehp2.&colon. The physical
memory used to store data while a computer is operating. The information in
most types of RAM is lost when power is turned off.
:p.
:hp2.RAM Disk:ehp2.&colon. A pseudo "disk drive", created by software,
which appears like a normal physical disk drive to programs. Sometimes also
called a :hp2.Virtual Disk:ehp2.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Range:ehp2.&colon. See :hp2.Date Range:ehp2., :hp2.Size Range:ehp2.,
:hp2.Time Range:ehp2., and :hp2.File Exclusion Range:ehp2.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Read-Only:ehp2.&colon. A file attribute indicating that the file can
be read, but not written or deleted by the operating system or the command
processor unless special commands are used.
:p.
:hp2.Reboot:ehp2.&colon. The process of restarting the computer with
software, with the keyboard (:hp1.e.g. :ehp1.by pressing Ctrl-Alt-Del), by
pressing a reset button, or by turning the power off and back on. See also
:hp2.Cold Reboot :ehp2.and :hp2.Warm Reboot:ehp2.&per.
:p.
:hp2.Redirection:ehp2.&colon. A method for collecting output from a program
in a file, and/or of providing the input for a program from a file. See
also :hp2.Pipe:ehp2.&per.
:p.
:hp2.REXX:ehp2.&colon. A file and text processing language developed by
IBM, and available on many PC and other platforms.
:p.
:hp2.ROM:ehp2. or :hp2.Read Only Memory:ehp2.&colon. A physical memory
device used to store information which cannot be readily modified, such as
the BIOS built into each PC system. The information in ROM is typically
retained when power is turned off.
:p.
:hp2.Root Directory:ehp2.&colon. The first directory on any disk, from
which all other directories are "descended." The root directory is
referenced with a single backslash [:hp2.\:ehp2.].

